// Explanation closing line is a meaningful clincher (equivalence / discriminator / hook), never a bare restatement.
if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
window.MM['radio_golden_13_18']=[

/*1*/ {"q":"Woman on HRT. What side effect is most likely?","o":["Thromboembolism","Endometrial CA","Ovarian CA","Osteoporosis"],"a":0,"e":"Hormone replacement therapy carries a well-recognised prothrombotic risk; oestrogen increases hepatic synthesis of clotting factors and reduces antithrombin, raising venous thromboembolism incidence, especially in the first year of use.<br><br>Endometrial cancer risk applies chiefly to unopposed oestrogen; combined HRT mitigates it. The earliest and most consistently quoted hazard is thromboembolism, not malignancy."},
/*2*/ {"q":"Man, with tremors, stooped posture and straight facial expressions. Lesion is in?","o":["Medulla","Cerebrum","Cerebellum","Basal ganglia"],"a":3,"e":"Resting tremor, bradykinesia, stooped posture and mask-like facies are the classic Parkinsonian tetrad, arising from dopaminergic degeneration in the substantia nigra of the basal ganglia.<br><br>Cerebellar disease gives intention tremor and ataxia, not the masked face; the expressionless visage plus pill-rolling tremor points squarely to basal ganglia."},
/*3*/ {"q":"Dystrophic calcification:","o":["Rickets","Hyperparathyroidism","Atheromatous plaque","Vitamin D intoxication"],"a":2,"e":"Dystrophic calcification deposits in already damaged or necrotic tissue with normal serum calcium; atheromatous plaques are a prototypical site, calcifying within lipid-laden necrotic intima.<br><br>Rickets, hyperparathyroidism and vitamin D toxicity disturb calcium/phosphate levels and cause metastatic calcification in normal tissue; the local-damage clue identifies the dystrophic type."},
/*4*/ {"q":"CNS gray matter repair by:","o":["Glial cells","Astrocytes","Oligodendrocytes","Microglia"],"a":1,"e":"After CNS injury astrocytes proliferate and lay down a dense fibrillary glial scar (astrogliosis), the principal reparative response in central grey and white matter since true regeneration is limited.<br><br>Oligodendrocytes myelinate but do not scar; microglia phagocytose debris. Repair equals gliosis, and gliosis is fundamentally an astrocytic process."},
/*5*/ {"q":"Stratified cuboidal epithelium:","o":["Salivary gland duct","Urethra","Ureter","Fallopian tubes"],"a":0,"e":"Stratified cuboidal epithelium lines the larger excretory ducts of exocrine glands, classically the salivary gland ducts, providing a tougher two-layer lining than simple cuboidal.<br><br>Ureter is transitional, fallopian tube is ciliated columnar, urethra varies. Think large gland duct and the answer is salivary duct (Ref. DiFiore's Histology)."},
/*6*/ {"q":"Clavicle fractured medial side raised by:","o":["Sternocleidomastoid","Trapezius","Pectoralis major","Deltoid"],"a":0,"e":"In a mid-shaft clavicular fracture the medial fragment is pulled upward by sternocleidomastoid, which inserts on the medial third, while the lateral fragment drops under arm weight.<br><br>Trapezius supports the lateral piece. The classic deformity, medial fragment up, is the signature pull of sternocleidomastoid."},
/*7*/ {"q":"Prolactinoma, increase prolactin because of deficiency of:","o":["Serotonin","Dopamine","Somatostatin","TRH"],"a":1,"e":"Prolactin is unique among pituitary hormones in being under tonic inhibition; dopamine from the hypothalamus continuously suppresses it, so loss of dopaminergic restraint or stalk effect elevates prolactin.<br><br>TRH stimulates prolactin but is not the tonic controller. The hyperprolactinaemia mechanism is fundamentally release from dopamine inhibition."},
/*8*/ {"q":"2-point discrimination:","o":["Lateral inhibition","Pre sympathetic","Post sympathetic","Recurrent inhibition"],"a":0,"e":"Two-point discrimination depends on lateral inhibition, where active sensory neurons inhibit their neighbours, sharpening contrast and allowing two adjacent stimuli to be perceived separately.<br><br>Sympathetic options are autonomic and irrelevant to tactile acuity; the sharpening of receptive fields is precisely the role of lateral inhibition."},
/*9*/ {"q":"Splenectomy planned for AIHA, splenic vessels to be ligated in:","o":["Splenorenal ligament","Lienorenal ligament","Gastrosplenic ligament","Phrenicocolic ligament"],"a":1,"e":"The splenic artery and vein run within the lienorenal (splenorenal) ligament along with the tail of the pancreas; this is the ligament ligated to control the splenic pedicle during splenectomy.<br><br>The gastrosplenic ligament carries the short gastric vessels only. The main pedicle equals the lienorenal ligament, the surgeon's target."},
/*10*/ {"q":"Langerhans giant cells are found in:","o":["Sarcoidosis","Wegener's granulomatosis","Syphilis","TB"],"a":3,"e":"Langhans giant cells, with peripheral horseshoe nuclear arrangement, are the hallmark of caseating granulomas in tuberculosis, formed by fusion of epithelioid macrophages.<br><br>Sarcoid granulomas are non-caseating and may show asteroid bodies; the peripheral-nucleus giant cell with caseation is most classically tuberculous."},
/*11*/ {"q":"Skeletal Muscles:","o":["Aponeurosis is fibrous","Belly fleshy throughout","Has tendons only","Has no fascia"],"a":1,"e":"Skeletal muscle has a fleshy contractile belly throughout its mid-portion, tapering to tendons or aponeuroses at attachments; the belly itself is the working muscular mass.<br><br>Aponeuroses are flat tendinous sheets, not the belly. The defining feature of the muscle body is its fleshy belly, distinguishing it from its fibrous attachments."},
/*12*/ {"q":"Unsaturated fatty acid:","o":["Soya bean oil","Butter","Ghee","Lard"],"a":0,"e":"Soya bean oil is rich in polyunsaturated fatty acids and remains liquid at room temperature, the practical hallmark of unsaturation due to cis double bonds preventing tight packing.<br><br>Butter, ghee and lard are saturated animal fats, solid at room temperature; liquid plant oil signals the unsaturated choice."},
/*13*/ {"q":"Most abundant glial cells in grey matter:","o":["Oligodendrocytes","Fibrous astrocytes","Protoplasmic astrocytes","Microglia"],"a":2,"e":"Protoplasmic astrocytes predominate in grey matter, possessing many short branching processes that envelop synapses and capillaries, distinct from the long-process fibrous astrocytes of white matter.<br><br>Oligodendrocytes are commonest overall but myelin-related; the grey-matter qualifier points specifically to the protoplasmic subtype."},
/*14*/ {"q":"Unable to oppose thumb, nerve injured:","o":["Ulnar nerve","Median nerve","Radial nerve","Axillary nerve"],"a":1,"e":"Thumb opposition is performed by opponens pollicis, supplied by the recurrent branch of the median nerve; median palsy abolishes opposition and flattens the thenar eminence (ape hand).<br><br>Ulnar palsy spares opposition but weakens adduction. Loss of opposition is the median nerve signature."},
/*15*/ {"q":"Patient with deep wound on scalp. Which layer has to be sutured otherwise will cause large gap?","o":["Epicranial aponeurosis","Pericranium","Loose connective tissue","Skin"],"a":0,"e":"The epicranial aponeurosis (galea) connects frontalis and occipitalis; when divided transversely these muscles pull the wound widely apart, so it must be sutured to prevent gaping.<br><br>Pericranium and loose areolar tissue do not exert this pull; the muscular traction on the galea is what mandates its repair."},
/*16*/ {"q":"Subarachnoid space ends at:","o":["S2-S3","L1-L2","L5-S1","S4-S5"],"a":0,"e":"The subarachnoid space and dural sac terminate at the level of the second sacral vertebra (S2), well below the conus medullaris, making lower lumbar puncture safe.<br><br>L1-L2 marks the cord's end, not the dural sac; the thecal sac's true caudal limit is S2."},
/*17*/ {"q":"Needle after piercing rough spinous ligament will enter:","o":["Epidural space","Subarachnoid space","Subdural space","Ligamentum flavum"],"a":0,"e":"Passing the supraspinous and interspinous ligaments and then the tougher ligamentum flavum, the needle next enters the epidural space, which contains fat and the internal vertebral venous plexus.<br><br>The subarachnoid space lies deeper, beyond the dura; immediately after the ligaments the space encountered is epidural."},
/*18*/ {"q":"Tractus Solitarius is related to:","o":["Vision","Touch","Hearing","Taste"],"a":3,"e":"The nucleus of the tractus solitarius receives special visceral afferents for taste from cranial nerves VII, IX and X, as well as general visceral sensation from the viscera.<br><br>Vision, hearing and touch use other pathways; the solitary nucleus is the gustatory and visceral relay, not visual or auditory."},
/*19*/ {"q":"Following Mitral valve replacement on HB Cola coloured urine: Microangiopathic hemolytic anemia. MHC contains:","o":["HLA","Genetic disease-causing","Both A and B","Neither"],"a":2,"e":"The major histocompatibility complex encodes HLA molecules central to antigen presentation, and the locus harbours numerous disease-association genes, so both statements hold true.<br><br>Restricting to HLA alone ignores the disease-linkage genes within the region; the combined option captures the MHC fully."},
/*20*/ {"q":"Musculoskeletal abnormality:","o":["Achondroplasia","Marfan","Osteogenesis imperfecta","Rickets"],"a":0,"e":"Achondroplasia, an FGFR3 gain-of-function disorder, produces rhizomelic short-limb dwarfism with a relatively normal trunk, the prototypical inherited musculoskeletal dysplasia in this list.<br><br>Rickets is nutritional and Marfan connective-tissue; the classic skeletal dysplasia keyed here is achondroplasia."},
/*21*/ {"q":"Related to Muscular dystrophy:","o":["Duchenne is X-linked","Autosomal dominant","Mitochondrial","Not heritable"],"a":0,"e":"Duchenne muscular dystrophy is an X-linked recessive dystrophin defect affecting boys, with proximal weakness, calf pseudohypertrophy and Gower's sign, the defining inheritance pattern.<br><br>Autosomal or mitochondrial patterns describe other myopathies; the hallmark of DMD is X-linked recessive transmission."},
/*22*/ {"q":"Female with pallor, loss of sensation in lower limbs:","o":["Folate deficiency","B12 deficiency","IDA","Anaemia of chronic disease"],"a":1,"e":"Combined pallor with posterior-column sensory loss indicates subacute combined degeneration from vitamin B12 deficiency, which impairs myelin synthesis and causes megaloblastic anaemia plus neuropathy.<br><br>Folate deficiency gives anaemia without neurological signs; the neuro-plus-anaemia combination is the B12 fingerprint."},
/*23*/ {"q":"Intrinsic factor released from:","o":["Body of stomach","Fundus of stomach","Pylorus","Cardia"],"a":0,"e":"Parietal (oxyntic) cells, concentrated in the body and fundus of the stomach, secrete both hydrochloric acid and intrinsic factor needed for ileal B12 absorption.<br><br>The pylorus contains G cells secreting gastrin, not intrinsic factor; trace intrinsic factor to the acid-secreting parietal cells of the body."},
/*24*/ {"q":"Lymph drain from outer aspects of nipple:","o":["Anterior axillary lymph nodes","Internal mammary","Supraclavicular","Posterior axillary"],"a":0,"e":"The lateral (outer) breast and nipple drain principally to the anterior (pectoral) axillary nodes, the first echelon for the majority of breast lymph.<br><br>Medial breast drains to internal mammary nodes; the outer-quadrant flow keys to the anterior axillary group."},
/*25*/ {"q":"Lower limb paralysis, lower facial weakness left, homonymous hemianopia:","o":["Cerebral cortex","Cerebellum","Midbrain","Thalamus"],"a":0,"e":"Contralateral leg-predominant weakness, lower facial palsy and homonymous hemianopia together localise to a large cerebral cortical or subcortical lesion affecting motor, facial and optic radiation fibres.<br><br>Cerebellar or midbrain lesions would not give hemianopia with this pattern; the triad points to a cortical territory infarct."},
/*26*/ {"q":"Fine motor movements controlled by:","o":["Corticospinal tract","Rubrospinal tract","Cerebellum","Vestibulospinal tract"],"a":0,"e":"Fine, fractionated voluntary movements of the digits are governed by the lateral corticospinal tract, whose direct motoneuron connections allow precise independent finger control.<br><br>The cerebellum coordinates but does not initiate fine motor commands; precision movement is the corticospinal tract's defining role."},
/*27*/ {"q":"Pt has tremor on fine movements of head, swings to right side on asking to walk in a line:","o":["Corticospinal tract","Cerebellum","Midbrain","Thalamus"],"a":1,"e":"Intention tremor worsening with fine movement plus gait deviation toward the lesion side indicates an ipsilateral cerebellar hemisphere disorder disrupting coordination and balance.<br><br>Corticospinal lesions cause spastic weakness, not intention tremor; the swaying-toward-side gait with action tremor is cerebellar."},
/*28*/ {"q":"Important inhibition in feedback:","o":["Negative feedback","Positive feedback","Feedforward","Lateral"],"a":0,"e":"Most physiological homeostatic loops use negative feedback, where the output inhibits the initiating stimulus, stabilising variables such as hormones, glucose and blood pressure around set points.<br><br>Positive feedback amplifies and is rare (e.g. parturition); the stabilising inhibitory loop is negative feedback."},
/*29*/ {"q":"Bicarbonates Secondary center of ossification in developing bones:","o":["Diaphysis","Epiphysis","Epiphyseal plate","Metaphysis"],"a":1,"e":"The epiphysis ossifies from a secondary ossification centre that appears after birth, distinct from the diaphysis which forms from the primary centre prenatally.<br><br>The epiphyseal plate is cartilage for growth, not an ossification centre; the secondary centre is located in the epiphysis."},
/*30*/ {"q":"In bone new matrix is formed by:","o":["Osteoblasts","Osteoclasts","Osteocytes","Osteoprogenitor cells"],"a":0,"e":"Osteoblasts synthesise and secrete osteoid, the unmineralised organic bone matrix, and then regulate its mineralisation, making them the bone-forming cells.<br><br>Osteoclasts resorb bone and osteocytes maintain it; new matrix production is exclusively the osteoblast's function."},
/*31*/ {"q":"From end of atrial depolarization to start of ventricular depolarization:","o":["ST segment","QRS complex","PR interval","QT interval"],"a":2,"e":"The PR interval spans atrial depolarisation through the AV nodal delay up to the onset of ventricular depolarisation, reflecting conduction time from atria to ventricles.<br><br>The ST segment lies after ventricular depolarisation; the atria-to-ventricle conduction window is precisely the PR interval."},
/*32*/ {"q":"In shock most important body response as whole?","o":["Adrenosympathetic response","CNS ischemic response","Renin-angiotensin","ADH release"],"a":0,"e":"The immediate, dominant whole-body compensatory reaction to shock is the adrenosympathetic discharge, causing tachycardia, vasoconstriction and catecholamine release to preserve perfusion.<br><br>The CNS ischaemic response is a late extreme reflex; the principal early systemic defence is adrenosympathetic activation."},
/*33*/ {"q":"Paracetamol Antidote:","o":["NaHCO3","Charcoal","N Acetylcysteine","Atropine"],"a":2,"e":"N-acetylcysteine replenishes hepatic glutathione, detoxifying the reactive metabolite NAPQI, and is the specific antidote for paracetamol overdose, most effective given early.<br><br>Activated charcoal limits absorption but is not the antidote; the glutathione-restoring agent is N-acetylcysteine."},
/*34*/ {"q":"Sequela of measles:","o":["Subacute sclerosing panencephalitis","Guillain-Barre","Reye syndrome","Encephalitis only"],"a":0,"e":"Subacute sclerosing panencephalitis is a rare, fatal delayed complication of measles, appearing years later from persistent defective virus in the CNS with progressive neurological decline.<br><br>The hallmark late measles sequela tested here is the panencephalitis, not an acute post-infectious syndrome."},
/*35*/ {"q":"If some of carbohydrate is liberated from protein what will occur?","o":["Proteolysis by proteases","Precipitation of protein","Uptake by liver and destruction","Glycosuria"],"a":0,"e":"Removing the carbohydrate moiety from a glycoprotein exposes the peptide backbone to proteolytic enzymes, since the sugar normally shields it, accelerating proteolysis by proteases.<br><br>Precipitation or hepatic uptake are not the immediate effect; deglycosylation primarily renders the protein protease-susceptible."},
/*36*/ {"q":"Most common physiological form of DNA in human:","o":["A form","B form","D form","Z form"],"a":1,"e":"B-DNA is the predominant right-handed double-helical form under physiological hydration and salt conditions, with about 10 base pairs per turn (Ref. Chatterjee).<br><br>A and Z forms occur under special conditions; the physiologically prevalent conformation is B-DNA."},
/*37*/ {"q":"Swelling at back at level of T10, lymphatic drainage:","o":["Axillary lymph nodes","Inguinal nodes","Para-aortic nodes","Internal mammary"],"a":0,"e":"Skin of the back above the level around T10 drains upward to the axillary nodes, while below that watershed it drains to the inguinal group.<br><br>A swelling at the T10 back level falls in the axillary drainage territory, the answer here."},
/*38*/ {"q":"Viral disease transmitted by mosquito bite:","o":["Yellow fever","Dengue","Malaria","Both A and B"],"a":3,"e":"Both yellow fever and dengue are mosquito-borne viral diseases transmitted chiefly by Aedes aegypti, so the inclusive option is correct.<br><br>Malaria is parasitic, not viral; selecting only one viral disease ignores the other, hence both A and B."},
/*39*/ {"q":"Fatty liver cause in Pakistan, leading cause:","o":["Obesity","Viral hepatitis","Protein deficiency","Alcohol"],"a":2,"e":"In the Pakistani context the textbook attributes fatty liver predominantly to protein-energy malnutrition and protein deficiency, impairing lipoprotein export from hepatocytes (per source).<br><br>Obesity dominates in Western data; in this regional source the keyed leading cause is protein deficiency."},
/*40*/ {"q":"3rd pharyngeal arch derivative:","o":["Stylopharyngeus","Muscles of mastication","Stapedius","Cricothyroid"],"a":0,"e":"The third pharyngeal arch gives rise to stylopharyngeus muscle and the greater horn of the hyoid, innervated by the glossopharyngeal nerve.<br><br>Muscles of mastication are first-arch and stapedius second-arch; the third-arch muscle is stylopharyngeus."},
/*41*/ {"q":"New born swelling on anterior abdominal wall with umbilicus attached:","o":["Omphalocele","Gastroschisis","Umbilical hernia","Patent urachus"],"a":0,"e":"Omphalocele is a midline anterior abdominal wall defect where herniated viscera are covered by a membranous sac and the umbilical cord inserts onto the sac apex.<br><br>Gastroschisis has no covering sac and is para-umbilical; cord attached to the sac defines omphalocele."},
/*42*/ {"q":"Defecation is carried out mainly by:","o":["Mass movement","Parasympathetic reflex","Segmentation","Peristalsis only"],"a":1,"e":"The defecation reflex is mediated chiefly by the parasympathetic (sacral) outflow, which intensifies colonic and rectal contraction and relaxes the internal sphincter once the rectum is distended.<br><br>Mass movements deliver stool to the rectum, but the act of defecation is driven by the parasympathetic reflex."},
/*43*/ {"q":"Pan Chewing history:","o":["Submucosal fibrosis","Leukoplakia","Erythroplakia","Lichen planus"],"a":0,"e":"Habitual betel-quid (pan) chewing classically produces oral submucous fibrosis, with progressive mucosal stiffening, trismus and a recognised premalignant risk.<br><br>Leukoplakia links more to tobacco/smoking; the specific pan-chewing association is submucous fibrosis."},
/*44*/ {"q":"Common midline cranial anomaly:","o":["Medial left lip","Cleft palate","Anencephaly","Encephalocele"],"a":1,"e":"Cleft palate results from failure of the palatal shelves to fuse in the midline, a common midline craniofacial developmental anomaly.<br><br>A medial lip cleft is rare; the frequent midline fusion defect tested here is cleft palate."},
/*45*/ {"q":"Non-invasive fungal sinusitis is common in:","o":["Prolonged antibiotics use","HIV","DM","Immunocompetent"],"a":3,"e":"Non-invasive (allergic or fungal-ball) sinusitis typically occurs in immunocompetent individuals, in contrast to invasive forms which strike the immunocompromised and diabetics (Ref. Dhingra).<br><br>HIV and uncontrolled DM predispose to the invasive type; the non-invasive form keys to the immunocompetent host."},
/*46*/ {"q":"Primordial cell derived:","o":["Endoderm","Ectoderm","Mesoderm","Yolk sac endoderm"],"a":1,"e":"Per the source key, primordial germ cells are traced to the ectoderm-derived epiblast before migrating through the yolk sac wall to the gonadal ridge (per source).<br><br>Many texts cite yolk sac endoderm; following this book's key the answer recorded is ectoderm."},
/*47*/ {"q":"Primary prevention of dental caries:","o":["Tooth brushing","Tooth extraction","Fluoride after decay","Restoration"],"a":0,"e":"Primary prevention acts before disease onset; regular tooth brushing with plaque removal prevents caries initiation, the true primary preventive measure.<br><br>Extraction and restoration are tertiary; preventing the disease from starting equals tooth brushing."},
/*48*/ {"q":"Subclavian vein is formed by the fusion of:","o":["Brachiocephalic and internal jugular veins","Axillary and cephalic continuation","Internal and external jugular","Vertebral and jugular"],"a":1,"e":"The subclavian vein is the continuation of the axillary vein at the lateral border of the first rib and joins the internal jugular to form the brachiocephalic vein.<br><br>The brachiocephalic vein is the product of subclavian plus IJV, not its origin; the subclavian itself continues from the axillary vein."},
/*49*/ {"q":"Cervical polyp lined by stratified squamous epithelium:","o":["Dysplasia","Metaplasia","Hyperplasia","Neoplasia"],"a":1,"e":"Endocervical glandular epithelium replaced by stratified squamous epithelium represents squamous metaplasia, an adaptive change at the transformation zone in response to the acidic vaginal environment.<br><br>Dysplasia implies atypia and hyperplasia implies increased cell number; an orderly epithelial type-switch is metaplasia."},
/*50*/ {"q":"Aponeurosis internal oblique and transversus abdominis forms:","o":["Conjoint tendon","Inguinal ligament","Lacunar ligament","Linea alba only"],"a":0,"e":"The fused aponeurotic fibres of internal oblique and transversus abdominis form the conjoint tendon (falx inguinalis), reinforcing the posterior wall of the inguinal canal medially.<br><br>The inguinal ligament is the lower external oblique edge; the internal-oblique-plus-transversus fusion is the conjoint tendon."},

/*51*/ {"q":"Child with bronchiolitis, causative organism most likely:","o":["RSV","Influenza","EBV","Streptococcus"],"a":0,"e":"Acute bronchiolitis in infants is overwhelmingly caused by respiratory syncytial virus, producing wheeze, tachypnoea and small-airway inflammation in winter epidemics.<br><br>Influenza and EBV are not typical bronchiolitis agents; the classic infantile small-airway pathogen is RSV."},
/*52*/ {"q":"During parturition which layer is shed?","o":["Stratum Basale","Stratum Functionalis","Endometrium","Basale + Functionalis"],"a":1,"e":"After delivery the superficial stratum functionalis of the decidua is shed as lochia, while the deeper stratum basale is retained to regenerate new endometrium.<br><br>The basal layer is preserved for regeneration; only the functional layer is sloughed at parturition."},
/*53*/ {"q":"Young boy fractured his arm while playing. Calcium 6, urinary CA is normal:","o":["Vitamin D deficiency","Hypoparathyroidism","Pseudohypoparathyroidism","Rickets"],"a":0,"e":"Hypocalcaemia with low serum calcium yet normal urinary calcium in a child with fragility fracture points to vitamin D deficiency impairing intestinal calcium absorption and bone mineralisation.<br><br>Hypoparathyroidism would alter urinary calcium handling differently; the absorption-defect picture keys to vitamin D deficiency."},
/*54*/ {"q":"Child with generalized swelling, periorbital edema cause:","o":["Na+ retention","Hypoalbuminemia","Increased aldosterone","Venous obstruction"],"a":1,"e":"Generalised oedema with periorbital prominence in a child classically reflects nephrotic-range hypoalbuminaemia lowering plasma oncotic pressure and shifting fluid into the interstitium.<br><br>Sodium retention contributes secondarily; the primary driver of the puffy-face oedema is low albumin."},
/*55*/ {"q":"Sign of UMN lesion:","o":["Flaccid paralysis","Absent DTR","Hyper reflexia","Fasciculations"],"a":2,"e":"Upper motor neuron lesions release spinal reflexes from cortical inhibition, producing hyperreflexia, spasticity, clonus and an extensor plantar response.<br><br>Flaccidity, areflexia and fasciculations are lower motor neuron signs; the disinhibited brisk reflexes mark the UMN lesion."},
/*56*/ {"q":"Thalassemia is due to:","o":["Defective hemoglobinization","Membrane defect","Enzyme defect","Iron deficiency"],"a":0,"e":"Thalassaemia results from reduced or absent synthesis of globin chains, causing defective haemoglobinisation and a microcytic hypochromic anaemia with ineffective erythropoiesis.<br><br>Membrane and enzyme defects describe spherocytosis and G6PD; impaired globin/Hb production is the thalassaemia mechanism."},
/*57*/ {"q":"Esophageal CA is caused by:","o":["Hydrocarbons","Nitrosamine","Aryl amines","Aflatoxin"],"a":1,"e":"Nitrosamines, formed from dietary nitrites and present in pickled or smoked foods, are recognised carcinogens implicated in oesophageal carcinoma.<br><br>Aryl amines link to bladder cancer and aflatoxin to liver; the oesophageal carcinogen here is nitrosamine."},
/*58*/ {"q":"Erythropoietin is increased by:","o":["CRF","ARF","High Altitude","Polycythemia vera"],"a":2,"e":"High altitude causes hypoxaemia, which stimulates renal peritubular interstitial cells to secrete erythropoietin, driving a compensatory secondary polycythaemia.<br><br>Chronic renal failure lowers EPO and polycythaemia vera is EPO-independent; hypoxic stimulus at altitude raises EPO."},
/*59*/ {"q":"Type A personality are prone to develop heart diseases because of:","o":["Sedentary lifestyle","Psychological reactivity of stress","Diet","Genetics"],"a":1,"e":"Type A behaviour, marked by time urgency, hostility and competitiveness, increases cardiovascular risk chiefly through heightened psychological and sympathetic reactivity to stress.<br><br>Lifestyle is a confounder, but the personality-linked mechanism tested is exaggerated stress reactivity."},
/*60*/ {"q":"Pt develops Urticaria, Antibodies involved?","o":["IgE Mediated","IgA Mediated","IgM Mediated","IgG Mediated"],"a":0,"e":"Acute urticaria is a type I immediate hypersensitivity reaction in which allergen cross-links IgE on mast cells, triggering histamine release and wheal formation.<br><br>IgG and IgM mediate other hypersensitivity types; the wheal-and-flare urticarial response is IgE-driven."},
/*61*/ {"q":"Major body buffer acting in DKA:","o":["Proteins","Ammonia","Bicarbonates","Phosphate"],"a":2,"e":"The bicarbonate buffer system is the principal extracellular buffer consumed in diabetic ketoacidosis as it neutralises excess ketoacids, reflected in the falling serum bicarbonate.<br><br>Proteins and phosphate buffer intracellularly; the major front-line plasma buffer in DKA is bicarbonate."},
/*62*/ {"q":"Secondary center of ossification in developing bones:","o":["Diaphysis","Epiphysis","Periosteum","Metaphysis"],"a":1,"e":"The secondary ossification centre develops postnatally within the epiphysis, separated from the primary diaphyseal centre by the growth plate until skeletal maturity.<br><br>The diaphysis houses the primary centre; the post-birth secondary centre is epiphyseal."},
/*63*/ {"q":"In bone new matrix is formed by:","o":["Osteoblasts","Osteoclasts","Osteocytes","Osteoprogenitor cells"],"a":0,"e":"Osteoblasts deposit osteoid, the new organic bone matrix, and orchestrate its subsequent mineralisation, fulfilling the bone-forming role.<br><br>Osteoclasts resorb and osteocytes maintain; matrix synthesis belongs to the osteoblast."},
/*64*/ {"q":"From end of atrial depolarization to start of ventricular depolarization:","o":["ST segment","QRS complex","PR interval","QT interval"],"a":2,"e":"The interval bridging completed atrial depolarisation and the onset of ventricular depolarisation is the PR interval, encompassing the AV nodal conduction delay.<br><br>QRS represents ventricular depolarisation itself; the atrial-to-ventricular bridge is the PR interval."},
/*65*/ {"q":"In shock most important body response as whole?","o":["Adrenosympathetic response","CNS ischemic response","Renin release","ADH release"],"a":0,"e":"The dominant integrated compensatory response in shock is adrenosympathetic activation, mobilising catecholamines for tachycardia and vasoconstriction to defend perfusion pressure.<br><br>The CNS ischaemic response is a terminal extreme; the principal whole-body defence is adrenosympathetic."},
/*66*/ {"q":"Paracetamol Antidote:","o":["NaHCO3","Charcoal","N Acetylcysteine","Atropine"],"a":2,"e":"N-acetylcysteine restores depleted hepatic glutathione, neutralising the toxic metabolite NAPQI, and is the definitive paracetamol overdose antidote within the effective window.<br><br>Charcoal only reduces absorption; the glutathione-replenishing antidote is N-acetylcysteine."},
/*67*/ {"q":"Sequela of measles:","o":["Subacute sclerosing panencephalitis","Guillain-Barre","Reye syndrome","Acute encephalitis only"],"a":0,"e":"Subacute sclerosing panencephalitis is the characteristic delayed, progressive and fatal CNS sequela of measles, due to persistent defective virus years after infection.<br><br>The hallmark long-term measles complication tested is SSPE, not an acute syndrome."},
/*68*/ {"q":"If some of carbohydrate is liberated from protein what will occur?","o":["Proteolysis by proteases","Precipitation of protein","Uptake by liver and destruction","Glycosuria"],"a":0,"e":"Loss of the protective carbohydrate moiety from a glycoprotein exposes the polypeptide chain to proteolytic enzymes, increasing its susceptibility to proteolysis.<br><br>Precipitation or hepatic clearance is not the immediate consequence; deglycosylation primarily promotes proteolytic degradation."},
/*69*/ {"q":"Most common physiological form of DNA in human:","o":["A form","B form","D form","Z form"],"a":1,"e":"B-DNA, the right-handed Watson-Crick double helix, is the predominant form at physiological hydration and ionic strength, with roughly ten base pairs per turn (Ref. Chatterjee).<br><br>A and Z forms require atypical conditions; the prevailing physiological conformation is B-DNA."},
/*70*/ {"q":"30 percent burn, to prevent contracture:","o":["Glucocorticoids","Skin graft","Pressure garment","Physiotherapy only"],"a":1,"e":"Early split-skin grafting of extensive burns restores the dermal cover, the most effective measure to prevent disabling wound contracture and hypertrophic scarring.<br><br>Glucocorticoids do not prevent contracture; coverage by skin graft is the keyed preventive step."},
/*71*/ {"q":"During exercise cardiac output is augmented by?","o":["Vasoconstriction","Local metabolites","Sympathetic action on resistance vessels","Reduced venous return"],"a":2,"e":"Exercise raises cardiac output largely through sympathetic stimulation increasing heart rate and contractility, while local metabolites cause muscle vasodilatation to match flow.<br><br>Per the source key the augmentation is attributed to sympathetic action on resistance vessels (per source key)."},
/*72*/ {"q":"Parasympathetic supply of heart:","o":["Glossopharyngeal nerve","Pericardiophrenic nerve","Cardiac plexus","Vagus nerve"],"a":3,"e":"Parasympathetic innervation of the heart is carried by the vagus nerve, which slows the sinoatrial and atrioventricular nodes via the cardiac plexus.<br><br>The pericardiophrenic nerve is sensory/motor to pericardium and diaphragm; cardiac vagal control is the vagus nerve."},
/*73*/ {"q":"Blood supply of epicardium:","o":["Pericardiophrenic artery","Aorta","Coronary artery","Internal thoracic artery"],"a":2,"e":"The epicardium (visceral pericardium) is supplied by branches of the coronary arteries that also nourish the underlying myocardium.<br><br>The pericardiophrenic artery serves the fibrous and parietal pericardium; the visceral layer is coronary-supplied."},
/*74*/ {"q":"Normal iron requirements in pregnancy:","o":["4g","3g","2g","1g"],"a":2,"e":"Pregnancy increases total iron requirement to approximately 1 gram extra, but the keyed total normal requirement quoted here is about 2 grams (Ref. Robbins, Chatterjee).<br><br>Lower figures underestimate the gestational demand; the source records roughly 2 grams as the requirement."},
/*75*/ {"q":"Fetal side of placenta:","o":["Cytotrophoblast","Chorionic frondosum","Syncytiotrophoblast","Decidua basalis"],"a":1,"e":"The chorion frondosum, the villous chorion facing the embryo, forms the fetal contribution to the placenta, while the decidua basalis is the maternal side.<br><br>Cyto- and syncytiotrophoblast are cellular layers within villi; the fetal placental plate is the chorion frondosum."},
/*76*/ {"q":"Patient presented with raised ALP and GGT, likely diagnosis:","o":["Hepatitis","Dubin Johnson Syndrome","Intrahepatic cholestasis","Extrahepatic cholestasis"],"a":3,"e":"Disproportionate elevation of alkaline phosphatase together with gamma-glutamyl transferase indicates a cholestatic, biliary obstructive pattern, classically extrahepatic cholestasis.<br><br>Hepatocellular disease elevates transaminases more; the ALP-plus-GGT rise is the obstructive cholestatic signature."},
/*77*/ {"q":"Child with nephrotic syndrome, cause of generalized edema?","o":["Salt and water retention","Decreased oncotic pressure","Increased hydrostatic pressure","Lymphatic block"],"a":1,"e":"In nephrotic syndrome massive albuminuria lowers plasma oncotic pressure, the primary force driving generalised oedema, with sodium retention as a secondary contributor.<br><br>Hydrostatic and lymphatic factors are not primary here; reduced oncotic pressure from hypoalbuminaemia is the cause."},
/*78*/ {"q":"Mitral valve area:","o":["2-4 cm2","3-4 cm2","4-6 cm2","6-8 cm2"],"a":2,"e":"The normal mitral valve orifice measures approximately 4 to 6 square centimetres; symptomatic stenosis develops as it narrows well below this range.<br><br>The 2-4 cm2 figure already represents mild stenosis; the normal valve area is 4-6 cm2."},
/*79*/ {"q":"Patient with HTN, hypokalaemia, VMA negative, cortisol normal, renin low, aldosterone high, diagnosis?","o":["Renal artery stenosis","Cushing syndrome","Conn syndrome","Pheochromocytoma"],"a":2,"e":"Hypertension with hypokalaemia, suppressed renin and elevated aldosterone, with normal cortisol and negative catecholamine metabolites, defines primary hyperaldosteronism (Conn syndrome).<br><br>Renal artery stenosis raises renin; the low-renin high-aldosterone pattern is diagnostic of Conn."},
/*80*/ {"q":"True about third ventricle:","o":["Subthalamus is posterior inferiorly","Roof is choroid plexus only","No foramina","Lies in cerebellum"],"a":0,"e":"The third ventricle is a midline diencephalic cavity whose walls are formed by the thalamus and hypothalamus, with the subthalamus situated postero-inferiorly.<br><br>It communicates via the interventricular and cerebral aqueduct foramina; the keyed true statement is the postero-inferior subthalamic relation."},
/*81*/ {"q":"Prevention of lung from collapse:","o":["Tidal volume","Residual volume","Inspiratory reserve volume","Surfactant only"],"a":1,"e":"The residual volume, the air remaining after maximal expiration, keeps alveoli patent and prevents complete lung collapse at end-expiration.<br><br>Tidal and reserve volumes describe ventilatory excursions; the anti-collapse standing air is the residual volume."},
/*82*/ {"q":"Plasma osmolality tends to decrease in response to:","o":["Vasopressin","Isotonic glucose solution","Normal saline","Hypertonic saline"],"a":0,"e":"Vasopressin (ADH) promotes renal free-water reabsorption, diluting body fluids and lowering plasma osmolality toward the regulated set point.<br><br>Saline solutions raise or maintain osmolality; the osmolality-lowering agent is vasopressin via water retention."},
/*83*/ {"q":"Ovarian artery is branch of:","o":["Renal artery","Internal iliac artery","Abdominal aorta","External iliac artery"],"a":2,"e":"The ovarian arteries arise directly from the abdominal aorta just below the renal arteries, reflecting the gonad's original lumbar developmental position.<br><br>Internal iliac supplies the uterus via uterine artery; the ovarian artery springs from the aorta."},
/*84*/ {"q":"Blood supply of internal capsule:","o":["ACA","PCA","MCA","Basilar"],"a":2,"e":"The internal capsule is supplied predominantly by the lenticulostriate branches of the middle cerebral artery, with contributions from the anterior choroidal artery.<br><br>ACA and PCA serve other territories; the principal capsular supply is from the MCA lenticulostriates."},
/*85*/ {"q":"Substance that is neither absorbed nor secreted by renal tubules:","o":["PAH","Insulin","Creatinine","Glucose"],"a":0,"e":"Inulin (listed as PAH in the source key) is freely filtered and neither reabsorbed nor secreted, making it the ideal marker for measuring glomerular filtration rate (per source).<br><br>PAH is actively secreted in reality; following the keyed answer the option marked is A."},
/*86*/ {"q":"Standard deviation:","o":["Square root of Variance","Variability","Mean dispersion","Range"],"a":0,"e":"Standard deviation is mathematically defined as the square root of the variance, expressing dispersion in the original units of measurement.<br><br>Variance is the squared quantity; the SD is precisely its square root, the keyed relationship."},
/*87*/ {"q":"Reliability of a procedure is assessed by:","o":["Extent to which it is reliable as it was when performed first","Ability to reproduce same results again and again","Validity","Sensitivity"],"a":1,"e":"Reliability denotes reproducibility, the consistency of obtaining the same result on repeated measurement under unchanged conditions.<br><br>Validity concerns measuring the true value; reliability is specifically repeatability of results."},
/*88*/ {"q":"Gland having dual supply but no reciprocal supply:","o":["Sweat gland","Sebaceous gland","Salivary gland","Adrenal gland"],"a":2,"e":"Salivary glands receive dual autonomic innervation, sympathetic and parasympathetic, but the two are not reciprocal; both increase secretion with differing composition.<br><br>Sweat and sebaceous glands lack this dual non-reciprocal pattern; the answer is the salivary gland."},
/*89*/ {"q":"Most common cause of physiological hypoxemia:","o":["Decreased V/Q ratio","Hypoventilation","Hyperventilation","High altitude"],"a":1,"e":"Hypoventilation reduces alveolar ventilation and alveolar oxygen tension, lowering arterial oxygen, and is cited here as the commonest physiological hypoxaemia cause.<br><br>Hyperventilation raises oxygenation; the keyed common mechanism is hypoventilation."},
/*90*/ {"q":"Hypoventilation occurs in:","o":["COPD","DKA","Anaemia","Exercise"],"a":0,"e":"Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease impairs alveolar ventilation through airflow limitation and air trapping, producing chronic hypoventilation with CO2 retention.<br><br>DKA and exercise drive hyperventilation; the hypoventilatory disorder here is COPD."},
/*91*/ {"q":"After strenuous exercise exhaustion is due to which subjective feeling?","o":["Low O2","Lactic acid and low pH","Tachycardia","Hypoglycaemia"],"a":1,"e":"Post-exercise muscular fatigue is subjectively driven by lactic acid accumulation and the consequent fall in intramuscular pH, impairing contractile function.<br><br>Oxygen lack is compensated; the perceived exhaustion correlates with lactate-induced acidosis."},
/*92*/ {"q":"Regarding fat embolism, true is:","o":["Occurs after tissue trauma","Occurs after 12hrs","Thrombocytosis","Fatal in 80% cases"],"a":1,"e":"Fat embolism syndrome characteristically manifests around 12 to 72 hours after long-bone trauma, with respiratory distress, petechiae and neurological signs (Ref. Robbins).<br><br>It follows skeletal not soft-tissue trauma primarily; the keyed true point is the delayed onset after about 12 hours."},
/*93*/ {"q":"Pelvic trauma patient, hypovolemia due to:","o":["Hemorrhage","Dehydration","Third spacing","Sepsis"],"a":0,"e":"Pelvic fractures disrupt large venous plexuses and arteries, so hypovolaemia in a pelvic trauma patient is overwhelmingly due to haemorrhage into the retroperitoneum.<br><br>Dehydration and sepsis are not the acute cause; massive concealed bleeding explains the hypovolaemia."},
/*94*/ {"q":"Blockage of superior mesenteric artery at its origin will affect:","o":["Jejunum, ileum, cecum, ascending colon","Duodenojejunal junction, ileum, flexure, cecum, right ascending colon","Duodenojejunal junction till 2/3rd transverse colon","Duodenojejunal junction till 1/3rd transverse colon"],"a":2,"e":"The superior mesenteric artery supplies the gut from the distal duodenum/duodenojejunal junction to about the proximal two-thirds of the transverse colon, the midgut territory.<br><br>The remaining options under- or over-state the extent; the SMA midgut field reaches the proximal two-thirds of transverse colon."},
/*95*/ {"q":"Abdominal aortic aneurysms:","o":["T12-L2","L3-L5","L1-L2","T10-T12"],"a":0,"e":"The abdominal aorta begins at the aortic hiatus around T12 and bifurcates at L4; aneurysms typically arise infrarenally within roughly the T12-L2 to lower lumbar segment quoted here.<br><br>The keyed level for the aneurysm position in this source is the T12-L2 range."},
/*96*/ {"q":"In adults, in sitting position, resonance of percussion on posterior side can be felt till:","o":["T6","T8","T10","T12"],"a":2,"e":"On posterior chest percussion in the sitting adult, resonant lung note extends down to about the level of the tenth thoracic vertebra, where the lung base lies.<br><br>Higher levels underestimate basal extent; posterior resonance reaches roughly T10."},
/*97*/ {"q":"A male is sick from a renal disease that affects males in the family. He has hematuria, vestibular nerve defect, corneal and other eye symptoms. Diagnosis?","o":["IgA nephropathy","IgM nephropathy","Alport's syndrome","Goodpasture syndrome"],"a":2,"e":"X-linked Alport syndrome combines hereditary nephritis with haematuria, sensorineural hearing loss and ocular lesions such as lenticonus, from defective type IV collagen.<br><br>IgA nephropathy lacks the eye and ear signs; the renal-cochlear-ocular triad with familial males is Alport."},
/*98*/ {"q":"Lymphatics from the back of skin till the 10th thoracic vertebrae:","o":["Post mediastinal","Deep inguinal","Super inguinal","Axillary"],"a":3,"e":"Skin of the back above approximately the T10 watershed drains to the axillary lymph nodes, while skin below drains to the superficial inguinal group.<br><br>Mediastinal nodes drain deep structures; the upper back skin lymph keys to the axillary nodes."},
/*99*/ {"q":"Pectoral nodes drain:","o":["Most of the part of breast","Anterior abdominal wall upper portion","Both A and B","Arm only"],"a":2,"e":"The pectoral (anterior axillary) nodes receive lymph from most of the breast and from the upper anterior abdominal wall, so both statements are correct.<br><br>Restricting to one territory ignores the other; the inclusive both-A-and-B option is correct."},
/*100*/ {"q":"Male with hypercalcemia, hyperparathyroidism, gastric ulcers:","o":["MEN1","Primary hyperparathyroidism","Zollinger Ellison Syndrome","MEN2"],"a":0,"e":"The combination of hyperparathyroidism with hypercalcaemia and gastrin-driven peptic ulceration suggests multiple endocrine neoplasia type 1 (parathyroid, pancreatic, pituitary).<br><br>Isolated primary hyperparathyroidism would not include the gastrinoma; the clustered endocrine tumours indicate MEN1."},

/*101*/ {"q":"Regarding pharmacokinetics true is:","o":["Reversal of hydralazine induced tachycardia with propranolol","Reversal of morphine induced CNS depression with naloxone","Increased toxicity of methotrexate with aspirin","Increased peripheral side effects of levodopa with carbidopa"],"a":2,"e":"Aspirin displaces methotrexate from plasma protein binding and reduces its renal clearance, raising free methotrexate levels and toxicity, a classic pharmacokinetic interaction.<br><br>Naloxone and carbidopa effects are pharmacodynamic; the true kinetic interaction here is aspirin increasing methotrexate toxicity."},
/*102*/ {"q":"Neurovascular bundle is present on:","o":["Superior border of rib","Inferior border of rib","Anterior border","Posterior border"],"a":1,"e":"The intercostal neurovascular bundle (vein, artery, nerve from above downward) runs in the costal groove along the inferior border of each rib, so chest drains are placed above the rib below.<br><br>The superior border is relatively safe; the bundle lies at the rib's inferior border."},
/*103*/ {"q":"Arteria pancreatic magna is branch of:","o":["Celiac trunk","Hepatic artery","Gastric artery","Splenic artery"],"a":3,"e":"The arteria pancreatica magna is the largest branch supplying the body and tail of pancreas, arising from the splenic artery as it courses along the superior pancreatic border.<br><br>The hepatic and gastric arteries do not give this branch; it springs from the splenic artery."},
/*104*/ {"q":"Sympathetic supply or lower airways:","o":["T4-T9","T1-T4","T6-T7","T3-T4"],"a":1,"e":"Sympathetic bronchodilator fibres to the lower airways originate from the upper thoracic spinal segments around T1 to T4 via the sympathetic chain.<br><br>Lower thoracic levels supply abdominal viscera; the bronchial sympathetic outflow is the upper thoracic T1-T4."},
/*105*/ {"q":"Type of hypersensitivity in erythroblastosis fetalis:","o":["Type 1","Type 2","Type 3","Type 4"],"a":1,"e":"Erythroblastosis fetalis is a type II antibody-mediated cytotoxic reaction, in which maternal anti-Rh IgG crosses the placenta and lyses fetal Rh-positive red cells.<br><br>Type III is immune-complex and type IV cell-mediated; antibody-directed red cell destruction is type II."},
/*106*/ {"q":"A 50-year-old patient came for routine checkup. Everything was normal except for occult blood in stool. On colonoscopy polyp with a stalk was found histo showed, colonic type tubular glands, stalk covered with normal intestinal epithelium:","o":["Peutz jeghers polyp","Adenomatous polyp","Hyperplastic polyp","Juvenile polyp"],"a":2,"e":"A pedunculated polyp lined by normal colonic epithelium with non-dysplastic tubular glands is a hyperplastic polyp, generally lacking malignant potential.<br><br>Adenomatous polyps show dysplastic glands; the normal-epithelium, non-atypical description fits a hyperplastic polyp."},
/*107*/ {"q":"Dec pressure in carotid sinus will cause:","o":["Reflex bradycardia","Increase heart rate","Hypotension","Vasodilation"],"a":1,"e":"Reduced carotid sinus pressure lowers baroreceptor firing, releasing the medulla from inhibition and producing reflex tachycardia and vasoconstriction to restore blood pressure.<br><br>Increased sinus pressure causes bradycardia; falling pressure conversely raises heart rate."},
/*108*/ {"q":"Memory is the function of which lobe:","o":["Frontal","Parietal","Occipital","Temporal"],"a":3,"e":"The temporal lobe, housing the hippocampus and adjacent medial structures, is central to the formation and consolidation of declarative memory.<br><br>Frontal lobe handles working memory and executive function; long-term memory encoding is the temporal lobe's domain."},
/*109*/ {"q":"A young athlete can't rotate the sole of foot medially, but can rotate it laterally which muscle group is involved?","o":["Peroneus longus and brevis","Tibialis anterior and posterior","Gastrocnemius","Soleus"],"a":1,"e":"Inversion (turning the sole medially) is performed by tibialis anterior and posterior; loss of inversion with preserved eversion implicates this tibialis group.<br><br>The peronei produce eversion, which is intact here; the impaired inversion points to the tibialis muscles."},
/*110*/ {"q":"At wrist joint bone which articulates with radius is:","o":["Lunate","Scaphoid","Capitate","Hamate"],"a":1,"e":"At the radiocarpal joint the radius articulates principally with the scaphoid and to a lesser extent the lunate, with the scaphoid being the dominant articulating bone.<br><br>Capitate and hamate are distal-row carpals; the radius mainly meets the scaphoid (scaphoid greater than lunate)."},
/*111*/ {"q":"Posterior central gyrus is:","o":["Sensory","Motor","Association","Visual"],"a":0,"e":"The postcentral gyrus is the primary somatosensory cortex, receiving the body's tactile, proprioceptive and thermal afferents arranged somatotopically.<br><br>The precentral gyrus is motor; the post-central strip is sensory."},
/*112*/ {"q":"Most common plasma buffer:","o":["Proteins","HCO3/H2CO3","H2PO4","Hemoglobin"],"a":1,"e":"The bicarbonate/carbonic acid system is the principal extracellular plasma buffer, quantitatively dominant and physiologically open because CO2 is exhaled by the lungs.<br><br>Proteins and phosphate buffer chiefly intracellularly; the major plasma buffer is bicarbonate."},
/*113*/ {"q":"A patient has anemia in 3rd trimester. Hb low, MCV low, MCHC low. But TIBC and ferritin normal. what further investigation should be done:","o":["Bone marrow biopsy","Peripheral smear","HbA2","Hb F"],"a":2,"e":"Microcytic hypochromic anaemia with normal iron studies in pregnancy suggests thalassaemia trait rather than iron deficiency; HbA2 quantification confirms beta-thalassaemia minor.<br><br>Normal ferritin and TIBC exclude iron deficiency; the discriminating test is HbA2."},
/*114*/ {"q":"Inferior rectal nerve is branch of:","o":["Internal iliac","Internal pudendal","Obturator","Sciatic"],"a":1,"e":"The inferior rectal nerve arises from the pudendal nerve in the pudendal canal and supplies the external anal sphincter and perianal skin.<br><br>The internal iliac is an arterial trunk; the inferior rectal nerve branches from the pudendal nerve."},
/*115*/ {"q":"Artery damaged at shoulder joint dislocation:","o":["Axillary nerve","Posterior circumflex humeral","Radial artery","Brachial artery"],"a":1,"e":"Anterior shoulder dislocation classically endangers the posterior circumflex humeral artery and the accompanying axillary nerve as they pass through the quadrangular space.<br><br>The radial and brachial arteries lie distally; the vessel at risk at the shoulder is the posterior circumflex humeral."},
/*116*/ {"q":"Neck of fibula injury, nerve damaged will be:","o":["Common peroneal nerve","Posterior tibial","Anterior tibial","Sural"],"a":0,"e":"The common peroneal nerve winds superficially around the fibular neck, making it the nerve most vulnerable to injury there, producing foot drop and lateral leg sensory loss.<br><br>The posterior tibial lies deep in the calf; the fibular-neck injury damages the common peroneal nerve."},
/*117*/ {"q":"Most frequent nonbacterial opportunistic organism recovered from burn tissues:","o":["Aspergillus","Candida","Fusarium","Phycomycetes"],"a":1,"e":"Candida species are the most frequent non-bacterial opportunistic colonisers and invaders of burn wound tissue, exploiting the compromised barrier and immunosuppression.<br><br>Aspergillus and mucorales are less frequent burn isolates; the commonest fungal organism here is Candida."},
/*118*/ {"q":"Head of humerus supplied by:","o":["Arcuate artery","Anterior circumflex","Posterior circumflex","Profunda brachii"],"a":1,"e":"The arcuate (ascending) branch of the anterior circumflex humeral artery is the chief blood supply to the humeral head, so its injury risks avascular necrosis.<br><br>The posterior circumflex supplies the deltoid region; the humeral head depends on the anterior circumflex branch."},
/*119*/ {"q":"Fatal food poisoning is caused by:","o":["Vibrio cholera","Shigella","E. Coli","C. Botulinum"],"a":3,"e":"Clostridium botulinum produces a potent neurotoxin causing descending flaccid paralysis and respiratory failure, the classic fatal food poisoning from improperly preserved food.<br><br>The other organisms cause self-limited gastroenteritis; lethal food poisoning is botulism."},
/*120*/ {"q":"Indirect bilirubin attaches with:","o":["Globulin","Albumin","Pre-Albumin","Haptoglobin"],"a":1,"e":"Unconjugated (indirect) bilirubin is lipid-soluble and transported in plasma tightly bound to albumin until hepatic uptake and conjugation.<br><br>Globulin and haptoglobin are not its carrier; indirect bilirubin travels bound to albumin."},
/*121*/ {"q":"Few months after parturition, the gradual regression of enlarged uterus and breast is caused by:","o":["C-Reactive Proteins","Golgi apparatus","Lysosomes","Mitochondria"],"a":2,"e":"Postpartum involution of the uterus and regression of breast tissue occur largely through lysosomal autophagy, with hydrolytic enzymes degrading surplus cellular components.<br><br>The Golgi and mitochondria do not mediate this; the regressive remodelling is lysosome-driven."},
/*122*/ {"q":"50 years old obese diabetic woman, C/O irregular vaginal bleeding. She had diagnostic uterine curettage. After seeing histopathology report she is advised to undergo hysterectomy. Most likely diagnosis is:","o":["Adenomatous hyperplasia","Atypical hyperplasia","Cystic hyperplasia","Carcinoma of cervix"],"a":1,"e":"In an obese diabetic woman with abnormal uterine bleeding, endometrial atypical hyperplasia carries a high progression risk to carcinoma, justifying hysterectomy.<br><br>Simple cystic or adenomatous hyperplasia rarely mandates hysterectomy; the atypical (complex) hyperplasia drives the surgical decision."},
/*123*/ {"q":"Valval intraepithelial lesion:","o":["Condyloma","Paget's disease","Cervical carcinoma in situ","Lichen sclerosus"],"a":2,"e":"A keyed intraepithelial neoplastic lesion analogous to cervical change is carcinoma in situ, dysplastic cells confined above the basement membrane without invasion (per source).<br><br>Condyloma is benign HPV warty change; the in-situ carcinoma is the keyed intraepithelial lesion."},
/*124*/ {"q":"Chromophilic erythroblast appears on H n E because of:","o":["Ribosomes and Hb","ER and lysosomes","Golgi","Mitochondria"],"a":0,"e":"The polychromatophilic/chromophilic erythroblast stains intermediately because abundant ribosomes (basophilic RNA) coexist with accumulating haemoglobin (eosinophilic), giving mixed tinctorial properties.<br><br>ER and lysosomes do not explain the dual staining; ribosomal RNA plus haemoglobin produces it."},
/*125*/ {"q":"Supporting cells of Pars Nervosa:","o":["Glial cells","Astrocytes","Pituicytes","Schwann cells"],"a":2,"e":"The pars nervosa of the posterior pituitary contains pituicytes, modified glial cells that support the unmyelinated hypothalamic axons storing oxytocin and vasopressin.<br><br>Schwann cells serve peripheral nerves; the neurohypophyseal supporting glia are pituicytes."},
/*126*/ {"q":"Caucasian population having blood group O+:","o":["43%","51%","38%","47%"],"a":3,"e":"O Rhesus-positive is the most prevalent blood group in Caucasian populations, with the keyed frequency cited here at approximately 47 percent.<br><br>The other percentages understate its prevalence; the source records about 47 percent for O+."},
/*127*/ {"q":"Ejaculation is caused by:","o":["Pudendal nerve","Sympathetic","Parasympathetic","Somatic only"],"a":1,"e":"Emission and ejaculation are mediated by sympathetic outflow (L1-L2), which contracts the vas, seminal vesicles and bladder neck, while erection is parasympathetic.<br><br>The pudendal nerve adds the somatic expulsive phase; the keyed cause of ejaculation is sympathetic."},
/*128*/ {"q":"Suprarenal gland:","o":["Lie along the inferior hypogastric plexus","Supplied by thoracic splanchnic nerves","Drain to internal iliac","Cortex from neural crest"],"a":1,"e":"The adrenal (suprarenal) glands receive preganglionic sympathetic innervation from the thoracic splanchnic nerves, which directly stimulate medullary chromaffin cells.<br><br>The hypogastric plexus serves pelvic viscera; adrenal supply is via thoracic splanchnic nerves."},
/*129*/ {"q":"Most common radiation induced CNS tumor:","o":["Leukemia","Meningioma","Glioma","Astrocytoma"],"a":1,"e":"Meningioma is the commonest tumour induced by prior cranial irradiation, arising after a long latency from the meningothelial cells.<br><br>Leukaemia is a common radiation-induced malignancy overall but not a CNS tumour; intracranially, radiation most often induces meningioma."},
/*130*/ {"q":"46XX with ambiguous genitalia:","o":["Klinefelter","Turner","Kallman","CAH"],"a":3,"e":"Congenital adrenal hyperplasia, usually from 21-hydroxylase deficiency, causes virilisation of a 46XX fetus, producing ambiguous genitalia in a genetic female.<br><br>Klinefelter is 47XXY and Turner 45X; the 46XX ambiguous-genitalia picture is CAH."},
/*131*/ {"q":"Content of posterior mediastinum:","o":["Arch of aorta","Ascending aorta","Descending aorta","SVC"],"a":2,"e":"The posterior mediastinum contains the descending thoracic aorta, oesophagus, thoracic duct, azygos system and sympathetic chains.<br><br>The aortic arch and ascending aorta lie in the superior/middle mediastinum; the posterior compartment holds the descending aorta."},
/*132*/ {"q":"Large mass in posterior mediastinum will compress:","o":["Trachea","Descending Thoracic aorta","Arch of aorta","SVC"],"a":1,"e":"A posterior mediastinal mass lies adjacent to and will compress the descending thoracic aorta and oesophagus, the structures of that compartment.<br><br>Trachea and SVC are anterior/superior; a posterior mass impinges the descending aorta."},
/*133*/ {"q":"Osteoporosis most common cause other than old age:","o":["Menopause","PTH","Cushing's syndrome","Hyperthyroidism"],"a":0,"e":"After ageing, oestrogen-deficiency at menopause is the leading cause of osteoporosis, accelerating bone resorption through increased osteoclast activity.<br><br>Cushing's and hyperparathyroidism are secondary causes; the commonest non-age aetiology is menopause."},
/*134*/ {"q":"Graves' disease effect on eyes:","o":["Usually bilateral","Optic nerve compression","Unilateral always","No eye effect"],"a":0,"e":"Graves ophthalmopathy typically produces bilateral, though sometimes asymmetric, proptosis and lid retraction from autoimmune retro-orbital inflammation.<br><br>Optic nerve compression is a late complication; the usual eye effect is bilateral involvement."},
/*135*/ {"q":"Vein anterior to SCM:","o":["Internal jugular vein","External jugular vein","Anterior jugular vein","Subclavian vein"],"a":1,"e":"The external jugular vein descends superficially crossing anterior to the sternocleidomastoid before piercing the deep fascia to drain into the subclavian vein.<br><br>The internal jugular runs deep to the muscle; the vein lying superficial and anterior to SCM is the external jugular."},
/*136*/ {"q":"Somatostatin released from brain inhibits:","o":["Cortisol","Glucagon","Insulin","GH"],"a":3,"e":"Hypothalamic somatostatin is the principal physiological inhibitor of growth hormone release from the anterior pituitary, opposing GHRH.<br><br>It also dampens insulin/glucagon in the pancreas, but the brain-released action here inhibits GH."},
/*137*/ {"q":"In a woman of years age, suspected premalignant lesion of cervix. Which of the following investigation will be easier and cheaper and reliable for diagnosis of carcinoma?","o":["Colposcopy","FNAC","Imprint of cervical biopsy","Pap smear"],"a":3,"e":"The Papanicolaou (Pap) smear is the cheap, easy and reliable screening test that detects premalignant cervical dysplasia by exfoliative cytology.<br><br>Colposcopy and biopsy are confirmatory and costlier; the first-line screening tool is the Pap smear."},
/*138*/ {"q":"Insulin increases the entry of glucose into:","o":["Hepatic cells","Neurons in cerebral cortex","Renal tubular cells","Skeletal muscles"],"a":3,"e":"Insulin recruits GLUT4 transporters in skeletal muscle and adipose tissue, markedly increasing glucose uptake there; brain and liver uptake are insulin-independent.<br><br>Neurons and hepatocytes use insulin-independent transport; the insulin-sensitive tissue here is skeletal muscle."},
/*139*/ {"q":"Brachiocephalic trunk is formed by:","o":["Internal jugular vein + Subclavian vein","Aorta branch","External jugular + subclavian","Vertebral + jugular"],"a":0,"e":"The brachiocephalic (innominate) vein is formed by the union of the internal jugular and subclavian veins behind the sternoclavicular joint.<br><br>The arterial brachiocephalic trunk arises from the arch; the venous one is IJV plus subclavian, the keyed answer."},
/*140*/ {"q":"2 bronchopulmonary segments present in:","o":["Right lower lobe","Right apical lobe","Left superior lobe","Right middle lobe"],"a":3,"e":"The right middle lobe contains exactly two bronchopulmonary segments, the medial and lateral, the fewest of the lobes.<br><br>Lower and upper lobes have more segments; the two-segment lobe is the right middle lobe."},
/*141*/ {"q":"Hemorrhage in internal capsule and anterior basal ganglia. Which artery is ruptured?","o":["Anterior choroidal","Middle cerebral artery anterior branch","Posterior communicating","Recurrent artery of Heubner"],"a":1,"e":"Haemorrhage into the internal capsule and basal ganglia classically arises from rupture of the lenticulostriate branches of the middle cerebral artery's anterior portion, the charcot artery of cerebral haemorrhage.<br><br>The anterior choroidal supplies a smaller field; the keyed ruptured vessel is the MCA anterior branch (lenticulostriate)."},
/*142*/ {"q":"Maximum vessels are present in:","o":["Epidural space","Subdural space","Subarachnoid space","Subpial space"],"a":2,"e":"The subarachnoid space, traversed by cerebral arteries and veins bathed in CSF, contains the maximum number of vessels of the meningeal compartments.<br><br>The epidural space has the venous plexus but fewer vessels overall; the most vascular is the subarachnoid space."},
/*143*/ {"q":"Which part of meningeal artery is more prone to rupture?","o":["Middle","Posterior","Anterior","Distal"],"a":2,"e":"The anterior branch of the middle meningeal artery, lying beneath the thin pterion, is most prone to rupture in lateral skull trauma, causing extradural haematoma.<br><br>The posterior branch is better protected; the vulnerable segment is the anterior division."},
/*144*/ {"q":"Parotid glands duct open in:","o":["2nd molar","Incisors","3rd molar","Canine"],"a":0,"e":"The parotid (Stensen's) duct opens into the oral vestibule opposite the crown of the upper second molar tooth.<br><br>Incisor and canine levels are too anterior; the duct orifice lies opposite the second upper molar."},
/*145*/ {"q":"Most common anomaly in a child of congenital infected mother in 4th week pregnancy:","o":["Anemia","Deafness","Cataract","PDA"],"a":2,"e":"Congenital rubella acquired early in the first trimester most characteristically causes cataract, along with cardiac defects and deafness; cataract is the keyed commonest anomaly.<br><br>Deafness predominates in slightly later infection; in the fourth week the keyed leading defect is cataract."},
/*146*/ {"q":"Most likely cause of negative montoux test in a patient with active TB?","o":["Miliary TB","ATT","Immunosuppression","Early TB"],"a":0,"e":"Miliary (disseminated) tuberculosis can cause anergy with a falsely negative tuberculin test due to overwhelming antigen load suppressing the cell-mediated response.<br><br>Early TB simply predates conversion; in active disease a negative Mantoux most classically reflects miliary anergy."},
/*147*/ {"q":"Patient underwent radiotherapy and few days later presented with skin ulceration and fibrosis, cause is?","o":["Endarteritis obliterans","Venous thrombosis","Infection","Anemia"],"a":0,"e":"Radiation injures small vessel endothelium causing obliterative endarteritis, leading to ischaemic skin ulceration, fibrosis and impaired wound healing.<br><br>Venous thrombosis is not the mechanism; the vascular basis of radiation skin damage is endarteritis obliterans."},
/*148*/ {"q":"A urologist doing transurethral surgery. Two arteries at 5 and 7 O'clock position came in his way. What is the exact name of these arteries?","o":["Superior vesicular artery","Falloch's artery","Inferior vesicle","Badenoch's artery"],"a":3,"e":"During transurethral prostatic resection the prostatic arteries entering at the classic 5 and 7 o'clock positions are termed Badenoch's arteries, requiring careful haemostasis.<br><br>The superior vesical supplies the bladder dome; the named TURP bleeders are Badenoch's arteries."},
/*149*/ {"q":"A little has hydronephrosis and hydroureter. Micturating cystourethrogram shows grade 3 reflux, which is defined as:","o":["Mild dilatation of calyces with fornix blunting","Severe dilation of calyces with blunting","No dilatation","Tortuous ureter only"],"a":0,"e":"Grade III vesicoureteric reflux denotes mild to moderate dilatation of the ureter and pelvicalyceal system with slight blunting of the calyceal fornices, without gross tortuosity.<br><br>Severe dilatation defines higher grades; grade III is mild calyceal dilatation with fornix blunting."},
/*150*/ {"q":"Patient alcoholic, Histological Findings?","o":["Councilman bodies","Mallory bodies","Ground glass hepatocytes","Fatty change only"],"a":1,"e":"Alcoholic hepatitis classically shows Mallory-Denk bodies, eosinophilic intracytoplasmic aggregates of damaged intermediate filaments within ballooned hepatocytes.<br><br>Councilman bodies typify viral hepatitis apoptosis; the alcoholic hallmark is Mallory bodies."},

/*151*/ {"q":"Patient underwent radiotherapy and few days later presented with skin ulceration and fibrosis, cause is?","o":["Endarteritis obliterans","Venous thrombosis","Infection","Desquamation"],"a":0,"e":"Ionising radiation damages small-vessel endothelium producing obliterative endarteritis, the basis of delayed ischaemic skin ulceration and dermal fibrosis after radiotherapy.<br><br>Acute desquamation is an early reaction; the late ulceration-fibrosis mechanism is endarteritis obliterans."},
/*152*/ {"q":"Following is prone to ischemic necrosis:","o":["Cardiac cell","Neuron","Liver","Skeletal muscle"],"a":2,"e":"Hepatocytes, particularly in the centrilobular zone, are highly susceptible to ischaemic (coagulative) necrosis owing to their position farthest from the oxygen supply.<br><br>Neurons undergo liquefactive change; among these, the liver is keyed as prone to ischaemic necrosis."},
/*153*/ {"q":"Most common complication of diabetes:","o":["Endarteritis obliterans","Wet gangrene","Dry gangrene","Microaneurysm"],"a":2,"e":"In diabetics, peripheral arterial occlusive disease leads commonly to dry gangrene of the extremities from chronic ischaemia of the small and medium arteries.<br><br>Wet gangrene supervenes with infection; the keyed common complication is dry gangrene."},
/*154*/ {"q":"A patient has BP increased and abdominal symptoms like pain etc, but his serum is negative for ANCA and negative for ANA. Serum creatinine 5.6. On electron microscopy medium sized renal artery and mesangial artery is involved and shows aneurysm? What is the pathology?","o":["Microangiopathic obliterans","Polyarteritis nodosa","Wegener's granulomatosis","Takayasu arteritis"],"a":1,"e":"Hypertension, abdominal pain, renal impairment and medium-vessel microaneurysms with negative ANCA and ANA characterise classic polyarteritis nodosa, a necrotising medium-vessel vasculitis.<br><br>Wegener's is ANCA-positive with granulomas; the medium-vessel aneurysms with negative serology indicate PAN."},
/*155*/ {"q":"Factor involved in one carbon transfer:","o":["Biotin","Folic acid/Folate","Thiamine","Niacin"],"a":1,"e":"Tetrahydrofolate is the principal carrier of single-carbon units in reactions such as purine, thymidylate and methionine synthesis.<br><br>Biotin carries CO2 (carboxylation); the dedicated one-carbon transfer cofactor is folate."},
/*156*/ {"q":"Structure that may be compressed by abscess in adductor canal:","o":["Profunda femoris artery","Profunda femoris vein","Femoral vein","Femoral artery"],"a":3,"e":"The adductor (subsartorial) canal transmits the femoral artery, femoral vein and saphenous nerve; an abscess there can compress the femoral artery within the canal.<br><br>The profunda vessels lie outside the canal; the structure compressed is the femoral artery."},
/*157*/ {"q":"Poor lady while carving flower in her cloth got pricked with needle, develops signs of inflammation with interphalgeal joint pain, if left untreated what will happen?","o":["Necrosis","Paronychia","Felon","Septic arthritis"],"a":2,"e":"A penetrating fingertip prick can seed the closed pulp space, producing a felon, a tense painful infection of the distal pulp that may progress to osteomyelitis if untreated.<br><br>Paronychia involves the nail fold only; the pulp-space infection from the prick is a felon."},
/*158*/ {"q":"Patent lumen of allantois results in:","o":["Urachal cyst","Urachal sinus","Urachal fistula","Vesicoureteric reflux"],"a":2,"e":"Complete persistence of the allantoic (urachal) lumen between bladder and umbilicus produces a urachal fistula, with urine discharge at the umbilicus.<br><br>A cyst forms with both ends closed; a fully patent lumen yields a urachal fistula."},
/*159*/ {"q":"Internal carotid artery blocked, blood passing in reverse direction thru artery that is supply of the scalp. What is that artery:","o":["Superficial temporal","Deep temporal","Supra orbital","Occipital"],"a":2,"e":"With internal carotid occlusion, collateral flow can reverse through the supraorbital and supratrochlear branches of the ophthalmic artery to perfuse the scalp from the external carotid.<br><br>The superficial temporal is purely external carotid; the reversed scalp collateral here is the supraorbital artery."},
/*160*/ {"q":"Accessory cervical rib arises from:","o":["C6","C5","T1","C7"],"a":3,"e":"A cervical rib characteristically arises from the seventh cervical vertebra, potentially compressing the lower brachial plexus trunk and subclavian vessels (thoracic outlet syndrome).<br><br>C5-C6 do not bear ribs; the accessory cervical rib springs from C7."},
/*161*/ {"q":"Recent thrombus/clot has:","o":["Fibrin","Fibroblasts","Platelets","Plasminogen"],"a":0,"e":"A recent (fresh) thrombus is composed principally of fibrin meshwork enmeshing trapped red cells and platelets, before organisation by fibroblasts occurs.<br><br>Fibroblast ingrowth marks an older organising clot; the recent thrombus is predominantly fibrin."},
/*162*/ {"q":"Which of the following is a carcinogen?","o":["Silica dust","Asbestos","Aluminium","Iron"],"a":1,"e":"Asbestos is an established human carcinogen, causally linked to bronchogenic carcinoma and malignant mesothelioma after a long latency.<br><br>Silica causes fibrosis (silicosis) but is a weaker carcinogen; the keyed carcinogen is asbestos."},
/*163*/ {"q":"Neurovascular bundle of ribs from Cephalon to caudal:","o":["Vein, Artery, Nerve","Nerve, Artery, Vein","Vein, Nerve, Artery","Artery, Vein, Nerve"],"a":0,"e":"In the costal groove the intercostal neurovascular bundle is arranged from superior to inferior as Vein, Artery, Nerve (the VAN mnemonic).<br><br>Reversing the order misplaces the nerve; the top-to-bottom sequence is Vein, Artery, Nerve."},
/*164*/ {"q":"Epithelium that is resistant to effects of friction:","o":["Non keratinized epi","Keratinized epi","Simple columnar","Transitional"],"a":1,"e":"Keratinised stratified squamous epithelium, with its tough surface keratin layer, is best adapted to resist mechanical friction and abrasion, as in skin.<br><br>Non-keratinised epithelium lines moist surfaces; friction resistance belongs to the keratinised type."},
/*165*/ {"q":"A patient has anemia in 3rd trimester. Hb low, MCV low, MCHC low. But TIBC and ferritin normal. what further investigation should be done:","o":["Bone marrow biopsy","Peripheral smear","HbA2","HbF"],"a":2,"e":"Microcytic hypochromic anaemia with normal iron parameters in pregnancy suggests thalassaemia trait; HbA2 estimation confirms beta-thalassaemia minor.<br><br>Normal ferritin excludes iron deficiency; the confirmatory test is HbA2."},
/*166*/ {"q":"Inferior rectal artery is branch of:","o":["Internal iliac","Internal pudendal","Obturator","Inferior gluteal"],"a":1,"e":"The inferior rectal artery arises from the internal pudendal artery within the pudendal canal and supplies the anal canal below the dentate line.<br><br>The internal iliac is the parent trunk further proximal; the immediate origin is the internal pudendal."},
/*167*/ {"q":"Which one is an end artery?","o":["Central retinal artery","Renal artery","Splenic artery","Hepatic artery"],"a":0,"e":"The central retinal artery is a true (functional) end artery without anastomoses, so its occlusion causes sudden, complete and irreversible retinal infarction.<br><br>Renal and splenic arteries have some collateral capacity; the prototypical end artery here is the central retinal."},
/*168*/ {"q":"How much blood is drained by coronary sinus?","o":["1/3rd","2/3rd","1/2","All"],"a":1,"e":"The coronary sinus collects roughly two-thirds of the venous return from the myocardium, the remainder draining via anterior cardiac and Thebesian veins.<br><br>The smaller fraction goes by other routes; the coronary sinus handles about two-thirds."},
/*169*/ {"q":"Cross bridges in skeletal muscle are formed by:","o":["Actin","Myosin","Troponin","Tropomyosin"],"a":1,"e":"The cross-bridges projecting from the thick filaments are the globular heads of myosin, which bind actin and pull it during the contractile cycle.<br><br>Troponin and tropomyosin regulate access but do not form bridges; the cross-bridge is myosin."},
/*170*/ {"q":"Electrical impulse travels in Cardiac muscles via:","o":["Gap Junction","E cadherin","Intercalated disc","Desmosome"],"a":0,"e":"Cardiac action potentials spread cell-to-cell through gap junctions (connexons) located within the intercalated discs, enabling functional syncytial conduction.<br><br>The intercalated disc is the structure housing them, but the impulse conduit itself is the gap junction."},
/*171*/ {"q":"Tumor progression factor:","o":["Basement breach","Down regulation of e-cadherin","Increased apoptosis","Decreased mitosis"],"a":1,"e":"Loss or down-regulation of E-cadherin weakens intercellular adhesion, promoting tumour cell detachment, invasion and metastasis, a key driver of progression.<br><br>Increased apoptosis would retard tumours; the progression factor is reduced E-cadherin."},
/*172*/ {"q":"Receptors for growth are at:","o":["Nucleus","Mitochondria","RER","Cell membrane"],"a":3,"e":"Receptors for growth factors are transmembrane proteins located in the cell membrane, transducing extracellular signals via intracellular tyrosine kinase cascades.<br><br>Steroid receptors are nuclear; peptide growth factor receptors sit on the cell membrane."},
/*173*/ {"q":"Blood supply of apex of heart:","o":["LCX","Post. Interventricular","Diagonal","RCA"],"a":3,"e":"The apex of the heart is typically supplied by the anterior interventricular (LAD) wrapping around it, but per this source key the recorded answer is the RCA territory (per source key).<br><br>The marginal branch is small; following the keyed answer the option marked is the RCA."},
/*174*/ {"q":"Main support of pelvic viscera is?","o":["Levator ani","Uterosacral ligament","Suspensory ligament","Pelvic diaphragm"],"a":3,"e":"The pelvic diaphragm, formed mainly by levator ani with coccygeus, provides the principal muscular support for the pelvic viscera.<br><br>Levator ani is its chief component, but the keyed comprehensive support is the pelvic diaphragm as a whole."},
/*175*/ {"q":"A 20-year male with dyspnea on lying down, the anatomical structure likely to cause this dyspnea is:","o":["Enlarged thyroid isthmus","Multinodular goiter","Puberty induced goiter","Retrosternal goiter"],"a":3,"e":"A retrosternal goitre extending into the thoracic inlet compresses the trachea, producing positional dyspnoea worse on lying down (Pemberton sign).<br><br>An isthmic enlargement rarely causes this; the substernal extension is the offending structure."},
/*176*/ {"q":"Arterial supply of spinal cord is:","o":["Vertebral artery","Anterior choroidal artery","Posterior choroidal artery","Occipital artery"],"a":0,"e":"The spinal cord is supplied by the anterior and posterior spinal arteries, which arise from the vertebral arteries, reinforced by radicular and the artery of Adamkiewicz.<br><br>Choroidal arteries supply the choroid plexus; the cord's parent supply is the vertebral artery."},
/*177*/ {"q":"A lady after surgery with acute blood loss. Type of anemia will be?","o":["Microcytic hypochromic","Microcytic normochromic","Normocytic normochromic","Macrocytic hypochromic"],"a":2,"e":"Acute haemorrhage causes a normocytic normochromic anaemia initially, since whole blood is lost and red cell indices remain normal until later iron-deficient compensation.<br><br>Microcytosis develops only with chronic loss; acute bleed gives normocytic normochromic anaemia."},
/*178*/ {"q":"A chronic alcoholic suffering from liver cirrhosis developed portal hypertension with caput medusa. In this condition, the veins around the umbilicus are connected to the left branch of portal vein through:","o":["Paraumbilical veins","Lumbar veins","Hepatic veins","Splenic vein"],"a":0,"e":"Caput medusae forms via dilated paraumbilical veins connecting the left branch of the portal vein to the systemic periumbilical veins, a portosystemic anastomosis.<br><br>Lumbar veins relate to retroperitoneal anastomoses; the umbilical connection is the paraumbilical veins."},
/*179*/ {"q":"In supine position foreign body most commonly lodge in:","o":["Posterior segment of rt upper lobe","Superior segment of rt lower lobe","Right middle lobe","Left lower lobe"],"a":1,"e":"In the supine patient an aspirated foreign body tends to lodge in the superior segment of the right lower lobe, the most dependent bronchopulmonary segment in that posture.<br><br>The posterior upper-lobe segment is dependent when sitting; supine it is the right lower lobe superior segment."},
/*180*/ {"q":"A team of cardiologists investigating the relationship between myocardial infarction in 1200 men aged between 50-75 years and activity level 24 hours preceding the attack. Activity level was classified as heavy exertion 50%, moderate exertion 35% and light exertion 15%. Which graph is appropriate to display this data?","o":["Bar diagram","Frequency polygon with percentage frequency on y-axis","Frequency polygon with raw frequency on y-axis","Histogram"],"a":0,"e":"Categorical activity-level data (heavy, moderate, light) are best displayed by a bar diagram, which compares discrete qualitative categories.<br><br>Frequency polygons and histograms suit continuous data; for these discrete categories a bar diagram is appropriate."},
/*181*/ {"q":"A chronic renal failure patient presented in emergency with shortness of breath. On examination he had no edema or dyspnea what is the cause?","o":["Diabetic ketoacidosis","Metabolic acidosis","Diuretics","Anemia"],"a":1,"e":"In chronic renal failure, retained acids cause metabolic acidosis driving compensatory Kussmaul hyperventilation, explaining breathlessness without oedema or true dyspnoea.<br><br>Without fluid overload, the breathlessness reflects acidotic respiratory compensation, i.e. metabolic acidosis."},
/*182*/ {"q":"10th intercostal nerve enters rectus abdominis muscle at level of:","o":["Xiphoid","Umbilicus","Suprapubic","Subcostal"],"a":1,"e":"The tenth thoracic (intercostal) nerve supplies the dermatome and rectus segment at the level of the umbilicus, the classic T10 landmark.<br><br>Xiphoid corresponds to T6 and suprapubic to L1; T10 enters at the umbilical level."},
/*183*/ {"q":"A 25-year-old girl presented with secondary Amenorrhea of 1-year duration. Physical examination and ultrasound scan of pelvis did not reveal any abnormality. The LH 40iu/L and FSH 42IU/L levels were high. The diagnosis of premature ovarian failure was established. The common cause of this condition is:","o":["Autoimmune disease","Chemotherapy","Chromosomal abnormality","Ovarian tumors"],"a":0,"e":"Premature ovarian failure with hypergonadotropic amenorrhoea in a young woman, with normal pelvis, is most commonly autoimmune in origin (autoimmune oophoritis).<br><br>Chemotherapy and chromosomal causes occur but are not commonest here; the keyed cause is autoimmune disease."},
/*184*/ {"q":"Child with SOB relieved on holding him up, and there are coils of intestine in chest on X-ray cause is:","o":["Patent pleuro peritoneal canal","Hiatal hernia","Diaphragm event ration","Eventration"],"a":0,"e":"Congenital diaphragmatic hernia from a persistently patent pleuroperitoneal canal allows bowel into the chest, causing respiratory distress relieved by upright posture.<br><br>Hiatal hernia involves the stomach through the oesophageal hiatus; the bowel-in-chest defect is the patent pleuroperitoneal canal."},
/*185*/ {"q":"Male presented with head injury, presented with decrease thirst cause of decrease thirst is?","o":["Stimulation of lateral hypothalamus","ADH (SIADH)","Osmoreceptor damage","Pituitary damage"],"a":1,"e":"Per this source key, suppressed thirst after head injury is attributed to inappropriate ADH (SIADH) with resultant dilutional state reducing the osmotic thirst drive (per source).<br><br>Lateral hypothalamic destruction abolishes thirst too, but the keyed answer here is SIADH-related ADH."},
/*186*/ {"q":"What is the most important role of bradykinin in acute inflammation?","o":["Increase in vascular permeability","Vasodilation","Mediation of pain","Bronchoconstriction"],"a":2,"e":"In acute inflammation bradykinin's most distinctive role is mediation of pain by stimulating nociceptors, alongside vasodilatation and increased permeability.<br><br>Vasodilatation and permeability are shared by many mediators; the kinin's signature contribution is pain."},
/*187*/ {"q":"Cimetidine given preoperatively:","o":["Competitive inhibitors of H2 blockers","Decrease gastric acidity","Decrease stomach metabolism","Increase motility"],"a":1,"e":"Cimetidine is a competitive H2-receptor antagonist that reduces gastric acid secretion, given preoperatively to lower the risk of acid aspiration pneumonitis.<br><br>It is itself the H2 blocker, not an inhibitor of one; its action is decreased gastric acidity."},
/*188*/ {"q":"Stratified squamous epithelium is found in?","o":["Colon","Pharynx","Ovary","Stomach"],"a":1,"e":"The oropharynx is lined by protective non-keratinised stratified squamous epithelium suited to the friction of swallowing.<br><br>Colon and stomach have simple columnar lining; stratified squamous is found in the pharynx."},
/*189*/ {"q":"A woman had RTA in which clavicle depressed posteriorly, which structure will be damaged at sternal end of clavicle?","o":["Aorta","SVC","Esophagus","Trachea"],"a":3,"e":"Posterior displacement of the medial (sternal) clavicular end can compress or injure the trachea lying immediately behind it, threatening the airway.<br><br>The aorta and SVC are more lateral/inferior; the structure directly behind the sternal clavicle is the trachea."},
/*190*/ {"q":"Man 60-year-old history of hypertension. Difficulty since two days in coming down stairs and is having diplopia he is having:","o":["Abducens nerve palsy","6th nerve palsy","Oculomotor nerve palsy","Trochlear nerve palsy"],"a":3,"e":"Difficulty descending stairs with vertical diplopia indicates superior oblique weakness from trochlear (CN IV) palsy; the explanation notes trochlear was not listed so oculomotor is next best, but the keyed disorder is the fourth nerve.<br><br>Sixth nerve palsy gives horizontal diplopia; the stairs-and-vertical-diplopia pattern is trochlear (per source explanation)."},
/*191*/ {"q":"Strong correlation with colorectal cancer is seen in:","o":["Peutz-Jeghers polyp","Familial polyposis coli","Juvenile polyposis","Hyperplastic polyp"],"a":1,"e":"Familial adenomatous polyposis (familial polyposis coli) carries near-certain progression to colorectal carcinoma if the colon is not removed, the strongest hereditary association.<br><br>Peutz-Jeghers and hyperplastic polyps have low malignant risk; the strong link is familial polyposis coli."},
/*192*/ {"q":"Most common feature of carpel tunnel syndrome:","o":["Wasting of thenar muscles","pain numbness and tingling in lateral aspect of hand","Loss of skin sensation of medial aspect of hand","Wrist drop"],"a":1,"e":"Carpal tunnel syndrome from median nerve compression presents earliest and most commonly with pain, numbness and tingling over the lateral (radial) palmar hand and fingers.<br><br>Thenar wasting is a late sign; the commonest feature is the lateral-hand paraesthesia (Reference: RJ last)."},
/*193*/ {"q":"For pericardial effusion pericardiocentesis should be done from:","o":["Left of sternum 5th and 6th intercostal space","Between 4th and 2nd ICS in midaxillary line","Between 4th and 5th ICS in mid axillary line","Between 4th and 5th ICS in midclavicular line"],"a":0,"e":"Pericardiocentesis is classically performed via the left parasternal route at the fifth to sixth intercostal space (or subxiphoid), avoiding the internal thoracic vessels.<br><br>Mid-axillary approaches risk the lung; the keyed safe site is left of sternum at the 5th-6th ICS."},
/*194*/ {"q":"Which of the following cellular process is most likely to occur in the myocardium of a patient with myocardial infarction who is being treated with fibrinolytic agents?","o":["Apoptosis","Free Radical Injury","Fatty Changes","Accumulation of Lipofuscin"],"a":1,"e":"Reperfusion of ischaemic myocardium after fibrinolysis generates a burst of reactive oxygen species, causing free-radical (reperfusion) injury to cardiomyocytes.<br><br>Lipofuscin accumulation is age-related; the thrombolysis-related event is free radical reperfusion injury."},
/*195*/ {"q":"In tension pneumothorax trachia is:","o":["Deviated to normal side","Deviated to affected side","Not deviated","Deviated upward"],"a":0,"e":"Tension pneumothorax raises ipsilateral intrapleural pressure, shifting the mediastinum and trachea away from the affected side toward the normal lung.<br><br>Collapse/fibrosis pulls the trachea toward the lesion; tension pushes it to the normal side."},
/*196*/ {"q":"Phrenic nerve avulsion near origin. What will happen?","o":["Dec expiration","Loss of respiratory stimulus","Loss of sensation in central part of diaphragm","Paralysis of hemidiaphragm"],"a":3,"e":"The phrenic nerve is the sole motor supply to the diaphragm, so avulsion paralyses the corresponding hemidiaphragm, which becomes elevated and paradoxical.<br><br>Loss of central diaphragmatic sensation also occurs, but the principal effect keyed is hemidiaphragm paralysis."},
/*197*/ {"q":"Median umbilical ligament is a remnant of:","o":["Urachus","Umbilical artery","Umbilical vein","Vitelline duct"],"a":0,"e":"The median umbilical ligament is the fibrous remnant of the obliterated urachus (allantois), running from bladder apex to umbilicus.<br><br>The medial umbilical ligaments are the obliterated umbilical arteries; the single midline one is the urachus."},
/*198*/ {"q":"A chronic smoker from 30 years working in a tyre factory presented with painless:","o":["Hematuria n on histopathology transitional cell carcinoma of bladder causative agent is: Aromatic amines","Tobacco smoking","Nitrites/nitrates","Shistosomia hematobium"],"a":0,"e":"Occupational aromatic amine exposure (rubber/tyre industry) plus heavy smoking causes painless haematuria from transitional cell carcinoma of the bladder.<br><br>Schistosomiasis links to squamous bladder cancer; the keyed agent for transitional cell carcinoma here is aromatic amines."},
/*199*/ {"q":"How many bronchopulmonary segments are in lower, middle and upper lobe of right lung respectively?","o":["3, 2, 5","5, 2, 3","5, 3, 2","2, 5, 3"],"a":1,"e":"The right lung has roughly 5 segments in the lower lobe, 2 in the middle lobe and 3 in the upper lobe, giving the order 5, 2, 3.<br><br>Other orderings misplace the two-segment middle lobe; the correct sequence is 5, 2, 3."},
/*200*/ {"q":"In a newborn:","o":["Thymus is very small","Thoracic circumference is circular","Ribs are ventricle","Lower limb is well developed"],"a":1,"e":"In the newborn the thoracic cage is relatively circular (barrel-shaped) with horizontally set ribs, unlike the elliptical adult thorax.<br><br>The neonatal thymus is in fact large; the keyed true feature is the circular thoracic circumference."},

/*201*/ {"q":"Pt is suffering from terminal stage of ovarian Ca, and will not survive, she asks u to keep it secret and confidential few weeks later her son and daughter visits and ask u regarding their mother's health, what will u do?","o":["Give some info to the family","Tell nothing to the family","Refer to another doctor","Refuse to meet them"],"a":1,"e":"Respecting a competent patient's explicit request for confidentiality, the physician must not disclose her diagnosis to family members without her consent, upholding autonomy and confidentiality.<br><br>Sharing information would breach the promise; the ethically correct action is to tell the family nothing."},
/*202*/ {"q":"Spinal cord damage due to fracture of vertebra, process of vertebrae inserted into spinal cord patient has acute difficulty in breathing the fracture part is from?","o":["Atlas","Axis","3rd Cervical","6th Cervical"],"a":1,"e":"High cervical injury at the level of the axis (C2) can damage the cord above the phrenic outflow (C3-C5), producing acute respiratory difficulty from diaphragmatic compromise.<br><br>Lower cervical levels spare the phrenic origin partly; the keyed breathing-critical fracture is the axis (C2)."},
/*203*/ {"q":"Submandibular gland is located in:","o":["the submandibular triangle, which is formed by Inferior edge of the mandible and by the anterior and posterior bellies of the digastric muscles","Carotid triangle","Muscular triangle","Occipital triangle"],"a":0,"e":"The submandibular gland occupies the digastric (submandibular) triangle, bounded by the mandibular base and the anterior and posterior bellies of digastric.<br><br>The carotid triangle lies below this; the gland sits in the submandibular triangle so defined."},
/*204*/ {"q":"Cyanotic spells are observed in a 10years old boy after playing crying and climbing stairs. What is the reason?","o":["ASD","VSD","PDA","TOF"],"a":3,"e":"Hypercyanotic (tet) spells precipitated by exertion or crying are characteristic of Tetralogy of Fallot, due to increased right-to-left shunting across the VSD.<br><br>Isolated ASD/VSD are acyanotic left-to-right shunts; exertional cyanotic spells indicate TOF."},
/*205*/ {"q":"Enzyme:","o":["Decrease activation of energy of reactants","Increase pH","Increase temperature","Increase activation energy"],"a":0,"e":"Enzymes accelerate reactions by lowering the activation energy of the reaction, providing an alternative pathway without altering the equilibrium.<br><br>They do not change temperature or pH; the defining catalytic action is reducing activation energy."},
/*206*/ {"q":"Testosterone lowest in:","o":["Fetus","Infancy","Preschool","Old age"],"a":2,"e":"Per this source key, testosterone is lowest in the prepubertal preschool child, when gonadotropin drive and Leydig cell activity are minimal before the pubertal rise.<br><br>Fetal testosterone is transiently high for genital development; the keyed nadir is the prepubertal preschool period."},
/*207*/ {"q":"Dorsal column system shows the following specific characteristic of:","o":["Fast pain transmission","Slow conduction of crude touch","Transmission of sexual sensation","Two-point discrimination"],"a":3,"e":"The dorsal column-medial lemniscus system carries fine touch, vibration and proprioception, supporting two-point discrimination with rapid, faithful conduction.<br><br>Pain and crude touch travel the spinothalamic tract; the dorsal column hallmark is two-point discrimination."},
/*208*/ {"q":"A patient has lost 2 liters water by sweating and replaced by 2 liters pure water. What will happen?","o":["Decrease intracellular volume","Decreased intracellular osmolality and increase intracellular fluid volume","Increased extracellular osmolality","Increased ECF volume"],"a":1,"e":"Sweat is hypotonic; replacing the loss with pure water dilutes body fluids, lowering osmolality and shifting water into cells, increasing intracellular volume.<br><br>Extracellular osmolality falls, not rises; the net effect is decreased intracellular osmolality with cell swelling."},
/*209*/ {"q":"Micturition reflex can be voluntarily inhibited by:","o":["Inc pressure on trigone","Through pudendal nerve","Through sacral plexus","Through sympathetic"],"a":1,"e":"Voluntary continence is maintained by somatic control of the external urethral sphincter via the pudendal nerve, allowing conscious inhibition of micturition.<br><br>The trigone and sacral parasympathetics drive voiding; voluntary hold-back works through the pudendal nerve."},
/*210*/ {"q":"Sympathetic nervous system originates:","o":["T1-L2","T11-T12","T8-T12","T6-L1"],"a":0,"e":"The sympathetic (thoracolumbar) outflow arises from the lateral horn of spinal segments T1 to L2.<br><br>The narrower ranges are incomplete; the full sympathetic origin is T1-L2."},
/*211*/ {"q":"What is the relation of terminal CBD with head of pancreas?","o":["Anterior","Posterior","Medial","Embedded in it"],"a":3,"e":"The terminal common bile duct runs through a groove or is embedded within the posterior part of the pancreatic head before entering the duodenum at the ampulla.<br><br>It is not freely anterior; the terminal CBD is embedded in the head of pancreas."},
/*212*/ {"q":"Sub arachnoid space ends at:","o":["T12","L2-L3","L1-L2","S2-S3"],"a":3,"e":"The subarachnoid (dural) sac terminates at the S2 vertebral level, well below the conus at L1-L2, making low lumbar puncture safe.<br><br>L1-L2 marks the spinal cord end; the thecal sac itself ends at S2-S3."},
/*213*/ {"q":"Wrist drop caused by damage to:","o":["Ulnar nerve","Radial nerve","Median nerve","Axillary nerve"],"a":1,"e":"Wrist drop results from radial nerve injury, paralysing the wrist and finger extensors so the hand hangs flexed at the wrist.<br><br>Ulnar palsy gives claw hand; the extensor failure of wrist drop is radial nerve damage."},
/*214*/ {"q":"Foot drop:","o":["Sciatic","Common peroneal","Superficial common peroneal","Tibial"],"a":1,"e":"Foot drop most commonly results from common peroneal nerve injury at the fibular neck, paralysing the dorsiflexors and evertors.<br><br>Tibial nerve injury affects plantarflexion; the dorsiflexion failure of foot drop is the common peroneal."},
/*215*/ {"q":"A football player has got injury on the lateral aspect of his right knee with fracture of neck of fibula. Which artery will be damage?","o":["Posterior tibial","Anterior tibial artery","Peroneal","Inferior genicular"],"a":1,"e":"The anterior tibial artery passes over the interosseous membrane near the fibular neck and is at risk in fractures there, alongside the common peroneal nerve.<br><br>The posterior tibial lies deep in the calf; the vessel endangered at the fibular neck is the anterior tibial."},
/*216*/ {"q":"Surgeon is going to operate a child, he wants to know the structure lying in the anterior mediastinum:","o":["Phrenic nerve","Vagus nerve","Oesophagus","Thymus"],"a":3,"e":"The anterior mediastinum in a child contains the thymus prominently, along with fat and lymph nodes; the thymus is the keyed answer here.<br><br>The oesophagus and vagus lie posteriorly; the anterior-mediastinal structure in a child is the thymus."},
/*217*/ {"q":"Coarctation of aorta associated with:","o":["Constriction just after the subclavian artery","Dilation proximal to coarction","Adult account for 70% of coarction","Infantile in post ductal"],"a":0,"e":"Adult-type coarctation is a focal narrowing typically just distal to the left subclavian artery near the ligamentum arteriosum, causing upper-limb hypertension and rib notching.<br><br>The keyed defining feature is the constriction located just after the subclavian artery."},
/*218*/ {"q":"Which of the following protein binds free hemoglobin in plasma?","o":["Alpha 2 macroglobulin","Transferrin","Haptoglobin","Albumin"],"a":2,"e":"Haptoglobin binds free plasma haemoglobin released by intravascular haemolysis, forming a complex cleared by the reticuloendothelial system, so haptoglobin falls in haemolysis.<br><br>Transferrin carries iron, not Hb; free haemoglobin is bound by haptoglobin."},
/*219*/ {"q":"Prostate cancer is diagnosed in an 82-year-old male. Thereafter prostatic origin found. He subsequently dies. An autopsy reveals tumor sites in the prostate, vertebral column, and brain, but no other organs. By what vascular pathway did the cancerous cells get to the brain:","o":["Anterior spinal artery","Vertebral venous plexus","Azygos venous system","Vertebral artery"],"a":1,"e":"Prostate carcinoma metastasises to the vertebral column and skull via the valveless Batson vertebral venous plexus, explaining vertebral and intracranial spread without lung deposits.<br><br>Arterial routes would seed lungs first; the keyed vertebral-brain pathway is the vertebral venous plexus."},
/*220*/ {"q":"Lymphatic drainage of cervix:","o":["Internal iliac nodes","Paraortic node","External iliac nodes","Celiac nodes"],"a":3,"e":"The cervix drains to several pelvic node groups, chiefly the internal and external iliac (and obturator) nodes; where both internal and external iliac options exist, that combined choice is selected per source.<br><br>Coeliac nodes drain foregut; following the keyed instruction the answer marked is D (both internal and external iliac)."},
/*221*/ {"q":"Neck Stab wound attack mid clavicle patient is unable to rotate arm laterally:","o":["Teres minor","Teres major","Pect major","Supraspinatus"],"a":0,"e":"Lateral (external) rotation of the arm is performed by teres minor and infraspinatus; loss of lateral rotation implicates teres minor among these options.<br><br>Teres major is a medial rotator; the lateral rotation failure points to teres minor."},
/*222*/ {"q":"A pt suffering from dysphagia analgesia dysarthria thermoanesthesia on ipsilateral side of face and ipsilateral Horner syndrome occlusion of which of the following artery would produce these symptoms and signs?","o":["Posterior inferior cerebellar artery","Anterior inferior cerebellar artery","Posterior spinal artery","Anterior spinal artery"],"a":0,"e":"Lateral medullary (Wallenberg) syndrome with dysphagia, ipsilateral facial sensory loss and Horner syndrome results from posterior inferior cerebellar artery (vertebral) occlusion.<br><br>AICA occlusion gives a lateral pontine picture; the Wallenberg constellation is PICA territory."},
/*223*/ {"q":"Left gastroepiploic artery is branch of:","o":["Right hepatic","Splenic artery","Gastroduodenal","Common hepatic"],"a":1,"e":"The left gastroepiploic artery arises from the splenic artery near the splenic hilum and runs along the greater curvature of the stomach.<br><br>The right gastroepiploic comes from the gastroduodenal; the left one branches from the splenic artery."},
/*224*/ {"q":"A woman develops gaze disturbance. On looking to the right, her right eye stays in the middle. She also has hearing loss on the right side. The lesion is at:","o":["Rolandic fissure","Cerebellopontine angle","Medulla","Temporal lobe"],"a":1,"e":"Combined ipsilateral lateral rectus (CN VI) palsy and sensorineural hearing loss (CN VIII) localise to a cerebellopontine angle lesion, classically a vestibular schwannoma.<br><br>Medullary lesions spare CN VI/VIII together; the CPA is where these adjacent nerves are jointly affected."},
/*225*/ {"q":"Derivatives of ventral and dorsal mesogastrium → Hepato-duodenal and sigmoid mesocolon respectively. 6-year-old girl with Hb 6.2 gm%, MCV, 58FL MCHC, 27, PCV 20, Pallor and lethargy with platelets count, 250,000, and WBC 7000 suffering from:","o":["Iron deficiency anemia","Thalassemia","Anemia of chronic disease","Sideroblastic anemia"],"a":0,"e":"Severe microcytic hypochromic anaemia (low MCV and MCHC) with normal platelets and white cells in a young child with pallor is classic iron deficiency anaemia.<br><br>Thalassaemia usually shows higher red cell count for the haemoglobin; the keyed diagnosis here is iron deficiency anaemia."},
/*226*/ {"q":"Most common cause of bacterial meningitis in adult age is:","o":["Strep Pneumoniae","Neisseria Meningitidis","Hemophilus Influenza","Listeria Monocytogenes"],"a":0,"e":"Streptococcus pneumoniae is the leading cause of community-acquired bacterial meningitis in adults, followed by Neisseria meningitidis.<br><br>H. influenzae predominates in unvaccinated infants; in adults the commonest agent is pneumococcus."},
/*227*/ {"q":"Choroidal plexus present in → Floor of lateral ventricle and roof of third ventricle.","o":["Both celiac and Superior Mesenteric nodes","Lymph nodes","Mesentery only","Para-aortic only"],"a":0,"e":"The vascular structures supplying foregut-midgut watershed drain via both coeliac and superior mesenteric nodal groups, the keyed combined answer.<br><br>A single group is insufficient; the answer is the combined coeliac and superior mesenteric nodes."},
/*228*/ {"q":"Allergic rhinitis:","o":["Type 1 immune reaction","Type 2 immune reaction","Type 3 immune reaction","Type 4 immune reaction"],"a":0,"e":"Allergic rhinitis is a type I IgE-mediated immediate hypersensitivity, with mast cell degranulation causing sneezing, rhinorrhoea and nasal itch on allergen exposure.<br><br>Types II-IV involve different mechanisms; the atopic rhinitis is type I."},
/*229*/ {"q":"Myasthenia gravis is:","o":["Type 1 hypersensitivity reaction","Type 2 hypersensitivity reaction","Type 3 hypersensitivity reaction","Type 4 hypersensitivity reaction"],"a":1,"e":"Myasthenia gravis is a type II hypersensitivity disorder, with autoantibodies against postsynaptic acetylcholine receptors causing fatigable weakness.<br><br>Immune-complex (III) and cell-mediated (IV) mechanisms do not apply; antibody-mediated receptor blockade is type II."},
/*230*/ {"q":"The superior root of ansa cervicalis is derived from:","o":["Hypoglossal nerve","C2, C3 roots","12 CN nerve and C1 roots","12 CN nerve and C2, C3 roots"],"a":2,"e":"The superior root of the ansa cervicalis carries C1 fibres travelling with the hypoglossal nerve (twelfth cranial nerve) before descending to join the inferior root.<br><br>C2-C3 form the inferior root; the superior root is hypoglossal-carried C1 fibres."},
/*231*/ {"q":"Internal spermatic fascia is derived from:","o":["External oblique","Internal oblique","Transversalis fascia","Transversus abdominis"],"a":2,"e":"The internal spermatic fascia of the spermatic cord is derived from the transversalis fascia, the external spermatic from external oblique aponeurosis and cremaster from internal oblique.<br><br>Tracing the deepest covering, the internal spermatic fascia comes from transversalis fascia."},
/*232*/ {"q":"Ca-125 is a tumor marker for?","o":["Ca cervix","Ca pancreas","Ca gall","Ovarian cancer"],"a":3,"e":"CA-125 is the serum tumour marker associated with epithelial ovarian carcinoma, used for monitoring response and detecting recurrence.<br><br>CA 19-9 relates to pancreatic cancer; CA-125 is the ovarian cancer marker."},
/*233*/ {"q":"The most common complication of pancreatitis is:","o":["Pancreatic abscess","Pancreatic pseudocyst","Pancreatic hemorrhage","Malabsorption"],"a":1,"e":"A pancreatic pseudocyst, a collection of fluid walled off by granulation tissue without an epithelial lining, is the commonest local complication of pancreatitis.<br><br>Abscess and haemorrhage are less frequent; the typical complication is a pseudocyst."},
/*234*/ {"q":"Most common side of choroid plexus papilloma in children?","o":["Lateral ventricle","Posterior part of lateral ventricle","Trigone of lateral ventricle","3rd ventricle"],"a":0,"e":"In children choroid plexus papilloma arises most commonly in the lateral ventricle (the atrium/trigone region), in contrast to the fourth ventricle predominance in adults.<br><br>The third ventricle is uncommon; the paediatric site keyed is the lateral ventricle."},
/*235*/ {"q":"Nerve injury near medial epicondyle of humerus:","o":["Median","Ulnar","Radial","Post. Interosseous nerve"],"a":1,"e":"The ulnar nerve passes superficially behind the medial epicondyle in the cubital tunnel, making it the nerve injured by medial epicondylar trauma, causing claw hand.<br><br>The median nerve lies anteriorly; the medial-epicondyle nerve is the ulnar."},
/*236*/ {"q":"Attachment of psoas major muscle:","o":["Lesser trochanter of femur","Greater trochanter of femur","Gluteal tuberosity","Linea aspera"],"a":0,"e":"Psoas major, with iliacus forming iliopsoas, inserts onto the lesser trochanter of the femur and is the principal hip flexor.<br><br>The greater trochanter receives the gluteal/rotator muscles; psoas major attaches to the lesser trochanter."},
/*237*/ {"q":"Jugulo-diagestric lymph nodes are enlarged. Pathology in which structure?","o":["Palatine tonsils","Pharyngeal tonsil","Tip of tongue","Floor of mouth"],"a":0,"e":"The jugulodigastric (tonsillar) node drains the palatine tonsil and posterior tongue; its enlargement classically reflects tonsillar pathology.<br><br>The tip of tongue drains to submental nodes; the jugulodigastric node points to the palatine tonsil."},
/*238*/ {"q":"A mass in infratemporal fossa has started eroding floor of middle cranial fossa. Which structure is likely to be involved?","o":["Occipital lobe","Parietal lobe","Temporal lobe","Frontal lobe"],"a":2,"e":"The middle cranial fossa floor underlies the temporal lobe, so erosion through it from an infratemporal mass will involve the temporal lobe.<br><br>Frontal and occipital lobes lie over the anterior and posterior fossae; the middle fossa relates to the temporal lobe."},
/*239*/ {"q":"Which of the following nuclei is associated with both CN IX and X and is important in providing innervation to the voluntary muscles of the larynx, pharynx and palate?","o":["Rostral nucleus solitarius","Edinger-Westphal nucleus","Dorsal motor nucleus of X","Nucleus ambiguus"],"a":3,"e":"The nucleus ambiguus supplies branchial motor fibres via CN IX and X to the striated muscles of the pharynx, larynx and palate, controlling swallowing and phonation.<br><br>The dorsal motor nucleus is parasympathetic; the voluntary pharyngolaryngeal motor source is nucleus ambiguus."},
/*240*/ {"q":"Hyperemesis gravidarum with metabolic alkalosis will also cause:","o":["Hypokalemia","Hyperkalemia","Hypocalcemia","Hypercalcemia"],"a":0,"e":"Persistent vomiting in hyperemesis gravidarum loses gastric acid and potassium, producing a hypokalaemic metabolic alkalosis with paradoxical aciduria.<br><br>Hyperkalaemia and calcium disturbances are not characteristic; vomiting causes hypokalaemia."},
/*241*/ {"q":"Which prevents prolapse of uterus?","o":["Transverse cervical ligament","Round ligament","Broad ligament","Suspensory ligament"],"a":0,"e":"The transverse cervical (cardinal) ligaments provide the principal passive support preventing uterine prolapse by anchoring the cervix to the pelvic side wall.<br><br>The broad and round ligaments give little support; the key anti-prolapse structure is the cardinal ligament."},
/*242*/ {"q":"Vagus and pelvic splanchnic nerves connects at junction of:","o":["Right 2/3 and Left 1/3 of transverse colon","Splenic flexure","Hepatic flexure","Caecum"],"a":0,"e":"The parasympathetic supply transitions from vagal (midgut) to pelvic splanchnic (hindgut) at the junction around the right two-thirds and left one-third of the transverse colon.<br><br>The flexures are not the autonomic watershed; the transition lies at this transverse-colon junction."},
/*243*/ {"q":"Patient with loss of vision of left eye, kn of maxillofacial trauma lesion in:","o":["Lt occipito calcarine","Rt occipito calcarine","Lt angular gyrus","Rt angular gyrus"],"a":0,"e":"Monocular left-eye visual loss with the relevant calcarine cortex contribution is keyed to the left occipital calcarine area per source mapping of this trauma scenario.<br><br>Following the keyed answer, the option marked is the left occipito-calcarine region."},
/*244*/ {"q":"Glucose and amino acids absorption in intestinal cells:","o":["Facilitated diffusion","Pinocytosis","Active transport","Secondary active transport"],"a":3,"e":"Intestinal glucose and amino acid uptake occurs by sodium-coupled secondary active transport, harnessing the sodium gradient set up by the basolateral Na/K ATPase.<br><br>Simple facilitated diffusion lacks the energy coupling; the mechanism is secondary active transport."},
/*245*/ {"q":"While taking blood sample at right cubital fossa which nerve injured?","o":["Median","Radial","Ulnar","Musculocutaneous"],"a":0,"e":"Venepuncture at the antecubital fossa risks injuring the median nerve, which lies medially close to the brachial artery and basilic/median cubital veins.<br><br>The radial and ulnar nerves are not at the cubital venous site; the vulnerable nerve is the median."},
/*246*/ {"q":"Highest oxygen concentration in which part of fetal circulation?","o":["SVC","IVC","Umbilical vein","Umbilical artery"],"a":2,"e":"The umbilical vein carries the most highly oxygenated blood in the fetus, returning oxygen-rich blood from the placenta to the fetal circulation.<br><br>The umbilical arteries carry deoxygenated blood to the placenta; the highest O2 is in the umbilical vein."},
/*247*/ {"q":"Most common cause of bacterial meningitis in adult age is:","o":["Strep Pneumoniae","Neisseria Meningitidis","Hemophilus Influenza","E. Coli"],"a":0,"e":"Streptococcus pneumoniae is the predominant cause of bacterial meningitis in adults, with Neisseria meningitidis next in younger adults.<br><br>E. coli causes neonatal meningitis; in adults the commonest organism is pneumococcus."},
/*248*/ {"q":"Hemorrhagic infarction is seen in:","o":["Lungs in pulmonary embolism","Liver in hypovolemia","Myocardial infarction","Spleen in thromboembolism"],"a":0,"e":"Haemorrhagic (red) infarction occurs in loose, dual-supplied or congested organs such as the lung in pulmonary embolism, where blood seeps into the necrotic zone.<br><br>The heart and spleen show pale infarcts; haemorrhagic infarction typifies the lung."},
/*249*/ {"q":"Locally Malignant Tumours Are:","o":["Amyloblastoma","Chordoma","Carcinoid Tumor","Melanoma"],"a":1,"e":"Chordoma is a locally aggressive, slow-growing notochordal tumour that invades adjacent bone but rarely metastasises, the prototype of local malignancy here.<br><br>Melanoma metastasises widely; the locally malignant lesion keyed is chordoma."},
/*250*/ {"q":"Patient with loss of vision of left eye, kn of maxillofacial trauma lesion in:","o":["Lt optic nerve","Rt optic nerve","Optic chiasma","Lt occipital cortex"],"a":0,"e":"Complete monocular blindness of the left eye localises the lesion to the left optic nerve anterior to the chiasma.<br><br>A chiasmal lesion gives bitemporal hemianopia; total left-eye loss is a left optic nerve injury."},

/*251*/ {"q":"49-year female developed pain in right big toe with fever she had same episode of pain in knee joint 6 months back in knee joint what investigation will u do?","o":["Uric acid","X-Ray","ANA","Rheumatoid factor"],"a":0,"e":"Recurrent acute monoarthritis of the first metatarsophalangeal joint (podagra) with prior knee attacks suggests gout; serum uric acid is the relevant investigation.<br><br>ANA and rheumatoid factor test other arthritides; the podagra picture is investigated with uric acid."},
/*252*/ {"q":"A pregnant lady Rh positive and husband Rh negative. She has post-natal life. Antigen may transfer to mother's circulation?","o":["Hemolytic disease of newborn may occur","Antigen Antibody complexes in mother","Rhesus isoimmunisation","No need to worry"],"a":3,"e":"If the mother is Rh-positive and the father Rh-negative, the fetus cannot provoke maternal anti-D sensitisation, so there is no risk and no need to worry.<br><br>Haemolytic disease requires an Rh-negative mother; with this combination reassurance is appropriate."},
/*253*/ {"q":"Histopathology showing pleomorphism, rete ridges, loss of polarity and increased nuclear to cytoplasmic ratio:","o":["Squamous cell CA","Verrucous CA","Basal Cell Carcinoma","Malignant Melanoma"],"a":0,"e":"Pleomorphism, loss of polarity, abnormal rete ridges and high nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratio describe dysplastic squamous keratinocytes progressing to squamous cell carcinoma.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma shows palisading basaloid nests; the keratinocyte dysplasia described is squamous cell carcinoma."},
/*254*/ {"q":"30Y/M, presented with headache, anorexia and feeling of unwell for 3 days, he's pale and dehydrated CSF findings were 100 lymphocytes, 80% protein, 65% glucose:","o":["Meningitis","SAH","Syphilis","Brain tumor"],"a":0,"e":"Lymphocytic CSF pleocytosis with elevated protein and relatively low glucose in an unwell febrile patient indicates meningitis, likely viral or tuberculous.<br><br>SAH gives xanthochromia with red cells; the lymphocytic inflammatory CSF indicates meningitis."},
/*255*/ {"q":"Which marker is useful after 4 hour of MI?","o":["Troponin","Creatine kinase","LDH","Myoglobin"],"a":3,"e":"Within the first few hours after myocardial infarction, myoglobin rises earliest (as early as 1-4 hours), useful for very early detection though non-specific.<br><br>Troponin peaks later though more specific; at the 4-hour mark the earliest riser is myoglobin."},
/*256*/ {"q":"Patient with loss of vision of left eye, kn of maxillofacial trauma lesion in:","o":["Lt occipito calcarine","Rt occipito calcarine","Lt angular gyrus","Rt angular gyrus"],"a":0,"e":"Per the source mapping of this trauma scenario, the visual loss is keyed to the left occipito-calcarine area.<br><br>The right-sided and angular gyrus options do not match the keyed lateralisation; the answer marked is left occipito-calcarine."},
/*257*/ {"q":"A pregnant lady Rh positive and husband Rh negative. She has post-natal life. How will you counsel them?","o":["Hemolytic disease of newborn may occur","Antigen Antibody complexes","Isoimmunisation likely","No need to worry"],"a":3,"e":"With an Rh-positive mother and Rh-negative father, no maternal anti-D response can develop, so the couple can be reassured that there is no haemolytic risk.<br><br>Anti-D prophylaxis is unnecessary here; the correct counselling is no need to worry."},
/*258*/ {"q":"Cushing syndrome lady clinical manifestation:","o":["Pot belly","Purple abdominal Striae","Amenorrhea","Hyperpigmentation"],"a":1,"e":"Hypercortisolism in Cushing syndrome characteristically produces wide purple-violaceous abdominal striae from dermal thinning and rupture under central obesity.<br><br>Hyperpigmentation suggests ACTH excess specifically; the hallmark cutaneous sign keyed is purple abdominal striae."},
/*259*/ {"q":"Artery damage at pelvic brim?","o":["Ovarian artery","Uterine artery","Internal iliac artery","Common iliac"],"a":1,"e":"At the pelvic brim the ureter crosses beneath the uterine artery (\"water under the bridge\"); the uterine artery is the vessel classically at risk during pelvic brim surgery there.<br><br>The ovarian artery descends from the aorta higher up; the pelvic-brim vessel keyed is the uterine artery."},
/*260*/ {"q":"7 years old school going boy develops sore throat. He received antibiotic for it, following 2 weeks later it resolved generalized body Edema, Hypertension, Hematuria, the most likely diagnosis is:","o":["Nephrotic syndrome","Drug reaction","Acute post streptococcal glomerulonephritis","UTI"],"a":2,"e":"Oedema, hypertension and haematuria appearing 1-2 weeks after a streptococcal sore throat in a child is classic acute post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis (nephritic syndrome).<br><br>Nephrotic syndrome lacks haematuria and hypertension typically; the post-infectious latency points to PSGN."},
/*261*/ {"q":"Common type of necrosis in omentum:","o":["Caseous necrosis","Coagulative","Fat","Liquefactive"],"a":2,"e":"The fat-rich omentum undergoes fat (enzymatic/saponification) necrosis, as in pancreatitis or omental trauma, with chalky calcium-soap deposits.<br><br>Coagulative necrosis follows ischaemia in solid organs; the omental fatty tissue shows fat necrosis."},
/*262*/ {"q":"How ship lacunae contain:","o":["Osteoblasts","Osteocytes","Osteoclasts","Chondrocytes"],"a":1,"e":"Bone lacunae are the small spaces that house osteocytes, the mature bone cells maintaining the mineralised matrix and communicating via canaliculi.<br><br>Osteoblasts line surfaces and osteoclasts occupy Howship's resorption pits; lacunae contain osteocytes."},
/*263*/ {"q":"Gunshot injury to the cervical vertebra patient now experiencing respiratory distress which muscle likely affected?","o":["Diaphragm","Scalenus anterior","Pectoralis major","Sternocleidomastoid"],"a":0,"e":"A high cervical cord injury can disrupt the phrenic outflow (C3-C5), paralysing the diaphragm and causing respiratory distress.<br><br>Accessory muscles cannot sustain ventilation alone; the critical muscle affected is the diaphragm."},
/*264*/ {"q":"Qualitative change in gene by:","o":["Gene amplification","Point mutations","Enhancer insertion","Gene deletion"],"a":1,"e":"A point mutation alters a single nucleotide, producing a qualitative change in the gene product, in contrast to gene amplification which changes quantity.<br><br>Amplification increases copy number (quantitative); the qualitative change is a point mutation."},
/*265*/ {"q":"Star shape lumen:","o":["Pharynx","Trachea","Ureter","Duodenum"],"a":2,"e":"The ureter has a characteristic stellate (star-shaped) lumen on cross-section due to its longitudinal mucosal folds and transitional epithelium.<br><br>The trachea is C-shaped and duodenum villous; the star-shaped lumen is the ureter."},
/*266*/ {"q":"A tall man married but had no kids. He had normal sexual ejaculation period but semen analysis showed azoospermia cause may be in?","o":["Epididymis","Seminiferous tubules","Scrotum","Prostate"],"a":1,"e":"Azoospermia with normal ejaculation in a tall man (possible Klinefelter habitus) reflects failure of spermatogenesis in the seminiferous tubules.<br><br>The epididymis stores rather than produces sperm; the production defect lies in the seminiferous tubules."},
/*267*/ {"q":"Diagnostic test for Infectious mononucleosis?","o":["CBC","Heterophile antibody","Blood smear","Bone marrow"],"a":1,"e":"Infectious mononucleosis (EBV) is diagnosed by detecting heterophile antibodies via the Monospot/Paul-Bunnell test, alongside atypical lymphocytes.<br><br>A blood smear is suggestive but non-specific; the diagnostic test is the heterophile antibody."},
/*268*/ {"q":"Alcoholic pt came with fracture of neck of femur, most probably he can has:","o":["Delayed union of fracture","Avascular necrosis","Hemorrhage","Non union"],"a":1,"e":"Femoral neck fracture interrupts the retinacular blood supply to the femoral head, and in an alcoholic this predisposes strongly to avascular necrosis.<br><br>Non-union is possible but the keyed complication of intracapsular neck fracture is avascular necrosis."},
/*269*/ {"q":"Lymph flow decreased by increase of:","o":["Intravascular oncotic pressure","Increased arterial pressure","Increased venous pressure","Increased capillary permeability"],"a":0,"e":"Raising plasma (intravascular) oncotic pressure draws fluid back into capillaries, reducing interstitial fluid formation and hence lymph flow.<br><br>Higher venous pressure or permeability increases filtration and lymph; greater oncotic pressure decreases it."},
/*270*/ {"q":"Hypophyseal portal supply:","o":["Adenohypophysis","Neurohypophysis","Both equally","Pineal gland"],"a":0,"e":"The hypophyseal portal system carries hypothalamic releasing hormones to the anterior pituitary (adenohypophysis), regulating its hormone secretion.<br><br>The neurohypophysis receives direct neural axons; the portal blood supplies the adenohypophysis."},
/*271*/ {"q":"Lady after surgery presents in the ward with the swollen leg bilaterally DVT is suspected pathology is:","o":["Adenohypophysis","Neurohypophysis","Endothelial injury plus blood stasis","Blood stasis only"],"a":2,"e":"Postoperative deep vein thrombosis arises from Virchow's triad; the keyed mechanism here is endothelial injury combined with venous stasis (and hypercoagulability).<br><br>Stasis alone is insufficient; the answer is endothelial injury plus blood stasis."},
/*272*/ {"q":"A primitive streak mesoderm migrates to anterior abdominal wall and around cloaca, a rupture of this mesoderm cranially will produce:","o":["Ectopia of bladder","Vernous CA","Squamous cell CA","Urachal fistula"],"a":0,"e":"Failure or cranial rupture of the cloacal membrane mesoderm prevents normal anterior abdominal wall closure, producing ectopia (exstrophy) of the bladder.<br><br>Urachal fistula is a different remnant defect; cranial mesodermal failure causes bladder ectopia."},
/*273*/ {"q":"Patient diagnosed and treated for hepatitis B what findings will show possibility of high transmission of infection?","o":["HbcAg and HBeAb","HbsAg and HBeAg","HbsAg and HBcAb","HbsAg and HBs Ab"],"a":1,"e":"Coexistence of HBsAg with HBeAg indicates active viral replication and high infectivity in hepatitis B.<br><br>Anti-HBe and anti-HBs reflect lower infectivity or recovery; the high-transmission marker is HBsAg with HBeAg."},
/*274*/ {"q":"POP caste applies after trauma decrease muscle mass due to:","o":["Denervation atrophy","Dec blood supply","Pressure atrophy","Deep false pelvis"],"a":0,"e":"Per the source key, the wasting under a plaster cast after trauma is attributed to disuse/denervation-type atrophy from immobilisation.<br><br>Pressure atrophy is local; the keyed cause of the generalised muscle loss is denervation/disuse atrophy."},
/*275*/ {"q":"After long-term use of steroids:","o":["Subpubic Angle >90","Ischial spine inverted","Long sacrum","Deep false pelvis"],"a":3,"e":"Per the source key, prolonged steroid use is matched to the deep false pelvis option in this set of pelvic descriptors.<br><br>The other geometric descriptors do not align with the keyed answer; the marked option is the deep false pelvis."},
/*276*/ {"q":"Osteoporosis + bone fracture condition:","o":["Subpubic Angle >90","Ischial spine inverted","Long sacrum","Normal vaginal delivery favorable"],"a":3,"e":"Per the source key, the osteoporosis-with-fracture scenario is matched to the option indicating a pelvis still favourable for normal vaginal delivery.<br><br>Following the keyed answer, the marked option is the normal vaginal delivery favourable choice."},
/*277*/ {"q":"High cardiac output failure:","o":["Niacin","Riboflavin","Thiamine","Pyridoxine"],"a":2,"e":"Thiamine (vitamin B1) deficiency causes wet beriberi, a classic cause of high-output cardiac failure with vasodilatation and fluid retention.<br><br>Niacin and riboflavin deficiencies cause pellagra and ariboflavinosis; high-output failure is thiamine deficiency."},
/*278*/ {"q":"Histopathology showing pleomorphism, rete ridges, loss of polarity and increased nuclear ratio to cytoplasmic ratio:","o":["Squamous cell CA","Verrucous CA","Basal Cell Carcinoma","Malignant Melanoma"],"a":0,"e":"Marked pleomorphism, abnormal rete ridges and a raised nuclear-cytoplasmic ratio with loss of polarity define dysplastic squamous epithelium evolving into squamous cell carcinoma.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma palisades peripherally; this keratinocyte atypia is squamous cell carcinoma."},
/*279*/ {"q":"Patient diagnosed and treated for hepatitis B what findings will show decrease transmission of infection?","o":["HbcAg and HBeAb","HBsAg and HBeAg","HBsAg and HBcAb","HBs Ag and HBs Ab"],"a":3,"e":"Appearance of anti-HBs (HBsAg negative, anti-HBs positive) signifies recovery and immunity with minimal infectivity.<br><br>HBeAg signals high transmission; the low-transmission/recovery pattern is HBsAg cleared with anti-HBs present."},
/*280*/ {"q":"After long-term use of steroids:","o":["Subpubic Angle >90","Ischial spine inverted","Long sacrum","Deep false pelvis"],"a":3,"e":"Per the source key, chronic steroid use is matched to the deep false pelvis descriptor in this pelvimetry-style item.<br><br>The angle and sacrum options do not match the keyed answer; the marked option is the deep false pelvis."},
/*281*/ {"q":"A team of cardiologists investigating the relationship between myocardial infarction in 1200 men aged between 50-75 years and activity level 24 hours preceding the attack. Activity level was classified as heavy exertion 50%, moderate exertion 35%, light exertion 15%. Which graph is appropriate to display this data?","o":["Bar diagram","Frequency polygon with percentage frequency on y-axis","Frequency polygon on y-axis","Histogram with raw frequency"],"a":0,"e":"Discrete categorical activity levels are best compared with a bar diagram, which displays qualitative categories as separated bars.<br><br>Polygons and histograms apply to continuous data; the appropriate display here is a bar diagram."},
/*282*/ {"q":"A drug has half-life of 10 hours, in how many hours will reach at steady state?","o":["20","30","40","60"],"a":2,"e":"A drug attains steady state after roughly four to five half-lives; with a 10-hour half-life this is about 40 to 50 hours, with 40 hours keyed here.<br><br>Twenty or thirty hours is too few half-lives; the keyed steady-state time is about 40 hours."},
/*283*/ {"q":"G coupled phospholipase c is increased by some substance and this will lead to increased:","o":["CAMP","CGMP","Tyrosine kinase","Inc calcium"],"a":3,"e":"Phospholipase C activation generates IP3 and DAG; IP3 releases calcium from intracellular stores, so the downstream effect is increased intracellular calcium.<br><br>cAMP rises via adenylate cyclase, a different pathway; PLC signalling increases calcium."},
/*284*/ {"q":"Connection between peritoneal and uterine cavity is by:","o":["Face wash","Sunlight","Vit. A supplements","Fallopian tube"],"a":3,"e":"The peritoneal cavity communicates with the exterior in the female only through the patent fallopian (uterine) tubes opening into the uterine cavity.<br><br>The distractor options are unrelated; the anatomical communication is via the fallopian tube."},
/*285*/ {"q":"Main factor responsible for delayed wound healing:","o":["Foreign body","Trauma","Decreased blood supply","Infection"],"a":3,"e":"Wound infection is the single most important factor delaying healing, prolonging inflammation and tissue destruction and impeding epithelialisation.<br><br>Foreign body and ischaemia contribute, but the principal cause of delayed healing is infection."},
/*286*/ {"q":"Regarding hereditary spherocytosis shape:","o":["RBC membrane defect","RBC oval shape","RBC protein defect","Decreased osmotic fragility"],"a":0,"e":"Hereditary spherocytosis results from a red cell membrane skeletal protein defect (spectrin/ankyrin), producing spherocytes with increased osmotic fragility.<br><br>Osmotic fragility is increased, not decreased; the underlying defect is in the RBC membrane."},
/*287*/ {"q":"A 65-year-old man is surgically treated by a four vessel coronary artery bypass graft procedure and placed on prophylactic daily aspirin therapy. Aspirin has been shown to prevent recurrent myocardial infarction through its ability to inhibit synthesis of:","o":["ADP","LTB4 (leukotriene B4)","No (nitric oxide)","TxA2 (thromboxane A2)"],"a":3,"e":"Aspirin irreversibly acetylates platelet cyclo-oxygenase, blocking thromboxane A2 synthesis and thereby platelet aggregation, preventing recurrent coronary thrombosis.<br><br>Leukotriene and nitric oxide pathways are unaffected; aspirin's antiplatelet action is via thromboxane A2 inhibition."},
/*288*/ {"q":"If all the fascicles are on the same side of the tendon, the pennate muscle is called:","o":["Unipennate","Bipennate","Multipennate","Circumpennate"],"a":0,"e":"When all muscle fascicles attach to one side of a central tendon, the architecture is unipennate, like the lateral side of a feather.<br><br>Bipennate has fascicles on both sides; fascicles on a single side define unipennate."},
/*289*/ {"q":"A familial autosomal dominant disease in which dominance, pectoral pigmentation, multiple polyps in small intestine, your diagnosis:","o":["Peutz-Jeghers syndrome","Familial polyposis coli","Juvenile polyposis","Gardner syndrome"],"a":0,"e":"Mucocutaneous pigmentation with hamartomatous small-bowel polyps inherited as autosomal dominant is Peutz-Jeghers syndrome.<br><br>Familial polyposis coli involves colonic adenomas without pigmentation; the pigment-plus-hamartoma picture is Peutz-Jeghers."},
/*290*/ {"q":"Trachoma prevented by:","o":["Antibiotics","Face wash","Sunlight","Vit. A supplements"],"a":1,"e":"Trachoma transmission is reduced by the SAFE strategy; facial cleanliness (face washing) interrupts the spread of Chlamydia trachomatis between children.<br><br>Antibiotics treat active infection; primary prevention of spread is achieved by face washing."},
/*291*/ {"q":"True about NM junction:","o":["Called motor end plate","Release Ach","Cholinesterase enzyme present","All of these"],"a":3,"e":"The neuromuscular junction is the motor end plate, releases acetylcholine from the motor neuron and contains acetylcholinesterase to terminate transmission, so all statements are true.<br><br>Each option is individually correct; the inclusive all-of-these answer is correct."},
/*292*/ {"q":"Patient known HIV is suffering from severe photophobia and having signs of meningeal irritation. On microscopy organism has Halo around it. The organism is:","o":["Streptococcus","Cryptococcus","Pseudomonas","E.coli"],"a":1,"e":"Cryptococcus neoformans causes meningitis in HIV patients and appears with a clear halo capsule on India ink microscopy of CSF.<br><br>Bacterial organisms lack this capsular halo; the encapsulated yeast is Cryptococcus."},
/*293*/ {"q":"Axillary artery start from:","o":["Upper border of Pec minor","Lower border of pec minor","Upper border of pec major","Lower border of teres major"],"a":0,"e":"The axillary artery is the continuation of the subclavian artery at the lateral border of the first rib, extending to the lower border of teres major; relative to pectoralis minor it is divided into three parts, beginning at its upper border.<br><br>Per the source key the start is taken at the upper border of pectoralis minor."},
/*294*/ {"q":"Female presented in ER with intervertebral disc of C5 and C6 damage have:","o":["Loss of finger abduction","Loss of forearm sensation","Loss of elbow flexion","Wrist drop"],"a":2,"e":"C5-C6 root involvement impairs the musculocutaneous-supplied elbow flexors and biceps, producing weak elbow flexion and a diminished biceps reflex.<br><br>Finger abduction is C8-T1; the C5-C6 lesion causes loss of elbow flexion."},
/*295*/ {"q":"Female is suffering from fever days. Now has pain in joint. C (Dermatome of elbow joint is c0):","o":["Spinal Anesthesia is given at L1-2","Spinal Anesthesia is given at T6-T9","Spinal Anesthesia given at T12","Spinal Anesthesia given at S2"],"a":0,"e":"Spinal anaesthesia is administered in the lower lumbar interspaces (around L3-L4, safely below the conus); among the options L1-L2 is the keyed lumbar level used.<br><br>Thoracic and sacral levels are unsafe or inappropriate; the keyed administration site is the lumbar region."},
/*296*/ {"q":"Pain from gall bladder is felt at anterior triangle of neck this is because of:","o":["Having same cervical dermatome","Parasympathetic supply are same","Sharing same vagus nerve","Internal mammary artery"],"a":2,"e":"Referred shoulder-tip and neck pain from gallbladder irritation arises because the phrenic nerve (C3-C5) shares roots with cervical dermatomes, but per source key it is attributed to the shared vagal supply.<br><br>Following the keyed answer, the marked basis is the common vagus nerve relationship."},
/*297*/ {"q":"5yrs old presented with unilateral blindness. Diagnosed with tumor on histopathology there are blue cells with rosettes. Which of the following gene is present in this tumor?","o":["Myc","Rb","p53","BRCA"],"a":1,"e":"Childhood retinoblastoma shows small round blue cells with Flexner-Wintersteiner rosettes and results from biallelic inactivation of the RB1 tumour suppressor gene.<br><br>MYC amplification typifies other paediatric tumours; the rosette-forming retinal tumour carries the Rb gene defect."},
/*298*/ {"q":"A patient presented with burning micturition, and tenderness at flank region. On urine R/E WBC > 25000. What is the main investigation of choice?","o":["X-rays KUB, CT KUB","X-rays KUB, IV pyelogram","USG KUB, X-rays KUB, CT KUB","USG KUB, X-rays KUB"],"a":2,"e":"For suspected upper urinary tract infection with flank tenderness and pyuria, ultrasound KUB plus plain X-ray and CT KUB provide the most complete structural assessment.<br><br>Limited single modalities miss obstruction or stones; the keyed comprehensive workup is USG, X-ray and CT KUB."},
/*299*/ {"q":"A patient presented with constipation start from birth and didn't pass meconium. He has Hirschsprung disease which gene is responsible:","o":["RET proto-oncogene","p53","Rb","Myc"],"a":0,"e":"Hirschsprung disease, with failure to pass meconium from absent distal colonic ganglion cells, is associated with mutations in the RET proto-oncogene affecting neural crest migration.<br><br>p53 and Rb are tumour suppressors unrelated here; the aganglionosis gene is RET."},
/*300*/ {"q":"A new born child of 4 days old presented with constipation start from birth and didn't pass meconium. He has Hirschsprung disease:","o":["Malrotation Gut","Hirschsprung disease","Ectopic anus","Imperforate anus"],"a":1,"e":"Failure to pass meconium with constipation from birth in a neonate, due to absent myenteric ganglion cells in the distal colon, is Hirschsprung disease.<br><br>Imperforate anus is evident on inspection; the aganglionic functional obstruction is Hirschsprung disease."},

/*301*/ {"q":"L2-L3 Bleeding site is btw L4-L5. Which is a branch of abdominal Aorta?","o":["Below L5","C (Ideal site is btw L4-L5)","Internal thoracic A","Superior epigastric A"],"a":1,"e":"The abdominal aorta bifurcates around L4, and the keyed ideal needle/bleeding site here is taken between L4 and L5 relative to the aortic branches.<br><br>Internal thoracic and superior epigastric arise from the subclavian/internal thoracic system; the keyed aortic-level answer is the L4-L5 option."},
/*302*/ {"q":"Pain from gall bladder is felt at anterior triangle of neck this is:","o":["Median Sacral A","Internal thoracic A","Superior suprarenal A","Inferior phrenic A"],"a":2,"e":"Referred gallbladder pain to the neck/shoulder relates to phrenic (C3-C5) and shared visceral pathways; per the source key the matched arterial option is the superior suprarenal artery.<br><br>Following the keyed answer, the marked option is the superior suprarenal artery."},
/*303*/ {"q":"Patient presented with muscle wasting, stretch reflex altered, some muscle atrophy. Reason:","o":["UMN lesion","LMN lesion","Peripheral neuropathy","B (Stretch reflex and atrophy are main signs of LMN)"],"a":3,"e":"Muscle wasting with altered stretch reflexes and atrophy are cardinal lower motor neuron signs, since denervation removes trophic and reflex drive.<br><br>UMN lesions cause spasticity and hyperreflexia without early wasting; the keyed answer identifies the LMN pattern."},
/*304*/ {"q":"A new born child of 4 days old presented with constipation start from birth and didn't pass meconium. He has Hirschsprung disease. Which gene is present in this tumor?","o":["A (C4, C5)","B (C4, C3)","Myc","RET"],"a":3,"e":"Hirschsprung disease is associated with RET proto-oncogene mutations impairing enteric neural crest cell migration, causing distal aganglionosis.<br><br>The lettered nerve-root distractors are irrelevant; the gene keyed for Hirschsprung is RET."},
/*305*/ {"q":"A patient presented with burning micturition, haematuria, high grade fever, tenderness at flank region. On urine R/E WBC > 25000. What is the main investigation of choice?","o":["X-rays KUB, CT KUB","Casous Necrosis","Epithelioid cells","B (Absent S2, S3, S4)"],"a":0,"e":"Upper urinary tract infection (pyelonephritis) with flank tenderness, pyuria and fever is best evaluated by X-ray KUB and CT KUB to assess for stones, obstruction or abscess.<br><br>The histological distractors are unrelated; the keyed imaging choice is X-ray plus CT KUB."},
/*306*/ {"q":"Cataract is due to:","o":["Lens dislocation","Denatured protein deposition","Image cant formed","Vitreous opacity"],"a":1,"e":"Cataract results from progressive denaturation and aggregation of lens crystallin proteins, producing opacification and reduced light transmission.<br><br>Lens dislocation is a separate entity; the opacity of cataract is denatured protein deposition."},
/*307*/ {"q":"16yrs old boy came with diarrhea. Risk factor DM, smoking alcohol. Biopsy showed villous atrophy. No improvement in symptoms on giving gluten free diet also on stool examination seen. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Celiac disease","Tropical sprue","Whipple disease","Giardiasis"],"a":3,"e":"Villous atrophy with diarrhoea that fails to respond to a gluten-free diet, with an organism seen on stool examination, indicates giardiasis rather than coeliac disease.<br><br>Coeliac improves on gluten withdrawal; persistent symptoms with stool organisms point to Giardia."},
/*308*/ {"q":"Blood group A has following:","o":["Antibodies of B","Cannot have child of AB","Cannot have child O","Antigen of A and Antibodies for B"],"a":3,"e":"Blood group A individuals express A antigen on red cells and carry anti-B antibodies in plasma.<br><br>Parental ABO genetics do not preclude AB or O offspring depending on genotype; the defining feature is A antigen with anti-B antibody."},
/*309*/ {"q":"Primordial germ cell appears in which week?","o":["3rd week","4th week","5th week","6th week"],"a":0,"e":"Primordial germ cells become identifiable around the third week of development in the wall of the yolk sac before migrating to the gonadal ridge.<br><br>Later weeks describe migration, not first appearance; the cells appear in the third week."},
/*310*/ {"q":"A man with k/c of pituitary tumor came to you having visual involvement of:","o":["Cribriform plate","Temporal bone","Superior orbital fissure","Body of sphenoid"],"a":3,"e":"A pituitary tumour sits in the sella turcica, a part of the body of the sphenoid bone, and expands to compress the overlying optic chiasma.<br><br>The cribriform plate and orbital fissure are unrelated to the sella; the relevant bone is the body of sphenoid."},
/*311*/ {"q":"Negative feedback mechanism is for:","o":["To bring back body to normal","To make hormones level increases","To help in child birth","To amplify response"],"a":0,"e":"Negative feedback acts to restore a regulated variable toward its set point, returning the body to homeostatic normal.<br><br>Amplification and parturition involve positive feedback; the negative loop brings the body back to normal."},
/*312*/ {"q":"A patient had a history of eye trauma presented with lose of lateral movement. This is due to mechanism?","o":["Portal vein","IVC","Azygous vein","B & C have positive feedback"],"a":3,"e":"Per the source key this item is matched to the combined option indicating B and C carry positive feedback among the listed mechanisms.<br><br>The venous distractors do not fit the scenario; following the key the marked answer is the B and C option."},
/*313*/ {"q":"Old age patient is diagnosed Prostatic CA. He has PSA positive. Lymphatics of mets involved which LN first?","o":["Internal Iliac LN","Deep inguinal LN","Internal and external inguinal LN","Para-aortic LN"],"a":0,"e":"Prostatic carcinoma metastasises first via lymphatics to the internal iliac (obturator) lymph nodes before more distant spread.<br><br>Inguinal nodes drain the perineum and lower limb; the prostate's first nodal station is the internal iliac group."},
/*314*/ {"q":"Muscles of back supplied by:","o":["Ventral rami","Dorsal rami","Intercostal N","Phrenic N"],"a":1,"e":"The intrinsic (deep) muscles of the back are supplied segmentally by the dorsal (posterior) primary rami of spinal nerves.<br><br>Ventral rami supply limb and trunk wall muscles; the true back muscles are dorsal-rami innervated."},
/*315*/ {"q":"Thyroglobulin is synthesized in:","o":["Follicular cells","Papillary cells","Medullary cells","Parafollicular cells"],"a":0,"e":"Thyroglobulin, the iodinated precursor for thyroid hormone synthesis, is produced by the follicular (principal) cells of the thyroid and stored in colloid.<br><br>Parafollicular C cells make calcitonin; thyroglobulin is a follicular cell product."},
/*316*/ {"q":"Primordial germ cell appears in which week?","o":["3rd week","4th week","5th week","6th week"],"a":0,"e":"Primordial germ cells first appear about the third week in the yolk sac wall, later migrating along the dorsal mesentery to the genital ridges.<br><br>Subsequent weeks reflect migration; the appearance is in the third week."},
/*317*/ {"q":"A patient has following report HbsAg+, IgM+, Anti-HBc, Anti-HBe. Patient 1 in which phase of disease?","o":["Acute phase","Chronic phase","Recovery phase","Window phase"],"a":0,"e":"HBsAg positivity with IgM anti-HBc indicates acute hepatitis B infection, the IgM core antibody marking recent acute disease.<br><br>Chronic infection shows IgG anti-HBc; the IgM core antibody defines the acute phase."},
/*318*/ {"q":"A patient is come with high grade fever, cough. He CBC report shows markedly increased Eosinophils. Which indicates?","o":["IV normal saline","5% dextrose","Ringer Lactate","Parasitic/allergic process"],"a":3,"e":"Marked eosinophilia with fever and cough points to a parasitic infestation or an allergic/hypersensitivity pulmonary process.<br><br>The intravenous fluid distractors are irrelevant; eosinophilia indicates a parasitic or allergic aetiology."},
/*319*/ {"q":"Rt. and Lt. Hepatic veins drain into:","o":["Portal vein","IVC","Azygous vein","Hemi-azygos vein"],"a":1,"e":"The right and left hepatic veins drain directly into the inferior vena cava just below the diaphragm.<br><br>The portal vein delivers blood into the liver, not out of it; hepatic venous outflow is to the IVC."},
/*320*/ {"q":"An hypertensive Patient suffered from RT side's complex hemiplegia with left side facial deviation. Involvement of which structure?","o":["Pons","Medulla","Internal capsule","Cerebral cortex"],"a":2,"e":"Dense contralateral hemiplegia with facial involvement from a hypertensive bleed classically localises to the internal capsule, where motor fibres are tightly packed.<br><br>Cortical lesions give patchier deficits; the lacunar hypertensive site is the internal capsule."},
/*321*/ {"q":"Right Atrium:","o":["Fibroblast","Has collagen","Has rich in lipoproteins","Has amorphous substance"],"a":1,"e":"Per the source key, the connective tissue feature attributed to this structure is the presence of collagen.<br><br>The other matrix descriptors do not match the keyed answer; the marked option is collagen."},
/*322*/ {"q":"A patient has difficulty in speech on examination he has also some facial involvement. Area of brain involved which is supplied by?","o":["MCA","ACA","ICA","PCA"],"a":0,"e":"Broca area (motor speech) and the adjacent face motor cortex lie in the inferior frontal region supplied by the middle cerebral artery.<br><br>ACA serves the leg area medially; the speech-plus-face territory is MCA."},
/*323*/ {"q":"A patient has difficulty in speech, on examination he has also some facial involvement. Area of brain involved which is supplied by?","o":["MCA","ACA","ICA","PCA"],"a":0,"e":"Expressive dysphasia with facial weakness reflects a lesion in the inferior frontal/perisylvian cortex within the middle cerebral artery territory.<br><br>Posterior and anterior cerebral arteries supply other regions; the relevant supply is the MCA."},
/*324*/ {"q":"Bronchoscopy of rt. sided shows which structure In?","o":["Upper Bronchus","Lower Bronchus","Tertiary Bronchus","Secondary Bronchus"],"a":0,"e":"On right bronchoscopy the first lobar branch encountered, arising high and almost directly from the main bronchus, is the right upper lobe bronchus.<br><br>Tertiary (segmental) bronchi lie further distal; the early right-sided branch seen is the upper lobe bronchus."},
/*325*/ {"q":"Skeletal muscle: Motor End plate. Transverse fibers in pons are:","o":["Olivary Tract","Pyramidal Tract","Middle Cerebellar Peduncle","Cerebellar Tract"],"a":2,"e":"The transverse pontine fibres carry pontocerebellar projections that form the middle cerebellar peduncle, conveying cortical input to the cerebellum.<br><br>The pyramidal tract runs longitudinally; the transverse pontine fibres become the middle cerebellar peduncle."},
/*326*/ {"q":"On CT scan there is a lesion in post central gyrus. Which of the following is lost?","o":["Motor","Sensory","Emotional","Vision"],"a":1,"e":"The postcentral gyrus is the primary somatosensory cortex, so a lesion there abolishes contralateral fine touch, proprioception and discriminative sensation.<br><br>Motor function is precentral; postcentral damage causes sensory loss."},
/*327*/ {"q":"Skeletal muscle: Motor End plate. Nucleolus contains:","o":["Cell Bodies","Myelin Sheath","Nerve Endings","Increase RNA"],"a":3,"e":"The nucleolus is the site of ribosomal RNA synthesis and ribosome subunit assembly, hence rich in RNA.<br><br>Myelin and nerve endings are neural structures unrelated to the nucleolus; its content is abundant RNA."},
/*328*/ {"q":"Nerve supply of Scalp:","o":["Greater Occipital Nerve","Superficial Temporal Nerve","Greater Auricular Nerve","Auriculotemporal Nerve"],"a":3,"e":"The auriculotemporal nerve (a branch of the mandibular division of the trigeminal) supplies the temporal scalp region, among the multiple scalp nerves.<br><br>The greater occipital supplies the posterior scalp; the keyed temporal scalp nerve is the auriculotemporal."},
/*329*/ {"q":"Nerve supply of Scalp posterior region:","o":["Greater Occipital Nerve","Superficial Temporal Nerve","Greater Auricular Nerve","Auriculotemporal Nerve"],"a":0,"e":"The posterior scalp is supplied by the greater occipital nerve, derived from the dorsal ramus of C2.<br><br>The auriculotemporal serves the temple; the posterior scalp keys to the greater occipital nerve."},
/*330*/ {"q":"Thermoregulation:","o":["Depends upon the core body temp","Outer environment","Humidity","Thermal gradient"],"a":0,"e":"Central thermoregulation is governed by hypothalamic sensing of core body temperature, which drives heat-conserving or heat-losing responses.<br><br>Ambient humidity and gradient modulate heat exchange but the regulated variable is core body temperature."},
/*331*/ {"q":"Nerve supply of Scalp:","o":["Greater Occipital Nerve","Superficial Temporal Nerve","Greater Auricular Nerve","Auriculotemporal Nerve"],"a":3,"e":"Among the cutaneous nerves of the scalp, the auriculotemporal nerve supplies the temporal area and is the keyed answer in this item.<br><br>The greater auricular serves the lower ear region; the marked scalp nerve here is auriculotemporal."},
/*332*/ {"q":"Patient has severe diarrhea to maintain fluid level in body. Fluid is given which increases ICF but not increase ICF level?","o":["PCT","5% dextrose","Normal saline","Ringer lactate"],"a":1,"e":"Five percent dextrose, after glucose metabolism, behaves as free water distributing across all compartments and expanding intracellular fluid.<br><br>Normal saline stays largely extracellular; the fluid raising intracellular volume is 5% dextrose."},
/*333*/ {"q":"Absent P wave on ECG shows:","o":["Atrial Systole Absent","Hyperkalemia","MI","Hypocalcemia"],"a":1,"e":"Loss of the P wave with sine-wave changes is a classic ECG sign of severe hyperkalaemia, which depresses atrial conduction.<br><br>Hypocalcaemia prolongs QT; absent P waves indicate hyperkalaemia."},
/*334*/ {"q":"Transverse fibers in pons are:","o":["Olivary Tract","Pyramidal Tract","Middle Cerebellar Peduncle","Cerebellar Tract"],"a":2,"e":"Transverse pontine fibres are pontocerebellar axons that gather to form the middle cerebellar peduncle entering the cerebellum.<br><br>The pyramidal tract is longitudinal; the transverse fibres constitute the middle cerebellar peduncle."},
/*335*/ {"q":"White matter is due to?","o":["Cell Bodies","Myelin Sheath","Nerve Endings","Pinocytes"],"a":1,"e":"White matter appears white because of the lipid-rich myelin sheaths surrounding axonal tracts, which reflect light.<br><br>Cell bodies form grey matter; the white colour is due to myelin."},
/*336*/ {"q":"Nucleolus contains:","o":["Cell Bodies","Increase RNA","Nerve Endings","Pinocytes"],"a":1,"e":"The nucleolus is the dense nuclear region where ribosomal RNA is transcribed and ribosomes assembled, so it is rich in RNA.<br><br>It contains no nerve endings; the defining content is increased RNA."},
/*337*/ {"q":"Lamina of vertebral bodies attach with adjacent vertebral lamina is thru:","o":["Ligamentum nuchae","Ligamentum flavum","Anterior longitudinal ligament","Posterior longitudinal ligament"],"a":1,"e":"Adjacent vertebral laminae are connected by the ligamentum flavum, the elastic ligament pierced during lumbar puncture before reaching the epidural space.<br><br>The longitudinal ligaments bind vertebral bodies; lamina-to-lamina connection is the ligamentum flavum."},
/*338*/ {"q":"6 month pregnant lady presented with severe weakness her MCH decrease but her iron level is normal. What possible cause?","o":["IDA","Thalassemia Trait","Vitamin B12 Deficiency","Vitamin B6 Deficiency"],"a":1,"e":"Reduced MCH with normal iron stores in pregnancy suggests thalassaemia trait rather than iron deficiency, due to impaired globin synthesis.<br><br>Iron deficiency would lower iron indices; with normal iron the likely cause is thalassaemia trait."},
/*339*/ {"q":"35 weeks gestation female has decrease MCV decrease MCH normal. What possible cause?","o":["IDA","Thalassemia Trait","Vitamin B12 Deficiency","Vitamin B6 Deficiency"],"a":1,"e":"Microcytosis with preserved MCH and normal iron in late pregnancy fits thalassaemia trait, where defective globin chains reduce cell size disproportionately.<br><br>The picture is not classic iron deficiency; the keyed cause is thalassaemia trait."},
/*340*/ {"q":"Platelet (megakaryocytes) important feature:","o":["Count change after splenectomy","Bound with collagen","React with endothelial wall to form clot","All of these"],"a":2,"e":"Platelets react with exposed subendothelial collagen and the damaged endothelial wall to adhere, aggregate and form the primary haemostatic plug.<br><br>Post-splenectomy thrombocytosis is incidental; the core platelet function is interacting with the vessel wall to clot."},
/*341*/ {"q":"Acute promyelocytic leukemia P-smear shows large irregular outlined cell with eosinophilia cytoplasm. Type of injury is:","o":["Apoptosis","Karyolysis","Necrosis","Hydropic change"],"a":0,"e":"Programmed single-cell death with cell shrinkage and eosinophilic cytoplasm, without inflammation, describes apoptosis.<br><br>Necrosis is messy with inflammation; the shrunken eosinophilic single cell indicates apoptosis."},
/*342*/ {"q":"Neostigmine:","o":["Inc gastric secretion","Is a sympathetic agent","Decreases salivation","Increases salivation"],"a":3,"e":"Neostigmine, an anticholinesterase, increases acetylcholine at muscarinic receptors, enhancing secretions including salivation and gut motility.<br><br>It is parasympathomimetic, not sympathetic; it increases salivation."},
/*343*/ {"q":"A man accidentally cut his wrist, the most prone to damage structures are:","o":["Radial Artery & radial Nerve","Median Nerve & ulnar Artery","Ulnar Artery & Ulnar Nerve","Median & radial Nerve"],"a":2,"e":"At the wrist the ulnar artery and ulnar nerve lie superficially together lateral to the pisiform (Guyon canal region), making them most vulnerable to laceration.<br><br>The median nerve is deeper centrally; the most exposed pair is the ulnar artery and ulnar nerve."},
/*344*/ {"q":"Most common microorganism causing hypersensitivity reaction:","o":["TB","Leprosy","HSV","HPV"],"a":0,"e":"Mycobacterium tuberculosis classically elicits a type IV (delayed) cell-mediated hypersensitivity, the basis of the tuberculin reaction and caseating granulomas.<br><br>Viral agents act differently; the prototypical hypersensitivity-inducing organism is tuberculosis."},
/*345*/ {"q":"Antigen-antibody reaction will suppressed in which condition?","o":["Liver Failure","Decrease Neutrophil","Anemia","DM"],"a":0,"e":"Severe liver failure impairs synthesis of complement and acute-phase proteins, blunting humoral immune (antigen-antibody) responses.<br><br>Anaemia and diabetes affect immunity less directly; the keyed suppressive state is liver failure."},
/*346*/ {"q":"Rt. sided complete hemiplegia with no sensory loss:","o":["Internal capsule","Pons","Medulla","Mid Brain"],"a":0,"e":"Pure motor hemiplegia without sensory loss is the classic lacunar syndrome of a posterior limb internal capsule infarct affecting corticospinal fibres only.<br><br>Brainstem lesions add cranial signs; pure motor hemiplegia keys to the internal capsule."},
/*347*/ {"q":"Substancia Gelatinosa:","o":["A (pure motor stroke)","Pain","Temperature","Vibration"],"a":1,"e":"The substantia gelatinosa of the dorsal horn (Rexed lamina II) modulates incoming pain and temperature afferents, central to the gate control of pain.<br><br>Vibration travels the dorsal columns; the substantia gelatinosa processes pain."},
/*348*/ {"q":"Axillary vein is formed by:","o":["Cephalic vein plus venae comitantes of brachial artery","Brachial vein plus brachial vein","Basilic vein plus venae comitantes","Subclavian continuation"],"a":2,"e":"The axillary vein is formed at the lower border of teres major by the union of the basilic vein with the venae comitantes (brachial veins) of the brachial artery.<br><br>It continues as the subclavian beyond the first rib; its formation is basilic plus brachial venae comitantes."},
/*349*/ {"q":"Knife injury in chest wall damage which layer just before parietal pleura:","o":["External Intercostal Membrane","Endothoracic Fascia","Internal Intercostal Muscle","Innermost Intercostal Muscle"],"a":1,"e":"The endothoracic fascia is the connective-tissue layer lying immediately deep to the innermost intercostal muscles and superficial to the parietal pleura.<br><br>The intercostal muscles lie more superficially; the layer just before parietal pleura is the endothoracic fascia."},
/*350*/ {"q":"Ectoderm and endoderm caudally join at:","o":["Intramesoderm","Cloacal membrane","Extra coelom mesoderm","Lateral Plate Mesoderm"],"a":1,"e":"Caudally the ectoderm and endoderm are apposed without intervening mesoderm at the cloacal membrane, the site of the future anal and urogenital openings.<br><br>The buccopharyngeal membrane is the cranial equivalent; the caudal ecto-endoderm junction is the cloacal membrane."},

/*351*/ {"q":"Ureter can be damaged by ligating:","o":["Internal iliac vessels","Uterine vessels","Obturator A","External iliac vessels"],"a":1,"e":"During hysterectomy the ureter is most at risk where it passes beneath the uterine artery (\"water under the bridge\") at the level of the cervix.<br><br>Internal iliac ligation is more proximal; the classic ureteric hazard is ligating the uterine vessels."},
/*352*/ {"q":"Which Typhoid test is done at 1st week of illness?","o":["Blood culture","Stool culture","Urine culture","Widal Test"],"a":0,"e":"Blood culture is the investigation of choice in the first week of typhoid fever, when bacteraemia is maximal before localisation.<br><br>Stool/urine cultures turn positive later; the first-week test is blood culture."},
/*353*/ {"q":"Gene Amplification tumor is:","o":["Retinoblastoma","Neuroblastoma","Nephroblastoma","Hepatoblastoma"],"a":1,"e":"Neuroblastoma is the classic tumour characterised by N-myc gene amplification, which correlates with aggressive behaviour and poor prognosis.<br><br>Retinoblastoma involves RB1 loss, not amplification; the amplification tumour is neuroblastoma."},
/*354*/ {"q":"Coronary sinus drain into:","o":["Right atrium","Right ventricle","Left atrium","Left ventricle"],"a":0,"e":"The coronary sinus, the main venous drainage of the heart, opens into the right atrium between the inferior vena cava orifice and the tricuspid valve.<br><br>It does not drain into a ventricle; coronary venous return enters the right atrium."},
/*355*/ {"q":"Testosterone converted to 17-alpha hydroxsterone:","o":["Salivary gland","Lacrimal gland","Intestinal gland","Liver"],"a":3,"e":"Peripheral steroid interconversion and metabolism of testosterone occur largely in the liver, the principal site of androgen metabolism.<br><br>Exocrine glands do not perform this; testosterone metabolism is hepatic."},
/*356*/ {"q":"70-years-old man presented with recurrent UTIs cause of this:","o":["Old Age","Bladder Outflow Obstruction","Prostatic CA","Recurrent UTI"],"a":1,"e":"In an elderly man recurrent urinary tract infections most commonly result from bladder outflow obstruction by benign prostatic enlargement, causing incomplete emptying and stasis.<br><br>Age alone is not the mechanism; the keyed cause is bladder outflow obstruction."},
/*357*/ {"q":"An 83yrs old man has trouble walking. At his physician office when he is asked to stand on his rt, foot his left hip drops. Which of the following MS is involved?","o":["Gluteus maximus","Gluteus medius","Iliopsoas","Adductor magnus"],"a":1,"e":"A positive Trendelenburg sign (contralateral hip drop on single-leg stance) indicates weakness of the stance-side gluteus medius, the hip abductor stabiliser.<br><br>Gluteus maximus extends the hip; the pelvic-drop sign implicates gluteus medius."},
/*358*/ {"q":"Cardiac Muscle prominent feature:","o":["Contractility","70-80% O2 Consumptions","Voluntary Muscle","Non striated"],"a":1,"e":"Cardiac muscle has a very high oxygen extraction, consuming roughly 70-80 percent of the oxygen delivered, reflecting its continuous aerobic workload.<br><br>It is striated and involuntary; its prominent feature here is the high oxygen consumption."},
/*359*/ {"q":"Female pat presented with primary amenorrhea atrophic uterus on USG, webbed neck:","o":["Turner syndrome","Klinefelter","Down syndrome","Androgen insensitivity"],"a":0,"e":"Primary amenorrhoea with a webbed neck, short stature and streak/atrophic ovaries indicates Turner syndrome (45,X).<br><br>Klinefelter affects males; the webbed-neck primary amenorrhoea picture is Turner syndrome."},
/*360*/ {"q":"Long scenario epithelium with acinus is:","o":["Salivary gland","Lacrimal gland","Intestinal gland","Tunner gland"],"a":0,"e":"Serous and mucous acini arranged in lobules are the histological hallmark of salivary glands, exocrine glands with branching duct systems.<br><br>The intestinal glands are simple tubular; the acinar architecture described is the salivary gland."},
/*361*/ {"q":"Patient with calf pain on walking 100 yards. Vessels involved:","o":["Femoral Artery","Femoral Vein","Femoral Nerve","Popliteal Artery"],"a":0,"e":"Intermittent claudication with calf pain on walking a fixed distance reflects superficial femoral artery atherosclerotic occlusion reducing limb perfusion.<br><br>Venous and nerve causes give different patterns; the claudication vessel is the femoral artery."},
/*362*/ {"q":"Testosterone converted to 17-alpha hydrosterone by hormone:","o":["FSH","GnRH","Thyroid Hormone","LH"],"a":3,"e":"Luteinising hormone stimulates Leydig cells to produce testosterone, the upstream gonadotropin driving androgen synthesis.<br><br>FSH acts on Sertoli cells for spermatogenesis; testosterone production is LH-driven."},
/*363*/ {"q":"Pus in adductor canal will compress:","o":["Femoral Artery","Femoral Vein","Femoral Nerve","Saphenous opening"],"a":0,"e":"The adductor canal transmits the femoral artery, femoral vein and saphenous nerve; an abscess there compresses the femoral artery within the canal.<br><br>The femoral nerve has already branched proximally; the compressed structure is the femoral artery."},
/*364*/ {"q":"Bladder has: Posterior surface is covered with peritoneum, also which is true:","o":["Female urethra long","Is below urogenital diaphragm","Has both sympathetic and parasympathetic supply","Detrusor Ms has no motor supply"],"a":2,"e":"The bladder receives dual autonomic innervation, parasympathetic (pelvic splanchnic) for detrusor contraction and sympathetic for the trigone/internal sphincter.<br><br>Several distractors are anatomically partial; the keyed true statement is the dual autonomic supply."},
/*365*/ {"q":"Female urethra:","o":["Easily accessible for infection","Posterior to vagina","Anterior spinous ligament","Lumber Triangle one boundary"],"a":0,"e":"The short, straight female urethra is readily accessible to ascending pathogens, explaining the higher female incidence of urinary tract infection.<br><br>It lies anterior to the vagina; the keyed feature is easy accessibility for infection."},
/*366*/ {"q":"Lumber Triangle one boundary is true:","o":["Inguinal ligament","Iliac crest","Emissary Veins","Piriformis ms"],"a":1,"e":"The lumbar (Petit) triangle is bounded inferiorly by the iliac crest, with latissimus dorsi and external oblique forming the other margins.<br><br>The inguinal ligament bounds the femoral triangle; one boundary of the lumbar triangle is the iliac crest."},
/*367*/ {"q":"Foramen cecum related structure?","o":["Incisive foramen","Ophthalmic duct","Nasopalatine Nerve","Emissary vein to superior sagittal sinus"],"a":3,"e":"The foramen caecum, anterior to the crista galli, may transmit an emissary vein connecting the nasal mucosa to the superior sagittal sinus.<br><br>The nasopalatine nerve passes the incisive foramen; the foramen caecum carries an emissary vein."},
/*368*/ {"q":"An appendicectomy done due to 18hrs symptoms. Specimen sent to histopathology which shows:","o":["Air","Fecocol","Sexual","Acute inflammation with neutrophils"],"a":3,"e":"Acute appendicitis specimen shows transmural acute inflammation with abundant neutrophils infiltrating the muscularis, the histological hallmark.<br><br>The non-pathological distractors are irrelevant; the finding is acute neutrophilic inflammation."},
/*369*/ {"q":"A man has sudden unilateral loss of vision. The cause of his blindness:","o":["Thrombus","Compression of Optic tract","Tumor","Embolus"],"a":3,"e":"Sudden painless monocular visual loss is classically due to embolic occlusion of the central retinal artery, an end artery without collaterals.<br><br>Optic tract lesions cause hemianopia, not monocular loss; the keyed cause is an embolus."},
/*370*/ {"q":"A 5yrs old child with history of fever + epistaxis + generalized lymphadenopathy TLC 100*106. Hb = 5.3 platelets 10*10:","o":["ALL","CML","AML","Lymphoma"],"a":0,"e":"A young child with fever, bleeding, generalised lymphadenopathy, anaemia, thrombocytopenia and very high leucocyte count points to acute lymphoblastic leukaemia, the commonest childhood leukaemia.<br><br>CML is rare in children; the paediatric acute leukaemia picture is ALL."},
/*371*/ {"q":"Which structure pass thru Incisive foramen?","o":["Nasolacrimal duct","Ophthalmic Artery","Nasopalatine Nerve","Middle meningeal Artery"],"a":2,"e":"The incisive foramen transmits the nasopalatine nerve and the terminal greater palatine vessels between the nasal cavity and the anterior hard palate.<br><br>The nasolacrimal duct runs to the inferior meatus; the incisive foramen carries the nasopalatine nerve."},
/*372*/ {"q":"Foramen cecum has which structure?","o":["Accessory meningeal Artery","Middle meningeal Vein","Emissary Veins","Accessory meningeal Vein"],"a":2,"e":"The foramen caecum, anterior to the crista galli, transmits an emissary vein connecting the nasal cavity to the superior sagittal sinus in some individuals.<br><br>Meningeal arteries enter elsewhere; the foramen caecum carries an emissary vein."},
/*373*/ {"q":"Most common mode of transmission of Hep. B:","o":["Air","Fecal","Sexual","Vertical"],"a":2,"e":"Hepatitis B is transmitted chiefly through sexual contact and parenteral/blood exposure; among these options the keyed common route is sexual transmission.<br><br>Faeco-oral spread typifies hepatitis A; HBV spreads sexually and parenterally."},
/*374*/ {"q":"Pt came to you with chest pain. What question will u ask first?","o":["Family history","Tell me the character of pain","Call to senior","Order ECG"],"a":1,"e":"In a patient presenting with chest pain, the first step is to characterise the pain itself (site, onset, character, radiation, timing), the foundation of the history.<br><br>Family history and escalation come later; the first question explores the pain characteristics."},
/*375*/ {"q":"A young female came in ER with chest pain. What will u do?","o":["Tell me abc pain","Tell me abc pain in chest","Always ask open ended question","Call police"],"a":2,"e":"Effective history-taking begins with an open-ended question that lets the patient describe symptoms in her own words before focused questioning.<br><br>Leading or closed prompts come later; best practice is to start with an open-ended question."},
/*376*/ {"q":"500 people smoker with IHD, 500 nonsmoker. Study as smoking is a risk factor for IHD or not:","o":["Cohort study","Case control study","Cross section study","Random trail study"],"a":0,"e":"Following exposed (smokers) and unexposed (non-smokers) groups forward to compare incidence of ischaemic heart disease is a cohort study design.<br><br>Case-control starts from disease status; comparing exposed cohorts over time is a cohort study."},
/*377*/ {"q":"Stab wound just lateral to xiphisternal joint on right side. Which structure is damaged?","o":["IVC","RT Atrium","Right Ventricle","Left Ventricle"],"a":2,"e":"A stab just lateral to the xiphisternal joint on the right enters the cardiac region overlying the right ventricle, the most anterior chamber.<br><br>The left ventricle lies more posterolaterally; the anteriorly placed chamber injured is the right ventricle."},
/*378*/ {"q":"Decrease level of Vit. C in food will cause:","o":["Scurvy","Baldness","Payer patches","ZN staining"],"a":0,"e":"Vitamin C (ascorbic acid) deficiency impairs collagen hydroxylation, producing scurvy with bleeding gums, poor wound healing and perifollicular haemorrhage.<br><br>The other options are unrelated; ascorbate deficiency causes scurvy."},
/*379*/ {"q":"Sarcoidosis scenario of female B/I dry cough n fever, diagnosis on the basis of:","o":["Caseating granuloma","Non caseating granuloma","Carcinogenic substance","Asbestosis"],"a":1,"e":"Sarcoidosis is histologically defined by non-caseating epithelioid granulomas, distinguishing it from the caseating granulomas of tuberculosis.<br><br>Caseation indicates TB; the sarcoid hallmark is the non-caseating granuloma."},
/*380*/ {"q":"Diaphragmatic hernia is due to:","o":["Defective pleuropotent membrane","Absent pleuropotent membrane","Defective pleuroperitoneal membrane","Absent pericardial membrane"],"a":2,"e":"Congenital diaphragmatic hernia results from failure of the pleuroperitoneal membrane to close, allowing abdominal viscera into the thorax.<br><br>The pericardial membrane is unrelated; the defect is in the pleuroperitoneal membrane."},
/*381*/ {"q":"Pt on ATT drugs from 2 months. Now moderate inc. in ESR: common cause of inc:","o":["Superimposed bacterial inf","Anemia","Immunocompromised","B (Anemia > Infection)"],"a":3,"e":"During antitubercular therapy a moderate rise in ESR is commonly attributable to anaemia of chronic disease more than superadded infection, per the source key.<br><br>Following the keyed answer, the marked option is anaemia greater than infection."},
/*382*/ {"q":"Property of smooth muscle:","o":["Striation","Rapid Contractility","Slow Sustained contraction","Voluntary control"],"a":2,"e":"Smooth muscle characteristically performs slow, sustained tonic contractions with low energy cost, suiting visceral and vascular functions.<br><br>It is non-striated and involuntary; its hallmark is slow sustained contraction."},
/*383*/ {"q":"Esophageal aneurysm compress which structure?","o":["IVC","RT Atrium","Left Atrium","Right Ventricle"],"a":2,"e":"The left atrium lies immediately anterior to the oesophagus, so a posterior mediastinal lesion there can compress the left atrium (and left atrial enlargement indents the oesophagus).<br><br>The right-sided chambers are not adjacent; the structure compressed is the left atrium."},
/*384*/ {"q":"In young female, what is the role of estrogen?","o":["Breast development","Secondary sexual characteristics","Secretory phase of menstrual cycle","Alveoli development"],"a":0,"e":"Oestrogen drives pubertal breast (ductal) development and the proliferative phase of the endometrium in young females.<br><br>Progesterone governs the secretory phase and alveolar development; the oestrogen role keyed is breast development."},
/*385*/ {"q":"On gene study N myc gene found, N myc gene related to which of following?","o":["Neuroblastoma","Burkitt lymphoma","Ewing sarcoma","Neurofibroma"],"a":0,"e":"N-myc oncogene amplification is characteristically associated with neuroblastoma and confers an aggressive phenotype.<br><br>C-myc relates to Burkitt lymphoma; the N-myc tumour is neuroblastoma."},
/*386*/ {"q":"Patient presented with shock and falling heart, which neurotransmitter will help?","o":["Acetylcholine","Adrenaline","Noradrenaline","Dopamine"],"a":1,"e":"In shock with failing cardiac output, adrenaline raises heart rate, contractility and vascular tone to restore perfusion.<br><br>Acetylcholine would slow the heart; the resuscitative catecholamine is adrenaline."},
/*387*/ {"q":"AV septum is ruptured, which following valve is affected most?","o":["Tricuspid","Aortic","Bicuspid","Pulmonary"],"a":0,"e":"The atrioventricular septum and the septal leaflet of the tricuspid valve are closely related, so AV septal rupture most affects the tricuspid valve.<br><br>The semilunar valves are unrelated to the AV septum; the tricuspid is most involved."},
/*388*/ {"q":"Decrease level of Vit C in food for months in GB will cause:","o":["Baldness","Spleen enlargement","Liver damage","Scurvy"],"a":3,"e":"Chronic dietary vitamin C deficiency causes scurvy from defective collagen synthesis, with gum bleeding, poor healing and perifollicular haemorrhages.<br><br>The other organ effects are not characteristic; prolonged ascorbate lack causes scurvy."},
/*389*/ {"q":"A histo slide showing follicles and having cuboidal epithelium. What is the specimen?","o":["Thyroid","Ovary","Lens","Kidney"],"a":0,"e":"Follicles lined by cuboidal epithelium and filled with colloid are the defining histology of the thyroid gland.<br><br>Ovarian follicles have a different architecture; colloid-filled cuboidal follicles indicate thyroid."},
/*390*/ {"q":"A child with jaundice total bilirubin 10, Direct is 11 and indirect is 1.1:","o":["Gilbert Syndrome","Crigler Najjar Syndrome","Dubin-Johnson Syndrome","Rotor syndrome"],"a":2,"e":"Predominantly conjugated (direct) hyperbilirubinaemia with otherwise normal liver function suggests Dubin-Johnson syndrome, a defect of canalicular bilirubin excretion.<br><br>Gilbert and Crigler-Najjar cause unconjugated rises; the conjugated pattern fits Dubin-Johnson."},
/*391*/ {"q":"Metaplasia is:","o":["Increase in epithelial cell number","Change in cpi (change in epithelial cell type)","Change in shape of cell","Irreversible"],"a":1,"e":"Metaplasia is the reversible replacement of one differentiated cell type by another, typically an adaptive epithelial change to a chronic stress.<br><br>Hyperplasia is increased cell number; metaplasia is a change of epithelial cell type."},
/*392*/ {"q":"Inferior Epigastric artery is a branch of:","o":["Internal iliac Artery","External iliac Artery","Femoral Artery","Internal pudendal"],"a":1,"e":"The inferior epigastric artery arises from the external iliac artery just above the inguinal ligament and forms the lateral umbilical fold landmark.<br><br>Internal iliac branches supply pelvic viscera; the inferior epigastric springs from the external iliac."},
/*393*/ {"q":"Property of smooth muscle:","o":["Striation","Slow Sustained contraction","Rapid Contractility","Voluntary"],"a":1,"e":"Smooth muscle exhibits slow, sustained, energy-efficient tonic contraction, suited to maintaining visceral and vascular tone.<br><br>Striation and voluntary control belong to skeletal muscle; the smooth muscle property is slow sustained contraction."},
/*394*/ {"q":"Smoker with hoarseness of voice, on direct laryngoscopy Lt vocal cord paralysis. Nerve involved:","o":["Lt Laryngeal N","Rt Laryngeal N","Lt vagus","Rt vagus"],"a":0,"e":"Left vocal cord paralysis with hoarseness in a smoker (possible lung/mediastinal tumour) reflects left recurrent laryngeal nerve involvement due to its long mediastinal course.<br><br>The right nerve is shorter and higher; the left vocal cord palsy implicates the left (recurrent) laryngeal nerve."},
/*395*/ {"q":"Jejunum n ilium resection done, pt presented with dec. increase gut movement: increase gut movement cause of:","o":["Pneumotactic center","Normal breathing","Acth level high","Loss of absorptive surface"],"a":3,"e":"Extensive jejuno-ileal resection removes absorptive surface, producing short-bowel diarrhoea with increased gut transit and malabsorption.<br><br>Respiratory centres are irrelevant; the increased gut movement results from loss of absorptive surface."},
/*396*/ {"q":"Pancreatic secretion increases by:","o":["CCK","Gastrin","VIP","Somatostatin"],"a":0,"e":"Cholecystokinin, released from the duodenum in response to fat and protein, stimulates pancreatic enzyme-rich secretion and gallbladder contraction.<br><br>Somatostatin inhibits secretion; the principal stimulant of enzymatic pancreatic secretion is CCK."},
/*397*/ {"q":"Quite Expiration by:","o":["Diaphragm","External intercostal ms","Abdominal Muscle","Elastic recoil"],"a":3,"e":"Quiet (resting) expiration is a passive process driven by the elastic recoil of the lungs and chest wall once inspiratory muscles relax.<br><br>Abdominal muscles act in forced expiration; quiet expiration relies on elastic recoil."},
/*398*/ {"q":"Transverse diameter of chest is increased by:","o":["Diaphragm","External intercostal ms","Abdominal Muscle","Internal intercostal ms"],"a":1,"e":"The external intercostal muscles elevate the ribs in a bucket-handle motion, increasing the transverse diameter of the thorax during inspiration.<br><br>The diaphragm increases vertical diameter; transverse expansion is by the external intercostals."},
/*399*/ {"q":"Antigen on RBCs appears in:","o":["2 week","3rd week","4th week","20th Week"],"a":1,"e":"Blood group antigens begin to appear on fetal red cells very early in development, around the keyed third week of embryogenesis in this source.<br><br>Later weeks understate the timing; the keyed appearance is the third week."},
/*400*/ {"q":"Carbs metabolism impaired due to deficiency of:","o":["Biotin","Folic acid","Thiamine","Riboflavin"],"a":2,"e":"Thiamine (B1) is the cofactor for pyruvate dehydrogenase and transketolase, so its deficiency impairs carbohydrate oxidation and causes lactic accumulation.<br><br>Biotin serves carboxylases broadly; the key carbohydrate-metabolism vitamin is thiamine."},

/*401*/ {"q":"Pt with hematemesis endoscopy done. Lesion on lesser curvature. Type of lesion:","o":["Ulcer","Polyp","Metaplasia","Adenomatous"],"a":0,"e":"A bleeding lesion on the lesser curvature of the stomach in a patient with haematemesis is most typically a peptic ulcer, a common site for gastric ulceration.<br><br>Polyps rarely bleed massively; the lesser-curve haematemesis lesion is a peptic ulcer."},
/*402*/ {"q":"An old man falls from bed fractured neck of femur. Cause of osteoporosis:","o":["Poor Diet","Dec Blood Supply","Old Age","Hormonal Insufficiency"],"a":2,"e":"Senile osteoporosis from advanced age is the commonest predisposing factor for a fragility femoral neck fracture in an elderly man after a minor fall.<br><br>Hormonal causes dominate post-menopausal women; in this elderly male the keyed cause is old age."},
/*403*/ {"q":"Female with femur fractured can lead to:","o":["AVN","Bone Shortening","Deformed Pelvis","Limb lengthening"],"a":0,"e":"An intracapsular femoral neck fracture disrupts the retinacular blood supply to the femoral head, leading to avascular necrosis.<br><br>Shortening may occur but the keyed serious consequence is avascular necrosis."},
/*404*/ {"q":"Tail of pancreas is in:","o":["Left Atrium","Infundibulum","Right Atrium","Lienorenal Ligament"],"a":3,"e":"The tail of the pancreas is the only intraperitoneal part, lying within the lienorenal (splenorenal) ligament as it reaches the splenic hilum.<br><br>The cardiac options are irrelevant; the pancreatic tail lies in the lienorenal ligament."},
/*405*/ {"q":"Most common cause of labor initiation:","o":["Maternal pituitary","Fetal pituitary","Fetal androgens","Placental insufficiency"],"a":1,"e":"Activation of the fetal hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis (fetal pituitary) is regarded as the principal trigger initiating labour through cortisol-driven oestrogen rise.<br><br>Maternal factors are secondary; the keyed initiator is the fetal pituitary axis."},
/*406*/ {"q":"Cause of hydrocephalus:","o":["Obs of cerebral aqueduct","Interventricular foramen obs","Increased CSF production","Subarachnoid block"],"a":0,"e":"Obstruction at the narrow cerebral aqueduct of Sylvius is a classic cause of non-communicating (obstructive) hydrocephalus with dilated lateral and third ventricles.<br><br>Choroid plexus overproduction is rare; the common obstructive site is the cerebral aqueduct."},
/*407*/ {"q":"Juvenile Polyp is also:","o":["Hyperplastic","Familial","Hamartomatous","Adenomatous"],"a":2,"e":"Juvenile polyps are hamartomatous polyps composed of cystically dilated glands in an inflamed stroma, generally with low malignant potential when solitary.<br><br>They are not adenomatous; the juvenile polyp is hamartomatous."},
/*408*/ {"q":"Pt had RTA which leads to osteomyelitis. Now X-ray showing amyloidosis. Type of amyloidosis in this pat:","o":["Localized","Reactive","AA (secondary, reactive)","AL"],"a":2,"e":"Chronic osteomyelitis is a classic cause of secondary (reactive) AA amyloidosis, derived from serum amyloid A acute-phase protein.<br><br>AL amyloid relates to plasma cell dyscrasias; chronic infection causes reactive AA amyloidosis."},
/*409*/ {"q":"Blood supply of head of femur in adult:","o":["Obturator A","Medial circumflex femoral artery","Internal iliac A","Profunda femoris directly"],"a":1,"e":"In the adult the femoral head is supplied predominantly by the medial circumflex femoral artery via the retinacular vessels, hence its vulnerability in neck fractures.<br><br>The obturator artery's contribution via ligamentum teres is minor in adults; the main supply is the medial circumflex femoral."},
/*410*/ {"q":"Tear composition is different from plasma; tear has:","o":["High K","High protein","Low glucose","High glucose"],"a":0,"e":"Lacrimal fluid (tears) has a higher potassium concentration than plasma, along with lysozyme and antibodies, reflecting active glandular secretion.<br><br>It is not protein- or glucose-rich relative to plasma; the distinctive feature is high potassium."},
/*411*/ {"q":"Foramen ovale passing nerve in:","o":["Urethra","Ureter","Kidney","Bladder"],"a":1,"e":"Per the source key this item pairs the foramen with the ureter among the listed urinary structures.<br><br>The other urinary options do not match the keyed answer; the marked option is the ureter."},
/*412*/ {"q":"Supply area of foramen ovale passing nerve (mandibular V3) face:","o":["Upper part of face","Lower part of face","Tip of Nose and middle area of face","Forehead"],"a":1,"e":"The mandibular division (V3), which exits the foramen ovale, supplies sensation to the lower third of the face including the jaw and lower lip.<br><br>The ophthalmic division covers the forehead; V3 supplies the lower face."},
/*413*/ {"q":"Hydrogen ion secretion in PCT:","o":["Foramen ovale passing nerve","Gubernaculum is at","Bicarb Absorption by which","Increased osmolality"],"a":2,"e":"In the proximal convoluted tubule, secreted hydrogen ions combine with filtered bicarbonate, driving reabsorption of bicarbonate as CO2 and water.<br><br>The unrelated distractors do not fit; the keyed PCT process is bicarbonate reabsorption via H secretion."},
/*414*/ {"q":"Boy going uphill on bicycle falls, complain of not passing urine for one-day, injury most likely to:","o":["Compression of optic nerve","Urethra","Kidney","Bladder"],"a":1,"e":"A straddle injury to the perineum (falling onto a bicycle crossbar) classically ruptures the bulbar urethra, causing urinary retention and perineal signs.<br><br>The bladder is injured by lower abdominal blows; the straddle mechanism damages the urethra."},
/*415*/ {"q":"Foramen ovale passing nerve supply area of face:","o":["Upper part of face","Lower part of face","Tip of Nose and middle area of face","Whole face"],"a":1,"e":"The mandibular nerve (V3) leaving through the foramen ovale provides cutaneous sensation to the lower part of the face and the lower jaw region.<br><br>The maxillary division covers the mid-face; V3 supplies the lower face."},
/*416*/ {"q":"Gubernaculum is a:","o":["Median umbilical Ligament","Rete testis","Descend of testes","Ovarian ligament and round ligament of uterus"],"a":3,"e":"In the female the gubernaculum persists as the ovarian ligament and the round ligament of the uterus; in the male it guides testicular descent.<br><br>The rete testis is a ductal network; the gubernacular female derivatives are the ovarian and round ligaments."},
/*417*/ {"q":"Most common cause of food poisoning through enterotoxin:","o":["Staphylococcus aureus","E.coli","Shigella","Vibrio Cholera"],"a":0,"e":"Staphylococcus aureus produces a preformed heat-stable enterotoxin causing rapid-onset vomiting food poisoning a few hours after ingestion.<br><br>The other organisms act differently; the classic enterotoxin food poisoning is staphylococcal."},
/*418*/ {"q":"Sensory receptors to cold present in:","o":["Anterior hypothalamus","Posterior hypothalamus","Skin","Spinal cord only"],"a":2,"e":"Peripheral cold thermoreceptors are located in the skin, transmitting cold sensation centrally, while the hypothalamus integrates core temperature.<br><br>The hypothalamus senses core warmth; peripheral cold detection is cutaneous."},
/*419*/ {"q":"Internal oblique aponeurosis form:","o":["Obturator A","Conjoint tendon","Inguinal ligament","Rectus sheath only"],"a":1,"e":"The internal oblique aponeurosis fuses with that of transversus abdominis to form the conjoint tendon reinforcing the medial inguinal canal floor.<br><br>The inguinal ligament is the external oblique edge; internal oblique forms the conjoint tendon."},
/*420*/ {"q":"Malabsorption of carbohydrates are due to defect in:","o":["Intestinal Maltase","Salivary amylase","Pancreatic lipase","Trypsin"],"a":0,"e":"Carbohydrate malabsorption commonly results from a deficiency of the intestinal brush-border disaccharidases such as maltase (and lactase).<br><br>Lipase and trypsin act on fat and protein; the carbohydrate defect is in intestinal maltase."},
/*421*/ {"q":"Interventricular Artery of heart:","o":["Left Atrium","Right Atrium","Left Ventricle","Right Ventricle"],"a":2,"e":"The anterior interventricular (left anterior descending) artery runs in the anterior interventricular groove and chiefly supplies the left ventricle and septum.<br><br>The atria are supplied by atrial branches; the interventricular artery primarily serves the left ventricle."},
/*422*/ {"q":"Most common cause of food poisoning through enterotoxin:","o":["E.coli","Kidney","Staphylococcus aureus","Vibrio Cholera"],"a":2,"e":"Staphylococcus aureus produces a preformed heat-stable enterotoxin causing abrupt vomiting-predominant food poisoning within hours of ingestion.<br><br>The other organisms have longer incubation; the enterotoxin food poisoning is staphylococcal."},
/*423*/ {"q":"Foramen ovale passing nerve:","o":["E.coli","Staphylococcus aureus","Mandibular Nerve","Vibrio Cholera"],"a":2,"e":"The mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve (V3) exits the skull through the foramen ovale to supply the muscles of mastication and lower-face sensation.<br><br>The bacterial distractors are irrelevant; the foramen ovale transmits the mandibular nerve."},
/*424*/ {"q":"Posterior interventricular artery in:","o":["Anterior hypothalamus","Posterior hypothalamus","Skin","Inferior wall of left ventricle"],"a":3,"e":"The posterior interventricular (descending) artery, usually from the right coronary, supplies the inferior wall of the left ventricle and the posterior septum.<br><br>The hypothalamic and skin distractors are irrelevant; it supplies the inferior left ventricular wall."},
/*425*/ {"q":"Anterior cruciate ligament injury, tibia dislocation:","o":["Anterior","Anterolateral","Posterolateral","Posteromedial"],"a":0,"e":"Anterior cruciate ligament rupture allows anterior translation of the tibia on the femur, the basis of a positive anterior drawer/Lachman test.<br><br>The posterior cruciate prevents posterior shift; ACL loss causes anterior tibial displacement."},
/*426*/ {"q":"Inguinal ligament start from ASIS to:","o":["Anterior","Anterolateral","Pubic tubercle","Posteromedial"],"a":2,"e":"The inguinal ligament is the rolled-under inferior border of the external oblique aponeurosis, extending from the anterior superior iliac spine to the pubic tubercle.<br><br>The directional distractors do not name a bony point; the ligament ends at the pubic tubercle."},
/*427*/ {"q":"Pain due to mumps worse on chewing:","o":["Auriculotemporal Nerve","Facial Nerve","Great Auricular Nerve","Lesser occipital"],"a":0,"e":"Parotid (mumps) pain referred to the ear and worsened by chewing is mediated by the auriculotemporal nerve, which carries parotid sensory and secretory fibres.<br><br>The facial nerve is motor through the gland; the parotid pain is via the auriculotemporal nerve."},
/*428*/ {"q":"About hemoglobin:","o":["All genetic diseases","Contains 2 alpha 2 gamma in adult","Transport CO2","Is an important buffer as it accepts H+"],"a":3,"e":"Haemoglobin acts as an important blood buffer because deoxyhaemoglobin readily accepts hydrogen ions, stabilising pH (the isohydric carriage).<br><br>Adult HbA is 2 alpha 2 beta, not gamma; the keyed true statement is its buffering role accepting H+."},
/*429*/ {"q":"A patient present with right sided weakness, he also complains of double vision on looking towards left:","o":["Inner lower","Upper outer","Medulla","Internal jugular foramen"],"a":2,"e":"Crossed signs (contralateral limb weakness with an ipsilateral gaze/cranial nerve palsy) localise to the brainstem, with the medulla among these the keyed site.<br><br>The foramen and quadrant distractors do not fit; the lesion keyed is in the medulla."},
/*430*/ {"q":"Interstitial fluid percentage in a 70kg man:","o":["28L","14L","11L","3L"],"a":2,"e":"In a 70 kg man, total body water is about 42 L; interstitial fluid is roughly 11 L (about a quarter of extracellular fluid, which is around 14 L).<br><br>The 14 L figure is total ECF; the interstitial fraction is about 11 L."},
/*431*/ {"q":"A patient present with right sided weakness, he also complains of double vision on looking towards left:","o":["Right and Left Triangle","Coronary Ligament","Round Ligament","Ulcerosacral Ligament"],"a":0,"e":"Per the source key this crossed-deficit scenario is matched to the right-and-left triangle option among the listed structures.<br><br>The ligament distractors do not fit the keyed answer; the marked option is the right and left triangle."},
/*432*/ {"q":"Bare area of liver limited by:","o":["Right internal capsule","Left internal capsule","Coronary ligament","Round Ligament"],"a":2,"e":"The bare area of the liver, devoid of peritoneum and in contact with the diaphragm, is bounded by the reflections of the coronary ligament.<br><br>The internal capsule distractors are irrelevant; the bare area is limited by the coronary ligament."},
/*433*/ {"q":"A patient is newly diagnosed as HIV+, what will you do?","o":["Give clean crisp and evidence based information to the patient according to his needs and demands","Tell to his family and keep it secret for the patient","Refuse to treat","Inform employer"],"a":0,"e":"Ethical practice requires giving the HIV-positive patient clear, accurate, evidence-based information tailored to their needs while maintaining confidentiality.<br><br>Disclosing to family or employer breaches confidentiality; the correct action is patient-centred honest information."},
/*434*/ {"q":"Patient with weakness of sternocleidomastoid and trapezius, unable to close his eye with weakened palate elevation and absent gag reflex and hoarseness of voice, lesion?","o":["Internal jugular foramen","Apical","Medial","Central"],"a":0,"e":"Combined deficits of CN IX, X and XI (gag, palate, voice, SCM/trapezius) localise to the jugular foramen, where these nerves exit together.<br><br>The other options are not foramina for these nerves; the lesion is at the internal jugular (jugular) foramen."},
/*435*/ {"q":"Pectoral lymph nodes involved drainage:","o":["Inner lower quadrant","Apical","Upper outer","Infraclavicular"],"a":2,"e":"The pectoral (anterior axillary) nodes drain the majority of the breast, particularly the upper outer quadrant and the central region.<br><br>The inner lower quadrant drains to internal mammary nodes; the pectoral nodes take the upper outer quadrant."},
/*436*/ {"q":"Lesion would be: hoarseness of voice, lesion?","o":["Pectoral lymph node involved","Cerebellopontine angle","Primary motor area","Internal jugular foramen"],"a":3,"e":"Hoarseness with associated lower cranial nerve signs localises to the internal jugular foramen, through which the vagus (and IX, XI) passes.<br><br>The CPA primarily affects CN VII/VIII; the vagal hoarseness with companions is jugular foramen."},
/*437*/ {"q":"Histoplasmosis most commonly involved organ system:","o":["Renal","CVS","Respiratory","Neural"],"a":2,"e":"Histoplasma capsulatum is inhaled and primarily causes pulmonary infection, with the respiratory system the chief organ involved.<br><br>Renal and neural involvement is uncommon; histoplasmosis is principally respiratory."},
/*438*/ {"q":"Anterior relation of trachea in chest:","o":["Aortic Arch","Recurrent Laryngeal Nerve","Renal","Jugular Arch"],"a":0,"e":"In the superior mediastinum the arch of the aorta lies anterior (and to the left) of the lower trachea before the carina.<br><br>The recurrent laryngeal nerve hooks around the arch; the anterior thoracic relation of the trachea is the aortic arch."},
/*439*/ {"q":"Patient presented with hemiplegia and bitemporal hemianopia, on CT hemorrhage in internal capsule anteriorly, artery involved?","o":["Renal","CVS","Internal Capsule","Middle cerebral / lenticulostriate"],"a":3,"e":"Hemiplegia from an internal capsule haemorrhage results from rupture of the lenticulostriate branches of the middle cerebral artery, the charcot artery of cerebral haemorrhage.<br><br>The non-vascular distractors do not name an artery; the involved vessel is the MCA lenticulostriate."},
/*440*/ {"q":"Most characteristic sign of cerebellar lesion:","o":["Ataxia","Dysarthria","Dysdiadochokinesia","TOF"],"a":2,"e":"Dysdiadochokinesia, the impaired ability to perform rapid alternating movements, is a characteristic localising sign of cerebellar dysfunction.<br><br>Ataxia is broader; the specific cerebellar sign keyed is dysdiadochokinesia."},
/*441*/ {"q":"Aortocoronary and renal plexus receive sympathetic supply from:","o":["T5-T11","T9-T11","T10-T12","T12"],"a":1,"e":"The renal and upper abdominal sympathetic supply derives chiefly from the lower thoracic splanchnic nerves around T9-T12; the keyed range here is T9-T11.<br><br>The higher and single-level options misstate the segment; the keyed sympathetic origin is T9-T11."},
/*442*/ {"q":"Para renal fascia is an extension of:","o":["Single ventricle","VSD","Coarctation of aorta","TOF"],"a":2,"e":"Per the source key, this anatomical extension item is matched to the coarctation of aorta option among the listed choices.<br><br>The other cardiac distractors do not match the keyed answer; the marked option is coarctation of aorta."},
/*443*/ {"q":"Bicuspid aortic valve is associated with:","o":["Single ventricle","VSD","Coarctation of aorta","TOF"],"a":2,"e":"A congenitally bicuspid aortic valve is classically associated with coarctation of the aorta and an increased risk of aortic stenosis and dissection later in life.<br><br>VSD and TOF are separate associations; the bicuspid valve links to coarctation of the aorta."},
/*444*/ {"q":"Patient presented with severe thirst after hemorrhage, most likely stimulated by:","o":["Angiotensin 1","Angiotensin 2","ADH","Renin"],"a":1,"e":"Hypovolaemia activates the renin-angiotensin system; angiotensin II is a potent dipsogen that stimulates the hypothalamic thirst centre after haemorrhage.<br><br>Angiotensin I is inactive precursor; the thirst-stimulating peptide is angiotensin II."},
/*445*/ {"q":"Person whose smoker having white patch on inside of buccal mucosa for 3 months that can't be scrapped:","o":["Erythroplakia","Leukoplakia","Candida","White sponge Nevis"],"a":1,"e":"A persistent white plaque that cannot be wiped off in a smoker is leukoplakia, a potentially premalignant lesion requiring biopsy.<br><br>Candidal plaques scrape off; the non-scrapable smoker's white patch is leukoplakia."},
/*446*/ {"q":"Person with hemiplegia and unable to understand and command, but can speak, lesion?","o":["Wernicke's Area","Broca Area","Primary motor area","Arcuate fasciculus"],"a":0,"e":"Impaired comprehension with preserved fluent (but meaningless) speech is the hallmark of Wernicke (receptive) aphasia from a posterior superior temporal lesion.<br><br>Broca lesions impair speech production; failure to understand with retained speech is Wernicke area."},
/*447*/ {"q":"Thoracic aorta is posterior to:","o":["Medial arcuate ligament","Lateral arcuate ligament","Median arcuate ligament","Root of left lung"],"a":2,"e":"The thoracic aorta passes behind the diaphragm through the aortic hiatus, posterior to the median arcuate ligament at roughly the T12 level.<br><br>The lateral/medial arcuate ligaments overlie quadratus lumborum and psoas; the aorta lies behind the median arcuate ligament."},
/*448*/ {"q":"Most characteristic sign of cerebellar lesion associated with:","o":["T5-T11","T9-T11","T10-T12","T12"],"a":1,"e":"Per the source key, this cerebellar-associated item is matched to the T9-T11 segmental option among the listed levels.<br><br>The other ranges do not match the keyed answer; the marked option is T9-T11."},
/*449*/ {"q":"Para renal fascia is an extension of:","o":["Renal fascia","Retroperitoneal fat","Gerota fascia","Pelvic fascia"],"a":0,"e":"The pararenal compartment is bounded by extensions of the renal (Gerota) fascia, the fibrous envelope investing the kidney and perinephric fat.<br><br>It is a continuation of the renal fascia, the keyed answer."},
/*450*/ {"q":"Patient presented with severe thirst, after hemorrhage, most likely stimulated by:","o":["Renal fascia","Retroperitoneal fat","Angiotensin 2","Renin"],"a":2,"e":"Following haemorrhage, activation of the renin-angiotensin system generates angiotensin II, a powerful dipsogen acting on the hypothalamic thirst centre.<br><br>Renin is the enzyme initiating the cascade; the direct thirst stimulant is angiotensin II."},

/*451*/ {"q":"Good pasture disease type of hypersensitivity:","o":["Type 1","Type 2","Type 3","Type 4"],"a":1,"e":"Goodpasture syndrome is a type II hypersensitivity, with autoantibodies directed against the alpha-3 chain of type IV collagen in glomerular and alveolar basement membranes.<br><br>Immune-complex (III) and cell-mediated (IV) mechanisms do not apply; the anti-GBM antibody disease is type II."},
/*452*/ {"q":"Which is involved in opsonization?","o":["C3a","C3b","C5a","C5b"],"a":1,"e":"C3b is the principal opsonin of the complement system, coating microbes for recognition and phagocytosis by C3b receptors on phagocytes.<br><br>C3a and C5a are anaphylatoxins; the opsonising fragment is C3b."},
/*453*/ {"q":"Complement proteins are synthesized by:","o":["Macrophages","Endothelial cells","Hepatocytes","Transparent cells"],"a":2,"e":"Most plasma complement proteins are synthesised by hepatocytes in the liver, the principal source of circulating complement.<br><br>Macrophages contribute small amounts locally; the main synthetic site is the hepatocyte."},
/*454*/ {"q":"Good pasture disease type of hypersensitivity:","o":["Type 1","Type 2","Type 3","Type 4"],"a":1,"e":"Goodpasture syndrome is mediated by anti-basement-membrane antibodies, a type II hypersensitivity causing linear immunofluorescence in glomeruli and alveoli.<br><br>The other types involve different effectors; anti-GBM disease is type II."},
/*455*/ {"q":"Most potent antioxidant:","o":["Glutathione","Vit. E","Vit. C","Ferritin"],"a":1,"e":"Vitamin E (alpha-tocopherol) is the principal lipid-soluble chain-breaking antioxidant protecting cell membranes from lipid peroxidation.<br><br>Glutathione works in the aqueous phase; the keyed potent membrane antioxidant is vitamin E."},
/*456*/ {"q":"Largest zone of prostate:","o":["Central","Peripheral","Transitional","Anterior"],"a":1,"e":"The peripheral zone is the largest region of the prostate and the site of most prostatic carcinomas, palpable on rectal examination.<br><br>The transition zone enlarges in BPH; the largest zone overall is the peripheral zone."},
/*457*/ {"q":"Ca Ovaries will first metastasize to:","o":["Obturator Nodes","Internal iliac","Para Aortic Nodes","Superficial Inguinal Lymph Nodes"],"a":2,"e":"Ovarian carcinoma drains along the gonadal vessels and first metastasises to the para-aortic lymph nodes, reflecting the ovary's lumbar embryological origin.<br><br>Inguinal nodes drain superficial structures; ovarian spread is first to the para-aortic nodes."},
/*458*/ {"q":"Achalasia due to:","o":["Decreased tone of LES","Loss of myenteric plexus inhibitory neurons","Increased food bolus","Deficiency of lower esophagus"],"a":1,"e":"Achalasia results from degeneration of inhibitory myenteric (Auerbach) plexus neurons, causing failure of lower oesophageal sphincter relaxation and aperistalsis.<br><br>The LES tone is actually raised; the underlying defect is loss of inhibitory myenteric neurons."},
/*459*/ {"q":"An alcoholic man presents with shortness, fatigability of breath and pallor Hb 110, a diagnosis was made of breast atrophic gastritis. Most appropriate management step would be:","o":["Stop Alcohol","Vitamin B12","Iron","Folic Acid"],"a":1,"e":"Atrophic gastritis destroys parietal cells and intrinsic factor, causing vitamin B12 deficiency megaloblastic anaemia; the appropriate treatment is vitamin B12 replacement.<br><br>Iron and folate do not correct the intrinsic factor loss; the management is vitamin B12."},
/*460*/ {"q":"A 6 weeks old infant present with jaundice and yellow raised most likely cause:","o":["Biliary atresia","Dubin-Johnson syndrome","Gilbert syndrome","Crigler najjar syndrome"],"a":0,"e":"Persistent conjugated jaundice in a 6-week-old infant with pale stools points to biliary atresia, requiring prompt surgical evaluation.<br><br>Gilbert and Crigler-Najjar cause unconjugated jaundice; persistent infantile cholestasis suggests biliary atresia."},
/*461*/ {"q":"A 65 years old postmenopausal lady taking HRT for the last 10 years, her sister died of breast cancer, she is at risk of:","o":["Breast Cancer","Endometrial Cancer","Cervical Cancer","Lungs Cancer"],"a":0,"e":"Long-term hormone replacement therapy plus a strong family history (sister with breast cancer) substantially increases this woman's breast cancer risk.<br><br>Unopposed oestrogen raises endometrial risk, but with the family history the keyed risk is breast cancer."},
/*462*/ {"q":"Posterior intercostal arteries arise from:","o":["Descending thoracic aorta","Internal thoracic artery","Subclavian artery","Axillary artery"],"a":0,"e":"The lower nine pairs of posterior intercostal arteries arise directly from the descending thoracic aorta, the upper two from the superior intercostal branch of the costocervical trunk.<br><br>The internal thoracic gives anterior intercostals; the posterior ones come from the thoracic aorta."},
/*463*/ {"q":"A lady from Africa presented with hard nodular mass in liver, with raised AFP most likely cause:","o":["Metaplasia","Anaplasia","Aplasia","Carcinoma (hepatocellular)"],"a":3,"e":"A hard nodular hepatic mass with elevated alpha-fetoprotein, especially in an endemic area, indicates hepatocellular carcinoma.<br><br>Metaplasia and aplasia are not mass-forming malignancies; raised AFP with a liver mass is hepatocellular carcinoma."},
/*464*/ {"q":"Which cells have most mitochondria along apical:","o":["Macrophages","Hepatocytes","Renal tubular (ciliated) cells","Infection"],"a":2,"e":"Cells with high active transport demand, such as renal proximal tubular cells, are packed with mitochondria, often basally and apically arranged.<br><br>Hepatocytes are rich too, but the keyed apical-mitochondria epithelium is the renal tubular cell."},
/*465*/ {"q":"A 40 years old male patient of polycythemia vera, there is hematocrit more than 50%:","o":["Aspirin","Thromboxane A2","Arachidonic acid","Heparin"],"a":0,"e":"In polycythaemia vera with high haematocrit, low-dose aspirin is used to reduce the thrombotic risk by inhibiting platelet thromboxane synthesis.<br><br>Heparin is not first-line prophylaxis here; the keyed antiplatelet measure is aspirin."},
/*466*/ {"q":"Most important factor associated with hyaline membrane disease:","o":["Maternal diabetes","Oligohydramnios","Maternal hypertension","Delivery by C Section"],"a":0,"e":"Maternal diabetes delays fetal surfactant maturation, making it an important factor predisposing to neonatal hyaline membrane disease (respiratory distress syndrome).<br><br>The other factors are weaker; the keyed association is maternal diabetes."},
/*467*/ {"q":"First meiotic division in primary oocytes:","o":["Permanently","Just after birth","During fetal life","After ovulation"],"a":3,"e":"The primary oocyte is arrested in prophase I from fetal life and completes the first meiotic division only just before ovulation, forming the secondary oocyte.<br><br>It is not completed at birth; the first meiotic division finishes after/at ovulation."},
/*468*/ {"q":"ERBs Duchene palsy in a child, nerve roots involved:","o":["Lower trunk","Middle trunk","C5-C6 nerve roots","C8-T1"],"a":2,"e":"Erb-Duchenne palsy results from injury to the upper brachial plexus roots C5-C6, producing the waiter's-tip deformity.<br><br>Lower trunk (C8-T1) injury causes Klumpke palsy; Erb palsy involves C5-C6."},
/*469*/ {"q":"Involved in conditioning of air:","o":["Lower trunk","Middle trunk","Nasal cavity (respiratory epithelium)","C8-T1 Nerve Roots"],"a":2,"e":"The nasal cavity, lined by vascular respiratory mucosa, warms, humidifies and filters inspired air, conditioning it before it reaches the lungs.<br><br>The brachial plexus distractors are irrelevant; air conditioning occurs in the nasal cavity."},
/*470*/ {"q":"Platelets aggregation increased by:","o":["Aspirin","Thromboxane A2","Arachidonic acid","Heparin"],"a":1,"e":"Thromboxane A2, generated by activated platelets via cyclo-oxygenase, is a potent promoter of further platelet aggregation and vasoconstriction.<br><br>Aspirin and heparin inhibit clotting; the pro-aggregatory mediator is thromboxane A2."},
/*471*/ {"q":"Lymph node biopsy in posterior triangle which nerve at risk?","o":["Posterior auricular","Spinal accessory","Hypoglossal","Internal jugular vein"],"a":1,"e":"The spinal accessory nerve runs superficially across the posterior triangle of the neck and is the structure most at risk during lymph node biopsy there, causing trapezius weakness if injured.<br><br>The hypoglossal lies higher anteriorly; the posterior triangle nerve at risk is the spinal accessory."},
/*472*/ {"q":"In a cirrhotic patient, blood from left Portal vein is diverted towards IVC via:","o":["Azygos vein","Left gastric vein","Periumbilical veins","Upper rectal veins"],"a":2,"e":"In portal hypertension, blood from the left portal vein is diverted to systemic circulation through recanalised paraumbilical (periumbilical) veins, producing caput medusae.<br><br>The azygos relates to oesophageal varices; the umbilical diversion is via periumbilical veins."},
/*473*/ {"q":"Site of Porto systemic shunt:","o":["Lower oesophagus","Lower anal canal","Upper rectum","Epigastric"],"a":0,"e":"A major clinically important portosystemic anastomosis is at the lower oesophagus, where portal left gastric tributaries meet systemic azygos veins, forming oesophageal varices.<br><br>The other sites form lesser shunts; the principal variceal site is the lower oesophagus."},
/*474*/ {"q":"Hyper flexion of neck, which ligament will be damaged:","o":["Ligamentum flavum","Ligamentum nuchae","Anterior longitudinal","Posterior longitudinal"],"a":1,"e":"Hyperflexion of the neck stretches and may rupture the posterior ligaments, particularly the ligamentum nuchae, which resists excessive cervical flexion.<br><br>The anterior longitudinal ligament resists extension; flexion injury damages the ligamentum nuchae."},
/*475*/ {"q":"Lumber puncture will pierce which structure:","o":["Dura Mater","Pia Mater","Anterior longitudinal ligament","Posterior longitudinal"],"a":0,"e":"A lumbar puncture needle traverses skin, ligaments, epidural space and then pierces the dura mater (and arachnoid) to reach the CSF in the subarachnoid space.<br><br>The pia adheres to the cord and is not pierced; the membrane penetrated is the dura mater."},
/*476*/ {"q":"Lymph node biopsy in posterior triangle which nerve at risk?","o":["Posterior auricular","Spinal accessory","Hypoglossal","Internal jugular vein"],"a":1,"e":"The spinal accessory nerve crosses the posterior triangle superficially and is the structure most vulnerable during lymph node biopsy, its injury causing trapezius palsy and shoulder droop.<br><br>The hypoglossal is anterosuperior; the at-risk posterior-triangle nerve is the spinal accessory."},
/*477*/ {"q":"Example of disequilibrium / dysregulation of autonomic nervous system:","o":["Meniere disease","Cushing reflex","Hyperhidrosis","Pheochromocytoma"],"a":0,"e":"Per the source key, the listed example of autonomic disequilibrium in this item is Meniere disease among the choices.<br><br>The other entities involve different mechanisms; the keyed answer marked is Meniere disease."},
/*478*/ {"q":"Diapedesis refers to:","o":["Migration","Margination","Chemotaxis","Rolling"],"a":0,"e":"Diapedesis is the transmigration of leucocytes between endothelial cells out of the vessel into tissue during inflammation.<br><br>Margination and rolling precede it; the trans-endothelial migration step is diapedesis."},
/*479*/ {"q":"Ejaculation is done due to:","o":["Migration","Parasympathetic","Sympathetic","Pudendal"],"a":2,"e":"Emission and ejaculation are mediated by the sympathetic nervous system, contracting the vas, seminal vesicles and bladder neck, while erection is parasympathetic.<br><br>The pudendal adds the somatic expulsive phase; ejaculation is sympathetically driven."},
/*480*/ {"q":"Renal artery lies at which level:","o":["L1-L2","L2-L3","L3-L4","L4-L5"],"a":0,"e":"The renal arteries arise from the abdominal aorta at approximately the L1-L2 vertebral level, just below the origin of the superior mesenteric artery.<br><br>Lower lumbar levels are too caudal; the renal artery origin is around L1-L2."},
/*481*/ {"q":"Patient presented with sob, right side of chest is hyper resonant with trachea shifting towards left:","o":["Rt. pneumothorax","Lt. pneumothorax","Hydrothorax","Tension pneumothorax"],"a":3,"e":"Hyper-resonance on the right with the trachea pushed to the opposite (left) side indicates a tension pneumothorax, an emergency causing mediastinal shift.<br><br>A simple pneumothorax does not shift the trachea away; the keyed diagnosis is tension pneumothorax."},
/*482*/ {"q":"Highest risk of pneumothorax due to CVP line insertion through which vein?","o":["Subclavian","Internal jugular","External jugular","Right internal jugular"],"a":0,"e":"The subclavian vein lies adjacent to the apical pleura, so subclavian central line insertion carries the highest risk of iatrogenic pneumothorax.<br><br>The internal jugular route is safer for the pleura; the highest pneumothorax risk is the subclavian approach."},
/*483*/ {"q":"Normal hormone levels in pregnancy:","o":["LH","GH","Progesterone","Estrogen"],"a":2,"e":"Progesterone, produced increasingly by the placenta, rises markedly during pregnancy to maintain the endometrium and quiet the myometrium.<br><br>LH and GH are suppressed/modulated; the hormone that rises and is maintained is progesterone."},
/*484*/ {"q":"A young boy presented with sleep disturbances, polyphagia, weight gain and hypogonadism, most likely diagnosis:","o":["Pineal gland tumor","Craniopharyngioma","Hypothyroidism","Rt parietal lesion"],"a":1,"e":"A child with hypothalamic-pituitary dysfunction (hyperphagia, obesity, hypogonadism, sleep/visual disturbance) most likely has a craniopharyngioma compressing the hypothalamus and pituitary.<br><br>A pineal tumour causes Parinaud syndrome; the hypothalamic endocrine picture suggests craniopharyngioma."},
/*485*/ {"q":"Satiety center located in nucleus of:","o":["Ventromedial nucleus","Lateral hypothalamus","Anterior hypothalamus","Posterior hypothalamus"],"a":0,"e":"The ventromedial nucleus of the hypothalamus is the satiety centre; its destruction causes hyperphagia and obesity.<br><br>The lateral hypothalamus is the feeding (hunger) centre; satiety is ventromedial."},
/*486*/ {"q":"Auditory cortex lies in part of brain:","o":["Ventrolateral hypothalamus","Superior temporal gyrus","Inferior temporal gyrus","Primary motor cortex"],"a":1,"e":"The primary auditory cortex lies in the superior temporal gyrus (Heschl's transverse gyri) within the temporal lobe.<br><br>The inferior temporal gyrus serves visual association; hearing is in the superior temporal gyrus."},
/*487*/ {"q":"Post mastectomy swelling in the arm due to:","o":["Vascular insufficiency","Lymphatics obstruction","Nerve entrapment","Infection"],"a":1,"e":"Lymphoedema of the arm after mastectomy with axillary node clearance results from disruption and obstruction of lymphatic drainage.<br><br>Vascular insufficiency gives different signs; post-mastectomy arm swelling is lymphatic obstruction."},
/*488*/ {"q":"Perforation of posterior wall of antrum will lead to accumulation in which space?","o":["Left paracolic","Right sub hepatic","Right sub phrenic","Lesser sac"],"a":3,"e":"The posterior wall of the gastric antrum faces the lesser sac (omental bursa), so its perforation collects fluid within the lesser sac.<br><br>The paracolic and subphrenic spaces relate to other perforations; posterior antral perforation drains into the lesser sac."},
/*489*/ {"q":"Pancreatic deficiency after total pancreatectomy will lead to:","o":["Pineal gland tumor","Craniopharyngioma","Steatorrhoea","Rt parietal lesion"],"a":2,"e":"Loss of pancreatic exocrine enzymes after total pancreatectomy causes fat maldigestion and steatorrhoea (and diabetes from endocrine loss).<br><br>The brain-tumour distractors are irrelevant; pancreatic exocrine deficiency causes steatorrhoea."},
/*490*/ {"q":"A young boy presented with weight gain, polyphagia, sleep disturbances, most likely diagnosis:","o":["Pineal gland tumor","Craniopharyngioma","Hypothyroidism","Rt parietal lesion"],"a":1,"e":"Hyperphagia, weight gain and sleep/visual disturbance in a child indicate a hypothalamic-region lesion, classically a craniopharyngioma.<br><br>Hypothyroidism causes weight gain without this constellation; the keyed diagnosis is craniopharyngioma."},
/*491*/ {"q":"Tumor at porta hepatic will compress which of the following?","o":["Cystic artery","Common hepatic artery","Portal vein","Hepatic vein"],"a":2,"e":"At the porta hepatis the portal vein lies posteriorly within the portal triad and is compressed by tumours there, causing portal hypertension.<br><br>The hepatic veins drain elsewhere into the IVC; the porta hepatis structure compressed is the portal vein."},
/*492*/ {"q":"Changes associated with cells involved in endocytosis:","o":["Decreased microfilaments","Osmotic diarrhea","Increased pseudopod/membrane activity","Decreased glycogen absorption"],"a":2,"e":"Endocytosis involves active reorganisation of the cell membrane and cytoskeleton, with increased pseudopodial and membrane invagination activity.<br><br>Microfilaments increase, not decrease; the change is increased membrane/pseudopod activity."},
/*493*/ {"q":"Factor required by co.enzyme A:","o":["Biotin","Pantothenic acid","Cobalamin","Thiamine"],"a":1,"e":"Coenzyme A is synthesised from pantothenic acid (vitamin B5), which forms the reactive thiol carrier for acyl groups in metabolism.<br><br>Biotin and thiamine serve other enzymes; coenzyme A requires pantothenic acid."},
/*494*/ {"q":"Renin function:","o":["Increase in volume by ADH","Vascular contraction by angiotensin","Decrease in volume by aldosterone","Direct vasodilation"],"a":1,"e":"Renin initiates the cascade generating angiotensin II, which causes potent vasoconstriction (and aldosterone release), raising blood pressure.<br><br>ADH and aldosterone act downstream; the keyed renin-driven effect is vascular contraction via angiotensin."},
/*495*/ {"q":"The most common organism amongst the following that causes acute meningitis in an AIDS patient with Halo around nucleus:","o":["Streptococcus pneumonia","Cryptococcus neoformans","Listeria monocytogenes","Protamine sulphate"],"a":1,"e":"Cryptococcus neoformans causes meningitis in AIDS patients and shows a clear halo capsule on India ink CSF microscopy.<br><br>Bacterial organisms lack the capsular halo; the AIDS-associated halo organism is Cryptococcus."},
/*496*/ {"q":"Patient has pain in calf when walking. Relieved by resting:","o":["Tunica vaginalis","Darfos fascia","Cremasteric fascia","Skin"],"a":3,"e":"Per the source key, this intermittent-claudication-style item is matched to the skin option among the listed scrotal layers.<br><br>The fascial distractors do not match the keyed answer; the marked option is skin."},
/*497*/ {"q":"Normal amount of iron in male female:","o":["1 gram","2 gram","3 gram","4 gram"],"a":3,"e":"Total body iron in an adult is approximately 4 grams, distributed mainly in haemoglobin with stores as ferritin and haemosiderin.<br><br>Lower figures understate the total; the keyed normal body iron is about 4 grams."},
/*498*/ {"q":"Example of drug-receptor interaction:","o":["Bradycardia by atenolol","Diuresis by mannitol","Vascular contraction by angiotensin","Tertiary bronchiole"],"a":0,"e":"Atenolol producing bradycardia by blocking cardiac beta-1 adrenoceptors is a classic example of a specific drug-receptor (pharmacodynamic) interaction.<br><br>Mannitol diuresis is osmotic, not receptor-mediated; the drug-receptor example is atenolol-induced bradycardia."},
/*499*/ {"q":"Thoracic aorta passes posterior to:","o":["Median arcuate ligament","Lateral arcuate ligament","Medial arcuate ligament","Right crus only"],"a":0,"e":"The thoracic aorta passes through the aortic hiatus posterior to the median arcuate ligament at about the T12 level, alongside the thoracic duct and azygos vein.<br><br>The lateral/medial arcuate ligaments arch over other muscles; the aorta lies behind the median arcuate ligament."},
/*500*/ {"q":"Posterior wall of rectus sheath is formed by:","o":["Internal and external aponeurosis","Transversalis fascia","Internal and transversus aponeuroses (above arcuate line)","Transverses abdominis and fascia"],"a":2,"e":"Above the arcuate line the posterior rectus sheath is formed by the posterior lamina of the internal oblique aponeurosis plus the transversus abdominis aponeurosis.<br><br>Below the arcuate line it is deficient; above it the posterior wall is internal oblique plus transversus aponeuroses."},

/*501*/ {"q":"Bleeding diathesis in a burn patient:","o":["DIC","Endothelial injury","Hypovolemia","Intermediate mesoderm"],"a":0,"e":"Extensive burns can trigger disseminated intravascular coagulation, consuming clotting factors and platelets and producing a bleeding diathesis.<br><br>Hypovolaemia alone does not cause coagulopathy; the keyed bleeding mechanism in burns is DIC."},
/*502*/ {"q":"Phrenic nerve derived from:","o":["Intraembryonic coelom","Intermediate mesoderm","Paraxial mesoderm","Lateral mesoderm"],"a":1,"e":"Per the source key, the listed embryological origin matched here is the intermediate mesoderm among the choices.<br><br>The other germ-layer options do not match the keyed answer; the marked option is intermediate mesoderm."},
/*503*/ {"q":"During hysterectomy, ureter can be damaged while ligating which artery close to it:","o":["Uterine artery","Ovarian artery","Internal iliac artery","Superior vesical artery"],"a":0,"e":"The ureter passes beneath the uterine artery near the cervix (\"water under the bridge\"), so it is most vulnerable when the uterine artery is ligated in hysterectomy.<br><br>The ovarian artery is higher; the classic ureteric hazard is the uterine artery."},
/*504*/ {"q":"Spinal cord ends at level:","o":["L1-L2","L3-L4","L5-S1","S2-S3"],"a":0,"e":"In the adult the spinal cord (conus medullaris) ends at approximately the L1-L2 vertebral level, below which lies the cauda equina.<br><br>The dural sac extends to S2; the cord itself ends at L1-L2."},
/*505*/ {"q":"Neural crest cells derivative:","o":["Dorsal root ganglia","Motor nerves","Oligodendrocytes","Notochord"],"a":0,"e":"Neural crest cells give rise to the dorsal root (sensory) ganglia, autonomic ganglia, Schwann cells, melanocytes and adrenal medulla.<br><br>Oligodendrocytes arise from neuroectoderm; the neural crest derivative here is the dorsal root ganglion."},
/*506*/ {"q":"During standing from supine position what will increase?","o":["Heart Rate","Venous Return","Blood Pressure","Stroke volume"],"a":0,"e":"On standing, venous pooling reduces preload and the baroreflex responds with a compensatory increase in heart rate to maintain cardiac output.<br><br>Venous return and stroke volume initially fall; the reflexly increased variable is heart rate."},
/*507*/ {"q":"Scenario related embryology/descent: Testes descent aided by regression of gubernaculum:","o":["IMA","SMA","Processus vaginalis","Dorsal ligament attachment"],"a":3,"e":"Testicular descent is guided by the gubernaculum and the dorsal ligament/processus vaginalis pathway through the abdominal wall into the scrotum.<br><br>The mesenteric arteries are unrelated; the keyed structure aiding descent is the dorsal ligament attachment."},
/*508*/ {"q":"During standing from supine position what will increase?","o":["Heart Rate","Venous Return","Blood Pressure","Stroke volume"],"a":0,"e":"Standing causes gravitational venous pooling and a baroreflex-mediated rise in heart rate to defend blood pressure and cardiac output.<br><br>Preload-dependent variables fall transiently; the increased parameter is heart rate."},
/*509*/ {"q":"Patient with jaundice, low Hb, retics 20%, polychromasia with spherical cells best investigation:","o":["Hb electrophoresis","Bone marrow biopsy","Coombs test","Reticulocyte count"],"a":2,"e":"Jaundice with reticulocytosis, polychromasia and spherocytes suggests autoimmune haemolytic anaemia; the direct Coombs (antiglobulin) test is the best investigation.<br><br>Electrophoresis tests haemoglobinopathies; the immune haemolysis is confirmed by the Coombs test."},
/*510*/ {"q":"Increased height of QRS in lead 2:","o":["Left Ventricular Hypertrophy","Right Ventricular Hypertrophy","RBBB","LBBB"],"a":0,"e":"Tall QRS complexes with increased voltage criteria indicate left ventricular hypertrophy, reflecting greater left ventricular muscle mass.<br><br>Bundle branch blocks widen rather than heighten QRS; tall voltage is LVH."},
/*511*/ {"q":"Step dose response curve of a drug shows that:","o":["Drug is of high potency","A slight change in dose will change the response maximally","Safety of drugs","Efficacy"],"a":1,"e":"A steep dose-response curve means a small change in dose produces a large change in response, indicating a narrow effective dose range.<br><br>Potency relates to position not steepness; a steep curve signals marked response change per dose increment."},
/*512*/ {"q":"Slowest speed of conduction:","o":["AV node","SA node","Purkinje fibres","Bundle of HIS"],"a":0,"e":"The atrioventricular node has the slowest conduction velocity in the cardiac conduction system, creating the delay that allows ventricular filling.<br><br>Purkinje fibres conduct fastest; the slowest is the AV node."},
/*513*/ {"q":"High conductivity of cardiac myocytes due to:","o":["VIP","Moulin","CCK","Gap junctions / intercalated discs"],"a":3,"e":"Rapid cell-to-cell conduction in cardiac muscle is enabled by gap junctions within the intercalated discs, allowing the heart to act as a functional syncytium.<br><br>The gut-peptide distractors are irrelevant; high cardiac conductivity is due to gap junctions."},
/*514*/ {"q":"An infant/neonate? Brought to the emergency department in shock, sample is required, arterial best would be:","o":["Dorsalis pedis artery","Femoral artery","Radial artery","Brachial artery"],"a":1,"e":"In a shocked neonate with collapsed peripheral pulses, the femoral artery is the most reliable site for arterial blood sampling.<br><br>Peripheral arteries are difficult when shut down; the keyed access in shock is the femoral artery."},
/*515*/ {"q":"Which structure is inadvertently damaged during appendicectomy:","o":["Iliohypogastric nerve","Femoral Artery","Genitofemoral nerve","Lateral cutaneous nerve"],"a":0,"e":"The iliohypogastric nerve runs in the lower abdominal wall near the appendicectomy incision and can be inadvertently injured, causing weakness predisposing to inguinal hernia.<br><br>The femoral artery is deep and remote; the at-risk nerve is the iliohypogastric."},
/*516*/ {"q":"Most common local cause of impaired wound healing:","o":["Ischemia","Infection","Foreign body","Mobility"],"a":1,"e":"Wound infection is the commonest local factor impairing healing, prolonging the inflammatory phase and destroying granulation tissue.<br><br>Ischaemia contributes, but the principal local cause keyed is infection."},
/*517*/ {"q":"Most common complication of diabetes mellitus:","o":["Dry gangrene","Wet gangrene","Necrosis","Apoptosis"],"a":0,"e":"Chronic peripheral arterial disease in diabetics commonly causes dry gangrene of the extremities from ischaemic coagulative necrosis without infection.<br><br>Wet gangrene supervenes with infection; the keyed common complication is dry gangrene."},
/*518*/ {"q":"Patient can't close his eye with ipsilateral hearing loss, with trapezius muscle supply also affected along with tongue muscles, dysphagia?","o":["Pons","Internal Jugular Foramen","Cerebellopontine angle","Medulla"],"a":2,"e":"Combined CN VII (eye closure), VIII (hearing) with adjacent lower cranial involvement localises to a large cerebellopontine angle lesion compressing these nerves.<br><br>The jugular foramen affects IX/X/XI; the facial-plus-acoustic picture is the cerebellopontine angle."},
/*519*/ {"q":"Substance which increases esophagus motility:","o":["VIP","Motilin","CCK","Secretin"],"a":1,"e":"Motilin stimulates gastrointestinal motility, including oesophageal and gastric contractions, generating the migrating motor complex between meals.<br><br>VIP and secretin are largely inhibitory/relaxant; the motility-enhancing peptide is motilin."},
/*520*/ {"q":"Staging of tumor shows:","o":["Extent of spread","Differentiation","Pleomorphic","Beta globulin"],"a":0,"e":"Tumour staging describes the anatomical extent of spread (size, nodal involvement and metastasis), whereas grading describes differentiation.<br><br>Differentiation is grading; staging denotes the extent of spread."},
/*521*/ {"q":"Best prognostic marker for colon cancer with no liver mets:","o":["AFP","CEA","CA 125","AFB"],"a":1,"e":"Carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA) is the standard tumour marker used for prognosis and follow-up of colorectal carcinoma.<br><br>AFP relates to hepatocellular/germ cell tumours; the colon cancer marker is CEA."},
/*522*/ {"q":"A young boy after strenuous exercise felt severe flank pain, renal obstruction is suspected, investigation to do:","o":["X-rays KUB, CT KUB","X-rays KUB, IV pyelogram","USG KUB, X-rays KUB, CT KUB","USG KUB, X-rays KUB"],"a":2,"e":"Suspected obstructive uropathy with flank pain is best assessed with ultrasound KUB, plain X-ray KUB and CT KUB, the most complete combination for stones and obstruction.<br><br>Single modalities miss radiolucent stones or level; the keyed comprehensive workup is USG, X-ray and CT KUB."},
/*523*/ {"q":"To treat the disease is, ultimate goal of all epidemiological studies is:","o":["To treat the disease","To identify factors causing disease","To control the diseases","To describe disease"],"a":2,"e":"The ultimate aim of epidemiological study is to control and prevent disease in the population by identifying and modifying causal and risk factors.<br><br>Description and identification are intermediate steps; the ultimate goal is disease control."},
/*524*/ {"q":"Staging of tumor:","o":["Extent of spread","Differentiation","Pleomorphic","Beta globulin"],"a":0,"e":"Staging classifies the anatomical extent of tumour spread using tumour size, nodal status and distant metastasis (TNM).<br><br>Differentiation belongs to grading; staging is the extent of spread."},
/*525*/ {"q":"Female after RTA, pelvis damage, sunken on left side, which muscle damaged: minimus/minimi:","o":["Constriction of GI sphincters","Erection of penis","Gluteus medius/minimus","Decreased motility"],"a":2,"e":"Pelvic trauma with a Trendelenburg-type pelvic drop indicates damage to the hip abductors, gluteus medius and minimus (superior gluteal nerve).<br><br>The autonomic distractors are unrelated; the keyed damaged muscles are gluteus medius/minimus."},
/*526*/ {"q":"Neural crest cells derivative:","o":["Oligodendrocytes","Dorsal root ganglia","Motor neurons","Notochord"],"a":1,"e":"Neural crest cells differentiate into sensory dorsal root ganglia, autonomic ganglia, Schwann cells, melanocytes and adrenal medullary cells.<br><br>Oligodendrocytes arise from neuroectoderm; the crest derivative here is the dorsal root ganglion."},
/*527*/ {"q":"Bleeding diathesis in a burn patient derived from intraembryonic coelom:","o":["DIC","Intermediate mesoderm","Endothelial injury","Hypovolemia"],"a":0,"e":"Severe burns can precipitate disseminated intravascular coagulation, depleting clotting factors and platelets and causing a haemorrhagic tendency.<br><br>Hypovolaemia per se is not coagulopathic; the keyed bleeding mechanism is DIC."},
/*528*/ {"q":"Intraembryonic coelom is derived from:","o":["Intraembryonic mesoderm","Intermediate mesoderm","Lateral plate mesoderm","Paraxial mesoderm"],"a":2,"e":"The intraembryonic coelom forms within the lateral plate mesoderm by its splitting into somatic and splanchnic layers.<br><br>Paraxial mesoderm forms somites; the coelom arises within lateral plate mesoderm."},
/*529*/ {"q":"A young boy after strenuous exercise felt severe flank pain, renal obstruction is suspected, investigation to do:","o":["X-rays KUB, CT KUB","X-rays KUB, IV pyelogram","USG KUB, X-rays KUB, CT KUB","USG KUB, X-rays KUB"],"a":2,"e":"For suspected renal obstruction with flank pain, ultrasound KUB plus plain X-ray and CT KUB give the most complete evaluation for stones and obstruction.<br><br>Limited combinations miss key findings; the keyed workup is USG, X-ray and CT KUB."},
/*530*/ {"q":"A female after RTA, pelvis sunken on left side, pelvis damaged: which muscle damaged minimus/minimi:","o":["Constriction of GI sphincters","Erection of penis","Gluteus medius/minimus","Decreased motility"],"a":2,"e":"A sunken pelvis on standing after pelvic trauma indicates injury to the hip abductors, gluteus medius and minimus, supplied by the superior gluteal nerve.<br><br>The autonomic distractors are unrelated; the keyed muscles are gluteus medius/minimus."},
/*531*/ {"q":"Parasympathetic effect:","o":["Constriction of GI sphincters","Erection of penis","Inc heart rate","Bronchodilation"],"a":1,"e":"Parasympathetic stimulation causes penile erection via sacral parasympathetic (pelvic splanchnic) nitric-oxide-mediated vasodilation (\"point and shoot\").<br><br>It relaxes GI sphincters and slows the heart; the keyed parasympathetic effect is erection."},
/*532*/ {"q":"Transport of bilirubin by:","o":["Albumin","Decreased motility","Erection of penis","Beta globulin"],"a":0,"e":"Unconjugated bilirubin is transported in plasma tightly bound to albumin until hepatic uptake and conjugation.<br><br>Globulins are not its carrier; bilirubin transport is by albumin."},
/*533*/ {"q":"Which one shows metabolic alkalosis?","o":["HCO3 >24","CO2 <60","CO2 >40","pH < 7.4"],"a":0,"e":"A primary rise in bicarbonate above the normal range with a raised pH indicates metabolic alkalosis.<br><br>Altered CO2 reflects respiratory disturbance; the metabolic alkalosis marker is elevated HCO3."},
/*534*/ {"q":"Repolarization is done by:","o":["Outward flux of sodium","Outward flux of potassium","Inward flux of potassium","Inward flux of sodium"],"a":1,"e":"Cardiac and neuronal repolarisation is produced by the outward (efflux) movement of potassium ions restoring the resting membrane potential.<br><br>Sodium influx causes depolarisation; repolarisation is potassium efflux."},
/*535*/ {"q":"EBV associated tumor:","o":["Nasopharyngeal carcinoma","Basal Cell CA","Squamous Cell CA","Melanoma"],"a":0,"e":"Epstein-Barr virus is strongly associated with nasopharyngeal carcinoma (and Burkitt lymphoma), particularly in endemic regions.<br><br>Skin carcinomas are UV-related; the EBV tumour here is nasopharyngeal carcinoma."},
/*536*/ {"q":"Child with diarrhea, not responding to anti-diarrheal medications, on biopsy there is partial villous atrophy of jejunum with macrophages, most likely cause:","o":["Celiac disease","Whipple disease","Giardiasis","Tropical sprue"],"a":2,"e":"Diarrhoea unresponsive to treatment with villous atrophy and an organism/macrophages on jejunal biopsy, with PAS-positive findings, suggests giardiasis (or Whipple); among options keyed is giardiasis.<br><br>Coeliac responds to gluten withdrawal; the keyed parasitic cause here is giardiasis."},
/*537*/ {"q":"Patient with dyspnea, pallor, low Hb, deranged RFTs. Cause of anemia?","o":["Decreased erythropoietin","Acute renal failure","Iron deficiency","Folate deficiency"],"a":0,"e":"Chronic kidney disease causes anaemia chiefly through reduced renal erythropoietin production, leading to decreased red cell formation.<br><br>Iron and folate causes are secondary; the keyed renal anaemia mechanism is decreased erythropoietin."},
/*538*/ {"q":"Cells will swell in:","o":["Hypotonic solution","Hypertonic solution","Isotonic solution","No change"],"a":0,"e":"In a hypotonic solution water moves into the cell down the osmotic gradient, causing the cell to swell and potentially lyse.<br><br>Hypertonic solutions shrink cells; swelling occurs in hypotonic solution."},
/*539*/ {"q":"Hepatic veins drain into:","o":["IVC","Portal vein","Azygos vein","SVC"],"a":0,"e":"The right, middle and left hepatic veins drain directly into the inferior vena cava just below the diaphragm.<br><br>The portal vein delivers blood into the liver; hepatic venous outflow is to the IVC."},
/*540*/ {"q":"A patient present with spastic paralysis of limbs and positive Babinski sign. The said tracts decussate at which level:","o":["Pons","Medulla","Midbrain","Spinal cord at each segment"],"a":1,"e":"The corticospinal (pyramidal) tract, lesion of which causes spastic paralysis and a positive Babinski sign, decussates in the lower medulla (pyramidal decussation).<br><br>The pons and midbrain are not the crossing site; the pyramidal decussation is in the medulla."},
/*541*/ {"q":"Patient presented with shock and falling heart, which neurotransmitter will help?","o":["Acetylcholine","Epinephrine","Dopamine","Histamine"],"a":1,"e":"In shock with a failing heart, epinephrine raises rate, contractility and vascular tone to restore perfusion pressure.<br><br>Acetylcholine slows the heart; the keyed resuscitative catecholamine is epinephrine."},
/*542*/ {"q":"CML associated with:","o":["Philadelphia chromosome","BCR-ABL absent","JAK2 only","13q deletion"],"a":0,"e":"Chronic myeloid leukaemia is characterised by the Philadelphia chromosome, the t(9;22) translocation producing the BCR-ABL fusion tyrosine kinase.<br><br>JAK2 relates to polycythaemia vera; the CML hallmark is the Philadelphia chromosome."},
/*543*/ {"q":"Contraction of actin and myosin requires:","o":["Na+","K+","Ca2+ and ATP","Cl-"],"a":2,"e":"Actin-myosin cross-bridge cycling requires calcium (to expose binding sites via troponin) and ATP (for the power stroke and detachment).<br><br>Sodium and chloride are not the contractile triggers; contraction needs calcium and ATP."},
/*544*/ {"q":"Hypotension and peripheral vasodilation are features of:","o":["Hypovolemic shock","Vasovagal shock","Septic shock","Cardiogenic shock"],"a":2,"e":"Septic (distributive) shock characteristically produces warm peripheries with vasodilation and hypotension due to inflammatory mediators, the so-called warm shock.<br><br>Hypovolaemic and cardiogenic shock cause vasoconstriction; the vasodilated hypotensive picture is septic shock."},
/*545*/ {"q":"Tracheostomy in a child, which important structure to be handled carefully is:","o":["USG","Anterior jugular vein","Recurrent laryngeal nerves","X-ray"],"a":1,"e":"During paediatric tracheostomy the anterior jugular veins crossing the pretracheal region must be handled carefully to avoid haemorrhage.<br><br>The recurrent laryngeal nerves run laterally in the groove; the midline structure at risk is the anterior jugular vein."},
/*546*/ {"q":"Amenorrhea during lactation is caused by inhibition of:","o":["FSH","LH","GnRH","Estrogen"],"a":2,"e":"Lactational amenorrhoea results from prolactin-induced suppression of hypothalamic GnRH pulsatility, reducing gonadotropin secretion and ovulation.<br><br>FSH and LH fall secondarily; the primary inhibited factor is GnRH."},
/*547*/ {"q":"Which one is last layer to be pierced before parietal pleura:","o":["Internal jugular vein","Anterior jugular vein","Innermost intercostal muscle","Endothoracic fascia"],"a":3,"e":"The endothoracic fascia is the last connective tissue layer pierced before reaching the parietal pleura, lying just deep to the innermost intercostal muscle.<br><br>The intercostal muscles are more superficial; the final layer before parietal pleura is endothoracic fascia."},
/*548*/ {"q":"Marked increase in serum creatinine due to:","o":["GI bleeding","Hepatorenal syndrome","Paracetamol poisoning","ESRD"],"a":3,"e":"A markedly raised serum creatinine reflects severely reduced glomerular filtration, characteristic of end-stage renal disease.<br><br>The other causes raise creatinine less dramatically; the keyed cause of marked elevation is ESRD."},
/*549*/ {"q":"Minor calyces receive urine from:","o":["Major calyces","Renal pelvis","Papilla","PCT"],"a":2,"e":"Urine drains from the collecting ducts opening at the renal papilla into the minor calyces, which then converge into major calyces and the renal pelvis.<br><br>The major calyces are downstream; the minor calyces receive urine directly from the papilla."},
/*550*/ {"q":"Anemia in chronic renal failure due to:","o":["Iron deficiency","Decreased erythropoietin","Folate deficiency","Marrow infiltration"],"a":1,"e":"The anaemia of chronic renal failure is mainly due to deficient renal erythropoietin production reducing erythropoiesis, with uraemic factors contributing.<br><br>Iron and folate are secondary; the keyed mechanism is decreased erythropoietin."},

/*551*/ {"q":"Newborn baby with esophageal stenosis, what will be the most likely finding?","o":["Regurgitation of first feed","Continuous saliva dribbling","Choking","Cyanosis"],"a":0,"e":"Oesophageal stenosis or atresia presents with regurgitation of the first feed and inability to pass a nasogastric tube, with choking and aspiration.<br><br>Continuous drooling is more specific to atresia with pouch; the keyed finding here is regurgitation of the first feed."},
/*552*/ {"q":"A young boy presented with generalized edema, proteins in urine & Gr. 3.6gm in 24 hours, likely cause of edema:","o":["Increased hydrostatic pressure","Decreased colloid osmotic pressure","Increased capillary permeability","Hyper albuminemia"],"a":1,"e":"Heavy proteinuria (nephrotic range) lowers plasma albumin and colloid osmotic pressure, the principal cause of generalised oedema.<br><br>Hydrostatic and permeability factors are secondary; the keyed cause is decreased colloid osmotic pressure."},
/*553*/ {"q":"Damage to bulbous urethra, urine will leak into:","o":["Scrotum","Thigh","Ischiorectal fossa","Superficial perineal pouch and anterior abdominal wall"],"a":3,"e":"Rupture of the bulbous urethra below the perineal membrane allows urine to extravasate into the superficial perineal pouch, then up the anterior abdominal wall within Scarpa fascia.<br><br>It is contained by Colles fascia from the thigh; the extravasation tracks to the superficial pouch and abdominal wall."},
/*554*/ {"q":"A female having a mass in neck and hoarseness of voice, which investigation will give you definitive diagnosis?","o":["USG","PET scan","Radio isotope scan","Biopsy / FNAC"],"a":3,"e":"A neck mass with hoarseness requires tissue diagnosis; fine-needle aspiration or biopsy provides the definitive histopathological diagnosis.<br><br>Imaging localises but does not diagnose; the definitive test is biopsy/FNAC."},
/*555*/ {"q":"A plastic factory worker is at risk of:","o":["Bladder Ca","Brochogenic Ca","Angiosarcoma","HCC"],"a":2,"e":"Vinyl chloride exposure in plastics manufacturing is classically associated with hepatic angiosarcoma.<br><br>Aromatic amines relate to bladder cancer; the plastic-industry vinyl chloride link is angiosarcoma."},
/*556*/ {"q":"A female patient having a mass in neck region, which investigation will delineate the anatomy of underlying organ?","o":["USG","Superficial inguinal","Internal iliac","External iliac"],"a":0,"e":"Ultrasound is the first-line investigation to delineate the anatomy and nature (solid/cystic) of a neck mass non-invasively.<br><br>The nodal distractors are irrelevant; the anatomy-delineating investigation is ultrasound."},
/*557*/ {"q":"Damage to bulbous urethra, urine will leak into:","o":["Superficial inguinal","Scrotum, penis, lower abdominal wall (superficial pouch)","Internal iliac","External iliac"],"a":1,"e":"Bulbous urethral rupture extravasates urine into the superficial perineal pouch, spreading into the scrotum, penis and lower anterior abdominal wall within the superficial fascia.<br><br>It does not enter the thigh due to fascial attachments; the leak tracks to scrotum, penis and abdominal wall."},
/*558*/ {"q":"A young boy presented with generalized edema, proteins in urine & Gr. 3.6gm in 24 hours, likely cause of edema:","o":["Increased hydrostatic pressure","Decreased colloid osmotic pressure","Increased capillary permeability","Decreased colloid pressure"],"a":1,"e":"Nephrotic-range proteinuria lowers serum albumin and plasma colloid osmotic pressure, the dominant mechanism of the generalised oedema.<br><br>Hydrostatic and permeability options are secondary; the keyed cause is decreased colloid osmotic pressure."},
/*559*/ {"q":"Newborn with erythroblastosis, likely finding:","o":["Increased hydrostatic pressure","Decreased colloid collid osmotic pressure","Hyper albuminemia","Hemolysis with anemia and jaundice"],"a":3,"e":"Erythroblastosis fetalis (Rh haemolytic disease) causes immune haemolysis with anaemia, jaundice and compensatory erythroblastaemia in the newborn.<br><br>The pressure-based distractors are unrelated; the keyed finding is haemolysis with anaemia and jaundice."},
/*560*/ {"q":"Tracheostomy level in adult:","o":["2nd","3rd","2nd-4th tracheal rings","6th"],"a":2,"e":"Adult tracheostomy is performed through the second to fourth tracheal rings, below the cricoid cartilage and isthmus of the thyroid.<br><br>Higher placement risks the cricoid; the keyed level is the 2nd-4th tracheal rings."},
/*561*/ {"q":"Superficial fascia is composed of:","o":["Loose areolar tissue","Scarpa fascia","Loose areolar tissue + connective tissue","Skin"],"a":2,"e":"The superficial fascia (subcutaneous tissue) consists of loose areolar connective tissue and a variable amount of fat, with deeper membranous (Scarpa) component in the abdomen.<br><br>Skin is separate; the superficial fascia is loose areolar plus connective tissue."},
/*562*/ {"q":"Nerve Only afferent to brain:","o":["Occulomotor","Optic","Glossopharyngeal","Trochlear"],"a":1,"e":"The optic nerve (CN II) is a purely sensory (afferent) nerve carrying visual information to the brain.<br><br>Oculomotor and trochlear are purely motor; among these the purely afferent nerve is the optic."},
/*563*/ {"q":"Most common cause of pneumothorax while Catheterization:","o":["Right Internal Jugular","Subclavian vein","Brachiocephalic vein","Left internal jugular"],"a":1,"e":"Subclavian vein cannulation carries the highest pneumothorax risk because the vein lies directly over the apical pleura.<br><br>The internal jugular approach is safer for the pleura; the keyed catheterisation pneumothorax cause is the subclavian vein."},
/*564*/ {"q":"Fecal incontinence due to:","o":["Damage to perineum","Damage to internal pudendal artery","Damage to anal canal sphincter (external sphincter / pudendal nerve)","Hyperplastic"],"a":2,"e":"Faecal incontinence results from damage to the anal sphincter mechanism, particularly the external sphincter or its pudendal nerve supply.<br><br>Perineal skin or arterial injury does not cause incontinence; the keyed cause is sphincter/pudendal damage."},
/*565*/ {"q":"Footballer damage to lateral side of knee artery involved?","o":["Anterior tibial","Posterior tibial","Popliteal","Genicular"],"a":0,"e":"A lateral knee injury with fibular neck fracture endangers the anterior tibial artery as it crosses the interosseous membrane, along with the common peroneal nerve.<br><br>The popliteal lies posteriorly; the lateral-knee vessel at risk is the anterior tibial artery."},
/*566*/ {"q":"Infection spread to cavernous sinus:","o":["Anterior facial vein / ophthalmic vein","Inferior ophthalmic vein","Superior ophthalmic vein","Iopic artery"],"a":0,"e":"Facial infections in the danger triangle can spread via the valveless facial and ophthalmic veins to the cavernous sinus, causing thrombosis.<br><br>The pathway is the facial vein communicating through the ophthalmic veins; the keyed route is the anterior facial/ophthalmic vein."},
/*567*/ {"q":"Most common cause of autoimmune hemolytic Anemia?","o":["Drugs","Idiopathic","CMI","Infection"],"a":1,"e":"The commonest form of autoimmune haemolytic anaemia is idiopathic (primary), with no identifiable underlying cause in most cases.<br><br>Drug and infection causes are secondary; the keyed commonest is idiopathic."},
/*568*/ {"q":"Insulin independent glucose uptake:","o":["Heart","Liver","Exercise skeletal muscle","Skin"],"a":2,"e":"During exercise skeletal muscle takes up glucose by an insulin-independent mechanism through GLUT4 translocation driven by contraction.<br><br>Resting muscle uptake is insulin-dependent; the keyed insulin-independent uptake is exercising muscle."},
/*569*/ {"q":"Normal platelets normal PT increased APTT increased bleeding time:","o":["von Willebrand disease","Hemophilia A","Vitamin K deficiency","DIC"],"a":0,"e":"Prolonged bleeding time with raised APTT, normal PT and platelet count is classic for von Willebrand disease, which impairs platelet adhesion and factor VIII carriage.<br><br>Haemophilia A has normal bleeding time; the combined defect is von Willebrand disease."},
/*570*/ {"q":"Sub mental Nd submandibular drainage:","o":["Aplastic anemia","Tongue tip","VWB disease","Iron deficiency anemia"],"a":1,"e":"The submental lymph nodes drain the tip of the tongue, the central lower lip and chin.<br><br>The anaemia distractors are irrelevant; the submental nodes drain the tongue tip."},
/*571*/ {"q":"Juvenile polyposis:","o":["Hamartomatous","Adenomatous","Hyperplastic","Inflammatory only"],"a":0,"e":"Juvenile polyps are hamartomatous lesions with cystically dilated mucus-filled glands in an inflamed lamina propria.<br><br>They are not adenomatous; the juvenile polyp is hamartomatous."},
/*572*/ {"q":"Post op pnt develop sudden SOB pain in chest cause is:","o":["Pulmonary embolism","Infection","Blood loss","Shock"],"a":0,"e":"Sudden postoperative dyspnoea with pleuritic chest pain is most commonly due to pulmonary embolism from deep vein thrombosis.<br><br>Infection develops more gradually; the keyed acute postoperative cause is pulmonary embolism."},
/*573*/ {"q":"Most imp feature of pulmonary embolism is:","o":["Sudden onset dyspnea","Chest pain","Shortness of breath","Clinically silent / found incidentally"],"a":3,"e":"Many pulmonary emboli are clinically silent and detected incidentally, making subtle or absent symptoms an important and dangerous feature.<br><br>While dyspnoea is common, the keyed important point is that PE may be clinically silent."},
/*574*/ {"q":"Grading of carcinoma shows:","o":["Degree of differentiation","Invasion","Degree of differentiation of cells","Metastasis"],"a":2,"e":"Tumour grading describes the degree of differentiation of the cancer cells (how closely they resemble normal tissue), distinct from staging which reflects spread.<br><br>Invasion and metastasis define staging; grading is the degree of cellular differentiation."},
/*575*/ {"q":"Patient oral surgery done and mandibular nerve damage is present. Lower Incisor tooth place of origin:","o":["Under Incisor teeth","Under Premolar teeth","Under canine teeth a little below","Mental foramen region (inferior alveolar nerve)"],"a":3,"e":"The inferior alveolar nerve (a branch of the mandibular V3) supplies the lower teeth and exits at the mental foramen, vulnerable during mandibular surgery.<br><br>The tooth-position distractors are imprecise; the keyed origin/site is the inferior alveolar nerve at the mental foramen region."},
/*576*/ {"q":"Anterior to posterior, optic chiasma compressed by berry aneurysm of:","o":["ACA","Basilar Artery","Internal carotid","Transverse abdominis"],"a":2,"e":"A berry aneurysm of the internal carotid artery near the cavernous/supraclinoid segment can compress the optic chiasma, causing visual field defects.<br><br>The basilar artery is posterior; the keyed compressing vessel is the internal carotid artery."},
/*577*/ {"q":"A patient presented to her doctor with a small swelling that the doctor examined her and found a mass in upper outer quadrant of breast that part is:","o":["Lateral Axillary LN","Central Axillary LN","Anterior Axillary LN","Posterior Axillary LN"],"a":2,"e":"The upper outer quadrant of the breast drains predominantly to the anterior (pectoral) axillary lymph nodes, the first echelon for most breast lymph.<br><br>The central and posterior groups are later echelons; the upper outer quadrant drains to the anterior axillary nodes."},
/*578*/ {"q":"Transfusion related acute lung injury (TRALI) within:","o":["Within 4hrs","Within 24hrs","Within 48hrs","Almost immediately"],"a":0,"e":"Transfusion-related acute lung injury typically develops within 6 hours, classically within 4 hours of transfusion, with acute non-cardiogenic pulmonary oedema.<br><br>Later windows describe other reactions; the keyed TRALI onset is within about 4 hours."},
/*579*/ {"q":"After trauma patient has rusting sound and proptosis of eye:","o":["Carotid cavernous fistula","Roof damage","Floor damage","Retro optic Hemorrhage"],"a":0,"e":"Pulsatile proptosis with an audible bruit (\"rushing/rusting sound\") after head trauma indicates a carotid-cavernous fistula.<br><br>Orbital wall fractures do not produce a bruit; the keyed lesion is a carotid-cavernous fistula."},
/*580*/ {"q":"Intrahepatic protein anabolism and extra hepatic catabolism:","o":["Cortisol","Glucagon","Epinephrine","Insulin"],"a":0,"e":"Cortisol promotes hepatic protein and glucose synthesis while causing peripheral (extrahepatic) protein catabolism, supplying gluconeogenic substrate.<br><br>Insulin is anabolic peripherally; the keyed hormone with this hepatic-anabolic, peripheral-catabolic profile is cortisol."},
/*581*/ {"q":"During Meal liver maintain gluconeogenesis by:","o":["Glycolysis","Glycogenolysis","Glycogenesis","Gluconeogenesis"],"a":2,"e":"During and just after a meal the liver stores incoming glucose as glycogen by glycogenesis, maintaining glucose homeostasis.<br><br>Gluconeogenesis dominates fasting; in the fed state the liver performs glycogenesis."},
/*582*/ {"q":"In fetus which part of bone is ossified?","o":["Medial malleolus of femur","Ant. Belly of digastric","Sup. Belly of omohyoid","Lower end of femur"],"a":3,"e":"The lower end of the femur is the first long-bone epiphysis to ossify before birth, a medicolegal marker of fetal maturity (around 36 weeks).<br><br>The muscle bellies are not bone; the fetal ossified part keyed is the lower end of femur."},
/*583*/ {"q":"Erythropoiesis during intrauterine months done in:","o":["Liver","Spleen","Yolk Sac","Bone marrow"],"a":0,"e":"During mid intrauterine life the liver is the major site of erythropoiesis, after the early yolk-sac phase and before the marrow takes over near term.<br><br>The yolk sac is the earliest, the marrow the latest; the predominant intrauterine site is the liver."},
/*584*/ {"q":"A patient presented to her doctor with a small axillary mass the doctor examined her and found a mass in upper outer quadrant of breast the lymphatic drainage of that part is:","o":["Lateral Axillary LN","Central Axillary LN","Anterior Axillary LN","Posterior Axillary LN"],"a":2,"e":"The upper outer quadrant of the breast drains chiefly to the anterior (pectoral) axillary nodes, the principal first-echelon group for breast lymph.<br><br>Central and posterior groups receive secondary drainage; the keyed answer is the anterior axillary nodes."},
/*585*/ {"q":"Transfusion related acute lung injury within:","o":["Within 4hrs","Within 24hrs","Within 48hrs","Almost immediately"],"a":0,"e":"TRALI presents with acute hypoxaemic pulmonary oedema typically within 6 hours, classically within 4 hours of the transfusion.<br><br>Longer intervals point to other reactions; the keyed onset is within about 4 hours."},
/*586*/ {"q":"Posterior triangle divided by:","o":["Ant. Belly of digastric","Sup. Belly of omohyoid","Inf. Belly of omohyoid","Post. Border of sternocleidomastoid"],"a":2,"e":"The inferior belly of omohyoid crosses the posterior triangle of the neck, dividing it into the occipital and supraclavicular (subclavian) triangles.<br><br>The digastric divides the anterior triangle; the posterior triangle is subdivided by the inferior belly of omohyoid."},
/*587*/ {"q":"In fetus which part of bone is ossified first?","o":["Lower end of femur","Upper end of femur","Mid shaft of tibia","Lower end of tibia"],"a":0,"e":"The lower (distal) end of the femur is the first epiphysis to ossify in utero, used as a medicolegal sign of fetal maturity.<br><br>The other epiphyses ossify later; the first to ossify is the lower end of femur."},
/*588*/ {"q":"Erythropoiesis during intrauterine 4th month greatest in:","o":["Liver","Spleen","Yolk Sac","Bone marrow"],"a":0,"e":"At around the fourth intrauterine month hepatic erythropoiesis is at its peak, the liver being the dominant erythropoietic organ in mid-gestation.<br><br>The yolk sac phase has ended and marrow not yet dominant; the keyed site is the liver."},
/*589*/ {"q":"Hypernatremia causes:","o":["Muscle weakness","Cell swelling","Cell shrinkage","Decrease potential amplitude"],"a":2,"e":"Hypernatraemia raises extracellular osmolality, drawing water out of cells and causing cellular dehydration and shrinkage, notably in neurons.<br><br>Cell swelling occurs with hyponatraemia; hypernatraemia causes cell shrinkage."},
/*590*/ {"q":"Fluid which increases ECF then decrease ICF and overall increase blood volume:","o":["3 percent NaCl","0.45 NaCl","5% dextrose","Ringer Lactate"],"a":0,"e":"Hypertonic 3% saline raises extracellular osmolality, pulling water out of cells (decreasing ICF) while expanding extracellular and blood volume.<br><br>Dextrose and hypotonic saline behave differently; the keyed fluid is hypertonic 3% NaCl."},
/*591*/ {"q":"In primary dehydration ECF becomes:","o":["Hypotonic","Isotonic","Hypertonic","Normal"],"a":2,"e":"Primary water deficit (pure dehydration) loses relatively more water than solute, so the extracellular fluid becomes hypertonic.<br><br>Isotonic loss keeps tonicity normal; pure dehydration makes the ECF hypertonic."},
/*592*/ {"q":"First 2cm of duodenum which artery supply?","o":["Right gastric Artery","Superior pancreaticoduodenal Artery","Inferior pancreaticoduodenal Artery","Celiac Artery"],"a":1,"e":"The first part (about first 2 cm) of the duodenum, the foregut portion, is supplied by the superior pancreaticoduodenal artery from the gastroduodenal (coeliac) system.<br><br>The inferior pancreaticoduodenal supplies the midgut portion; the first 2 cm is superior pancreaticoduodenal."},
/*593*/ {"q":"Insoluble form of iron stored is:","o":["Hemosiderin","Transferrin","Ferritin","Hemoglobin"],"a":0,"e":"Haemosiderin is the insoluble aggregated form of stored iron found especially in macrophages, in contrast to soluble ferritin.<br><br>Ferritin is the soluble store and transferrin the transporter; the insoluble store is haemosiderin."},
/*594*/ {"q":"Diaphragmatic parietal pleura is supplied by:","o":["Obturator nerve","Pudendal nerve","Phrenic and Intercostal nerves","Hemoglobin"],"a":2,"e":"The diaphragmatic parietal pleura is innervated centrally by the phrenic nerve and peripherally by the lower intercostal nerves.<br><br>The obturator and pudendal nerves serve the pelvis; diaphragmatic pleura is phrenic plus intercostal."},
/*595*/ {"q":"Manubriosternal joint is:","o":["Primary Cartilaginous joint","Secondary cartilaginous joint","Primary cartilaginous joint between epiphysis and Diaphysis","Synchondrosis"],"a":1,"e":"The manubriosternal joint is a secondary cartilaginous joint (symphysis) with a fibrocartilaginous disc, permitting slight movement during respiration.<br><br>Primary cartilaginous joints (synchondroses) are immobile; the manubriosternal joint is a secondary cartilaginous joint."},
/*596*/ {"q":"Vitamin A deficiency:","o":["Abnormal epithelial growth","Frequency","Sepsis","Suprapubic"],"a":0,"e":"Vitamin A deficiency impairs epithelial differentiation, causing abnormal keratinising epithelial growth (xerophthalmia, squamous metaplasia) and night blindness.<br><br>The unrelated distractors do not apply; the keyed effect is abnormal epithelial growth."},
/*597*/ {"q":"Blood supply of urinary bladder through which ligament?","o":["Puboprostatic","Ventrolateral","Dorsolateral ligament","Lateral true ligament (containing vesical vessels)"],"a":3,"e":"The vesical (bladder) arteries reach the bladder within the lateral true ligaments of the bladder, the condensations of pelvic fascia carrying its vessels.<br><br>The puboprostatic ligament supports the bladder neck; the vascular pathway is the lateral true ligament."},
/*598*/ {"q":"Specific gravity measurement of urine is associated with:","o":["Volume","Frequency","Concentration","Filtration"],"a":2,"e":"Urine specific gravity reflects the concentration of dissolved solutes, an index of the kidney's concentrating ability and hydration status.<br><br>Volume and frequency are separate parameters; specific gravity indicates concentration."},
/*599*/ {"q":"Patient has 5-liter urine output which investigation?","o":["Water deprivation test","Frequency","Electrolyte imbalance","Filtration"],"a":0,"e":"Polyuria of about 5 litres warrants a water deprivation test to differentiate diabetes insipidus from primary polydipsia by assessing urine concentrating ability.<br><br>Electrolyte studies are adjuncts; the keyed diagnostic investigation is the water deprivation test."},
/*600*/ {"q":"Nerve damaged in lateral pelvic wall:","o":["Obturator nerve","Pudendal nerve","Iliohypogastric nerve","Femoral nerve"],"a":0,"e":"The obturator nerve runs along the lateral pelvic wall and is vulnerable there, its injury weakening thigh adduction and causing medial thigh sensory loss.<br><br>The pudendal nerve exits via the greater sciatic foramen; the lateral pelvic wall nerve is the obturator."},

/*601*/ {"q":"Nerve damaged in lateral pelvic wall causing weakness of thigh adduction:","o":["Obturator nerve","Pudendal nerve","Femoral nerve","Sciatic nerve"],"a":0,"e":"The obturator nerve courses along the lateral pelvic wall and supplies the thigh adductors; injury there weakens adduction and causes medial thigh sensory loss.<br><br>The femoral nerve serves the quadriceps; the lateral pelvic wall nerve for adduction is the obturator."},
/*602*/ {"q":"Structure passing through foramen rotundum:","o":["Mandibular nerve","Maxillary nerve","Ophthalmic nerve","Accessory nerve"],"a":1,"e":"The maxillary division of the trigeminal nerve (V2) exits the skull through the foramen rotundum into the pterygopalatine fossa.<br><br>The mandibular nerve passes the foramen ovale; the foramen rotundum transmits the maxillary nerve."},
/*603*/ {"q":"Most important cause of male infertility:","o":["Klinefelter syndrome","Cryptorchidism","Varicocele","Down syndrome"],"a":2,"e":"Varicocele is the commonest correctable cause of male infertility, raising testicular temperature and impairing spermatogenesis (Ref. Robbins pathology).<br><br>Klinefelter and cryptorchidism contribute but are less frequent overall; the keyed leading cause is varicocele."},
/*604*/ {"q":"Turner syndrome Karyotyping:","o":["46XX","45XO","47XXY","46XY"],"a":1,"e":"Turner syndrome has a 45,XO karyotype, producing short stature, webbed neck, streak gonads and primary amenorrhoea.<br><br>47XXY is Klinefelter; the Turner karyotype is 45,XO."},
/*605*/ {"q":"Specific gravity measurement of urine output:","o":["Volume","Frequency","Concentration","Filtration"],"a":2,"e":"Urine specific gravity reflects the concentration of solutes, indicating the kidney's concentrating capacity and the patient's hydration state.<br><br>Volume and frequency are separate; specific gravity indicates concentration."},
/*606*/ {"q":"A pregnant lady with 3rd trimester experienced an episode of fainting; doctor advised her to change position to avoid compression of which structure?","o":["Aorta","IVC","Portal vein","Splenic vein"],"a":1,"e":"Supine hypotensive syndrome in late pregnancy results from the gravid uterus compressing the inferior vena cava, reducing venous return; left lateral positioning relieves it.<br><br>Aortic compression is less critical for fainting; the keyed compressed vessel is the IVC."},
/*607*/ {"q":"Muscle which keeps the scapula opposite to chest wall:","o":["Serratus anterior","Rhomboid major","Levator scapulae","Trapezius"],"a":0,"e":"Serratus anterior holds the medial border of the scapula against the thoracic wall; its paralysis (long thoracic nerve) causes winging of the scapula.<br><br>Rhomboids retract the scapula; scapular apposition to the chest is serratus anterior."},
/*608*/ {"q":"Damage to lateral thigh, lateral popliteal nerve and eversion lost. Root value of femoral nerve:","o":["L2-L3","L1-L2","L2-L4","L5-S1"],"a":2,"e":"The femoral nerve arises from the lumbar plexus, root values L2-L4, supplying the anterior thigh muscles and skin.<br><br>L5-S1 contributes to the sciatic/peroneal system; the femoral nerve root value is L2-L4."},
/*609*/ {"q":"Muscle which keeps the scapula opposite to chest wall:","o":["L2","L3","Serratus anterior","L4"],"a":2,"e":"Serratus anterior anchors the scapula flat against the chest wall; long thoracic nerve injury causes medial scapular winging.<br><br>The vertebral-level distractors are irrelevant; the muscle is serratus anterior."},
/*610*/ {"q":"Damage to upper thigh, lateral popliteal nerve, sensory and tongue deviation:","o":["L2-L3","S1-S2","T2-T6","L2-L3-L4"],"a":3,"e":"Per the source key, the femoral/lumbar plexus root value relevant in this composite item is L2-L3-L4 among the listed options.<br><br>The other ranges do not match the keyed answer; the marked option is L2-L3-L4."},
/*611*/ {"q":"A patient with severe metabolic acidosis:","o":["Decrease HCO3","Decrease H+","Increase pH","Decrease CO2"],"a":0,"e":"Metabolic acidosis is characterised by a primary fall in plasma bicarbonate as it buffers excess acid, with a compensatory fall in CO2.<br><br>pH falls, not rises; the hallmark metabolic change is decreased bicarbonate."},
/*612*/ {"q":"A Pregnant lady with 3rd trimester experienced an episode of fainting, doctor advised her to change position to avoid compression of:","o":["Causative organism of pneumonia in alcoholic patients","Myoplasma","IVC","Pneumocystis carinii"],"a":2,"e":"The supine hypotensive syndrome of late pregnancy is caused by uterine compression of the inferior vena cava; lateral positioning restores venous return.<br><br>The infective distractors are irrelevant; the keyed compressed structure is the IVC."},
/*613*/ {"q":"Patient with normal ADH and glucose level but with 5 lit urine, diagnose is:","o":["Central D.I","Nephrogenic D.I","DM 1","DM 2"],"a":1,"e":"Polyuria with normal ADH levels and normal glucose indicates nephrogenic diabetes insipidus, where the kidney fails to respond to ADH.<br><br>Central DI shows low ADH; with normal ADH and glucose the diagnosis is nephrogenic DI."},
/*614*/ {"q":"Common site of ureteric stone obstruction:","o":["Pelviureteric junction","Mid ureter","Vesicoureteric junction","Ureteric crossing of iliac vessels"],"a":2,"e":"The vesicoureteric junction is the narrowest point of the ureter and the commonest site for an impacted stone, along with the pelviureteric junction and pelvic brim.<br><br>Among the physiological constrictions the narrowest, keyed here, is the vesicoureteric junction."},
/*615*/ {"q":"Radial artery lies between which 2 tendons?","o":["Brachioradialis and Flexor carpi radialis","Flexor pollicis longus and palmaris longus","Flexor carpi ulnaris and palmaris longus","Extensor pollicis longus and brevis"],"a":0,"e":"At the wrist the radial artery pulse lies between the tendons of brachioradialis (laterally) and flexor carpi radialis (medially).<br><br>The ulnar artery lies near flexor carpi ulnaris; the radial pulse is between brachioradialis and flexor carpi radialis."},
/*616*/ {"q":"Acidic duodenum cause:","o":["Decrease H2CO3","Increase gastric emptying","Increase secretin release and decrease gastric emptying","Increase HCl"],"a":2,"e":"Acid entering the duodenum stimulates secretin release, which neutralises acid via pancreatic bicarbonate and slows gastric emptying.<br><br>It does not speed emptying; duodenal acid triggers secretin and reduced gastric emptying."},
/*617*/ {"q":"Cardiac muscles have 2 tendons?","o":["Inferior thyroid","Highest intercostal","Thoracoacromial","No tendons (cardiac muscle)"],"a":3,"e":"Cardiac muscle is arranged in a syncytial network attached to the fibrous skeleton of the heart, lacking discrete tendons like skeletal muscle.<br><br>The arterial distractors are irrelevant; cardiac muscle has no tendons."},
/*618*/ {"q":"Treatment of cystic acne in pregnant female that lead to fetal abnormalities?","o":["Vitamin A (isotretinoin)","Vitamin C","Vitamin D","Vitamin E"],"a":0,"e":"Isotretinoin, a vitamin A derivative used for severe cystic acne, is a potent teratogen causing serious fetal abnormalities and is contraindicated in pregnancy.<br><br>The other vitamins are not teratogenic at normal doses; the keyed agent is vitamin A (isotretinoin)."},
/*619*/ {"q":"Ligamentum arteriosum recurring nerve?","o":["Right recurrent laryngeal nerve","Left recurrent laryngeal nerve","Phrenic nerve","Vagus trunk"],"a":1,"e":"The left recurrent laryngeal nerve hooks beneath the arch of the aorta at the ligamentum arteriosum before ascending to the larynx.<br><br>The right nerve loops around the right subclavian; at the ligamentum arteriosum it is the left recurrent laryngeal nerve."},
/*620*/ {"q":"Facial muscle nerve supply:","o":["Facial","Mandibular","Buccal nerve","Phrenic"],"a":0,"e":"The muscles of facial expression are supplied by the facial nerve (CN VII), derived from the second pharyngeal arch.<br><br>The mandibular nerve supplies the muscles of mastication; facial expression is the facial nerve."},
/*621*/ {"q":"Platelet formation:","o":["ADP and thromboxane A2","Fibrinogen and thromboxane 2","Thrombopoietin-driven megakaryocyte fragmentation","Erythropoietin"],"a":2,"e":"Platelets are produced by fragmentation of megakaryocyte cytoplasm in the bone marrow, regulated chiefly by thrombopoietin.<br><br>ADP and thromboxane mediate aggregation, not formation; platelet production is thrombopoietin-driven megakaryocyte fragmentation."},
/*622*/ {"q":"Patient in emergency room presented with high grade fever in unconscious condition. Most likely diagnosis is:","o":["Septic shock","Hypovolemic shock","Cardiogenic shock","Anaphylactic shock"],"a":0,"e":"High-grade fever with altered consciousness and circulatory collapse points to septic shock from systemic infection and inflammatory vasodilation.<br><br>Hypovolaemic and cardiogenic shock lack fever; the febrile shock picture is septic shock."},
/*623*/ {"q":"Radial artery lies between which 2 tendons?","o":["Brachioradialis and Flexor carpi radialis","Pectoral major flap blood supply","Inf thyroid","Hypothyroidism"],"a":0,"e":"At the distal forearm the radial artery is palpated between the brachioradialis tendon laterally and flexor carpi radialis medially.<br><br>The non-tendon distractors are irrelevant; the radial pulse lies between brachioradialis and flexor carpi radialis."},
/*624*/ {"q":"Direct branch of subclavian artery taking part in shoulder joint anastomosis:","o":["Suprascapular artery","Pelvic brim","Superior to ischial spine","Nearest to kidney"],"a":0,"e":"The suprascapular artery, a branch of the thyrocervical trunk from the subclavian, contributes to the scapular anastomosis around the shoulder.<br><br>The non-arterial distractors are irrelevant; the keyed vessel is the suprascapular artery."},
/*625*/ {"q":"An uncovered Person is sitting at room temperature. Mechanism of heat loss will be:","o":["Conduction","Convection","Radiation","Evaporation"],"a":2,"e":"At normal room temperature most body heat is lost by radiation (infrared emission) from the exposed skin surface.<br><br>Evaporation dominates only with sweating or high ambient temperature; at rest the chief loss is radiation."},
/*626*/ {"q":"Appendix lymphatic drainage:","o":["Ileocolic nodes","Conduction","Convection","Standard deviation"],"a":0,"e":"The vermiform appendix drains its lymph to the ileocolic lymph nodes along the ileocolic vessels.<br><br>The heat-transfer and statistical distractors are irrelevant; appendiceal lymph drains to the ileocolic nodes."},
/*627*/ {"q":"Mean media mode same in:","o":["Normal distribution curve","Confidence Interval","Standard deviation","Skewed curve"],"a":0,"e":"In a perfectly symmetrical normal (Gaussian) distribution the mean, median and mode coincide at the centre.<br><br>In skewed distributions they diverge; equality occurs in the normal distribution."},
/*628*/ {"q":"Dual nerve supply to which muscle?","o":["Quadratus femoris","Biceps femoris","Adductor Magnus","Pectineus"],"a":2,"e":"Adductor magnus has a dual nerve supply: the adductor portion from the obturator nerve and the hamstring portion from the sciatic (tibial) nerve.<br><br>The other muscles have single supply; the dual-innervated muscle is adductor magnus."},
/*629*/ {"q":"Structure anterior to IVC:","o":["Aorta To IVC","Right testicular artery","Left renal vein","Right renal artery"],"a":0,"e":"Per the source key, among these vascular relations the structure matched as anterior in this item is the aorta-to-IVC option.<br><br>The other vessels do not match the keyed answer; the marked option is aorta to IVC."},
/*630*/ {"q":"Virus causes cell damage by which mechanism?","o":["Oncogene activation / direct cytopathic effect","Necrosis only","Apoptosis only","No damage"],"a":0,"e":"Viruses damage cells by direct cytopathic effects and, for oncogenic viruses, by activating oncogenes or inactivating tumour suppressors leading to transformation.<br><br>A single mechanism is incomplete; the keyed answer reflects oncogene/direct cytopathic injury."},
/*631*/ {"q":"Petrous part of temporal damage which nerve?","o":["Facial nerve","Trigeminal nerve","Abducens nerve","Vagus nerve"],"a":0,"e":"The facial nerve traverses the petrous temporal bone in the facial canal, so petrous fractures commonly injure the facial nerve, causing lower motor neuron facial palsy.<br><br>The trigeminal lies anteromedially; the petrous-temporal nerve is the facial nerve."},
/*632*/ {"q":"Structure anterior to IVC:","o":["Right renal vein","Left renal vein","Right testicular artery","Common hepatic artery / portal triad relation"],"a":3,"e":"Per the source key, the structure related anteriorly to the IVC in this item is the common hepatic/portal triad option among the choices.<br><br>The renal-vessel distractors do not match the keyed answer; the marked option is the common hepatic relation."},
/*633*/ {"q":"Structure anterior to IVC:","o":["Right renal vein","Right renal artery","Portal vein","Left renal vein"],"a":2,"e":"At the porta hepatis and epiploic foramen the portal vein lies anterior to the inferior vena cava, an important surgical relation.<br><br>The renal vessels relate at a lower level; the structure anterior to the IVC here is the portal vein."},
/*634*/ {"q":"A girl with primary amenorrhea On examination breasts not developed and uterus absent on USG. Karyotype was asked:","o":["46XX","46XX (with absent uterus)","47XXY","46XO"],"a":3,"e":"Primary amenorrhoea with absent breast development and absent uterus, with a 46,XO type pattern, points to gonadal dysgenesis/Turner-spectrum karyotype per the source key.<br><br>Following the keyed answer, the marked karyotype option is 46,XO."},
/*635*/ {"q":"Growth hormone needs which hormone for its function?","o":["Insulin","Epinephrine","Glucagon","Thyroid hormone"],"a":3,"e":"Thyroid hormone is permissive for growth hormone action, required for normal somatic growth and the anabolic effects of GH.<br><br>Insulin and glucagon are metabolic regulators; GH function requires thyroid hormone permissiveness."},
/*636*/ {"q":"Common site of ureteric stone obstruction:","o":["Pelvic brim","Pelviureteric junction","Vesicoureteric junction","Mid ureter"],"a":2,"e":"The vesicoureteric junction is the narrowest ureteric segment and the commonest site of stone impaction, with the pelviureteric junction and pelvic brim also constricted.<br><br>The narrowest of these, keyed here, is the vesicoureteric junction."},
/*637*/ {"q":"Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy scenario, structure:","o":["Decrease diastolic filling","Increase diastolic filling","Normal filling","Increase systolic filling"],"a":0,"e":"Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy causes a thick, stiff non-compliant ventricle with impaired relaxation, resulting in decreased diastolic filling (diastolic dysfunction).<br><br>Systolic function is often preserved; the hallmark is decreased diastolic filling (Ref. Ganong Physiology)."},
/*638*/ {"q":"A girl with primary amenorrhea On examination breasts not developed and uterus absent on USG. Karyotype was asked:","o":["46XX","46XY","47XXY","46XO"],"a":3,"e":"Absent breast development and absent uterus with primary amenorrhoea, keyed to a 46,XO-type karyotype, indicates gonadal dysgenesis in this source.<br><br>Following the keyed answer the marked karyotype is 46,XO."},
/*639*/ {"q":"Ovarian artery is branch of:","o":["Femoral","Celiac","Abdominal aorta","Internal iliac"],"a":2,"e":"The ovarian arteries arise directly from the abdominal aorta just below the renal arteries, reflecting the ovary's lumbar embryological origin.<br><br>The internal iliac supplies the uterus; the ovarian artery springs from the abdominal aorta."},
/*640*/ {"q":"Virus causes cell damage by which mechanism?","o":["Oncogene activation","Left colic","Left ovarian","Left atrium"],"a":0,"e":"Oncogenic viruses cause cellular transformation by activating cellular oncogenes or inactivating tumour suppressor genes, alongside direct cytopathic injury.<br><br>The vascular/anatomical distractors are irrelevant; the keyed mechanism is oncogene activation."},
/*641*/ {"q":"A drug having half-life 10*4=40. When will it achieve steady state?","o":["30mins","40mins","60mins","20mins"],"a":1,"e":"Steady state is reached after roughly four to five half-lives; with the values given the keyed time is about 40 minutes.<br><br>Shorter intervals represent too few half-lives; the keyed steady-state time is 40 minutes."},
/*642*/ {"q":"Soldier coming from siachin having breathlessness and cyanosis cause is?","o":["Polycythemia Vera","Methemoglobinemia","Secondary polycythemia","Heart Failure"],"a":2,"e":"Chronic high-altitude hypoxia (Siachen) stimulates erythropoietin and causes secondary polycythaemia, with breathlessness and cyanosis from hypoxaemia.<br><br>Polycythaemia vera is EPO-independent; altitude-induced is secondary polycythaemia."},
/*643*/ {"q":"Irreversible sign of cardiac cell injury?","o":["Cell Swelling","Contraction bands in cytoplasm","Hydropic change","Membrane blebs"],"a":1,"e":"Contraction band necrosis, hypereosinophilic transverse bands in irreversibly injured cardiomyocytes, is a sign of irreversible (lethal) injury, often after reperfusion.<br><br>Cell swelling and hydropic change are reversible; the irreversible sign is contraction bands."},
/*644*/ {"q":"Bare area of liver limited by:","o":["Down syndrome","Turner syndrome","Coronary ligament","Kline filter syndrome"],"a":2,"e":"The bare area of the liver, in direct contact with the diaphragm without peritoneal cover, is bounded by the reflections of the coronary ligament.<br><br>The chromosomal distractors are irrelevant; the bare area is limited by the coronary ligament."},
/*645*/ {"q":"Patient has test come positive for infectious mononucleosis which organ will be susceptible to injury?","o":["Liver","Kidney","Spleen","Lung"],"a":2,"e":"Infectious mononucleosis causes splenomegaly, making the enlarged spleen susceptible to rupture, hence contact sports are restricted.<br><br>Liver involvement is usually mild; the organ at risk of injury is the spleen."},
/*646*/ {"q":"Apex of heart is supplied by:","o":["Diagonal","Marginal","LAD (anterior interventricular)","Posterior interventricular"],"a":2,"e":"The cardiac apex is typically supplied by the anterior interventricular branch (LAD) of the left coronary artery as it wraps around the apex.<br><br>The marginal artery supplies the right ventricle border; the apex is chiefly LAD-supplied."},
/*647*/ {"q":"Phrenic nerve root value:","o":["C3 to C5","C2 to C4","C4 to C6","C1 to C3"],"a":0,"e":"The phrenic nerve arises from cervical roots C3, C4 and C5 (\"C3, 4, 5 keep the diaphragm alive\") and is the sole motor supply to the diaphragm.<br><br>The other ranges misstate the roots; the phrenic nerve root value is C3-C5."},
/*648*/ {"q":"Stab injury at 6th costal cartilage will pierce:","o":["Upper border of rib","Lower border of rib","Lower end of intercostal space","Lower border of 6th rib region"],"a":1,"e":"A stab wound at the costal cartilage tracks along the lower border of the rib where the intercostal neurovascular bundle lies in the costal groove.<br><br>The upper border is relatively safe; the bundle is at the lower border of the rib."},
/*649*/ {"q":"Renal pyramid is supplied by:","o":["Interlobar artery","Arcuate artery","Interlobular artery","Vasa recta"],"a":3,"e":"The renal medullary pyramids are supplied by the vasa recta, the straight capillaries arising from the efferent arterioles of juxtamedullary nephrons.<br><br>Interlobar and arcuate arteries supply the cortex/junction; the pyramid is perfused by vasa recta."},
/*650*/ {"q":"Irreversible sign of cardiac cell injury:","o":["Upper border of rib","Lower border of rib","Lower end of intercostal","Cell membrane rupture / contraction bands"],"a":3,"e":"Plasma membrane rupture with contraction band necrosis indicates irreversible (lethal) cardiomyocyte injury, beyond the point of recovery.<br><br>The rib-margin distractors are irrelevant; the irreversible sign is membrane rupture/contraction bands."},

/*651*/ {"q":"X-ray of middle aged man smoker working in Construction. He is most likely suffering from:","o":["Endarteritis obliterans","Asbestosis","Silicosis","Anthracosis"],"a":2,"e":"A construction worker with chronic silica dust exposure and characteristic upper-zone nodular X-ray changes most likely has silicosis.<br><br>Asbestosis causes lower-zone fibrosis and pleural plaques; the construction/quartz exposure points to silicosis."},
/*652*/ {"q":"Patient has test come positive for infectious mononucleosis which organ will be susceptible to injury?","o":["Liver","Kidney","Spleen","Lung"],"a":2,"e":"Infectious mononucleosis enlarges the spleen, which becomes fragile and prone to rupture even with minor trauma.<br><br>Hepatic involvement is usually mild; the organ at risk of rupture is the spleen."},
/*653*/ {"q":"Cleft lip and palate involves:","o":["Lower jaw fracture","Medial nasal and maxillary processes","Mandibular process only","Lateral nasal only"],"a":1,"e":"Cleft lip and palate result from failure of fusion between the medial nasal processes and the maxillary processes during facial development.<br><br>The mandibular process forms the lower jaw; the cleft involves medial nasal and maxillary process fusion failure."},
/*654*/ {"q":"Knife injury in chest wall, which layer just before parietal pleura is damaged?","o":["External Intercostal Membrane","Endothoracic Fascia","Internal Intercostal Membrane","Innermost Intercostal Muscle"],"a":1,"e":"The endothoracic fascia is the thin connective tissue layer lying immediately deep to the innermost intercostal muscle and just superficial to the parietal pleura.<br><br>The intercostal muscles are more superficial; the layer just before parietal pleura is the endothoracic fascia."},
/*655*/ {"q":"Ketone bodies seen in type 1 diabetes:","o":["S1 S2","T2-T5","C1 to C5","Excess fatty acid oxidation"],"a":3,"e":"In type 1 diabetes, insulin deficiency drives unrestrained lipolysis and hepatic fatty acid oxidation, generating ketone bodies and ketoacidosis.<br><br>The segmental-level distractors are irrelevant; ketosis arises from excess fatty acid oxidation."},
/*656*/ {"q":"Obturator nerve damage at lateral pelvic wall, sign:","o":["Loss of hip abduction","Loss of thigh adduction and medial thigh sensation","Foot drop","Loss of knee extension"],"a":1,"e":"Obturator nerve injury weakens the thigh adductors and causes sensory loss over the medial thigh.<br><br>Foot drop and knee-extension loss involve peroneal and femoral nerves; obturator damage impairs adduction and medial thigh sensation."},
/*657*/ {"q":"Patient with backache after lifting heavy radiating to back, thigh and lateral foot weekend ankle jerk and flexor hallucis longus, pain on raising leg till 30, which structure compressed?","o":["L4 nerve root","L5-S1 disc / S1 nerve root","L2 root","Femoral nerve"],"a":1,"e":"Sciatica with lateral foot symptoms, weak ankle jerk and flexor hallucis longus, and positive straight leg raise indicates an L5-S1 disc prolapse compressing the S1 root.<br><br>L4 root affects the knee jerk; the ankle-jerk and lateral-foot pattern is S1 (L5-S1 disc)."},
/*658*/ {"q":"Shoulder joint dislocation, ligament injury?","o":["Subscapular","Acromioclavicular","Coracoclavicular","Glenohumeral / inferior capsule"],"a":3,"e":"Anterior shoulder dislocation typically tears the inferior glenohumeral ligament and anterior capsule, with possible labral (Bankart) injury.<br><br>The acromioclavicular ligament relates to AC joint injury; shoulder dislocation damages the glenohumeral capsule/ligament."},
/*659*/ {"q":"Portal vein to liver run in which ligament?","o":["Ligamentum teres","Hepatoduodenal ligament","Falciform ligament","Coronary ligament"],"a":1,"e":"The portal vein, along with the hepatic artery and bile duct (portal triad), runs within the hepatoduodenal ligament, the free edge of the lesser omentum.<br><br>The falciform ligament carries the obliterated umbilical vein; the portal triad runs in the hepatoduodenal ligament."},
/*660*/ {"q":"AIDS patient what will be early change in peripheral blood smear?","o":["Decrease T cells","Decrease neutrophils","Decrease platelets","Decrease eosinophils"],"a":0,"e":"HIV infection selectively depletes CD4+ T-helper lymphocytes, the earliest and hallmark change reflected in falling T-cell counts.<br><br>Cytopenias of other lines occur later; the early change is decreased T cells."},
/*661*/ {"q":"Which of the following muscle causes abduction of arm above 90?","o":["Trapezius and Serratus Anterior","Deltoid","Supraspinatus","Pectoralis major"],"a":0,"e":"Abduction of the arm above 90 degrees requires upward rotation of the scapula by trapezius and serratus anterior acting as a force couple.<br><br>Supraspinatus initiates and deltoid continues to 90; beyond 90 the scapular rotators trapezius and serratus anterior are essential."},
/*662*/ {"q":"Which cell line seen in type 1 hypersensitivity Cause?","o":["Neutrophil","Eosinophil","PTH adenoma","Sarcoidosis"],"a":1,"e":"Type I hypersensitivity involves IgE-mediated mast cell degranulation with prominent eosinophil recruitment in the late phase.<br><br>Neutrophils dominate acute pyogenic inflammation; the type I associated cell line is the eosinophil."},
/*663*/ {"q":"Prostatic carcinoma spread to skull through:","o":["Wedding gait nerve damage","Sup. Gluteal","Inf. Gluteal","Vertebral venous plexus (Batson)"],"a":3,"e":"Prostate carcinoma metastasises to the vertebral column and skull via the valveless Batson vertebral venous plexus.<br><br>The gluteal-nerve distractors are irrelevant; the keyed metastatic route is the vertebral venous plexus."},
/*664*/ {"q":"Collagen type in healthy skin:","o":["Type 2 and 3","Type 3 and 5","Type 1 and 3","Type 1 and 2"],"a":2,"e":"Normal skin contains predominantly type I collagen with a smaller proportion of type III, the latter increasing in early wound healing.<br><br>Type II is cartilage collagen; healthy skin is mainly type I with some type III."},
/*665*/ {"q":"A patient with massive splenomegaly Spleen was palpable below 10*ICS:","o":["Myelofibrosis","Thalassemia","Type 1 and 2","Type 3 hypersensitivity reactions"],"a":0,"e":"Massive splenomegaly (spleen well below the costal margin) is classically seen in chronic myeloproliferative disease such as myelofibrosis (and CML).<br><br>Thalassaemia causes moderate enlargement; massive splenomegaly keys to myelofibrosis."},
/*666*/ {"q":"Type 3 hypersensitivity reaction:","o":["SLE","Sciatic nerve","L4 nerve root","Femoral nerve"],"a":0,"e":"Systemic lupus erythematosus is a prototypical type III immune-complex hypersensitivity disorder, with complex deposition causing tissue injury.<br><br>The nerve distractors are irrelevant; the type III example is SLE."},
/*667*/ {"q":"Most common fertilization site in humans:","o":["Ovary","Uterus","Cervix","Ampulla of fallopian tube"],"a":3,"e":"Fertilisation normally occurs in the ampulla, the widest part of the uterine tube, where the sperm meets the secondary oocyte.<br><br>Implantation occurs later in the uterus; fertilisation takes place in the ampulla of the fallopian tube."},
/*668*/ {"q":"AIDS patient what will be early change in peripheral blood?","o":["Decrease T cells","Erythropoiesis","Old Age","Decrease platelets"],"a":0,"e":"The earliest haematological hallmark of HIV is depletion of CD4+ T lymphocytes, reducing the T-cell count.<br><br>Cytopenias of other lines develop later; the early change is decreased T cells."},
/*669*/ {"q":"Which of the following muscle causes abduction of arm above 90?","o":["Trapezius & Serratus Anterior","Deltoid","Supraspinatus","Pectoralis"],"a":0,"e":"Abduction above 90 degrees depends on scapular upward rotation produced by the trapezius and serratus anterior force couple.<br><br>Deltoid and supraspinatus act below 90; beyond that, trapezius and serratus anterior are required."},
/*670*/ {"q":"Regarding Hodgkin lymphoma True statement is:","o":["Absent RS cells","Contiguous spread","Common in old age","Extra nodal involvement is common"],"a":1,"e":"Hodgkin lymphoma characteristically spreads in a contiguous, predictable fashion from one nodal group to the adjacent one.<br><br>Reed-Sternberg cells are present and extranodal spread is uncommon; the true statement is contiguous spread."},
/*671*/ {"q":"Female pelvis is tilted in relation of spine?","o":["Upward","Downward","Forward","Backward"],"a":2,"e":"The female pelvis is tilted forward (anteverted) relative to the spine, with the anterior superior iliac spine and pubic symphysis in the same vertical plane.<br><br>Backward tilt is incorrect; the female pelvic inclination is forward."},
/*672*/ {"q":"A patient is suffering from 2nd degree heart Block? Which of the following is true?","o":["There is high incidence of ventricular tachycardia","Not all atrial impulses are conducted to the ventricles","Stroke volume is decreased","Cardiac output increased"],"a":1,"e":"In second-degree AV block, some atrial impulses fail to conduct to the ventricles, so not every P wave is followed by a QRS.<br><br>Complete dissociation is third-degree; the defining second-degree feature is intermittent failure of AV conduction."},
/*673*/ {"q":"Which of the following muscle helps in deep inspiration during yawning and increases COP?","o":["Medial pterygoid","Lateral pterygoid","Masseter","Supraspinatus"],"a":1,"e":"Per the source key, among these the muscle matched to the deep-inspiration/jaw-opening yawning action is the lateral pterygoid.<br><br>Masseter and medial pterygoid close the jaw; the keyed answer is the lateral pterygoid."},
/*674*/ {"q":"A study is performed to study neoplastic characteristic of biopsies. The biopsies were taken to surgeon for malignancy. Of the following finding is not an indicator of malignancy?","o":["Pleomorphism","Atypia","Encapsulated","Increased N/C ratio"],"a":2,"e":"Encapsulation indicates a well-circumscribed benign tumour; malignant lesions are typically invasive and non-encapsulated.<br><br>Pleomorphism, atypia and high N/C ratio favour malignancy; the non-malignant feature is encapsulation."},
/*675*/ {"q":"65-year-old man is suffering from pneumonia and unable to recognize faces and died. Which Bug is responsible?","o":["Staphylococcus aureus","Hemophilus","Streptococcus P","Klebsiella"],"a":2,"e":"Streptococcus pneumoniae is the commonest cause of community-acquired lobar pneumonia, particularly in older adults.<br><br>Klebsiella causes pneumonia in alcoholics/diabetics; the typical elderly lobar pneumonia organism is pneumococcus."},
/*676*/ {"q":"Loss of water by evaporation/insensible loss from body called?","o":["Sweating","Slow writhing movements","Thermal gradient","Insensible perspiration"],"a":3,"e":"Continuous evaporative water loss through skin and respiratory passages that is not perceived is termed insensible perspiration.<br><br>Sweating is sensible, visible loss; the unperceived evaporative loss is insensible perspiration."},
/*677*/ {"q":"Which of the following Structure is between celiac plexus and SMA?","o":["Stomach","Spleen","Gall bladder","Pancreas (body / neck)"],"a":3,"e":"The neck and body of the pancreas lie between the coeliac trunk above and the superior mesenteric artery below, draped over the latter.<br><br>The stomach and spleen are anterior/lateral; the structure between the two arteries is the pancreas."},
/*678*/ {"q":"Slow writhing movements are called athetosis due to defect in which of following?","o":["Caudate","Globus pallidus","Subthalamus","Thalamus"],"a":1,"e":"Athetosis, slow writhing involuntary movements, results from a lesion of the globus pallidus within the basal ganglia.<br><br>Subthalamic lesions cause hemiballismus; athetosis localises to the globus pallidus."},
/*679*/ {"q":"Most common valve involved in endocarditis in IV drug users:","o":["Mitral","Aortic","Tricuspid","Pulmonary"],"a":2,"e":"In intravenous drug users infective endocarditis most commonly affects the right-sided tricuspid valve, seeded by venous-borne organisms.<br><br>Left-sided valves predominate in non-users; in IV drug users it is the tricuspid valve."},
/*680*/ {"q":"Clostridium botulinum specific symptoms in food poisoning:","o":["Flaccid paralysis of respiratory muscles","Watery diarrhea","Bloody diarrhea","Fever and vomiting"],"a":0,"e":"Botulinum toxin blocks acetylcholine release at the neuromuscular junction, causing descending flaccid paralysis including respiratory muscle failure.<br><br>Diarrhoeal symptoms typify other organisms; botulism causes flaccid paralysis."},
/*681*/ {"q":"While attempting to suture the distal end of a coronary bypass artery, the surgeon accidentally passed the needle through the adjacent vein. Which vein was damaged?","o":["Anterior cardiac vein","Coronary sinus","Great cardiac vein","Middle cardiac vein"],"a":2,"e":"The great cardiac vein runs alongside the anterior interventricular (LAD) artery in the anterior interventricular groove, so it is the vein adjacent to that bypass site.<br><br>The middle cardiac vein accompanies the posterior interventricular artery; with the LAD it is the great cardiac vein."},
/*682*/ {"q":"All of these supply the first 2cm of duodenum except:","o":["Right gastric artery","Supraduodenal artery","Gastroduodenal artery","Inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery"],"a":3,"e":"The first 2 cm of duodenum (foregut) is supplied by the right gastric, supraduodenal and gastroduodenal/superior pancreaticoduodenal arteries; the inferior pancreaticoduodenal (midgut) does not supply it.<br><br>That midgut vessel begins distal to the ampulla; the exception is the inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery."},
/*683*/ {"q":"Xiphoid process is present at which vertebral level?","o":["T7","T8","T9","T10"],"a":2,"e":"The xiphisternal joint and xiphoid process lie at approximately the T9 vertebral level, an important surface landmark.<br><br>T7 corresponds to the inferior scapular angle; the xiphoid is around T9."},
/*684*/ {"q":"During hysterectomy, ureter is identified by which of the following structure?","o":["Anterior cardiac vein","Coronary sinus","Uterine artery (water under the bridge)","Middle cardiac vein"],"a":2,"e":"During hysterectomy the ureter is identified passing beneath the uterine artery (\"water under the bridge\"), an essential surgical landmark to avoid injury.<br><br>The cardiac veins are irrelevant; the ureter relation is to the uterine artery."},
/*685*/ {"q":"Left Gastric vein drains into:","o":["Portal vein","Splenic vein","Superior mesenteric vein","Inferior mesenteric vein"],"a":0,"e":"The left gastric (coronary) vein drains directly into the portal vein and is an important site of portosystemic anastomosis at the lower oesophagus.<br><br>The splenic and mesenteric veins are separate tributaries; the left gastric vein drains into the portal vein."},
/*686*/ {"q":"Most common cause of endocarditis in IV drug users:","o":["Streptococcus viridans","Staphylococcus aureus","Enterococcus","Candida"],"a":1,"e":"Staphylococcus aureus is the commonest organism causing right-sided infective endocarditis in intravenous drug users.<br><br>Streptococcus viridans causes subacute endocarditis on damaged valves; in IV drug users it is Staph aureus."},
/*687*/ {"q":"Biochemical change in wilsons disease?","o":["Decreased ceruloplasmin and copper accumulation","Increased ceruloplasmin","Decreased copper","Increased iron"],"a":0,"e":"Wilson disease causes decreased serum ceruloplasmin with toxic copper accumulation in the liver, brain (basal ganglia) and cornea (Kayser-Fleischer rings).<br><br>Iron overload describes haemochromatosis; Wilson disease is low ceruloplasmin with copper deposition."},
/*688*/ {"q":"Slow writhing movements are called atetosis due to defect in which of following?","o":["Caudate","Globus pallidus","Subthalamus","Thalamus"],"a":1,"e":"Athetosis, slow sinuous involuntary movements, arises from globus pallidus dysfunction within the basal ganglia.<br><br>Subthalamic lesions give hemiballismus; athetosis is a globus pallidus disorder."},
/*689*/ {"q":"Xiphoid process is present at which vertebral level?","o":["T7","T8","T9","T11"],"a":2,"e":"The xiphoid process lies at about the T9 vertebral level, used as a thoracic surface landmark.<br><br>T7 marks the inferior scapular angle; the xiphoid corresponds to T9."},
/*690*/ {"q":"Regarding palpebral ligament (Medial canthal ligament) attachment?","o":["Frontonasal","Anterior lacrimal ridge","Posterior lacrimal ridge","Anterior and posterior lacrimal ridges"],"a":3,"e":"The medial palpebral ligament splits to attach to both the anterior and posterior lacrimal crests, embracing the lacrimal sac so blinking aids tear drainage.<br><br>A single ridge attachment is incomplete; the ligament attaches to both lacrimal ridges."},
/*691*/ {"q":"Regarding Atherosclerotic plaque which of following is true?","o":["Necrotic lipid core with fibrous cap","Pure calcific only","Cellular without lipid","Reversible always"],"a":0,"e":"A mature atherosclerotic plaque (atheroma) consists of a necrotic lipid core covered by a fibrous cap, prone to rupture and thrombosis.<br><br>It is not purely calcific or reversible; the true description is a lipid core with fibrous cap."},
/*692*/ {"q":"Costo-diaphragmatic recess is present between:","o":["Costal and diaphragmatic pleura","Costal and visceral pleura","Costal and mediastinal pleura","Visceral and parietal"],"a":0,"e":"The costodiaphragmatic recess is the potential pleural space between the costal and diaphragmatic parietal pleura, where fluid collects and the lung expands on deep inspiration.<br><br>It is a parietal-parietal reflection; the recess lies between costal and diaphragmatic pleura (Ref. Ganong Physiology)."},
/*693*/ {"q":"Circumflex artery supplies which of following?","o":["Right Atrium","Left atrium and left ventricle (lateral wall)","Right Ventricle","SA node always"],"a":1,"e":"The circumflex branch of the left coronary artery supplies the left atrium and the lateral wall of the left ventricle.<br><br>The right ventricle is mainly RCA territory; the circumflex supplies the left atrium and lateral left ventricle."},
/*694*/ {"q":"Macrophages in lungs are termed as:","o":["Alveolar dust cells","Kupffer cells","Langhans cells","Histiocytes"],"a":0,"e":"Pulmonary macrophages are called alveolar (dust) cells, which phagocytose inhaled particles within the alveoli.<br><br>Kupffer cells are hepatic macrophages; the lung macrophages are alveolar dust cells."},
/*695*/ {"q":"A patient is known case of Asthma. He is suffering from shortness of Breath. Increased Airway constriction is due to:","o":["Parasympathetic","Sympathetic","Parasympathetic & sympathetic","Hormonal"],"a":0,"e":"Bronchoconstriction in asthma is mediated chiefly by parasympathetic (vagal) cholinergic stimulation of bronchial smooth muscle.<br><br>Sympathetic activity causes bronchodilation; the constriction is parasympathetic."},
/*696*/ {"q":"Which of following is feature of Benign Tumor?","o":["Invasion","Pleomorphism","Irregular margin","Encapsulated"],"a":3,"e":"Benign tumours are typically well-circumscribed and encapsulated, growing by expansion without invasion or metastasis.<br><br>Invasion and pleomorphism indicate malignancy; the benign feature is encapsulation."},
/*697*/ {"q":"A patient is diagnosed case of COPD (Chronic bronchitis) diagnostic feature histologically is:","o":["Reid index increase / mucus gland hyperplasia","Alveolar wall destruction","Granuloma","Caseation"],"a":0,"e":"Chronic bronchitis shows hyperplasia of bronchial mucous glands with an increased Reid index on histology.<br><br>Alveolar wall destruction defines emphysema; the chronic bronchitis hallmark is mucous gland hyperplasia (raised Reid index)."},
/*698*/ {"q":"A child with disturbed behavior suffering from Fever and Atrophy of serous glands following is most likely diagnosis:","o":["Viral meningitis","Bacterial meningitis","Fungal meningitis","Brain tumor"],"a":1,"e":"Per the source key, the febrile child scenario in this item is matched to bacterial meningitis among the options.<br><br>The other diagnoses do not match the keyed answer; the marked option is bacterial meningitis."},
/*699*/ {"q":"A patient is suffering from fever & chest pain. He is producing Greenish sputum. Which of following organism nerve is damaged?","o":["Myobacterium tuberculosis","Klebsiella","Streptococcus pneumonia","Pseudomonas"],"a":2,"e":"Fever with chest pain and purulent (rusty/greenish) sputum is classically due to Streptococcus pneumoniae lobar pneumonia.<br><br>Pseudomonas affects specific hosts; the typical pneumonia organism here is pneumococcus."},
/*700*/ {"q":"Which of the following organism causes Lobar pneumonia?","o":["Klebsiella","Legionella","Streptococcus pneumonia","Mycoplasma"],"a":2,"e":"Streptococcus pneumoniae is the classic cause of lobar pneumonia, with consolidation of an entire lobe progressing through histological stages.<br><br>Mycoplasma causes atypical interstitial pneumonia; lobar pneumonia is pneumococcal (Ref. Wheater's Histology)."},

/*701*/ {"q":"A patient is suffering from fever. He is producing Greenish sputum. Which of the following organism is producing:","o":["Klebsiella","Legionella","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Streptococcus"],"a":2,"e":"Pseudomonas aeruginosa characteristically produces blue-green pigmented (pyocyanin) purulent sputum in respiratory infection, especially in compromised hosts.<br><br>Pneumococcus gives rusty sputum; the green pigment-producing organism is Pseudomonas."},
/*702*/ {"q":"What is most common location of ureter damage in oophorectomy?","o":["Pelvic brim","Broad ligament","Cardinal ligament near uterine artery","Vesicoureteric junction"],"a":2,"e":"During oophorectomy/hysterectomy the ureter is most commonly injured near the cardinal ligament where it passes beneath the uterine artery.<br><br>The pelvic brim is another risk site; the commonest surgical injury is at the uterine artery crossing."},
/*703*/ {"q":"Which of following structure is anterior to pancreas?","o":["Stomach","IVC","Aorta","Right kidney"],"a":0,"e":"The stomach lies anterior to the body of the pancreas, separated by the lesser sac.<br><br>The IVC and aorta lie posteriorly; the structure anterior to the pancreas is the stomach."},
/*704*/ {"q":"Doctor injury at the anterior inferior iliac, which artery emerges from genu?","o":["Femoral artery","Iliac artery","Left ventricle","Right atrium"],"a":0,"e":"Per the source key the femoral artery is the vessel matched in this item among the listed structures.<br><br>The cardiac chamber distractors are irrelevant; the marked answer is the femoral artery."},
/*705*/ {"q":"Infection from face can travel to:","o":["Cavernous sinus","Sagittal sinus","Sigmoid sinus","Bone of skull"],"a":0,"e":"Infection in the danger area of the face spreads via the valveless facial and ophthalmic veins to the cavernous sinus, risking septic thrombosis.<br><br>The other sinuses are not the facial route; facial infection travels to the cavernous sinus."},
/*706*/ {"q":"Which structure is damaged in fracture of surgical neck of humerus?","o":["Axillary nerve and posterior circumflex humeral artery","Radial nerve","Median nerve","Ulnar nerve"],"a":0,"e":"A surgical neck of humerus fracture endangers the axillary nerve and the posterior circumflex humeral artery as they pass through the quadrangular space.<br><br>The radial nerve is at risk in mid-shaft fractures; the surgical neck injures the axillary nerve and posterior circumflex artery."},
/*707*/ {"q":"In bronchoscopy after entering right bronchus, first structure to be seen:","o":["Right upper lobe bronchus","Right middle lobe bronchus","Carina","Right lower lobe bronchus"],"a":0,"e":"After passing the carina into the right main bronchus, the first lobar branch encountered, arising early and high, is the right upper lobe bronchus.<br><br>The middle and lower lobe bronchi arise more distally; the first seen is the right upper lobe bronchus."},
/*708*/ {"q":"Deltoid ligament is damaged due to which of following movement?","o":["Inversion","Eversion","Plantar flexion","Dorsiflexion"],"a":1,"e":"The deltoid (medial) ligament of the ankle resists eversion, so excessive eversion strains or tears it.<br><br>Inversion injures the lateral ligaments; the deltoid ligament is damaged by eversion."},
/*709*/ {"q":"Which structure is anterior to pancreas?","o":["Stomach","Right renal artery","Left renal vein","None"],"a":0,"e":"The stomach lies directly anterior to the pancreatic body across the lesser sac, an important anatomical relation.<br><br>The renal vessels lie posteriorly; the anterior relation of the pancreas is the stomach."},
/*710*/ {"q":"Doronum of foot is supply by which of following nerve?","o":["Deep peroneal nerve (first web space) / superficial peroneal","Sural","Tibial","Saphenous"],"a":0,"e":"The dorsum of the foot is supplied mainly by the superficial peroneal nerve, with the first web space by the deep peroneal nerve.<br><br>The sural supplies the lateral foot; the dorsum is chiefly peroneal nerve territory."},
/*711*/ {"q":"A patient is presented in Emergency following RTA. Numbness of ear lobule while doing internal jugular lymph node biopsy. Which of the following nerve is damaged?","o":["Great auricular nerve","Lesser occipital","Transverse cervical","Supraclavicular"],"a":0,"e":"Numbness of the ear lobule after posterior triangle/IJV node biopsy indicates injury to the great auricular nerve (C2-C3), which supplies the ear lobule and angle of jaw skin.<br><br>The lesser occipital serves the scalp behind the ear; the lobule numbness is the great auricular nerve."},
/*712*/ {"q":"Infection can travel from face through superior ophthalmic vein to:","o":["Cavernous sinus","Sigmoid sinus","Transverse sinus","Straight sinus"],"a":0,"e":"The superior ophthalmic vein communicates with the facial vein and drains into the cavernous sinus, the route for facial infection spread.<br><br>The other dural sinuses are not connected to the ophthalmic vein; the destination is the cavernous sinus."},
/*713*/ {"q":"Deltoid ligament is damaged due to which of following excessive movement?","o":["Eversion","Inversion","Dorsiflexion","Plantar flexion"],"a":0,"e":"The strong deltoid ligament resists ankle eversion; forced eversion is the movement that damages it.<br><br>Inversion injures the lateral ligament complex; the deltoid ligament fails with eversion."},
/*714*/ {"q":"Mullerian duct develops into?","o":["Uterus & Vagina","Penis & Testis","Bladder","Prostate"],"a":0,"e":"The paramesonephric (Mullerian) ducts develop into the uterus, fallopian tubes and upper vagina in the female.<br><br>Wolffian ducts form male structures; the Mullerian derivatives are the uterus and vagina."},
/*715*/ {"q":"Golgi Tendon Organ detects tension in which of following?","o":["Terminal Bronchiole","Trachea","Bronchi","Larynx"],"a":3,"e":"Per the source key, this Golgi tendon organ item is matched to the larynx option among the choices.<br><br>The other respiratory structures do not match the keyed answer; the marked option is larynx."},
/*716*/ {"q":"Clara cells are abundant in which of following?","o":["Terminal Bronchiole","Trachea","Bronchi","Alveoli"],"a":0,"e":"Club (Clara) cells are most abundant in the terminal and respiratory bronchioles, where they secrete surfactant proteins and detoxify inhaled substances.<br><br>The trachea has goblet cells; Clara cells concentrate in the terminal bronchioles."},
/*717*/ {"q":"Which helps in regulation of extracellular potassium?","o":["Insulin","Glucagon","Cortisol","Epinephrine"],"a":0,"e":"Insulin promotes cellular potassium uptake via stimulation of the Na/K ATPase, an important regulator of extracellular potassium.<br><br>Glucagon has minimal effect; the keyed potassium-shifting hormone is insulin."},
/*718*/ {"q":"Regarding Bile duct which of following is true?","o":["Posterior portal vein","Right to hepatic artery","Anterior to portal vein in free edge of lesser omentum","Posterior to duodenum"],"a":2,"e":"In the free edge of the lesser omentum the bile duct lies anterior and to the right, the hepatic artery to the left and the portal vein behind both.<br><br>It is not posterior to the portal vein; the bile duct lies anterior to it in the hepatoduodenal ligament."},
/*719*/ {"q":"A patient is suffering from Severe Diarrhea K+ infusion given. Which channel through which K+ go into cell through which channel?","o":["Na-k pump","K-ATPase","H-pump","Ca-pump"],"a":0,"e":"Potassium is driven into cells primarily by the Na+/K+ ATPase pump, which exchanges three sodium out for two potassium in.<br><br>The H-pump and Ca-pump handle other ions; cellular K uptake is via the Na/K pump."},
/*720*/ {"q":"Conduction in nerve fibers is slow down due to?","o":["Myelinated","Non-myelinated","Short fiber","Increase diameter"],"a":1,"e":"Unmyelinated (non-myelinated) fibres conduct impulses slowly because they lack saltatory conduction, unlike myelinated fibres.<br><br>Larger diameter and myelination speed conduction; slow conduction occurs in non-myelinated fibres."},
/*721*/ {"q":"Broca area present in:","o":["Superior frontal gyrus","Inferior frontal gyrus","Middle frontal gyrus","Superior temporal gyrus"],"a":1,"e":"Broca motor speech area lies in the inferior frontal gyrus (pars opercularis and triangularis) of the dominant hemisphere.<br><br>The superior temporal gyrus houses Wernicke area; Broca is in the inferior frontal gyrus."},
/*722*/ {"q":"70yr old man with urinary retention comes to emergency and has urgency frequency since 1 month. PSA is significantly raised. On rectal examination prostate is palpable, moderately enlarged. Pulse pressure is increased in which of the following condition?","o":["ADH","Angiotensin-2","Renin","Aortic stenosis"],"a":1,"e":"Per the source key, the increased pulse pressure in this composite item is matched to the angiotensin-2 option among the choices.<br><br>The other endocrine distractors do not match the keyed answer; the marked option is angiotensin-2."},
/*723*/ {"q":"Clara cells are abundant in which of following?","o":["Terminal Bronchiole","Trachea","Posterior lobe","Anterior lobe"],"a":0,"e":"Clara (club) cells are most numerous in the terminal bronchioles, secreting surfactant components and detoxifying inhaled xenobiotics.<br><br>The trachea is lined by ciliated and goblet cells; Clara cells are in the terminal bronchioles."},
/*724*/ {"q":"Which of following structure is present between stomach and pancreas?","o":["Para umbilical veins","Gastric vein","Esophageal veins","Lesser sac (omental bursa)"],"a":3,"e":"The lesser sac (omental bursa) lies between the posterior surface of the stomach and the anterior surface of the pancreas.<br><br>The venous distractors are not interposed; the space between is the lesser sac."},
/*725*/ {"q":"A 45-year male presented in emergency following RTA with operated next day died. Cause of death after fracture of neck of femur:","o":["Fat embolism","Air embolism","Thromboembolism","Amniotic embolism"],"a":0,"e":"Death a day or two after a long-bone (femoral neck) fracture with respiratory distress and petechiae is classically due to fat embolism syndrome.<br><br>Air and amniotic emboli have different settings; the post-fracture cause is fat embolism."},
/*726*/ {"q":"Pyloric ulcer rupture about operated next day died:","o":["Fat embolism","Air embolism","Thromboembolism","Peritonitis / sepsis"],"a":3,"e":"A perforated peptic ulcer that ruptures leads to chemical then bacterial peritonitis and sepsis, a common cause of postoperative death.<br><br>The embolic distractors fit fractures, not perforation; the keyed cause is peritonitis/sepsis."},
/*727*/ {"q":"4*cranial nerve palsy causes difficulty in?","o":["Looking down and in (descending stairs)","Looking up","Looking laterally","Convergence"],"a":0,"e":"Trochlear (CN IV) palsy weakens superior oblique, causing vertical diplopia and difficulty looking down and inward, classically when descending stairs.<br><br>Lateral gaze is abducens; the fourth nerve deficit is impaired downward-inward gaze."},
/*728*/ {"q":"The deep branch of radial nerve supply all except:","o":["Extensor carpi radialis longus","Extensor digitorum","Supinator","Extensor pollicis longus"],"a":0,"e":"Extensor carpi radialis longus is supplied by the radial nerve proper before the deep (posterior interosseous) branch; the deep branch supplies the other extensors.<br><br>The deep branch innervates extensor digitorum, supinator and EPL; the exception is extensor carpi radialis longus."},
/*729*/ {"q":"Innervation of triceps muscle is:","o":["Radial nerve","Median nerve","Ulnar nerve","Musculocutaneous nerve"],"a":0,"e":"All three heads of triceps brachii are supplied by the radial nerve (C7, C8).<br><br>The musculocutaneous supplies the anterior arm flexors; triceps is radial nerve innervated."},
/*730*/ {"q":"Ca pancreas patient is admitted in ward. His brother is not letting you tell the patient that he has cancer. You discuss according to his brother's family. What will you do?","o":["Give family time to discuss among themselves","Tell his brother that it will be dishonesty with patient family and medical staff","Will ask him to mind his own business","Refuse to treat"],"a":1,"e":"Ethical practice and patient autonomy require honest disclosure to the competent patient; the family should be told that withholding the diagnosis would be dishonest and inappropriate.<br><br>Colluding in concealment violates the patient's rights; the correct action is to explain the duty of honesty."},
/*731*/ {"q":"Regarding confidence interval?","o":["Mean and standard error of mean","Only mean","Only standard error","Standard deviation"],"a":0,"e":"A confidence interval is constructed from the sample mean and the standard error of the mean, indicating the precision of the estimate.<br><br>It is not the mean or standard error alone; it combines the mean with the standard error."},
/*732*/ {"q":"Blood supply to which organ remains unchanged during moderate exercise?","o":["Brain","Splanchnic","Skeletal muscle","Heart"],"a":0,"e":"Cerebral blood flow is tightly autoregulated and remains essentially constant during exercise, unlike muscle (increases) or splanchnic flow (decreases).<br><br>Skeletal muscle and heart flow rise; the unchanged organ is the brain (Ref. BRS Physiology)."},
/*733*/ {"q":"Thirst is stimulated by which of following?","o":["ADH","Angiotensin-2","Renin","Aldosterone"],"a":1,"e":"Angiotensin II is a potent dipsogen, acting on the hypothalamic thirst centre to stimulate water intake during hypovolaemia.<br><br>ADH conserves water but is not the thirst stimulant; the dipsogenic peptide is angiotensin II."},
/*734*/ {"q":"Pulse pressure is increased in which of the following condition?","o":["Aortic regurgitation","Aortic stenosis","Mitral stenosis","Cardiac tamponade"],"a":0,"e":"Aortic regurgitation produces a wide pulse pressure from a high systolic and low diastolic pressure (water-hammer pulse).<br><br>Aortic stenosis and tamponade narrow the pulse pressure; widening occurs in aortic regurgitation (Ref. BRS Physiology)."},
/*735*/ {"q":"The most likely complication in ventricular muscle is caused by:","o":["Na influx","Ca influx","Increased K conductance","Decreased K conductance"],"a":1,"e":"The plateau phase of the cardiac ventricular action potential is maintained by slow calcium influx through L-type channels, sustaining contraction.<br><br>Potassium efflux causes repolarisation; the plateau depolarisation is calcium influx."},
/*736*/ {"q":"Most common organism causing pneumonia in alcoholic patients:","o":["Streptococcus pneumonia","Klebsiella pneumoniae","Mycoplasma","Legionella"],"a":1,"e":"Klebsiella pneumoniae classically causes severe lobar pneumonia with currant-jelly sputum in alcoholics and debilitated patients.<br><br>Pneumococcus is commonest overall; in alcoholics the characteristic organism is Klebsiella."},
/*737*/ {"q":"Action potential depolarization in ventricular muscle is caused by:","o":["Na influx","Ca influx","K efflux","Cl influx"],"a":0,"e":"The rapid upstroke (phase 0) of the ventricular action potential is produced by fast sodium influx through voltage-gated Na channels.<br><br>Calcium influx sustains the plateau; the initial depolarisation is sodium influx."},
/*738*/ {"q":"Which of the following type of hernia is associated with Hesselbach triangle?","o":["Femoral hernia","Direct inguinal hernia","Indirect inguinal hernia","Umbilical hernia"],"a":1,"e":"A direct inguinal hernia protrudes through the floor of Hesselbach triangle, medial to the inferior epigastric vessels.<br><br>Indirect hernias pass lateral to these vessels through the deep ring; the Hesselbach triangle hernia is direct."},
/*739*/ {"q":"Sinus artery is branch of which of following?","o":["RCA","LAD","LCX","Marginal"],"a":0,"e":"The sinoatrial nodal artery most commonly arises from the right coronary artery in the majority of individuals.<br><br>It is a left circumflex branch in a minority; predominantly it is an RCA branch."},
/*740*/ {"q":"26yr old man had gunshot wound to the spine after which he lost power but increased tone and up going plantar with central clonus lesion at?","o":["Lateral spinothalamic","Both corticospinal and lateral","Corticospinal","Cerebellum"],"a":1,"e":"Loss of power with increased tone, upgoing plantars and clonus indicates an upper motor neuron (corticospinal/pyramidal) lesion; the keyed answer reflects both corticospinal and lateral tract involvement.<br><br>A pure sensory tract lesion would not give spasticity; the keyed site is the corticospinal pathway."},
/*741*/ {"q":"Growth hormone needs which hormone for regulation?","o":["Insulin","Cortisol","Thyroxine","Glucagon"],"a":2,"e":"Thyroxine is permissive for growth hormone secretion and action, essential for normal somatic growth and bone maturation.<br><br>Insulin and glucagon regulate metabolism; GH function requires thyroxine permissiveness."},
/*742*/ {"q":"Which of the following zone is most commonly involved in BPH?","o":["Peripheral zone","Central zone","Anterior zone","Transitional zone"],"a":3,"e":"Benign prostatic hyperplasia characteristically arises in the periurethral transition zone, compressing the urethra.<br><br>The peripheral zone is the site of carcinoma; BPH involves the transition zone."},
/*743*/ {"q":"Blood supply of rectum is from:","o":["Superior mesenteric","Inferior mesenteric (via superior rectal)","Celiac trunk","Gastroduodenal"],"a":1,"e":"The rectum is supplied by the superior rectal artery (a continuation of the inferior mesenteric artery), with middle and inferior rectal contributions.<br><br>The superior mesenteric supplies the midgut; the rectal supply originates from the inferior mesenteric."},
/*744*/ {"q":"Sinus artery is branch of which of following?","o":["RCA","LAD","Conus","Marginal"],"a":0,"e":"The sinoatrial nodal artery arises from the right coronary artery in about 60 percent of hearts.<br><br>It is occasionally a circumflex branch; predominantly it is an RCA branch."},
/*745*/ {"q":"What is most likely cause of paroxysmal hypertension?","o":["Pheochromocytoma","Conn syndrome","Renal artery stenosis","Cushing syndrome"],"a":0,"e":"Episodic (paroxysmal) hypertension with headache, palpitations and sweating is characteristic of phaeochromocytoma from catecholamine surges.<br><br>Conn and Cushing cause sustained hypertension; the paroxysmal pattern is phaeochromocytoma."},
/*746*/ {"q":"A man drinks 2 L of water so most replenish the fluids lost by sweating during a period of exercise. Compared with the period of sweating, his intracellular fluid will be:","o":["Greater","Lesser","Unchanged","Doubled"],"a":0,"e":"Replacing hypotonic sweat loss with plain water lowers extracellular osmolality, drawing water into cells so intracellular fluid volume becomes greater.<br><br>It does not stay unchanged; net water shifts in, increasing intracellular fluid."},
/*747*/ {"q":"Water proofing of skin is done by:","o":["Keratin","Elastin","Hair follicles","Collagen"],"a":0,"e":"The keratinised stratified squamous epidermis, rich in keratin and lipids, provides the waterproofing barrier of the skin.<br><br>Elastin and collagen are dermal; the waterproofing protein is keratin."},
/*748*/ {"q":"Patient has hemoptysis & probable diagnosis is glomerulonephritis. The most probable diagnosis is:","o":["Wegener's Granulomatosis","Goodpasture Syndrome","Diabetic glomerulopathy","SLE nephritis"],"a":1,"e":"Pulmonary haemorrhage (haemoptysis) with glomerulonephritis is the classic pulmonary-renal syndrome of Goodpasture (anti-GBM) disease (Ref. Robbins Pathology).<br><br>Wegener's adds upper-airway granulomas; the haemoptysis-plus-GN picture keyed is Goodpasture."},
/*749*/ {"q":"What is the age of closure of anterior fontanelle?","o":["9 month","12 month to 18 months","24 month","36 month"],"a":1,"e":"The anterior fontanelle normally closes between about 12 and 18 months of age.<br><br>Earlier or much later closure is abnormal; the typical range is 12-18 months."},
/*750*/ {"q":"A female with non caseating granuloma and hilar lymphadenopathy (sarcoidosis). The type of cells involved:","o":["Basophils","T-lymphocytes","Eosinophils","Neutrophils"],"a":1,"e":"Sarcoid non-caseating granulomas are formed by CD4+ T-lymphocytes and epithelioid macrophages, reflecting a T-cell-mediated immune response.<br><br>Eosinophils and neutrophils are not central here; the key cells are T-lymphocytes."},

/*751*/ {"q":"True hermaphroditism karyotype:","o":["46XX","45XO","47XXY","46XX/46XY mosaic"],"a":3,"e":"True hermaphroditism, with both ovarian and testicular tissue, is most often associated with a 46XX karyotype or 46XX/46XY mosaicism per source mapping.<br><br>Among the options the keyed answer reflects the 46XX/46XY mosaic possibility for true hermaphroditism."},
/*752*/ {"q":"Which of following is single motor supply muscle?","o":["Diaphragm","Mylohyoid","Adductor magnus","Pectoralis"],"a":0,"e":"The diaphragm receives its sole motor supply from the phrenic nerve, a true single-nerve motor innervation.<br><br>Adductor magnus has dual supply; the single motor-supplied muscle is the diaphragm."},
/*753*/ {"q":"A female with non caseating granuloma and hilar lymphadenopathy (sarcoidosis). The type of cells involved:","o":["Basophils","T-lymphocytes","Eosinophils","Neutrophils"],"a":1,"e":"Sarcoid non-caseating granulomas are driven by CD4+ T-lymphocytes interacting with epithelioid macrophages.<br><br>Granulocytes are not central; the principal cells are T-lymphocytes."},
/*754*/ {"q":"Which of the following is single motor supply muscle?","o":["Diaphragm","Mylohyoid","Sternocleidomastoid","Trapezius"],"a":0,"e":"The diaphragm is innervated solely by the phrenic nerve, a clean example of single motor innervation.<br><br>Sternocleidomastoid and trapezius receive accessory nerve plus cervical contributions; the single-supply muscle is the diaphragm."},
/*755*/ {"q":"Which sutures were prematurely closed in frontal and occipital bossing?","o":["Coronal","Sagittal","Lambdoid","Coronal + lambdoid"],"a":1,"e":"Premature closure of the sagittal suture causes scaphocephaly with frontal and occipital bossing and a long narrow skull.<br><br>Coronal synostosis gives brachycephaly; frontal-occipital bossing keys to sagittal suture closure."},
/*756*/ {"q":"Right vocal cord weakness which of following recurrent laryngeal nerve is involved?","o":["Right recurrent laryngeal","Left recurrent laryngeal","Both","Vagus trunk"],"a":0,"e":"Right vocal cord weakness indicates a lesion of the right recurrent laryngeal nerve, which loops around the right subclavian artery.<br><br>The left nerve causes left cord palsy; right cord weakness is the right recurrent laryngeal nerve."},
/*757*/ {"q":"What is the age of closure of posterior fontanelle?","o":["2-3 months","6 months","12 months","18 months"],"a":0,"e":"The posterior fontanelle normally closes early, by about 2-3 months of age.<br><br>The anterior fontanelle closes much later (12-18 months); the posterior closes at 2-3 months."},
/*758*/ {"q":"Part of heart form most of the sternal surface (anterior surface):","o":["Right atrium","Right ventricle","Left ventricle","Left atrium"],"a":1,"e":"The right ventricle forms the majority of the anterior (sternocostal) surface of the heart.<br><br>The left ventricle forms the apex and left border; the bulk of the anterior surface is the right ventricle."},
/*759*/ {"q":"A female with non caseating lymphadenopathy and hilar lymphadenopathy (sarcoidosis). The type of cells involved:","o":["Basophils","T-lymphocytes","Eosinophils","Neutrophils"],"a":1,"e":"Sarcoidosis granulomas are formed predominantly by CD4+ T-lymphocytes and epithelioid macrophages.<br><br>Eosinophils and neutrophils are not key; the involved cells are T-lymphocytes."},
/*760*/ {"q":"Person naked in room, Temp 21 C, humidity present, heat loss will occur by:","o":["Radiation","Conduction","Convection","Evaporation"],"a":0,"e":"At 21 degrees ambient temperature with a nude body, the dominant mechanism of heat loss is radiation from the skin surface.<br><br>Evaporation dominates only with sweating or high humidity/temperature; at this temperature it is radiation."},
/*761*/ {"q":"Diabetic patient has increased urination and frequency due to?","o":["Glomerular protein defect","Osmotic diuresis from glucosuria","Decreased ADH","Decreased aldosterone"],"a":1,"e":"In diabetes mellitus, glucose exceeding the renal threshold causes osmotic diuresis, drawing water into the tubule and producing polyuria.<br><br>ADH and protein defects are not the cause; the polyuria is osmotic diuresis from glucosuria."},
/*762*/ {"q":"Nerve only afferent to brain:","o":["Olfactory / Optic","Oculomotor","Trochlear","Abducens"],"a":0,"e":"The olfactory and optic nerves are purely sensory (afferent) cranial nerves carrying smell and vision to the brain.<br><br>Oculomotor, trochlear and abducens are purely motor; the afferent-only nerve is the optic/olfactory."},
/*763*/ {"q":"Osmotic pressure is due to which of following?","o":["Hypoproteinemia","Albumin","Globulin","Fibrinogen"],"a":1,"e":"Plasma colloid osmotic (oncotic) pressure is generated mainly by albumin, the most abundant and osmotically active plasma protein.<br><br>Globulin and fibrinogen contribute little; oncotic pressure is chiefly due to albumin."},
/*764*/ {"q":"In burn patient edema is due to:","o":["Hyperpyrexia","Arteriolar and venous vasodilation","Vasoconstriction","Decreased capillary permeability"],"a":1,"e":"Burn oedema results from inflammatory mediator-induced vasodilation and markedly increased capillary permeability, leaking protein-rich fluid into tissue.<br><br>Vasoconstriction and decreased permeability are incorrect; burn oedema is from vasodilation and increased permeability."},
/*765*/ {"q":"38 years old HIV positive patient is complaining of headache. On examination neck stiffness is positive fungal meningitis is suspected to be the cause. Which of the following is thought to be the cause in the HIV/AIDS patient?","o":["Aspergillus fumigatus","Blastomyces dermatitis","Cryptococcus neoformans","Histoplasma capsulatum"],"a":2,"e":"Cryptococcus neoformans is the commonest cause of fungal meningitis in HIV/AIDS patients, diagnosed by India ink or cryptococcal antigen.<br><br>Aspergillus and histoplasma less commonly cause meningitis; the AIDS meningitis fungus is Cryptococcus."},
/*766*/ {"q":"Mother gave immunoglobulin to hydrops baby which?","o":["IgA","IgM","IgG","IgE"],"a":2,"e":"IgG is the only immunoglobulin that crosses the placenta, so maternal IgG (anti-D) mediates haemolytic disease causing hydrops fetalis.<br><br>IgM does not cross the placenta; the relevant maternal antibody is IgG."},
/*767*/ {"q":"Patient during surgery blood transfusion is given. She develops:","o":["Hypocalcemia","Hyperkalemia","Hypothermia","Acidosis"],"a":0,"e":"Massive transfusion of citrated blood can chelate calcium and cause hypocalcaemia, with paraesthesia and cardiac effects.<br><br>While hyperkalaemia can occur with old blood, the keyed citrate-related complication is hypocalcaemia."},
/*768*/ {"q":"In anaphylactic shock what changes occur in patient?","o":["Hyperpyrexia","Arteriolar and venous vasodilation","Vasoconstriction","Bradycardia"],"a":1,"e":"Anaphylactic (distributive) shock causes widespread arteriolar and venous vasodilation with increased permeability, producing hypotension and oedema.<br><br>Vasoconstriction characterises hypovolaemic shock; anaphylaxis causes vasodilation."},
/*769*/ {"q":"A patient came in emergency, what type of shock is this?","o":["Anaphylactic shock","Cardiac tamponade","Hypovolemic shock","Septic shock"],"a":2,"e":"Per the source key, the emergency scenario in this item is matched to cardiac tamponade among the choices, with obstructive shock physiology.<br><br>Following the keyed answer, the marked option is cardiac tamponade."},
/*770*/ {"q":"A child with erythroblastosis need blood transfusion which blood group to give?","o":["A negative","A positive","O negative","O positive"],"a":2,"e":"For Rh haemolytic disease of the newborn, group O Rh-negative blood is used for exchange transfusion to avoid further antigen-driven haemolysis.<br><br>Rh-positive blood would worsen haemolysis; the safe choice is O negative."},
/*771*/ {"q":"Which of following is strong adductor of femur?","o":["Sartorius","Gluteus Maximus","Gluteus Minimus","Adductor magnus"],"a":3,"e":"Adductor magnus is the largest and most powerful adductor of the thigh, with combined adductor and hamstring portions.<br><br>Sartorius and gluteals are not primary adductors; the strong adductor is adductor magnus."},
/*772*/ {"q":"Common relation of ureter to gonadal vessels and artery:","o":["Ureter posterior to gonadal vessels","Ureter anterior to gonadal vessels","Ureter medial","Ureter lateral"],"a":0,"e":"The ureter passes posterior (deep) to the gonadal vessels, an important relation when ligating the gonadal pedicle.<br><br>Crossing it anteriorly would risk injury; the ureter lies behind the gonadal vessels."},
/*773*/ {"q":"What is most common cause of edema in hypertensive patient?","o":["Sympathetic + parasympathetic","Increased hydrostatic pressure","Decreased oncotic pressure","Lymphatic block"],"a":1,"e":"In hypertensive heart failure, raised venous and capillary hydrostatic pressure is the principal cause of dependent oedema.<br><br>Oncotic and lymphatic causes are secondary; the keyed mechanism is increased hydrostatic pressure."},
/*774*/ {"q":"What is most common cause of mental retardation?","o":["Down syndrome","Turner syndrome","Klinefelter syndrome","Fragile X syndrome"],"a":3,"e":"Fragile X syndrome is the commonest inherited (single-gene) cause of intellectual disability; Down syndrome is the commonest chromosomal cause overall.<br><br>Per this source key the marked answer for commonest genetic cause is Fragile X syndrome."},
/*775*/ {"q":"Warfarin affects which pathway of coagulation?","o":["Intrinsic","Extrinsic","Common pathway","Extrinsic + Intrinsic (vitamin K factors)"],"a":3,"e":"Warfarin inhibits vitamin K-dependent factors II, VII, IX and X, affecting the extrinsic, intrinsic and common pathways, monitored by the PT/INR (chiefly extrinsic).<br><br>Limiting to one pathway is incomplete; warfarin's vitamin-K factors span extrinsic and intrinsic systems."},
/*776*/ {"q":"In a young female pt with prolactin level 28 (normal 26) but no galactorrhea, what will you do?","o":["Rule out physiological cause","Pituitary profile","CT/MRI pituitary","Start cabergoline"],"a":0,"e":"A trivially raised prolactin (28 vs normal 26) without galactorrhoea is most likely physiological (stress, sampling); the first step is to exclude physiological causes and repeat.<br><br>Imaging and treatment are premature; the appropriate step is to rule out a physiological cause."},
/*777*/ {"q":"Most potent chemotactic agent:","o":["LTB4","C5a","C3b","Histamine"],"a":1,"e":"C5a is among the most potent chemotactic and anaphylatoxic complement fragments; LTB4 is also a powerful chemoattractant, but per source key the marked answer is C5a.<br><br>Following the keyed answer, the strongest chemotactic agent here is C5a."},
/*778*/ {"q":"Diapedesis refers to:","o":["Migration of leukocytes across endothelium","Margination","Chemotaxis","Rolling"],"a":0,"e":"Diapedesis is the transmigration of leucocytes between or through endothelial cells from the vessel lumen into the tissue.<br><br>Margination and rolling are earlier steps; the trans-endothelial movement is diapedesis."},
/*779*/ {"q":"Ejaculation is done due to:","o":["Sympathetic + parasympathetic","Parasympathetic","Sympathetic","Pudendal only"],"a":2,"e":"Emission and ejaculation are mediated by the sympathetic system (L1-L2) contracting the vas, seminal vesicles and bladder neck, with the pudendal adding the somatic expulsive phase.<br><br>Erection is parasympathetic; ejaculation is sympathetically driven."},
/*780*/ {"q":"In hypertensive patient what is cause of edema?","o":["Sympathetic + parasympathetic","Increased hydrostatic pressure","Decreased oncotic pressure","Lymphatic obstruction"],"a":1,"e":"Hypertensive cardiac dysfunction raises venous and capillary hydrostatic pressure, the principal cause of dependent oedema in these patients.<br><br>Oncotic and lymphatic causes are secondary; the keyed cause is increased hydrostatic pressure."},
/*781*/ {"q":"What is most common cause of mental retardation?","o":["ITP","DIC","Factor 8 deficiency","Fragile X syndrome"],"a":3,"e":"Fragile X syndrome is the commonest inherited cause of intellectual disability, an X-linked trinucleotide repeat disorder.<br><br>The coagulation-disorder distractors are irrelevant; the keyed cause is Fragile X syndrome."},
/*782*/ {"q":"Marker raised 60% in colon cancer:","o":["CEA","CA 19-9","CA 125","AFP"],"a":0,"e":"Carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA) is the marker classically elevated in colorectal carcinoma, used for prognosis and follow-up.<br><br>CA 19-9 relates to pancreatic cancer; the colon cancer marker is CEA."},
/*783*/ {"q":"Acute laryngotracheobronchitis (Croup) is caused by which of following?","o":["Parainfluenza virus","Respiratory Syncytial virus","Adenovirus","Rhinovirus"],"a":0,"e":"Croup (acute laryngotracheobronchitis) with barking cough and stridor is most commonly caused by parainfluenza virus.<br><br>RSV typically causes bronchiolitis; croup is chiefly parainfluenza."},
/*784*/ {"q":"The chance of bleeding in a patient with epidural will be greatest in patient on warfarin:","o":["Patient on warfarin","Heparin","LMWH","Aspirin"],"a":0,"e":"Warfarin produces sustained anticoagulation by depleting vitamin K-dependent factors, carrying the greatest bleeding risk with neuraxial procedures.<br><br>Aspirin's effect is milder; the highest epidural bleeding risk is on warfarin."},
/*785*/ {"q":"Most potent Na retaining hormone is:","o":["Cortisol","Aldosterone","ADH","Angiotensin 2"],"a":1,"e":"Aldosterone is the most potent sodium-retaining mineralocorticoid, acting on the distal nephron to reabsorb sodium and excrete potassium (Ref. Guyton Physiology).<br><br>Cortisol has weak mineralocorticoid activity; the principal sodium-retaining hormone is aldosterone."},
/*786*/ {"q":"Percentage of Thalassemia trait in Pakistan:","o":["5%","15%","17%","12%"],"a":0,"e":"The carrier frequency of beta-thalassaemia trait in Pakistan is around 5 percent per this source.<br><br>Higher figures overstate prevalence; the keyed carrier rate is about 5 percent."},
/*787*/ {"q":"All are neural crest cell derivative except:","o":["Vomer bone","Choroid and sclera of eye","Tunica media of great vessels","Vestibule and cochlea"],"a":3,"e":"Neural crest contributes to facial bones, the choroid/sclera and the tunica media of great vessels; the cochlea and vestibule derive from the otic placode/ectoderm.<br><br>The non-crest structure among these is the vestibule and cochlea."},
/*788*/ {"q":"Ovulation occurs on which day of menstrual cycle?","o":["10th","14th","18th","19th"],"a":1,"e":"In a typical 28-day cycle ovulation occurs around day 14, triggered by the mid-cycle LH surge.<br><br>Days 10 and 18 do not fit the standard cycle; ovulation is about day 14."},
/*789*/ {"q":"In which of the following maximum chemotaxis occur?","o":["10a","14a","18a","19a"],"a":3,"e":"Per the source key, the maximum chemotaxis option in this item is matched to the 19a choice among the listed labels.<br><br>The other labels do not match the keyed answer; the marked option is 19a."},
/*790*/ {"q":"Anti tuberculosis drug causes Red green color blindness?","o":["Ethambutol","INH","Rifampicin","Streptomycin"],"a":0,"e":"Ethambutol causes optic neuritis with red-green colour blindness and reduced visual acuity, a dose-dependent toxicity.<br><br>Isoniazid causes peripheral neuropathy; the colour-vision toxicity is ethambutol."},
/*791*/ {"q":"AV septum is ruptured following valve is affected most?","o":["Tricuspid","Bicuspid","Aortic","Pulmonary"],"a":0,"e":"The septal leaflet of the tricuspid valve relates closely to the atrioventricular septum, so AV septal rupture most affects the tricuspid valve.<br><br>The semilunar valves are remote; the tricuspid is most involved."},
/*792*/ {"q":"Which of the following is not characteristic of hypopituitarism?","o":["Cachexia","Infertility","Pallor","Hyperpigmentation"],"a":3,"e":"Hypopituitarism causes pallor (loss of MSH/ACTH effect), infertility and weight loss; hyperpigmentation is a feature of primary adrenal failure (Addison), not hypopituitarism.<br><br>The non-characteristic feature here is hyperpigmentation."},
/*793*/ {"q":"Spermatogenesis complete how much period of:","o":["60 days","74 days","87 days","49 days"],"a":1,"e":"Human spermatogenesis takes approximately 74 days from spermatogonium to mature spermatozoon.<br><br>The other figures misstate the duration; the keyed period is about 74 days."},
/*794*/ {"q":"Most sensitive test for screening of SLE?","o":["Anti smith","Anti phospholipid","Anti DS","ANA"],"a":3,"e":"Antinuclear antibody (ANA) is the most sensitive screening test for systemic lupus erythematosus; anti-dsDNA and anti-Sm are more specific.<br><br>For screening sensitivity the keyed test is ANA."},
/*795*/ {"q":"An 32 years old obese male comes complaining of heart rate, 9kg weight loss in 2 months and heat intolerance. His pulse is 110/min and serum T4 levels are elevated. Upon questioning, he admits to taking thyroxin tablets for losing weight. The parameter which shows an increase is?","o":["TSH","Serum free T4","Serum T3","Thyroid uptake"],"a":1,"e":"Exogenous thyroxine ingestion (thyrotoxicosis factitia) raises serum free T4 while suppressing TSH and reducing thyroid radioiodine uptake.<br><br>TSH and uptake fall; the parameter that rises is serum free T4."},
/*796*/ {"q":"Cephalohematoma common site is:","o":["Loose areolar tissue","Connective tissue","Under the skin","Subperiosteal (does not cross sutures)"],"a":3,"e":"A cephalhaematoma is a subperiosteal haemorrhage confined by suture lines, so it does not cross sutures.<br><br>Subgaleal bleeds cross sutures; the cephalhaematoma is subperiosteal."},
/*797*/ {"q":"A patient is suffering from dysphagia dysarthria analgesia on ipsilateral side of face and ipsilateral Horner syndrome. Occlusion of which artery would produce these symptoms and signs?","o":["Posterior inferior cerebellar artery","Anterior inferior cerebellar artery","Posterior spinal artery","Anterior spinal artery"],"a":0,"e":"Lateral medullary (Wallenberg) syndrome with dysphagia, ipsilateral facial sensory loss and Horner syndrome is due to posterior inferior cerebellar (vertebral) artery occlusion.<br><br>AICA gives a lateral pontine picture; this constellation is PICA territory."},
/*798*/ {"q":"Parasympathetic stimulation causes:","o":["Bronchial constriction","Increase heart rate","Decrease secretions","Pupillary dilation"],"a":0,"e":"Parasympathetic (vagal) stimulation causes bronchoconstriction, bradycardia, increased glandular secretion and pupillary constriction.<br><br>Heart rate and pupil effects listed are sympathetic; the parasympathetic effect is bronchial constriction."},
/*799*/ {"q":"Weakness of right side of body and diplopia on looking left?","o":["Left internal capsule","Right internal capsule","Midbrain","Left cerebral cortex"],"a":0,"e":"Right-sided weakness from a left internal capsule lesion, with associated gaze/diplopia, localises the motor pathway lesion to the left internal capsule.<br><br>The crossed pattern places the lesion contralateral to the weakness, in the left internal capsule."},
/*800*/ {"q":"A patient presents with vertical diplopia, head tilting. Blurred vision and also difficulty in coming down stairs. The likely nerve damaged is:","o":["Oculomotor nerve","Trochlear nerve","Trigeminal nerve","Abducent nerve"],"a":1,"e":"Vertical diplopia with compensatory head tilt and difficulty descending stairs is the classic presentation of trochlear (CN IV) palsy affecting superior oblique.<br><br>Abducens palsy gives horizontal diplopia; the stairs-and-head-tilt pattern is trochlear."},

/*801*/ {"q":"Which of the following ligaments keeps the vertebral bodies in place?","o":["Ligamentum flavum","Anterior and posterior longitudinal ligament","Supraspinous ligament","Interspinous ligament"],"a":1,"e":"The anterior and posterior longitudinal ligaments run along the vertebral bodies, binding them and limiting hyperextension and hyperflexion respectively.<br><br>The ligamentum flavum connects laminae; vertebral bodies are held by the longitudinal ligaments."},
/*802*/ {"q":"During hysterectomy, ureter can be damaged at which site?","o":["Pelvic brim","Behind the broad ligament","Crossing common iliac arteries","Beneath uterine artery near cervix"],"a":3,"e":"The ureter is most commonly injured during hysterectomy where it passes beneath the uterine artery near the cervix (\"water under the bridge\").<br><br>The pelvic brim is a secondary risk; the classic site is beneath the uterine artery."},
/*803*/ {"q":"A patient is suffering from dysphagia, dysarthria, analgesia on ipsilateral side of face. Occlusion of which artery would produce these symptoms?","o":["Posterior inferior cerebellar artery","Anterior inferior cerebellar artery","Posterior cerebral artery","Anterior communicating artery"],"a":0,"e":"Lateral medullary (Wallenberg) syndrome with dysphagia, dysarthria and ipsilateral facial sensory loss results from PICA (vertebral) occlusion.<br><br>AICA gives a pontine syndrome; this medullary picture is PICA territory."},
/*804*/ {"q":"A patient is presented in OPD with bitemporal hemianopia. Aneurysm is most likely in which of following?","o":["Anterior cerebral artery","Posterior cerebral artery","Middle cerebral artery","Internal carotid artery"],"a":3,"e":"Bitemporal hemianopia from optic chiasm compression is classically produced by an internal carotid artery aneurysm (or pituitary tumour) near the chiasm.<br><br>The posterior cerebral artery is remote; the keyed vessel here is the internal carotid artery."},
/*805*/ {"q":"Weakness of right side of body and diplopia on looking left?","o":["Left internal capsule","Right internal capsule","Midbrain","Pons"],"a":0,"e":"Right-sided body weakness with associated gaze diplopia indicates a left-sided motor pathway lesion at the internal capsule.<br><br>The crossed motor representation places the lesion in the left internal capsule."},
/*806*/ {"q":"A patient presents with vertical diplopia, head tilting, blurred vision and also difficulty in coming down stairs. The likely site of trochlear nucleus is:","o":["Midbrain","Pons","Medulla","Thalamus"],"a":0,"e":"The trochlear nucleus, lesion of which causes superior oblique palsy with vertical diplopia and head tilt, is located in the midbrain at the level of the inferior colliculus.<br><br>The other brainstem levels house different nuclei; the trochlear nucleus is in the midbrain."},
/*807*/ {"q":"Which of the following ligaments keeps the vertebral bodies in place?","o":["Anterior and posterior longitudinal ligament","Ligamentum flavum","Interspinous ligament","Supraspinous ligament"],"a":0,"e":"The anterior and posterior longitudinal ligaments span the vertebral bodies and discs, maintaining their alignment and limiting extreme movement.<br><br>The ligamentum flavum joins laminae; the body-stabilising ligaments are the longitudinal ligaments."},
/*808*/ {"q":"Bicornuate uterus abnormality of:","o":["Mesonephric duct","Paramesonephric duct (Mullerian fusion failure)","Urogenital sinus","Genital tubercle"],"a":1,"e":"A bicornuate uterus results from incomplete fusion of the paramesonephric (Mullerian) ducts.<br><br>The mesonephric duct forms male structures; the bicornuate uterus is a Mullerian fusion defect."},
/*809*/ {"q":"Droplet infection can spread up to:","o":["1-2 feet","3-6 feet","8-9 feet","15 feet"],"a":1,"e":"Respiratory droplets typically travel a limited distance, classically about 3-6 feet, before settling, the basis for droplet precautions.<br><br>Larger distances apply to airborne aerosols; droplet spread is about 3-6 feet."},
/*810*/ {"q":"A patient died of chronic renal failure which of the following will likely be hypertrophied on autopsy?","o":["Adrenal gland","Adrenal medulla","Parathyroid gland","Pituitary"],"a":2,"e":"Chronic renal failure causes secondary hyperparathyroidism from hypocalcaemia and phosphate retention, leading to parathyroid gland hyperplasia/hypertrophy.<br><br>The adrenal is not characteristically enlarged; the keyed hypertrophied gland is the parathyroid."},
/*811*/ {"q":"Potassium depletion may cause:","o":["Fall in plasma PCO2","Fall in plasma pH","Rise in hydrogen ion in plasma","Rise in plasma bicarbonate"],"a":3,"e":"Hypokalaemia is associated with metabolic alkalosis and a rise in plasma bicarbonate, as potassium shifts and renal H+ excretion change.<br><br>Plasma pH rises (alkalosis); potassium depletion raises plasma bicarbonate."},
/*812*/ {"q":"A child born with genetically male but external appearance of genital are like female what is diagnosis?","o":["Testicular feminization syndrome","Klinefelter","Turner syndrome","Pretracheal fascia"],"a":0,"e":"A genetic male (46,XY) with female external genitalia due to androgen receptor insensitivity is androgen insensitivity (testicular feminisation) syndrome.<br><br>Klinefelter and Turner have different karyotypes; the keyed diagnosis is testicular feminisation syndrome."},
/*813*/ {"q":"Biopsy taken from posterior triangle of neck damage to which of following nerve?","o":["Spinal part of accessory nerve","Long thoracic nerve","Radial nerve","Phrenic nerve"],"a":0,"e":"The spinal accessory nerve runs superficially across the posterior triangle and is the nerve most at risk during biopsy there, causing trapezius weakness.<br><br>The long thoracic nerve is on the chest wall; the posterior triangle nerve is the spinal accessory."},
/*814*/ {"q":"The extracellular matrix and the cytoskeleton communicate across the cell membrane through which of the following?","o":["Proteoglycans","Integrins","Cadherins","Microtubules"],"a":1,"e":"Integrins are transmembrane receptors that physically link the extracellular matrix to the intracellular cytoskeleton, transmitting mechanical and signalling information.<br><br>Cadherins mediate cell-cell adhesion; ECM-cytoskeleton communication is via integrins."},
/*815*/ {"q":"Cimetidine interaction causes:","o":["Cimetidine decreases metabolism of other drugs (CYP inhibition)","Increases their excretion","No interaction","Increases their absorption"],"a":0,"e":"Cimetidine inhibits hepatic cytochrome P450 enzymes, decreasing the metabolism of co-administered drugs and raising their levels and toxicity.<br><br>It does not enhance excretion; the interaction is CYP-mediated decreased metabolism of other drugs."},
/*816*/ {"q":"A thyroid mass usually moves with swallowing because of which of the following fascia?","o":["Pretracheal fascia","Prevertebral fascia","Carotid sheath","Investing layer of deep cervical fascia"],"a":0,"e":"The thyroid gland is enclosed by the pretracheal fascia, which attaches to the larynx, so the gland moves with swallowing.<br><br>The prevertebral fascia and carotid sheath are unrelated; the swallow-movement is due to the pretracheal fascia."},
/*817*/ {"q":"Biopsy taken from posterior triangle of neck damage to which of following nerve?","o":["Spinal accessory nerve","Long thoracic nerve","Pretracheal fascia","Salmonella"],"a":0,"e":"The spinal accessory nerve crosses the posterior triangle superficially and is the nerve most vulnerable during lymph node biopsy there.<br><br>The non-nerve distractors are irrelevant; the at-risk nerve is the spinal accessory."},
/*818*/ {"q":"Most potent stimulus for gallbladder contraction:","o":["Gastrin","CCK","Secretin","Salmonella"],"a":1,"e":"Cholecystokinin (CCK), released from the duodenum by fat and protein, is the most potent stimulus for gallbladder contraction and sphincter of Oddi relaxation.<br><br>Secretin acts on the pancreas; the gallbladder contraction stimulus is CCK."},
/*819*/ {"q":"Ossification of sternum completed by:","o":["15 yr","21 yr","25 yr","30 yr"],"a":1,"e":"The sternum completes ossification, including fusion of its segments, by approximately 21-25 years of age, with the xiphoid latest; the keyed answer here is around 21 years.<br><br>Earlier ages are incomplete; per source the keyed age is about 21 years."},
/*820*/ {"q":"Glucose level between meals is maintained by:","o":["Glycolysis","Hepatic glycogenolysis","Glycogenesis","Lipolysis"],"a":1,"e":"Between meals, blood glucose is maintained chiefly by hepatic glycogenolysis releasing stored glucose, with gluconeogenesis later in prolonged fasting.<br><br>Glycogenesis stores glucose in the fed state; inter-meal glucose comes from glycogenolysis."},
/*821*/ {"q":"A 50 year old housewife is suffering from gastric ulcer and arthritis. A safe drug to give her relief from joint pain would be:","o":["Aspirin","Celecoxib","Ibuprofen","Indomethacin"],"a":1,"e":"In a patient with peptic ulcer disease, a selective COX-2 inhibitor such as celecoxib provides analgesia with less gastric mucosal injury than non-selective NSAIDs.<br><br>Aspirin and ibuprofen worsen ulcers; the safer choice is celecoxib."},
/*822*/ {"q":"A patient is diagnosed as case of aplastic anemia. He is suffering from the most likely organism?","o":["Streptococcus pneumoniae","Staphylococcus aureus","Pseudomonas","Salmonella"],"a":2,"e":"Aplastic anaemia causes neutropenia, predisposing to severe infections, with Pseudomonas aeruginosa a classic dangerous opportunist in neutropenic patients.<br><br>Among these, the keyed neutropenic pathogen is Pseudomonas."},
/*823*/ {"q":"Stony dull percussion note shows:","o":["Pneumonia","Fluid in pleural cavity (effusion)","Atelectasis","Spontaneous rupture of bulla"],"a":1,"e":"A stony dull percussion note is characteristic of a pleural effusion, fluid in the pleural cavity.<br><br>Consolidation gives a less marked dullness; the stony dull note is a pleural effusion."},
/*824*/ {"q":"Which structure lie posterior to arch of aorta?","o":["Left phrenic nerve","SVC","Brachiocephalic vein","Trachea and oesophagus"],"a":3,"e":"The trachea and oesophagus lie posterior (and to the right) of the aortic arch in the superior mediastinum.<br><br>The phrenic nerve runs anterolaterally; posterior to the arch are the trachea and oesophagus."},
/*825*/ {"q":"After surgical neck of humerus fracture there is loss of abduction and proximal upper limb sensation. Injury at the anterior inferior iliac involved is:","o":["Axillary nerve","Musculocutaneous nerve","Radial nerve","Median nerve"],"a":0,"e":"Surgical neck of humerus fracture injures the axillary nerve, causing deltoid paralysis (loss of abduction) and sensory loss over the regimental badge area.<br><br>The radial nerve is mid-shaft; the surgical neck injury is the axillary nerve."},
/*826*/ {"q":"Cytoskeleton communicates across the cell membrane through which of the following?","o":["Glycolysis","Hepatic glycogenolysis","Integrins","Microtubules"],"a":2,"e":"Integrins are transmembrane adhesion receptors that connect the extracellular matrix to the intracellular cytoskeleton across the plasma membrane.<br><br>The metabolic distractors are irrelevant; ECM-cytoskeleton communication is via integrins."},
/*827*/ {"q":"A 50 year old housewife is suffering from gastric ulcer and arthritis. A safe drug to give her relief from joint pain would be:","o":["Aspirin","Celecoxib","Ibuprofen","Indomethacin"],"a":1,"e":"With coexisting peptic ulcer, a selective COX-2 inhibitor (celecoxib) gives anti-inflammatory relief while sparing gastric mucosal prostaglandins.<br><br>Non-selective NSAIDs worsen the ulcer; the safer analgesic is celecoxib."},
/*828*/ {"q":"True regarding action potential of a neuron?","o":["Is initiated by efflux of K+","Is terminated by efflux of K+","Is initiated by efflux of Na+","Is terminated by influx of Na+"],"a":1,"e":"The neuronal action potential is terminated (repolarised) by the efflux of potassium ions restoring the resting membrane potential.<br><br>It is initiated by sodium influx; termination is potassium efflux."},
/*829*/ {"q":"Phrenic nerve passes anterior to which of the following at the root of the neck?","o":["Subclavian artery","Scalenus anterior muscle","Vagus nerve","Internal jugular vein"],"a":1,"e":"At the root of the neck the phrenic nerve passes anterior to (over) the scalenus anterior muscle as it descends into the thorax.<br><br>It crosses in front of scalenus anterior; that is the structure it lies anterior to here."},
/*830*/ {"q":"Maxillary nerve enters through which foramen?","o":["Foramen ovale","Foramen rotundum","Foramen spinosum","Jugular foramen"],"a":1,"e":"The maxillary division of the trigeminal nerve (V2) exits the skull through the foramen rotundum.<br><br>The foramen ovale transmits the mandibular nerve; V2 passes the foramen rotundum."},
/*831*/ {"q":"All of the following cause edema except:","o":["Decreased arterial blood flow","Increased hydrostatic pressure","Decreased oncotic pressure","Increased capillary permeability"],"a":0,"e":"Oedema results from raised hydrostatic pressure, low oncotic pressure or increased permeability; decreased arterial inflow reduces capillary pressure and does not cause oedema.<br><br>The exception, not causing oedema, is decreased arterial blood flow."},
/*832*/ {"q":"Mono spot test is diagnostic for which disease?","o":["Typhoid","HIV","Infectious mononucleosis","Tuberculosis"],"a":2,"e":"The Monospot (heterophile antibody) test is diagnostic for infectious mononucleosis caused by Epstein-Barr virus.<br><br>It is not used for typhoid or HIV; Monospot diagnoses infectious mononucleosis."},
/*833*/ {"q":"Aspiration of foreign body in supine position, the object will be lodged in which lung lobe?","o":["Posterior segment of right upper lobe","Superior segment of right lower lobe","Posterior segment of right lower lobe","Apical segment of right upper lobe"],"a":1,"e":"In the supine patient an aspirated foreign body usually lodges in the superior segment of the right lower lobe, the most dependent segment in that posture.<br><br>The posterior upper-lobe segment is dependent when sitting; supine it is the right lower lobe superior segment."},
/*834*/ {"q":"Voluntary inhibition of micturition reflex:","o":["Pudendal nerve","Pelvic splanchnic","Sympathetic chain","Sacral plexus"],"a":0,"e":"Voluntary continence is maintained by somatic control of the external urethral sphincter through the pudendal nerve.<br><br>The pelvic splanchnics drive voiding; voluntary inhibition is via the pudendal nerve."},
/*835*/ {"q":"Newborn baby intubated, breath sounds absent on right side. Cause of endobronchial intubation, the endotracheal tube most likely lodged in:","o":["Right main bronchus","Left main bronchus","Trachea","Oesophagus"],"a":0,"e":"The right main bronchus is wider and more vertical, so an over-inserted endotracheal tube preferentially enters it, with absent left-sided breath sounds.<br><br>The left main bronchus is more angled; endobronchial intubation usually goes right."},
/*836*/ {"q":"In a 60 yr old female with breast cancer and osteoporosis HX of chest, cancer and osteoporosis HX of chest. Which drug should be given?","o":["Raloxifene","Bisphosphonates","Vitamin D","Calcium"],"a":0,"e":"Raloxifene, a selective oestrogen receptor modulator, treats osteoporosis while reducing breast cancer risk, ideal in a woman with both concerns.<br><br>Bisphosphonates treat bone only; the dual-benefit choice is raloxifene."},
/*837*/ {"q":"Microscopic feature of malignancy is:","o":["Dysplasia","Dysmoplasia","Dysplasia and pleomorphism","Increased N/C ratio with pleomorphism"],"a":3,"e":"Microscopic hallmarks of malignancy include nuclear pleomorphism with an increased nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratio, hyperchromasia and abnormal mitoses.<br><br>The most complete malignant descriptor here is high N/C ratio with pleomorphism."},
/*838*/ {"q":"Difference between right and left kidney?","o":["Size","Weight","Color","Level (left kidney higher than right)"],"a":3,"e":"The left kidney lies slightly higher than the right because the right kidney is displaced inferiorly by the liver.<br><br>Size, weight and colour are similar; the key difference is the level (left higher)."},
/*839*/ {"q":"Aspiration of foreign body in supine position, the object will be lodged in which lobe?","o":["Posterior segment of right upper lobe","Superior segment of right lower lobe","Apical segment of right upper lobe","Right middle lobe"],"a":1,"e":"In the supine position an inhaled foreign body most often lodges in the superior segment of the right lower lobe, the dependent segment in that posture.<br><br>The posterior upper-lobe segment is dependent when upright; supine it is the right lower lobe superior segment."},
/*840*/ {"q":"The diagnosis of amyloidosis is best confirmed by:","o":["Bence jones proteinuria","Clinical observation","Congo red stain of biopsy","Serum electrophoresis"],"a":2,"e":"Amyloidosis is definitively confirmed by Congo red staining of a tissue biopsy, showing apple-green birefringence under polarised light.<br><br>Bence-Jones protein is suggestive; the confirmatory test is Congo red staining."},
/*841*/ {"q":"HLA-DR4 is associated with:","o":["Rheumatoid arthritis","SLE","Scleroderma","Reactive arthritis"],"a":0,"e":"HLA-DR4 is strongly associated with rheumatoid arthritis.<br><br>SLE and scleroderma have different HLA associations; HLA-DR4 links to rheumatoid arthritis."},
/*842*/ {"q":"Structurally which lobe of prostate is the largest?","o":["Median","Lateral","Anterior","Posterior"],"a":1,"e":"The lateral lobes constitute the largest part of the prostate by volume and are commonly enlarged in benign prostatic hyperplasia.<br><br>The median lobe is smaller; structurally the lateral lobes are largest."},
/*843*/ {"q":"Through which structure does an inguinal hernia come out?","o":["Internal oblique muscle","Hesselbach triangle (direct) / deep ring (indirect)","Femoral ring","External oblique only"],"a":1,"e":"An indirect inguinal hernia passes through the deep inguinal ring lateral to the inferior epigastric vessels, while a direct hernia comes through Hesselbach triangle medially.<br><br>The femoral ring relates to femoral hernia; inguinal hernias use the deep ring/Hesselbach triangle."},
/*844*/ {"q":"A patient was diagnosed as a case of incisional hernia. The structure in this lump is most likely to push from within out:","o":["Internal oblique muscle","Transversalis fascia","Abdominal hernia (bowel/omentum through abdominal wall defect)","External oblique muscle"],"a":2,"e":"An incisional hernia protrudes abdominal contents (bowel or omentum) through a defect in a previous surgical wound from within outward.<br><br>The named muscle layers are not the protruding content; the lump is the herniating abdominal viscera."},
/*845*/ {"q":"In liver cell injury, enzyme decreased is:","o":["AST","Pseudocholinesterase","ALT","LDH"],"a":1,"e":"Pseudocholinesterase is synthesised by hepatocytes, so its plasma level falls with significant hepatocellular dysfunction, unlike AST/ALT which rise with injury.<br><br>Transaminases increase with damage; the enzyme that decreases is pseudocholinesterase."},
/*846*/ {"q":"Assessment of muscle injury by:","o":["Myoglobin","CKMB","CKBB","CKMM"],"a":3,"e":"CK-MM is the creatine kinase isoenzyme predominant in skeletal muscle, so it is used to assess skeletal muscle injury.<br><br>CK-MB indicates cardiac injury; skeletal muscle damage is assessed by CK-MM."},
/*847*/ {"q":"Type of necrosis seen in liver:","o":["Caseous","Coagulative","Liquefactive","Gas"],"a":1,"e":"Ischaemic hepatocyte death produces coagulative necrosis, with preservation of tissue architecture as eosinophilic ghost cells.<br><br>Liquefactive necrosis typifies brain; the liver shows coagulative necrosis."},
/*848*/ {"q":"Appendices epiploic are present in:","o":["Duodenum","Jejunum","Rectum","Colon"],"a":3,"e":"Appendices epiploicae, small fat-filled peritoneal tags, are a distinguishing feature of the colon (large intestine).<br><br>The small bowel lacks them; appendices epiploicae are found on the colon."},
/*849*/ {"q":"Labia majora lymphatic drainage:","o":["Internal iliac","Para-aortic","External iliac","Superficial inguinal lymph nodes"],"a":3,"e":"The labia majora and lower vagina drain to the superficial inguinal lymph nodes.<br><br>Internal pelvic nodes drain deeper structures; the labia majora drain to superficial inguinal nodes."},
/*850*/ {"q":"Inversion of foot by which muscle?","o":["Peroneus longus","Tibialis posterior","Peroneus brevis","Extensor digitorum longus"],"a":1,"e":"Inversion of the foot is performed mainly by tibialis posterior (with tibialis anterior).<br><br>The peronei produce eversion; foot inversion is chiefly tibialis posterior."},

/*851*/ {"q":"Hypercalcemia, oblique palpebral fissure:","o":["AIDS","SCID","Down syndrome","CMV"],"a":2,"e":"Upward-slanting (oblique) palpebral fissures are a characteristic facial feature of Down syndrome, which may also feature various medical associations.<br><br>The immune/infective distractors do not give this facies; the keyed answer is Down syndrome."},
/*852*/ {"q":"A lady having immune problems. Now developed lymphoma in lymph node in neck. What happened?","o":["AIDS","SCID","CMV","EBV-driven lymphoma in immunosuppression"],"a":3,"e":"Immunosuppressed patients are prone to EBV-driven lymphoproliferative disease and lymphoma; reactivation of EBV underlies many such nodal lymphomas.<br><br>Per source key the keyed mechanism is EBV-related lymphoma in the setting of immune compromise."},
/*853*/ {"q":"5-nucleotidase is a marker for:","o":["Bone disease","Hepatobiliary (cholestatic) disease","Muscle injury","Renal disease"],"a":1,"e":"5'-nucleotidase rises in cholestatic hepatobiliary disease and helps confirm that a raised alkaline phosphatase is of hepatic rather than bony origin.<br><br>It is not a bone or muscle marker; 5-nucleotidase indicates hepatobiliary disease."},
/*854*/ {"q":"Assessment of muscle injury by:","o":["AST","Myoglobin","CK-MM","LDH"],"a":2,"e":"CK-MM is the skeletal-muscle predominant creatine kinase isoenzyme and the specific marker for skeletal muscle injury.<br><br>Myoglobin is sensitive but non-specific; the keyed muscle-injury marker is CK-MM."},
/*855*/ {"q":"Nerve supply of triceps muscle is:","o":["Radial nerve","Median nerve","Ulnar nerve","Musculocutaneous nerve"],"a":0,"e":"All heads of triceps brachii are innervated by the radial nerve (C7, C8).<br><br>The musculocutaneous supplies the anterior compartment; triceps is radial nerve supplied."},
/*856*/ {"q":"Inversion of foot by which muscle?","o":["Peroneus longus","Tibialis posterior","Peroneus brevis","Extensor hallucis longus"],"a":1,"e":"Tibialis posterior is the principal inverter of the foot, assisted by tibialis anterior.<br><br>The peronei evert; foot inversion is mainly tibialis posterior."},
/*857*/ {"q":"Fracture neck of fibula injures which nerve?","o":["Tibial nerve","Common peroneal nerve","Sural nerve","Saphenous nerve"],"a":1,"e":"The common peroneal nerve winds around the fibular neck superficially and is the nerve injured in fibular neck fractures, causing foot drop.<br><br>The tibial nerve lies deep in the calf; the fibular-neck nerve is the common peroneal."},
/*858*/ {"q":"In a pregnant lady to diagnose early open neural tube defect, which one of the following is used?","o":["Maternal serum alpha-fetoprotein","Beta hCG","Estriol","Inhibin A"],"a":0,"e":"Elevated maternal serum alpha-fetoprotein is the screening marker for open neural tube defects such as spina bifida and anencephaly.<br><br>The other markers screen for aneuploidy; open NTDs raise AFP."},
/*859*/ {"q":"Measles in pregnant lady, doctor worried about:","o":["Chorionic villus sampling","Amniocentesis","Congenital anomalies / fetal infection","Ultrasound"],"a":2,"e":"Maternal viral infection (rubella/measles) in pregnancy raises concern for congenital anomalies and fetal infection, especially in the first trimester.<br><br>The sampling techniques are investigations, not the worry; the concern is congenital anomalies."},
/*860*/ {"q":"Old man with C/O anemia and worried about cataract. Scan is in:","o":["Hypogonadism, lesion on CT","Hyperaldosteronism","Hyperkalemia","Metabolic acidosis"],"a":0,"e":"Per the source key, the composite scenario in this item is matched to the hypogonadism with CT lesion option among the choices.<br><br>The metabolic distractors do not match the keyed answer; the marked option is hypogonadism with lesion on CT."},
/*861*/ {"q":"Corona radiata in secondary oocyte which layer forms it?","o":["Granulosa cells","Theca interna","Theca externa","Zona pellucida"],"a":0,"e":"The corona radiata surrounding the secondary oocyte is formed by granulosa (cumulus) cells that remain attached after ovulation.<br><br>The theca layers lie outside the follicle; the corona radiata is granulosa-cell derived."},
/*862*/ {"q":"Arcuate nucleus of hypothalamus, lesion on CT:","o":["Anencephaly","Hypogonadism","Hyperprolactinaemia","Diabetes insipidus"],"a":1,"e":"The hypothalamic arcuate nucleus secretes GnRH; its lesion causes hypogonadotropic hypogonadism.<br><br>Diabetes insipidus relates to the supraoptic/paraventricular nuclei; arcuate damage causes hypogonadism."},
/*863*/ {"q":"A patient of acute tonsillitis. Mediators of acute inflammation:","o":["TNF and IL-1","Histamine","Bradykinin","Nitric oxide"],"a":0,"e":"TNF and IL-1 are the principal cytokine mediators of acute inflammation, driving fever, leucocyte recruitment and the acute-phase response.<br><br>Histamine acts in the immediate vascular phase; the key inflammatory cytokines are TNF and IL-1."},
/*864*/ {"q":"BPH is due to enlargement of which lobe?","o":["Median lobe","Lateral lobe","Anterior lobe","Posterior lobe"],"a":0,"e":"Benign prostatic hyperplasia characteristically enlarges the median (and lateral) lobes, the periurethral transition zone, causing bladder outflow obstruction.<br><br>The posterior lobe is the carcinoma site; BPH classically involves the median lobe."},
/*865*/ {"q":"Hyperaldosteronism associated with all except:","o":["Hypertension","Hypokalemia","Hypernatremia","Hyperkalemia"],"a":3,"e":"Primary hyperaldosteronism causes hypertension, hypokalaemia and mild hypernatraemia; hyperkalaemia is the opposite of its effect.<br><br>Aldosterone promotes potassium excretion; the exception not seen is hyperkalaemia."},
/*866*/ {"q":"Old man with C/O anemia and worried about:","o":["TOF","Tricuspid atresia","Metastatic carcinoma / occult malignancy","Mitral stenosis"],"a":2,"e":"An elderly man with unexplained anaemia should raise concern for occult malignancy (often gastrointestinal) causing chronic blood loss.<br><br>The cardiac distractors do not explain anaemia; the worry is occult malignancy."},
/*867*/ {"q":"A player was hit by a ball on the elbow with fracture of medial epicondyle and damage to medial epicondyle and dorsal surface. This would result in sensory loss over?","o":["Medial 1/3 over dorsal surface","Lateral 2/3 over dorsal surface","Lateral 1/3 over palmar surface","Medial 1/3 over medial surface"],"a":0,"e":"Ulnar nerve injury at the medial epicondyle causes sensory loss over the medial one and a half digits and the medial dorsal/palmar hand.<br><br>The lateral hand is median/radial; ulnar loss is the medial one-third dorsal surface."},
/*868*/ {"q":"Blood supply of head of femur in adults:","o":["Obturator artery","Medial circumflex femoral artery","Lateral circumflex femoral artery","Nutrient artery"],"a":1,"e":"In adults the femoral head is supplied predominantly by the medial circumflex femoral artery via the retinacular vessels.<br><br>The obturator artery's ligamentum teres branch is minor in adults; the main supply is the medial circumflex femoral."},
/*869*/ {"q":"In avascular necrosis of femur head which artery is involved?","o":["Obturator artery","Medial circumflex femoral artery","Retinacular artery","Nutrient artery"],"a":1,"e":"Avascular necrosis of the femoral head follows disruption of the medial circumflex femoral artery (and its retinacular branches) after a neck fracture.<br><br>The obturator contribution is minimal in adults; the key vessel is the medial circumflex femoral artery."},
/*870*/ {"q":"A patient having ST elevation in lead 2 and complete heart block vessel involved?","o":["RCA (right coronary artery)","LAD","LCX","Diagonal"],"a":0,"e":"Inferior myocardial infarction (ST elevation in lead II, III, aVF) with complete heart block indicates right coronary artery occlusion, which supplies the AV node in most people.<br><br>LAD causes anterior MI; the inferior MI with heart block is RCA."},
/*871*/ {"q":"Most common valve involved in endocarditis in IV drug users:","o":["Mitral","Aortic","Tricuspid","Pulmonary"],"a":2,"e":"Intravenous drug users develop right-sided infective endocarditis most commonly on the tricuspid valve, seeded by venous organisms.<br><br>Left-sided valves predominate otherwise; in IV drug users it is the tricuspid valve."},
/*872*/ {"q":"Regarding the pubic symphysis, what type of joint is it?","o":["Primary cartilaginous","Secondary cartilaginous","Fibrous","Synovial"],"a":1,"e":"The pubic symphysis is a secondary cartilaginous joint (symphysis) with a fibrocartilaginous disc, permitting slight movement, important in childbirth.<br><br>Primary cartilaginous joints are synchondroses; the pubic symphysis is secondary cartilaginous."},
/*873*/ {"q":"Adrenal cortex is derived from?","o":["Mesoderm","Endoderm","Ectoderm","Neural crest"],"a":0,"e":"The adrenal cortex develops from coelomic (intermediate/mesodermal) mesothelium, whereas the medulla derives from neural crest.<br><br>The cortex is mesodermal; only the medulla is neural crest derived."},
/*874*/ {"q":"All of these supply the first 2cm of duodenum except:","o":["Right gastric artery","Supraduodenal artery","Gastroduodenal artery","Inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery"],"a":3,"e":"The first 2 cm of duodenum (foregut) is supplied by the right gastric, supraduodenal and superior pancreaticoduodenal/gastroduodenal vessels; the inferior pancreaticoduodenal (midgut) does not.<br><br>That midgut vessel begins beyond the ampulla; the exception is the inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery."},
/*875*/ {"q":"Which structure is not present in lesser omentum?","o":["Portal vein","Hepatic artery","Bile duct","Splenic artery"],"a":3,"e":"The free edge of the lesser omentum (hepatoduodenal ligament) contains the portal vein, hepatic artery and bile duct; the splenic artery runs in the lienorenal ligament, not here.<br><br>The structure not present is the splenic artery."},
/*876*/ {"q":"The most common organism for UTI:","o":["E. Coli","Pseudomonas","S-aureus","Klebsiella species"],"a":0,"e":"Escherichia coli is the commonest organism causing community-acquired urinary tract infection, accounting for the large majority of cases.<br><br>Klebsiella and Pseudomonas are less frequent; the leading uropathogen is E. coli."},
/*877*/ {"q":"In histology slide serous acini with stratified epithelium in ducts:","o":["Parotid glands","Lacrimal glands","Sublingual glands","Sweat glands"],"a":0,"e":"The parotid gland is a purely serous gland with serous acini and stratified ductal epithelium in its larger ducts.<br><br>The sublingual gland is mucous-predominant; the purely serous gland is the parotid."},
/*878*/ {"q":"In which of the following area the vomiting center is located?","o":["Thalamus","Hypothalamus","Medulla oblongata","Pons"],"a":2,"e":"The vomiting centre is located in the medulla oblongata, coordinating the emetic reflex with input from the chemoreceptor trigger zone.<br><br>The thalamus and pons are not the emetic centre; vomiting is controlled in the medulla."},
/*879*/ {"q":"Most common valve involved in endocarditis in IV drug users:","o":["Mitral","Tricuspid","Aortic","Pulmonary"],"a":1,"e":"Right-sided infective endocarditis on the tricuspid valve is the commonest in intravenous drug users, from venous-borne organisms.<br><br>Left-sided valves predominate in others; in IV drug users it is the tricuspid valve."},
/*880*/ {"q":"Clostridium botulinum specific symptoms in food poisoning:","o":["Flaccid paralysis","Bloody diarrhea","Watery diarrhea","Fever with rash"],"a":0,"e":"Botulinum toxin blocks acetylcholine release at the neuromuscular junction, producing descending flaccid paralysis and respiratory compromise.<br><br>Diarrhoeal pictures fit other organisms; botulism causes flaccid paralysis."},
/*881*/ {"q":"All of these supply the first 2cm of duodenum except:","o":["Right gastric artery","Supraduodenal artery","Gastroduodenal artery","Inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery"],"a":3,"e":"The proximal 2 cm of duodenum is foregut, supplied by the right gastric, supraduodenal and gastroduodenal/superior pancreaticoduodenal vessels; the inferior pancreaticoduodenal supplies the midgut portion.<br><br>The exception not supplying this segment is the inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery."},
/*882*/ {"q":"The most common organism for hospital acquired UTI:","o":["E. Coli","Pseudomonas","S-aureus","Klebsiella species"],"a":1,"e":"Hospital-acquired (catheter-associated) urinary tract infections frequently involve Pseudomonas aeruginosa and other resistant organisms; per source key the marked answer is Pseudomonas.<br><br>E. coli dominates community UTI; the keyed nosocomial organism is Pseudomonas."},
/*883*/ {"q":"In histology slide serous acini with stratified epithelium in ducts:","o":["Parotid glands","Sublingual glands","Submandibular glands","Sweat glands"],"a":0,"e":"The parotid gland is entirely serous, with serous acini and stratified epithelium lining its larger excretory ducts.<br><br>The submandibular gland is mixed; the purely serous gland is the parotid."},
/*884*/ {"q":"Posterior fibers of temporalis muscle contraction causes:","o":["Protrusion of mandible","Retraction of mandible","Elevation of mandible","Depression of mandible"],"a":1,"e":"The posterior horizontal fibres of temporalis retract the mandible, while its anterior fibres elevate it.<br><br>Lateral pterygoid protrudes the jaw; the posterior temporalis fibres retract the mandible."},
/*885*/ {"q":"Blood leaving placenta have oxygen saturation of:","o":["100%","80%","26%","30%"],"a":1,"e":"Blood leaving the placenta in the umbilical vein has the highest fetal oxygen saturation, approximately 80 percent.<br><br>The umbilical arteries carry far less; the umbilical vein saturation is about 80 percent."},
/*886*/ {"q":"An epileptic lady who currently on phenytoin has become pregnant. She is concerned about her medication in Pregnancy. Which of the following is correct?","o":["Add lithium","Switch phenytoin","Continue phenytoin with folic acid supplementation","Add valproic acid"],"a":2,"e":"Anticonvulsant therapy in pregnancy is generally continued at the lowest effective dose with high-dose folic acid supplementation to reduce neural tube defect risk, since uncontrolled seizures are more harmful.<br><br>Valproate is more teratogenic; the appropriate advice is to continue phenytoin with folate."},
/*887*/ {"q":"A patient of TB is on Att for 2 months. TB is on Att for 2 antibodies:","o":["Circulating in plasma","Bound to nucleus","Bound to cell membrane","Cell bound"],"a":0,"e":"Humoral antibodies produced against the organism circulate freely in the plasma, mediating systemic humoral immunity.<br><br>They are not nucleus-bound; antibodies circulate in plasma."},
/*888*/ {"q":"Basophilia of the cell is due to:","o":["SER","Ribosomes (rough ER / RNA)","Mitochondria","Golgi apparatus"],"a":1,"e":"Cytoplasmic basophilia is due to abundant ribosomal RNA on the rough endoplasmic reticulum, which binds basic dyes.<br><br>Smooth ER and mitochondria do not stain basophilic; basophilia reflects ribosomes/RNA."},
/*889*/ {"q":"Man in marathon in July collapses cause?","o":["Dehydration","Heat stroke","Heat exhaustion","Hyponatremia"],"a":1,"e":"Collapse during strenuous exertion in hot weather with hyperthermia and altered mentation indicates heat stroke, a medical emergency from thermoregulatory failure.<br><br>Heat exhaustion lacks the central nervous system change; the keyed cause is heat stroke."},
/*890*/ {"q":"Presence of pancreatic tissue in gastric mucosa is termed as:","o":["Metaplasia","Heteroplasia","Choristoma","Hamartoma"],"a":2,"e":"Normal pancreatic tissue at an abnormal site (ectopic, e.g. in gastric mucosa) is a choristoma, a mass of normal tissue in a foreign location.<br><br>A hamartoma is disorganised tissue native to the site; ectopic normal tissue is a choristoma."},
/*891*/ {"q":"Most common cause of hereditary mental retardation:","o":["Down syndrome","Fragile X syndrome","Turner syndrome","Klinefelter syndrome"],"a":1,"e":"Fragile X syndrome is the commonest inherited (heritable) cause of intellectual disability, an X-linked trinucleotide-repeat disorder.<br><br>Down syndrome is the commonest chromosomal cause but is usually sporadic; the heritable cause is Fragile X."},
/*892*/ {"q":"Which part of the male genital tract is partially motile sperm?","o":["Seminiferous tubule","Epididymis","Rete testis","Vas deferens"],"a":1,"e":"Spermatozoa acquire progressive motility and full maturation during transit and storage in the epididymis.<br><br>Sperm leaving the seminiferous tubules are immotile; motility develops in the epididymis."},
/*893*/ {"q":"Karyotype of klinefelter syndrome:","o":["47XXY","47XYY","45XO","46XX"],"a":0,"e":"Klinefelter syndrome has a 47,XXY karyotype, producing tall stature, small firm testes, gynaecomastia and infertility.<br><br>45,XO is Turner; the Klinefelter karyotype is 47,XXY."},
/*894*/ {"q":"During transport of oxygen and CO2, amount of CO2 dissolved in plasma at 45mmHg is:","o":["0.3%","3%","7%","23%"],"a":2,"e":"About 7 percent of carbon dioxide is transported dissolved in plasma, with the majority as bicarbonate and a portion as carbamino compounds.<br><br>The 23 percent figure is carbamino-bound; the dissolved fraction is about 7 percent."},
/*895*/ {"q":"In a 15 year old boy medullary carcinoma of thyroid is considered familial because of:","o":["Age","Increase secretion of hormone","Metastasis","RET proto-oncogene mutation (MEN 2)"],"a":3,"e":"Medullary thyroid carcinoma in a young patient suggests a familial RET proto-oncogene mutation as part of MEN 2 syndrome.<br><br>Young age is a clue, but the underlying reason is the inherited RET mutation."},
/*896*/ {"q":"Nonbacterial endocarditis is associated with:","o":["Congenital heart disease","Ischemic heart disease","Rheumatic endocarditis","Marantic (malignancy/SLE) endocarditis"],"a":3,"e":"Non-bacterial thrombotic (marantic) endocarditis is associated with hypercoagulable states such as advanced malignancy, and Libman-Sacks endocarditis with SLE.<br><br>Rheumatic and infective forms are bacterial/immune; non-bacterial endocarditis links to malignancy/SLE."},
/*897*/ {"q":"Terminal neoplastic disease, epithelial cells with neoplasia is associated with:","o":["Cytokeratin","Vimentin","Desmin","Myoglobin"],"a":0,"e":"Cytokeratin is the intermediate filament marker of epithelial cells, used immunohistochemically to identify carcinomas (epithelial neoplasia).<br><br>Vimentin marks mesenchymal cells; epithelial neoplasia expresses cytokeratin."},
/*898*/ {"q":"A baby dies after birth with edema jaundice and anemia on following changes: Bile pigments in basal ganglia. The condition is:","o":["Heart problem","Kernicterus","Liver problem","GIT problem"],"a":1,"e":"Bilirubin deposition in the basal ganglia of a jaundiced neonate (here from haemolytic disease) causes kernicterus, a bilirubin encephalopathy.<br><br>The non-CNS distractors are irrelevant; basal ganglia bile staining is kernicterus."},
/*899*/ {"q":"An Anemic lady with reticulocyte shows small spherocytes. Test for diagnosis:","o":["Direct Coombs test","Indirect Coombs test","Osmotic fragility test","Peripheral smear"],"a":0,"e":"Spherocytes with reticulocytosis raise autoimmune haemolytic anaemia; the direct Coombs (antiglobulin) test confirms antibody-coated red cells.<br><br>Osmotic fragility tests hereditary spherocytosis; the immune cause is confirmed by the direct Coombs test."},
/*900*/ {"q":"Liquefactive necrosis is seen in:","o":["Heart","Kidney","Brain infarct","Spleen"],"a":2,"e":"Liquefactive necrosis is characteristic of cerebral (brain) infarction, where enzymatic digestion liquefies the dead tissue forming a cystic cavity.<br><br>Solid organs show coagulative necrosis; liquefactive necrosis occurs in brain infarcts."},

/*901*/ {"q":"Coagulative necrosis is most characteristically seen in:","o":["Brain","Heart (myocardial infarct)","Pancreas","Tubercular lymph node"],"a":1,"e":"Coagulative necrosis is the typical pattern of ischaemic infarction in solid organs, classically the myocardium after infarction, preserving tissue outline as ghost cells.<br><br>The brain shows liquefactive necrosis; the prototype of coagulative necrosis is the heart."},
/*902*/ {"q":"Most common cause of acute pancreatitis:","o":["Gallstones","Alcohol","Hyperlipidemia","Trauma"],"a":0,"e":"Gallstones are the commonest cause of acute pancreatitis worldwide, by obstructing the ampulla and causing pancreatic duct hypertension.<br><br>Alcohol is the next commonest; the leading cause overall is gallstones."},
/*903*/ {"q":"Curling ulcer is associated with:","o":["Burns","Head injury","NSAIDs","H. pylori"],"a":0,"e":"A Curling ulcer is an acute gastroduodenal stress ulcer occurring after severe burns, from splanchnic hypoperfusion.<br><br>A Cushing ulcer follows head injury; the burn-associated ulcer is the Curling ulcer."},
/*904*/ {"q":"Cushing ulcer is associated with:","o":["Burns","Raised intracranial pressure / head injury","Alcohol","Aspirin"],"a":1,"e":"A Cushing ulcer is a stress ulcer associated with raised intracranial pressure or head injury, mediated by vagal acid hypersecretion.<br><br>The burn-related stress ulcer is the Curling ulcer; Cushing relates to CNS injury."},
/*905*/ {"q":"Fatty change in liver is reversible and occurs due to:","o":["Increased triglyceride accumulation in hepatocytes","Necrosis","Apoptosis","Fibrosis"],"a":0,"e":"Hepatic steatosis (fatty change) is a reversible accumulation of triglycerides within hepatocytes from impaired lipid metabolism or export.<br><br>Necrosis and fibrosis are irreversible; fatty change is reversible triglyceride accumulation."},
/*906*/ {"q":"Hyaline arteriolosclerosis is characteristically seen in:","o":["Benign hypertension and diabetes","Acute inflammation","Vasculitis","Amyloidosis"],"a":0,"e":"Hyaline arteriolosclerosis, with pink homogeneous arteriolar wall thickening, is characteristic of benign hypertension and diabetes mellitus.<br><br>Vasculitis shows inflammatory change; hyaline arteriolosclerosis links to hypertension and diabetes."},
/*907*/ {"q":"Most common site of carcinoid tumor:","o":["Appendix","Stomach","Colon","Rectum"],"a":0,"e":"The appendix is the commonest site of gastrointestinal carcinoid (neuroendocrine) tumours, usually found incidentally and generally benign.<br><br>The other sites are less frequent; the commonest carcinoid site is the appendix."},
/*908*/ {"q":"Psammoma bodies are seen in all except:","o":["Papillary thyroid carcinoma","Meningioma","Serous ovarian cystadenocarcinoma","Renal cell carcinoma"],"a":3,"e":"Psammoma bodies (laminated calcified concretions) occur in papillary thyroid carcinoma, meningioma and serous ovarian tumours, but not in renal cell carcinoma.<br><br>The exception lacking psammoma bodies is renal cell carcinoma."},
/*909*/ {"q":"Reed-Sternberg cells are diagnostic of:","o":["Hodgkin lymphoma","Non-Hodgkin lymphoma","Burkitt lymphoma","CLL"],"a":0,"e":"Binucleate \"owl-eye\" Reed-Sternberg cells are the diagnostic hallmark of Hodgkin lymphoma.<br><br>Non-Hodgkin lymphomas lack them; RS cells define Hodgkin lymphoma."},
/*910*/ {"q":"Auer rods are characteristic of:","o":["Acute myeloid leukemia","Acute lymphoblastic leukemia","CLL","CML"],"a":0,"e":"Auer rods, needle-shaped azurophilic cytoplasmic inclusions, are characteristic of acute myeloid leukaemia, particularly the promyelocytic subtype.<br><br>Lymphoid leukaemias lack them; Auer rods indicate AML."},
/*911*/ {"q":"Philadelphia chromosome is t(9;22) seen in:","o":["Chronic myeloid leukemia","Acute lymphoblastic leukemia only","Hodgkin lymphoma","Multiple myeloma"],"a":0,"e":"The Philadelphia chromosome, t(9;22) producing BCR-ABL, is the hallmark of chronic myeloid leukaemia (and a subset of ALL).<br><br>It is not seen in Hodgkin or myeloma; the classic CML marker is the Philadelphia chromosome."},
/*912*/ {"q":"Bence Jones proteins are associated with:","o":["Multiple myeloma","Hodgkin lymphoma","CLL","Hairy cell leukemia"],"a":0,"e":"Bence Jones proteins (free monoclonal light chains in urine) are characteristic of multiple myeloma.<br><br>The lymphoid disorders listed do not typically produce them; Bence Jones protein indicates myeloma."},
/*913*/ {"q":"Most common primary malignant tumor of bone:","o":["Osteosarcoma","Multiple myeloma","Ewing sarcoma","Chondrosarcoma"],"a":1,"e":"Multiple myeloma is the commonest primary malignant tumour of bone overall; osteosarcoma is the commonest primary bone-forming sarcoma.<br><br>Per source key the marked commonest primary malignant bone tumour is multiple myeloma."},
/*914*/ {"q":"Most common benign tumor of liver:","o":["Hemangioma","Hepatic adenoma","Focal nodular hyperplasia","Bile duct adenoma"],"a":0,"e":"Cavernous haemangioma is the commonest benign tumour of the liver, often an incidental imaging finding.<br><br>Hepatic adenoma is less common; the commonest benign hepatic tumour is haemangioma."},
/*915*/ {"q":"Krukenberg tumor is metastasis to ovary from:","o":["Stomach","Lung","Breast","Kidney"],"a":0,"e":"A Krukenberg tumour is a metastatic ovarian deposit, classically from a gastric (signet-ring) carcinoma.<br><br>Other primaries are less typical; the classic Krukenberg primary is the stomach."},
/*916*/ {"q":"Most common cause of right heart failure is:","o":["Left heart failure","COPD","Pulmonary embolism","Tricuspid disease"],"a":0,"e":"The commonest cause of right heart failure is left heart failure, which raises pulmonary venous pressure and burdens the right ventricle.<br><br>Cor pulmonale from lung disease is next; the leading cause is left heart failure."},
/*917*/ {"q":"Most common cause of cor pulmonale:","o":["COPD","Asthma","Pulmonary fibrosis","Bronchiectasis"],"a":0,"e":"Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease is the commonest cause of cor pulmonale (right heart strain from pulmonary disease).<br><br>The other lung diseases are less frequent; the leading cause of cor pulmonale is COPD."},
/*918*/ {"q":"Dressler syndrome is:","o":["Post-myocardial infarction pericarditis","Constrictive pericarditis","Cardiac tamponade","Restrictive cardiomyopathy"],"a":0,"e":"Dressler syndrome is an autoimmune post-myocardial infarction pericarditis occurring weeks after the infarct.<br><br>It is not tamponade or restriction primarily; Dressler is post-MI pericarditis."},
/*919*/ {"q":"Most common congenital heart disease:","o":["Ventricular septal defect","Atrial septal defect","Patent ductus arteriosus","Tetralogy of Fallot"],"a":0,"e":"Ventricular septal defect is the commonest congenital heart defect overall.<br><br>ASD and PDA are less frequent; the most common congenital cardiac anomaly is VSD."},
/*920*/ {"q":"Most common cyanotic congenital heart disease:","o":["Tetralogy of Fallot","Transposition of great arteries","Tricuspid atresia","Truncus arteriosus"],"a":0,"e":"Tetralogy of Fallot is the commonest cyanotic congenital heart disease beyond infancy.<br><br>Transposition presents earliest in the neonate; the commonest cyanotic lesion overall is TOF."},
/*921*/ {"q":"Eisenmenger syndrome is:","o":["Reversal of left-to-right shunt to right-to-left","Pure left-to-right shunt","Coarctation","Valvular stenosis"],"a":0,"e":"Eisenmenger syndrome is the reversal of a left-to-right cardiac shunt to right-to-left, following pulmonary hypertension from chronic overcirculation.<br><br>It is not a simple shunt; Eisenmenger is shunt reversal with cyanosis."},
/*922*/ {"q":"Most common renal stone composition:","o":["Calcium oxalate","Struvite","Uric acid","Cystine"],"a":0,"e":"Calcium oxalate stones are the commonest type of renal calculi.<br><br>Struvite, uric acid and cystine stones are less frequent; the commonest are calcium oxalate."},
/*923*/ {"q":"Staghorn calculi are typically composed of:","o":["Struvite (magnesium ammonium phosphate)","Calcium oxalate","Uric acid","Cystine"],"a":0,"e":"Staghorn calculi filling the renal pelvis are typically struvite (magnesium ammonium phosphate) stones associated with urease-producing infection.<br><br>Calcium oxalate forms smaller stones; staghorn calculi are usually struvite."},
/*924*/ {"q":"Most common cause of nephrotic syndrome in children:","o":["Minimal change disease","Membranous nephropathy","FSGS","Membranoproliferative GN"],"a":0,"e":"Minimal change disease is the commonest cause of nephrotic syndrome in children, with effacement of podocyte foot processes on electron microscopy.<br><br>Membranous nephropathy predominates in adults; in children it is minimal change disease."},
/*925*/ {"q":"Most common cause of nephrotic syndrome in adults:","o":["Membranous nephropathy","Minimal change disease","IgA nephropathy","Diabetic nephropathy"],"a":0,"e":"Membranous nephropathy is the commonest primary cause of nephrotic syndrome in adults; diabetic nephropathy is the commonest secondary cause overall.<br><br>Per source key the marked primary cause is membranous nephropathy."},
/*926*/ {"q":"IgA nephropathy (Berger disease) typically presents with:","o":["Recurrent hematuria after URTI","Massive proteinuria","Hypertension only","Renal stones"],"a":0,"e":"IgA nephropathy classically presents with episodic gross haematuria coinciding with or soon after an upper respiratory tract infection.<br><br>The post-streptococcal latency is longer; IgA nephropathy haematuria is concurrent with the URTI."},
/*927*/ {"q":"Most common renal malignancy in adults:","o":["Renal cell carcinoma","Wilms tumor","Transitional cell carcinoma","Angiomyolipoma"],"a":0,"e":"Renal cell carcinoma is the commonest primary renal malignancy in adults, arising from proximal tubular epithelium.<br><br>Wilms tumour is the paediatric renal cancer; in adults it is renal cell carcinoma."},
/*928*/ {"q":"Wilms tumor is associated with mutation of:","o":["WT1 gene","RB gene","APC gene","BRCA gene"],"a":0,"e":"Wilms tumour (nephroblastoma) is associated with WT1 gene mutations on chromosome 11.<br><br>RB and APC relate to other tumours; the Wilms tumour gene is WT1."},
/*929*/ {"q":"Most common cause of community-acquired pneumonia:","o":["Streptococcus pneumoniae","Mycoplasma","Haemophilus","Legionella"],"a":0,"e":"Streptococcus pneumoniae is the commonest cause of community-acquired pneumonia.<br><br>Atypicals and Haemophilus are less frequent; the leading cause is pneumococcus."},
/*930*/ {"q":"Ghon complex is characteristic of:","o":["Primary tuberculosis","Sarcoidosis","Histoplasmosis","Silicosis"],"a":0,"e":"The Ghon complex (parenchymal focus plus regional lymph node) is the hallmark of primary pulmonary tuberculosis.<br><br>Sarcoid and silicosis have different patterns; the Ghon complex indicates primary TB."},
/*931*/ {"q":"Most common lung cancer in non-smokers:","o":["Adenocarcinoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Small cell carcinoma","Large cell carcinoma"],"a":0,"e":"Adenocarcinoma is the commonest lung cancer in non-smokers and overall, typically peripheral in location.<br><br>Squamous and small cell are strongly smoking-related; in non-smokers it is adenocarcinoma."},
/*932*/ {"q":"Small cell lung carcinoma is associated with:","o":["Paraneoplastic syndromes (SIADH, ACTH)","No paraneoplastic effects","Peripheral location","Best prognosis"],"a":0,"e":"Small cell lung carcinoma, a central neuroendocrine tumour, is strongly associated with paraneoplastic syndromes such as SIADH and ectopic ACTH.<br><br>It has a poor prognosis; the key association is paraneoplastic syndromes."},
/*933*/ {"q":"Mesothelioma is most strongly associated with:","o":["Asbestos exposure","Smoking","Silica","Radon"],"a":0,"e":"Malignant mesothelioma of the pleura is strongly associated with prior asbestos exposure, often after a long latency.<br><br>Smoking is not its main cause; mesothelioma links to asbestos."},
/*934*/ {"q":"Most common cause of esophageal varices:","o":["Portal hypertension from cirrhosis","Esophageal cancer","Achalasia","Reflux esophagitis"],"a":0,"e":"Oesophageal varices result from portal hypertension, most commonly due to hepatic cirrhosis, with portosystemic shunting at the lower oesophagus.<br><br>The other oesophageal conditions are unrelated; varices arise from cirrhotic portal hypertension."},
/*935*/ {"q":"Barrett esophagus is:","o":["Columnar metaplasia of lower esophagus","Squamous metaplasia","Adenocarcinoma","Achalasia"],"a":0,"e":"Barrett oesophagus is intestinal columnar metaplasia of the lower oesophageal squamous mucosa due to chronic acid reflux, predisposing to adenocarcinoma.<br><br>It is metaplasia, not yet carcinoma; Barrett is columnar metaplasia of the lower oesophagus."},
/*936*/ {"q":"Most common site of peptic ulcer:","o":["First part of duodenum","Stomach body","Pylorus","Lower esophagus"],"a":0,"e":"Duodenal peptic ulcers, most often in the first part (duodenal cap), are the commonest site of peptic ulceration.<br><br>Gastric ulcers are less frequent; the commonest peptic ulcer site is the first part of duodenum."},
/*937*/ {"q":"Most common cause of peptic ulcer disease:","o":["Helicobacter pylori","NSAIDs","Stress","Zollinger-Ellison"],"a":0,"e":"Helicobacter pylori infection is the commonest cause of peptic ulcer disease, with NSAIDs the second commonest.<br><br>Zollinger-Ellison is rare; the leading cause is H. pylori."},
/*938*/ {"q":"Virchow node is:","o":["Left supraclavicular lymph node (gastric cancer)","Right axillary node","Inguinal node","Para-aortic node"],"a":0,"e":"Virchow node is an enlarged left supraclavicular lymph node, classically signalling metastatic gastric (or other abdominal) carcinoma.<br><br>It is not axillary or inguinal; Virchow node is the left supraclavicular node."},
/*939*/ {"q":"Most common malignancy of the stomach:","o":["Adenocarcinoma","Lymphoma","GIST","Carcinoid"],"a":0,"e":"Gastric adenocarcinoma is by far the commonest malignancy of the stomach.<br><br>Lymphoma, GIST and carcinoid are less frequent; the commonest is adenocarcinoma."},
/*940*/ {"q":"Most common site of diverticulosis:","o":["Sigmoid colon","Cecum","Transverse colon","Rectum"],"a":0,"e":"Colonic diverticulosis is most common in the sigmoid colon, where intraluminal pressure is highest.<br><br>The other segments are less involved; the commonest site is the sigmoid colon."},
/*941*/ {"q":"Apple-core lesion on barium enema suggests:","o":["Colorectal carcinoma","Diverticulitis","Ulcerative colitis","Crohn disease"],"a":0,"e":"An annular \"apple-core\" stricture on barium enema is characteristic of a constricting colorectal carcinoma.<br><br>Inflammatory diseases give different patterns; the apple-core lesion indicates colorectal carcinoma."},
/*942*/ {"q":"Skip lesions and transmural inflammation are characteristic of:","o":["Crohn disease","Ulcerative colitis","Ischemic colitis","Pseudomembranous colitis"],"a":0,"e":"Crohn disease shows discontinuous skip lesions with transmural granulomatous inflammation anywhere in the gut.<br><br>Ulcerative colitis is continuous and mucosal; skip lesions with transmural inflammation indicate Crohn."},
/*943*/ {"q":"Continuous mucosal inflammation limited to colon, with crypt abscesses, is:","o":["Ulcerative colitis","Crohn disease","Tuberculous colitis","Amoebic colitis"],"a":0,"e":"Ulcerative colitis shows continuous mucosal inflammation from the rectum proximally, with crypt abscesses and no skip lesions.<br><br>Crohn is transmural and patchy; continuous mucosal colitis with crypt abscesses is ulcerative colitis."},
/*944*/ {"q":"Most common cause of acute appendicitis:","o":["Fecolith obstruction","Lymphoid hyperplasia","Tumor","Parasite"],"a":0,"e":"Luminal obstruction by a faecolith is the commonest cause of acute appendicitis in adults; lymphoid hyperplasia predominates in children.<br><br>Per source key the marked commonest cause is faecolith obstruction."},
/*945*/ {"q":"Most common primary liver malignancy:","o":["Hepatocellular carcinoma","Cholangiocarcinoma","Angiosarcoma","Hepatoblastoma"],"a":0,"e":"Hepatocellular carcinoma is the commonest primary malignant tumour of the liver, often on a background of cirrhosis.<br><br>Cholangiocarcinoma is less common; the commonest primary liver cancer is HCC."},
/*946*/ {"q":"Alpha-fetoprotein is a tumor marker for:","o":["Hepatocellular carcinoma and germ cell tumors","Colon cancer","Breast cancer","Prostate cancer"],"a":0,"e":"Alpha-fetoprotein is elevated in hepatocellular carcinoma and non-seminomatous germ cell tumours.<br><br>CEA and PSA relate to colon and prostate; AFP marks HCC and germ cell tumours."},
/*947*/ {"q":"Most common cause of acute cholecystitis:","o":["Gallstone obstructing cystic duct","Tumor","Parasite","Trauma"],"a":0,"e":"Acute cholecystitis is most commonly caused by a gallstone impacted in the cystic duct, leading to inflammation of the obstructed gallbladder.<br><br>Acalculous causes are rarer; the commonest cause is cystic duct stone obstruction."},
/*948*/ {"q":"Courvoisier law states a palpable non-tender gallbladder with jaundice suggests:","o":["Carcinoma of head of pancreas","Gallstones","Cirrhosis","Hepatitis"],"a":0,"e":"Courvoisier law: a palpable, non-tender, distended gallbladder with jaundice is unlikely to be due to stones and suggests malignant biliary obstruction such as pancreatic head carcinoma.<br><br>Stone disease usually scars the gallbladder; the painless palpable gallbladder indicates pancreatic head cancer."},
/*949*/ {"q":"Most common cause of chronic pancreatitis:","o":["Chronic alcohol abuse","Gallstones","Hyperlipidemia","Idiopathic"],"a":0,"e":"Chronic alcohol abuse is the commonest cause of chronic pancreatitis in adults.<br><br>Gallstones cause acute attacks more than chronic disease; the leading chronic cause is alcohol."},
/*950*/ {"q":"Whipple disease is caused by:","o":["Tropheryma whipplei","Giardia lamblia","Mycobacterium avium","Candida"],"a":0,"e":"Whipple disease is a systemic infection caused by the actinomycete Tropheryma whipplei, with PAS-positive macrophages in the intestinal lamina propria.<br><br>The other organisms cause different enteropathies; Whipple disease is due to T. whipplei."},

/*951*/ {"q":"Most common cause of small bowel obstruction in adults:","o":["Adhesions","Hernia","Tumor","Intussusception"],"a":0,"e":"Postoperative adhesions are the commonest cause of small bowel obstruction in adults.<br><br>Hernias and tumours are less frequent; the leading cause is adhesions."},
/*952*/ {"q":"Most common cause of large bowel obstruction in adults:","o":["Colorectal carcinoma","Volvulus","Diverticular stricture","Hernia"],"a":0,"e":"Colorectal carcinoma is the commonest cause of large bowel obstruction in adults.<br><br>Volvulus and strictures are less frequent; the leading cause is colorectal carcinoma."},
/*953*/ {"q":"Intussusception in children most commonly occurs at:","o":["Ileocecal junction","Sigmoid","Duodenum","Jejunum"],"a":0,"e":"Childhood intussusception most commonly occurs at the ileocaecal (ileocolic) region.<br><br>Other sites are uncommon; the commonest site is the ileocaecal junction."},
/*954*/ {"q":"Most common cause of lower GI bleeding in adults:","o":["Diverticulosis","Hemorrhoids","Angiodysplasia","Colon cancer"],"a":0,"e":"Diverticulosis is the commonest cause of significant lower gastrointestinal bleeding in adults.<br><br>Haemorrhoids cause minor bleeding; the leading cause of major lower GI bleed is diverticulosis."},
/*955*/ {"q":"Most common cause of upper GI bleeding:","o":["Peptic ulcer disease","Esophageal varices","Mallory-Weiss tear","Gastritis"],"a":0,"e":"Peptic ulcer disease is the commonest cause of upper gastrointestinal bleeding.<br><br>Varices and Mallory-Weiss tears are less frequent; the leading cause is peptic ulcer."},
/*956*/ {"q":"Most common organism causing infective endocarditis on native valves:","o":["Streptococcus viridans","Staphylococcus aureus","Enterococcus","Candida"],"a":0,"e":"Streptococcus viridans is the commonest cause of subacute infective endocarditis on previously damaged native valves; Staph aureus predominates in acute and IV drug-related cases.<br><br>Per source key the marked native-valve organism is Streptococcus viridans."},
/*957*/ {"q":"Most common valvular lesion in rheumatic heart disease:","o":["Mitral stenosis","Aortic stenosis","Tricuspid regurgitation","Pulmonary stenosis"],"a":0,"e":"Mitral stenosis is the commonest chronic valvular lesion of rheumatic heart disease.<br><br>The other valves are less affected; rheumatic disease classically causes mitral stenosis."},
/*958*/ {"q":"Janeway lesions and Osler nodes are seen in:","o":["Infective endocarditis","Rheumatic fever","SLE","Polyarteritis nodosa"],"a":0,"e":"Painless Janeway lesions and painful Osler nodes are peripheral stigmata of infective endocarditis from septic emboli and immune complexes.<br><br>They are not features of rheumatic fever; these signs indicate infective endocarditis."},
/*959*/ {"q":"Aschoff bodies are pathognomonic of:","o":["Rheumatic fever","Infective endocarditis","Sarcoidosis","Tuberculosis"],"a":0,"e":"Aschoff bodies, granulomatous foci with Anitschkow cells, are pathognomonic of rheumatic fever/carditis.<br><br>They are not seen in infective endocarditis; Aschoff bodies indicate rheumatic fever."},
/*960*/ {"q":"Most common primary cardiac tumor in adults:","o":["Myxoma","Rhabdomyoma","Angiosarcoma","Fibroma"],"a":0,"e":"Atrial myxoma, usually in the left atrium, is the commonest primary cardiac tumour in adults.<br><br>Rhabdomyoma is the commonest in children; in adults it is myxoma."},
/*961*/ {"q":"Most common primary cardiac tumor in children:","o":["Rhabdomyoma","Myxoma","Fibroma","Angiosarcoma"],"a":0,"e":"Rhabdomyoma is the commonest primary cardiac tumour in children, often associated with tuberous sclerosis.<br><br>Myxoma predominates in adults; in children it is rhabdomyoma."},
/*962*/ {"q":"Buerger disease (thromboangiitis obliterans) is strongly associated with:","o":["Heavy smoking","Diabetes","Hypertension","Hyperlipidemia"],"a":0,"e":"Thromboangiitis obliterans (Buerger disease) is strongly linked to heavy tobacco smoking in young men, with segmental vascular inflammation and thrombosis.<br><br>The other risk factors are not its main driver; Buerger disease is smoking-related."},
/*963*/ {"q":"Temporal (giant cell) arteritis classically presents with:","o":["Headache and jaw claudication with raised ESR","Hypertension","Hematuria","Skin rash"],"a":0,"e":"Giant cell (temporal) arteritis in the elderly presents with temporal headache, jaw claudication and a markedly raised ESR, risking blindness if untreated.<br><br>Renal and skin features are not typical; the hallmark is headache with jaw claudication and high ESR."},
/*964*/ {"q":"Takayasu arteritis is also known as:","o":["Pulseless disease","Saddle nose disease","Strawberry tongue disease","Mask facies"],"a":0,"e":"Takayasu arteritis (\"pulseless disease\") is a granulomatous large-vessel vasculitis of the aorta and its branches in young women, causing absent peripheral pulses.<br><br>The other eponyms describe different conditions; Takayasu is the pulseless disease."},
/*965*/ {"q":"Most common site of berry aneurysm:","o":["Anterior communicating artery","Middle cerebral artery","Basilar artery","Posterior cerebral artery"],"a":0,"e":"Berry (saccular) aneurysms most commonly arise at the anterior communicating artery in the circle of Willis.<br><br>Other sites are less frequent; the commonest is the anterior communicating artery."},
/*966*/ {"q":"Most common cause of subarachnoid hemorrhage:","o":["Ruptured berry aneurysm","Hypertensive bleed","AV malformation","Trauma (spontaneous excluded)"],"a":0,"e":"Spontaneous subarachnoid haemorrhage is most commonly due to rupture of a berry aneurysm in the circle of Willis.<br><br>AV malformations are less frequent; the leading cause is ruptured berry aneurysm."},
/*967*/ {"q":"Most common site of hypertensive intracerebral hemorrhage:","o":["Basal ganglia (putamen)","Cerebellum","Pons","Cortex"],"a":0,"e":"Hypertensive intracerebral haemorrhage most commonly occurs in the basal ganglia, particularly the putamen, from rupture of lenticulostriate microaneurysms.<br><br>The other sites are less frequent; the commonest is the putamen/basal ganglia."},
/*968*/ {"q":"Most common primary brain tumor in adults:","o":["Glioblastoma multiforme","Meningioma","Schwannoma","Oligodendroglioma"],"a":0,"e":"Glioblastoma multiforme is the commonest malignant primary brain tumour in adults; meningioma is the commonest benign one.<br><br>Per source key the marked commonest primary brain tumour is glioblastoma multiforme."},
/*969*/ {"q":"Most common posterior fossa tumor in children:","o":["Medulloblastoma","Glioblastoma","Meningioma","Schwannoma"],"a":0,"e":"Medulloblastoma is the commonest malignant posterior fossa tumour in children, arising in the cerebellar vermis.<br><br>The other tumours are uncommon in children; the commonest is medulloblastoma."},
/*970*/ {"q":"Acoustic neuroma (vestibular schwannoma) arises from:","o":["CN VIII","CN V","CN VII","CN IX"],"a":0,"e":"A vestibular schwannoma (acoustic neuroma) arises from the Schwann cells of the eighth cranial (vestibulocochlear) nerve at the cerebellopontine angle.<br><br>It does not arise from V or VII; the origin is CN VIII."},
/*971*/ {"q":"Most common cause of dementia:","o":["Alzheimer disease","Vascular dementia","Lewy body dementia","Frontotemporal dementia"],"a":0,"e":"Alzheimer disease is the commonest cause of dementia, with amyloid plaques and neurofibrillary tangles.<br><br>Vascular dementia is the second commonest; the leading cause is Alzheimer disease."},
/*972*/ {"q":"Neurofibrillary tangles and amyloid plaques are seen in:","o":["Alzheimer disease","Parkinson disease","Huntington disease","Multiple sclerosis"],"a":0,"e":"Extracellular amyloid plaques and intraneuronal neurofibrillary tangles are the histological hallmarks of Alzheimer disease.<br><br>Parkinson shows Lewy bodies; the plaque-and-tangle pathology is Alzheimer disease."},
/*973*/ {"q":"Lewy bodies are characteristic of:","o":["Parkinson disease","Alzheimer disease","Huntington disease","ALS"],"a":0,"e":"Lewy bodies, eosinophilic intracytoplasmic alpha-synuclein inclusions, are characteristic of Parkinson disease (and Lewy body dementia).<br><br>Alzheimer shows tangles/plaques; Lewy bodies indicate Parkinson disease."},
/*974*/ {"q":"Demyelination of CNS with periventricular plaques is seen in:","o":["Multiple sclerosis","Guillain-Barre syndrome","ALS","Myasthenia gravis"],"a":0,"e":"Multiple sclerosis is a CNS demyelinating disease with periventricular white-matter plaques disseminated in space and time.<br><br>Guillain-Barre affects peripheral nerves; CNS periventricular plaques indicate multiple sclerosis."},
/*975*/ {"q":"Guillain-Barre syndrome is:","o":["Acute inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy","CNS demyelination","Anterior horn cell disease","Neuromuscular junction disorder"],"a":0,"e":"Guillain-Barre syndrome is an acute immune-mediated demyelinating polyneuropathy of peripheral nerves, often post-infectious, causing ascending paralysis.<br><br>It is not a CNS or anterior-horn disease; it is a peripheral demyelinating polyneuropathy."},
/*976*/ {"q":"Anterior horn cell degeneration with upper and lower motor neuron signs is seen in:","o":["Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis","Multiple sclerosis","Myasthenia gravis","Guillain-Barre syndrome"],"a":0,"e":"Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis causes combined upper and lower motor neuron degeneration with anterior horn cell loss, producing mixed weakness without sensory loss.<br><br>The other disorders lack this combined motor picture; the diagnosis is ALS."},
/*977*/ {"q":"Most common cause of bacterial meningitis in neonates:","o":["Group B Streptococcus and E. coli","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Neisseria meningitidis","Haemophilus influenzae"],"a":0,"e":"Neonatal bacterial meningitis is most commonly caused by Group B Streptococcus and Escherichia coli acquired perinatally.<br><br>Pneumococcus and meningococcus predominate later; in neonates it is GBS and E. coli."},
/*978*/ {"q":"Most common cause of viral encephalitis (sporadic):","o":["Herpes simplex virus","Rabies","Measles","Mumps"],"a":0,"e":"Herpes simplex virus is the commonest cause of sporadic fatal viral encephalitis, with a predilection for the temporal lobes.<br><br>Rabies is rarer; sporadic encephalitis is most often HSV."},
/*979*/ {"q":"Most common pituitary tumor:","o":["Prolactinoma","Growth hormone adenoma","ACTH adenoma","Non-functioning adenoma"],"a":0,"e":"Prolactinoma is the commonest functioning pituitary adenoma, presenting with galactorrhoea, amenorrhoea or hypogonadism.<br><br>GH and ACTH adenomas are less frequent; the commonest is prolactinoma."},
/*980*/ {"q":"Most common cause of Cushing syndrome (excluding iatrogenic):","o":["Pituitary ACTH adenoma (Cushing disease)","Adrenal adenoma","Ectopic ACTH","Adrenal carcinoma"],"a":0,"e":"Excluding exogenous steroids, the commonest cause of endogenous Cushing syndrome is a pituitary ACTH-secreting adenoma (Cushing disease).<br><br>Adrenal and ectopic causes are less frequent; the leading endogenous cause is Cushing disease."},
/*981*/ {"q":"Most common cause of hyperthyroidism:","o":["Graves disease","Toxic multinodular goiter","Toxic adenoma","Thyroiditis"],"a":0,"e":"Graves disease, an autoimmune TSH-receptor antibody disorder, is the commonest cause of hyperthyroidism.<br><br>Toxic nodular goitre is next; the leading cause is Graves disease."},
/*982*/ {"q":"Most common cause of hypothyroidism (iodine-sufficient areas):","o":["Hashimoto thyroiditis","Iodine deficiency","Thyroidectomy","Drugs"],"a":0,"e":"In iodine-sufficient regions, Hashimoto autoimmune thyroiditis is the commonest cause of primary hypothyroidism.<br><br>Iodine deficiency predominates where iodine is scarce; otherwise it is Hashimoto thyroiditis."},
/*983*/ {"q":"Most common thyroid carcinoma:","o":["Papillary carcinoma","Follicular carcinoma","Medullary carcinoma","Anaplastic carcinoma"],"a":0,"e":"Papillary carcinoma is the commonest thyroid malignancy, with the best prognosis and characteristic nuclear features and psammoma bodies.<br><br>The other types are less frequent; the commonest is papillary carcinoma."},
/*984*/ {"q":"Medullary thyroid carcinoma arises from:","o":["Parafollicular C cells","Follicular cells","Lymphocytes","Fibroblasts"],"a":0,"e":"Medullary thyroid carcinoma arises from the calcitonin-secreting parafollicular C cells and may be part of MEN 2.<br><br>Follicular-cell tumours are papillary/follicular; medullary carcinoma is from C cells."},
/*985*/ {"q":"Most common cause of hypercalcemia in outpatients:","o":["Primary hyperparathyroidism","Malignancy","Vitamin D toxicity","Sarcoidosis"],"a":0,"e":"Primary hyperparathyroidism is the commonest cause of hypercalcaemia in ambulatory outpatients; malignancy is commonest in hospitalised patients.<br><br>Per source key the marked outpatient cause is primary hyperparathyroidism."},
/*986*/ {"q":"Most common cause of Addison disease (developed countries):","o":["Autoimmune adrenalitis","Tuberculosis","Metastasis","Hemorrhage"],"a":0,"e":"In developed countries autoimmune adrenalitis is the commonest cause of primary adrenal insufficiency (Addison disease); tuberculosis predominates where TB is common.<br><br>Per source key the marked answer is autoimmune adrenalitis."},
/*987*/ {"q":"Pheochromocytoma arises from:","o":["Adrenal medulla chromaffin cells","Adrenal cortex","Sympathetic ganglia only","Renal cells"],"a":0,"e":"Phaeochromocytoma is a catecholamine-secreting tumour of the chromaffin cells of the adrenal medulla, causing paroxysmal hypertension.<br><br>Cortical tumours secrete steroids; phaeochromocytoma is of the adrenal medulla."},
/*988*/ {"q":"Rule of 10s is classically associated with:","o":["Pheochromocytoma","Insulinoma","Gastrinoma","Carcinoid"],"a":0,"e":"The \"rule of 10s\" (10% bilateral, extra-adrenal, malignant, familial, paediatric) is classically taught for phaeochromocytoma.<br><br>The other neuroendocrine tumours have different rules; the rule of 10s is phaeochromocytoma."},
/*989*/ {"q":"Most common cause of secondary hypertension:","o":["Renal/renovascular disease","Pheochromocytoma","Conn syndrome","Cushing syndrome"],"a":0,"e":"Renal parenchymal and renovascular disease is the commonest cause of secondary hypertension.<br><br>The endocrine causes are less frequent; the leading secondary cause is renal disease."},
/*990*/ {"q":"Most common cause of primary hyperaldosteronism:","o":["Adrenal adenoma (Conn syndrome)","Bilateral hyperplasia","Adrenal carcinoma","Ectopic secretion"],"a":0,"e":"An aldosterone-producing adrenal adenoma (Conn syndrome) is the commonest cause of primary hyperaldosteronism, with bilateral hyperplasia next.<br><br>Per source key the marked commonest cause is an adrenal adenoma."},
/*991*/ {"q":"Diabetes mellitus type 1 is due to:","o":["Autoimmune beta-cell destruction","Insulin resistance","Obesity","Pancreatic cancer"],"a":0,"e":"Type 1 diabetes mellitus results from autoimmune destruction of pancreatic beta cells, causing absolute insulin deficiency.<br><br>Insulin resistance defines type 2; type 1 is autoimmune beta-cell loss."},
/*992*/ {"q":"Most specific autoantibody for SLE:","o":["Anti-dsDNA / anti-Smith","ANA","Rheumatoid factor","Anti-CCP"],"a":0,"e":"Anti-double-stranded DNA and anti-Smith antibodies are highly specific for systemic lupus erythematosus, while ANA is sensitive but non-specific.<br><br>For specificity the keyed answer is anti-dsDNA/anti-Sm."},
/*993*/ {"q":"Anti-CCP antibody is most specific for:","o":["Rheumatoid arthritis","SLE","Scleroderma","Sjogren syndrome"],"a":0,"e":"Anti-cyclic citrullinated peptide (anti-CCP) antibody is highly specific for rheumatoid arthritis and indicates erosive disease.<br><br>It is not specific for the other connective tissue diseases; anti-CCP marks rheumatoid arthritis."},
/*994*/ {"q":"Anti-centromere antibody is associated with:","o":["Limited scleroderma (CREST)","SLE","Rheumatoid arthritis","Dermatomyositis"],"a":0,"e":"Anti-centromere antibody is associated with limited cutaneous systemic sclerosis (CREST syndrome).<br><br>It is not typical of SLE or RA; anti-centromere indicates limited scleroderma."},
/*995*/ {"q":"Anti-Jo-1 antibody is associated with:","o":["Polymyositis/dermatomyositis","SLE","Scleroderma","Rheumatoid arthritis"],"a":0,"e":"Anti-Jo-1 (anti-histidyl tRNA synthetase) antibody is associated with polymyositis and dermatomyositis, often with interstitial lung disease.<br><br>It is not a lupus or RA marker; anti-Jo-1 indicates inflammatory myositis."},
/*996*/ {"q":"c-ANCA is associated with:","o":["Granulomatosis with polyangiitis (Wegener)","Microscopic polyangiitis","Goodpasture syndrome","SLE"],"a":0,"e":"c-ANCA (anti-proteinase 3) is associated with granulomatosis with polyangiitis (Wegener granulomatosis).<br><br>p-ANCA relates to microscopic polyangiitis; c-ANCA indicates Wegener granulomatosis."},
/*997*/ {"q":"Anti-mitochondrial antibody is characteristic of:","o":["Primary biliary cholangitis","Autoimmune hepatitis","Primary sclerosing cholangitis","Hemochromatosis"],"a":0,"e":"Anti-mitochondrial antibody is characteristic of primary biliary cholangitis, a chronic destructive cholangiopathy of small bile ducts.<br><br>Autoimmune hepatitis has ANA/anti-smooth muscle; AMA indicates primary biliary cholangitis."},
/*998*/ {"q":"HLA-B27 is associated with:","o":["Ankylosing spondylitis","Rheumatoid arthritis","SLE","Osteoarthritis"],"a":0,"e":"HLA-B27 is strongly associated with ankylosing spondylitis and other seronegative spondyloarthropathies.<br><br>RA and SLE have different HLA links; HLA-B27 indicates ankylosing spondylitis."},
/*999*/ {"q":"Gout is caused by deposition of:","o":["Monosodium urate crystals","Calcium pyrophosphate","Calcium oxalate","Cholesterol"],"a":0,"e":"Gout results from deposition of monosodium urate crystals in joints, producing acute negatively birefringent needle-shaped crystals on polarised microscopy.<br><br>Calcium pyrophosphate causes pseudogout; gout is monosodium urate."},
/*1000*/ {"q":"Pseudogout is caused by deposition of:","o":["Calcium pyrophosphate dihydrate crystals","Monosodium urate","Hydroxyapatite","Cystine"],"a":0,"e":"Pseudogout (chondrocalcinosis) is caused by calcium pyrophosphate dihydrate crystal deposition, showing rhomboid positively birefringent crystals.<br><br>Urate causes true gout; pseudogout is calcium pyrophosphate."},

/*1001*/ {"q":"Rheumatoid arthritis characteristically spares which joint?","o":["Distal interphalangeal joints","Metacarpophalangeal joints","Proximal interphalangeal joints","Wrist"],"a":0,"e":"Rheumatoid arthritis typically spares the distal interphalangeal joints, which are characteristically involved in osteoarthritis.<br><br>RA affects MCP and PIP joints; the spared joints are the DIPs."},
/*1002*/ {"q":"Heberden nodes are seen in:","o":["Osteoarthritis","Rheumatoid arthritis","Gout","Psoriatic arthritis"],"a":0,"e":"Heberden nodes are bony osteophytic swellings at the distal interphalangeal joints in osteoarthritis.<br><br>RA does not cause them; Heberden nodes indicate osteoarthritis."},
/*1003*/ {"q":"Most common organism causing osteomyelitis:","o":["Staphylococcus aureus","Streptococcus","Salmonella","Pseudomonas"],"a":0,"e":"Staphylococcus aureus is the commonest cause of acute osteomyelitis in all age groups.<br><br>Salmonella is classic in sickle cell disease; overall the leading cause is Staph aureus."},
/*1004*/ {"q":"Osteomyelitis in sickle cell disease is classically caused by:","o":["Salmonella","Staphylococcus aureus","Pseudomonas","E. coli"],"a":0,"e":"In sickle cell disease, Salmonella species are the classically associated cause of osteomyelitis.<br><br>Staph aureus is commonest generally; in sickle cell it is Salmonella."},
/*1005*/ {"q":"Most common benign bone tumor:","o":["Osteochondroma","Osteoid osteoma","Giant cell tumor","Enchondroma"],"a":0,"e":"Osteochondroma is the commonest benign bone tumour, a cartilage-capped bony outgrowth typically near the metaphysis.<br><br>The others are less frequent; the commonest benign bone tumour is osteochondroma."},
/*1006*/ {"q":"Codman triangle and sunburst appearance on X-ray suggest:","o":["Osteosarcoma","Ewing sarcoma","Osteochondroma","Giant cell tumor"],"a":0,"e":"A Codman triangle with sunburst periosteal reaction is the classic radiological appearance of osteosarcoma.<br><br>Ewing sarcoma shows an onion-skin pattern; sunburst with Codman triangle is osteosarcoma."},
/*1007*/ {"q":"Onion-skin periosteal reaction is characteristic of:","o":["Ewing sarcoma","Osteosarcoma","Chondrosarcoma","Osteoid osteoma"],"a":0,"e":"An onion-skin (lamellated) periosteal reaction is characteristic of Ewing sarcoma, a small round blue cell tumour of children.<br><br>Osteosarcoma gives a sunburst pattern; onion-skin indicates Ewing sarcoma."},
/*1008*/ {"q":"Ewing sarcoma is associated with translocation:","o":["t(11;22)","t(9;22)","t(14;18)","t(8;14)"],"a":0,"e":"Ewing sarcoma is associated with the t(11;22) translocation producing the EWS-FLI1 fusion gene.<br><br>t(9;22) is CML; the Ewing sarcoma translocation is t(11;22)."},
/*1009*/ {"q":"Most common location of giant cell tumor of bone:","o":["Epiphysis of long bones (around knee)","Diaphysis","Metaphysis only","Flat bones"],"a":0,"e":"Giant cell tumour of bone characteristically arises at the epiphysis of long bones, classically around the knee.<br><br>It is epiphyseal not diaphyseal; the typical site is the epiphysis near the knee."},
/*1010*/ {"q":"Most common cause of pathological fracture in elderly:","o":["Osteoporosis","Metastasis","Multiple myeloma","Paget disease"],"a":0,"e":"Osteoporosis is the commonest cause of pathological (fragility) fractures in the elderly.<br><br>Metastasis and myeloma are less frequent overall; the leading cause is osteoporosis."},
/*1011*/ {"q":"Most common cancers to metastasize to bone:","o":["Breast and prostate","Lung and colon","Brain and skin","Pancreas and liver"],"a":0,"e":"Breast and prostate carcinomas are the commonest cancers metastasising to bone, along with lung, thyroid and kidney.<br><br>Per source key the marked pair is breast and prostate."},
/*1012*/ {"q":"Prostate cancer bone metastases are typically:","o":["Osteoblastic (sclerotic)","Osteolytic","Mixed only","No bone change"],"a":0,"e":"Prostate carcinoma classically produces osteoblastic (sclerotic) bone metastases, raising alkaline phosphatase.<br><br>Most other cancers cause lytic lesions; prostate metastases are osteoblastic."},
/*1013*/ {"q":"Paget disease of bone shows raised:","o":["Alkaline phosphatase with normal calcium and phosphate","Serum calcium markedly raised","Serum phosphate low","PTH high"],"a":0,"e":"Paget disease of bone shows a markedly raised alkaline phosphatase with characteristically normal serum calcium and phosphate.<br><br>Calcium is usually normal; the hallmark biochemistry is isolated high alkaline phosphatase."},
/*1014*/ {"q":"Most common skin cancer:","o":["Basal cell carcinoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Melanoma","Merkel cell carcinoma"],"a":0,"e":"Basal cell carcinoma is the commonest skin cancer, slow-growing and locally invasive but rarely metastasising.<br><br>Squamous cell and melanoma are less frequent; the commonest is basal cell carcinoma."},
/*1015*/ {"q":"Most common cause of skin cancer:","o":["Ultraviolet (sun) exposure","Arsenic","Radiation","Chronic ulcer"],"a":0,"e":"Chronic ultraviolet sun exposure is the commonest cause of skin cancers including basal and squamous cell carcinomas and melanoma.<br><br>The other agents are less common; the leading cause is UV exposure."},
/*1016*/ {"q":"Marjolin ulcer is:","o":["Squamous cell carcinoma arising in a chronic wound/scar","Basal cell carcinoma","Melanoma","Venous ulcer"],"a":0,"e":"A Marjolin ulcer is a squamous cell carcinoma that develops within a chronic non-healing wound, scar or burn.<br><br>It is not basal cell or melanoma; Marjolin ulcer is squamous cell carcinoma in a chronic wound."},
/*1017*/ {"q":"Most important prognostic factor in melanoma:","o":["Breslow thickness (depth of invasion)","Diameter","Color","Site"],"a":0,"e":"The Breslow thickness (vertical tumour depth in millimetres) is the single most important prognostic factor in cutaneous melanoma.<br><br>Diameter and colour are less predictive; prognosis depends chiefly on Breslow thickness."},
/*1018*/ {"q":"Acanthosis nigricans may be a marker of:","o":["Internal malignancy / insulin resistance","Vitamin deficiency","Infection","Trauma"],"a":0,"e":"Acanthosis nigricans, velvety hyperpigmented skin in flexures, is associated with insulin resistance and, when sudden and extensive, internal (gastric) malignancy.<br><br>It is not infective or traumatic; it marks insulin resistance or malignancy."},
/*1019*/ {"q":"Pemphigus vulgaris is due to antibodies against:","o":["Desmoglein (desmosomes)","Hemidesmosomes","Basement membrane collagen","Keratin"],"a":0,"e":"Pemphigus vulgaris is caused by autoantibodies against desmoglein in desmosomes, producing intraepidermal acantholytic blisters with a positive Nikolsky sign.<br><br>Bullous pemphigoid targets hemidesmosomes; pemphigus targets desmoglein."},
/*1020*/ {"q":"Bullous pemphigoid is due to antibodies against:","o":["Hemidesmosomes (basement membrane)","Desmoglein","Keratin","Collagen IV in glomerulus"],"a":0,"e":"Bullous pemphigoid results from autoantibodies against hemidesmosomal antigens at the basement membrane, causing tense subepidermal blisters with a negative Nikolsky sign.<br><br>Pemphigus targets desmosomes; pemphigoid targets hemidesmosomes."},
/*1021*/ {"q":"Most common cause of erythema multiforme:","o":["Herpes simplex virus / drugs","Bacteria","Fungi","Trauma"],"a":0,"e":"Erythema multiforme is most commonly triggered by herpes simplex virus infection and certain drugs, producing target lesions.<br><br>Fungal and traumatic causes are uncommon; the main triggers are HSV and drugs."},
/*1022*/ {"q":"Koebner phenomenon is characteristic of:","o":["Psoriasis","Eczema","Tinea","Acne"],"a":0,"e":"The Koebner phenomenon, appearance of lesions at sites of skin trauma, is characteristic of psoriasis (and lichen planus).<br><br>It is not typical of eczema or acne; Koebner indicates psoriasis."},
/*1023*/ {"q":"Most common malignancy in women worldwide:","o":["Breast cancer","Cervical cancer","Lung cancer","Colon cancer"],"a":0,"e":"Breast cancer is the commonest malignancy in women worldwide.<br><br>Cervical and lung cancers are less common overall; the leading female cancer is breast cancer."},
/*1024*/ {"q":"Most common gynecological malignancy in developed countries:","o":["Endometrial carcinoma","Cervical carcinoma","Ovarian carcinoma","Vulvar carcinoma"],"a":0,"e":"Endometrial carcinoma is the commonest gynaecological malignancy in developed countries; cervical cancer predominates in developing regions.<br><br>Per source key the marked answer is endometrial carcinoma."},
/*1025*/ {"q":"Most common ovarian tumor overall:","o":["Serous cystadenoma/cystadenocarcinoma (surface epithelial)","Germ cell tumor","Sex cord tumor","Metastatic"],"a":0,"e":"Surface epithelial tumours, particularly serous types, are the commonest ovarian neoplasms overall.<br><br>Germ cell and sex-cord tumours are less common; the commonest are surface epithelial (serous) tumours."},
/*1026*/ {"q":"Call-Exner bodies are seen in:","o":["Granulosa cell tumor","Dysgerminoma","Serous cystadenoma","Teratoma"],"a":0,"e":"Call-Exner bodies (rosette-like follicular structures) are characteristic of granulosa cell tumours of the ovary, which may produce oestrogen.<br><br>The other tumours lack them; Call-Exner bodies indicate granulosa cell tumour."},
/*1027*/ {"q":"Most common ovarian germ cell tumor:","o":["Mature cystic teratoma (dermoid cyst)","Dysgerminoma","Yolk sac tumor","Choriocarcinoma"],"a":0,"e":"Mature cystic teratoma (dermoid cyst) is the commonest ovarian germ cell tumour, benign and containing tissues from all three germ layers.<br><br>Dysgerminoma is less common; the commonest germ cell tumour is the mature cystic teratoma."},
/*1028*/ {"q":"Schiller-Duval bodies are seen in:","o":["Yolk sac (endodermal sinus) tumor","Dysgerminoma","Granulosa cell tumor","Teratoma"],"a":0,"e":"Schiller-Duval bodies (glomeruloid structures) are characteristic of yolk sac (endodermal sinus) tumour, which secretes AFP.<br><br>The other tumours lack them; Schiller-Duval bodies indicate yolk sac tumour."},
/*1029*/ {"q":"Most common cause of cervical carcinoma:","o":["HPV infection (types 16, 18)","HSV","EBV","Chlamydia"],"a":0,"e":"Persistent infection with high-risk human papillomavirus, especially types 16 and 18, is the principal cause of cervical carcinoma.<br><br>The other organisms are not primary causes; cervical cancer is HPV-driven."},
/*1030*/ {"q":"Most common type of cervical carcinoma:","o":["Squamous cell carcinoma","Adenocarcinoma","Small cell carcinoma","Sarcoma"],"a":0,"e":"Squamous cell carcinoma is the commonest histological type of cervical cancer, arising at the transformation zone.<br><br>Adenocarcinoma is less frequent; the commonest is squamous cell carcinoma."},
/*1031*/ {"q":"Most common benign tumor of the uterus:","o":["Leiomyoma (fibroid)","Endometrial polyp","Adenomyoma","Leiomyosarcoma"],"a":0,"e":"Leiomyoma (fibroid) is the commonest benign uterine tumour and the commonest tumour in women overall.<br><br>Leiomyosarcoma is malignant and rare; the commonest benign uterine tumour is leiomyoma."},
/*1032*/ {"q":"Complete hydatidiform mole karyotype is usually:","o":["46XX (paternal origin, diploid)","69XXY","45XO","47XXY"],"a":0,"e":"A complete hydatidiform mole is usually 46XX of entirely paternal origin, with no fetal tissue and diffuse trophoblastic proliferation.<br><br>Triploidy occurs in partial moles; the complete mole is typically 46XX paternal."},
/*1033*/ {"q":"Tumor marker for choriocarcinoma:","o":["Beta-hCG","AFP","CEA","CA 125"],"a":0,"e":"Beta-human chorionic gonadotropin is the tumour marker for gestational trophoblastic disease and choriocarcinoma.<br><br>AFP relates to yolk sac tumours; choriocarcinoma is monitored with beta-hCG."},
/*1034*/ {"q":"Most common location of ectopic pregnancy:","o":["Ampulla of fallopian tube","Ovary","Cervix","Abdomen"],"a":0,"e":"The ampulla of the fallopian tube is the commonest site of ectopic pregnancy.<br><br>Ovarian and abdominal ectopics are rare; the commonest site is the tubal ampulla."},
/*1035*/ {"q":"Most common cause of postmenopausal bleeding requiring exclusion:","o":["Endometrial carcinoma","Atrophic vaginitis","Cervical polyp","Fibroid"],"a":0,"e":"Postmenopausal bleeding must be investigated to exclude endometrial carcinoma, the most important serious cause, even though atrophy is commonest.<br><br>Per source key the marked answer to exclude is endometrial carcinoma."},
/*1036*/ {"q":"Most common breast malignancy:","o":["Invasive ductal carcinoma","Invasive lobular carcinoma","Medullary carcinoma","Mucinous carcinoma"],"a":0,"e":"Invasive ductal carcinoma (no special type) is the commonest histological type of breast cancer.<br><br>Lobular and special types are less frequent; the commonest is invasive ductal carcinoma."},
/*1037*/ {"q":"Peau d'orange appearance of breast indicates:","o":["Lymphatic obstruction by carcinoma","Infection","Fibroadenoma","Fat necrosis"],"a":0,"e":"Peau d'orange (orange-peel skin) results from dermal lymphatic obstruction by infiltrating breast carcinoma causing skin dimpling around follicles.<br><br>Benign lesions do not cause it; peau d'orange indicates carcinomatous lymphatic obstruction."},
/*1038*/ {"q":"Most common benign breast tumor in young women:","o":["Fibroadenoma","Phyllodes tumor","Intraductal papilloma","Lipoma"],"a":0,"e":"Fibroadenoma is the commonest benign breast tumour in young women, a mobile firm painless lump (\"breast mouse\").<br><br>Phyllodes is rarer; the commonest benign breast tumour is fibroadenoma."},
/*1039*/ {"q":"Bloody nipple discharge is most commonly due to:","o":["Intraductal papilloma","Fibroadenoma","Duct ectasia","Carcinoma always"],"a":0,"e":"Intraductal papilloma is the commonest cause of bloody nipple discharge, a benign papillary lesion of a lactiferous duct.<br><br>Carcinoma must be excluded but is less common; the usual cause is intraductal papilloma."},
/*1040*/ {"q":"Paget disease of the nipple is associated with:","o":["Underlying ductal carcinoma","Fibroadenoma","Mastitis","Fat necrosis"],"a":0,"e":"Paget disease of the nipple, an eczematous nipple change, is associated with an underlying breast ductal carcinoma.<br><br>It is not benign; nipple Paget disease indicates underlying carcinoma."},
/*1041*/ {"q":"Most common cause of nephrolithiasis-related hypercalciuria:","o":["Idiopathic hypercalciuria","Hyperparathyroidism","Sarcoidosis","Vitamin D excess"],"a":0,"e":"Idiopathic hypercalciuria is the commonest metabolic abnormality underlying calcium stone formation.<br><br>Hyperparathyroidism is less common; the leading cause is idiopathic hypercalciuria."},
/*1042*/ {"q":"Most common cause of acute kidney injury (intrinsic):","o":["Acute tubular necrosis","Glomerulonephritis","Interstitial nephritis","Vasculitis"],"a":0,"e":"Acute tubular necrosis from ischaemia or nephrotoxins is the commonest intrinsic cause of acute kidney injury.<br><br>Glomerular and interstitial causes are less frequent; the leading intrinsic cause is ATN."},
/*1043*/ {"q":"Muddy brown granular casts in urine suggest:","o":["Acute tubular necrosis","Glomerulonephritis","Pyelonephritis","Nephrotic syndrome"],"a":0,"e":"Muddy brown granular casts in the urine are characteristic of acute tubular necrosis.<br><br>Red cell casts indicate glomerulonephritis; muddy brown casts indicate ATN."},
/*1044*/ {"q":"Red cell casts in urine indicate:","o":["Glomerulonephritis","Acute tubular necrosis","Lower urinary tract infection","Normal finding"],"a":0,"e":"Red blood cell casts in the urine indicate glomerular bleeding, characteristic of glomerulonephritis (nephritic syndrome).<br><br>ATN gives granular casts; RBC casts indicate glomerulonephritis."},
/*1045*/ {"q":"WBC casts in urine indicate:","o":["Pyelonephritis / interstitial nephritis","Glomerulonephritis","Acute tubular necrosis","Normal"],"a":0,"e":"White blood cell casts indicate renal parenchymal inflammation, classically acute pyelonephritis or interstitial nephritis.<br><br>They are not seen in simple cystitis; WBC casts indicate pyelonephritis."},
/*1046*/ {"q":"Most common cause of chronic kidney disease:","o":["Diabetes mellitus","Hypertension","Glomerulonephritis","Polycystic kidney disease"],"a":0,"e":"Diabetes mellitus is the commonest cause of chronic kidney disease and end-stage renal failure.<br><br>Hypertension is the second commonest; the leading cause is diabetes."},
/*1047*/ {"q":"Adult polycystic kidney disease inheritance is:","o":["Autosomal dominant","Autosomal recessive","X-linked","Mitochondrial"],"a":0,"e":"Adult (autosomal dominant) polycystic kidney disease is inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern, usually from PKD1/PKD2 mutations.<br><br>The infantile form is recessive; the adult form is autosomal dominant."},
/*1048*/ {"q":"Adult polycystic kidney disease is associated with:","o":["Berry aneurysms","Renal stones only","Liver failure always","Diabetes"],"a":0,"e":"Autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease is associated with intracranial berry aneurysms (risk of subarachnoid haemorrhage) and hepatic cysts.<br><br>The other associations are weaker; the classic link is berry aneurysms."},
/*1049*/ {"q":"Most common cause of nephritic syndrome in children:","o":["Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis","Minimal change disease","IgA nephropathy","Membranous nephropathy"],"a":0,"e":"Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis is the commonest cause of acute nephritic syndrome in children, following a streptococcal infection.<br><br>Minimal change causes nephrotic syndrome; the nephritic cause is post-streptococcal GN."},
/*1050*/ {"q":"Subepithelial humps on electron microscopy are characteristic of:","o":["Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis","Minimal change disease","Membranous nephropathy","IgA nephropathy"],"a":0,"e":"Subepithelial electron-dense humps are the classic electron microscopy finding of post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis.<br><br>Membranous nephropathy shows subepithelial spikes; the humps indicate post-streptococcal GN."},

/*1051*/ {"q":"Kimmelstiel-Wilson nodules are characteristic of:","o":["Diabetic nephropathy","Membranous nephropathy","Amyloidosis","Minimal change disease"],"a":0,"e":"Kimmelstiel-Wilson nodules (nodular glomerulosclerosis) are characteristic of diabetic nephropathy.<br><br>Amyloid shows Congo-red positivity; the nodular glomerulosclerosis is diabetic nephropathy."},
/*1052*/ {"q":"Most common cause of death in diabetes mellitus:","o":["Cardiovascular disease","Renal failure","Infection","Hypoglycemia"],"a":0,"e":"Cardiovascular disease (myocardial infarction and stroke) is the commonest cause of death in diabetes mellitus.<br><br>Renal failure and infection are less frequent; the leading cause of death is cardiovascular disease."},
/*1053*/ {"q":"Most common cause of blindness in working-age adults in developed countries:","o":["Diabetic retinopathy","Glaucoma","Cataract","Macular degeneration"],"a":0,"e":"Diabetic retinopathy is the commonest cause of blindness in working-age adults in developed countries.<br><br>Age-related macular degeneration affects the elderly more; in working adults it is diabetic retinopathy."},
/*1054*/ {"q":"Most common cause of irreversible blindness worldwide:","o":["Cataract","Glaucoma","Diabetic retinopathy","Trachoma"],"a":0,"e":"Cataract is the commonest cause of blindness worldwide, although it is reversible by surgery; glaucoma is the leading cause of irreversible blindness. Per source key the marked answer is cataract.<br><br>Following the keyed answer, the marked option is cataract."},
/*1055*/ {"q":"Most common cause of glaucoma:","o":["Open-angle glaucoma","Closed-angle glaucoma","Congenital glaucoma","Secondary glaucoma"],"a":0,"e":"Primary open-angle glaucoma is the commonest type, with insidious painless visual field loss from raised intraocular pressure.<br><br>Closed-angle is acute and less common; the commonest is open-angle glaucoma."},
/*1056*/ {"q":"Cherry-red spot at the macula is seen in:","o":["Central retinal artery occlusion / Tay-Sachs","Retinal detachment","Glaucoma","Cataract"],"a":0,"e":"A cherry-red macular spot occurs in central retinal artery occlusion and in lipid storage diseases such as Tay-Sachs.<br><br>Detachment and cataract give different findings; the cherry-red spot indicates CRAO or Tay-Sachs."},
/*1057*/ {"q":"Most common cause of conjunctivitis:","o":["Viral (adenovirus)","Bacterial","Allergic","Chemical"],"a":0,"e":"Viral conjunctivitis, most often adenoviral, is the commonest cause of infectious conjunctivitis.<br><br>Bacterial and allergic forms are less frequent; the commonest is viral conjunctivitis."},
/*1058*/ {"q":"Ophthalmia neonatorum within first 48 hours is most likely due to:","o":["Neisseria gonorrhoeae","Chlamydia","Herpes simplex","Staphylococcus"],"a":0,"e":"Hyperacute neonatal conjunctivitis within the first 48 hours of life is classically due to Neisseria gonorrhoeae.<br><br>Chlamydial conjunctivitis appears later (days 5-14); very early onset indicates gonococcal infection."},
/*1059*/ {"q":"Most common intraocular malignancy in children:","o":["Retinoblastoma","Melanoma","Medulloepithelioma","Glioma"],"a":0,"e":"Retinoblastoma is the commonest primary intraocular malignancy of childhood, due to RB1 gene inactivation, presenting with leukocoria.<br><br>Uveal melanoma affects adults; in children it is retinoblastoma."},
/*1060*/ {"q":"Most common intraocular malignancy in adults:","o":["Uveal melanoma","Retinoblastoma","Lymphoma","Metastasis"],"a":0,"e":"Uveal (choroidal) melanoma is the commonest primary intraocular malignancy in adults.<br><br>Retinoblastoma is paediatric; in adults the commonest is uveal melanoma."},
/*1061*/ {"q":"Most common cause of otitis media:","o":["Streptococcus pneumoniae","Staphylococcus aureus","Pseudomonas","E. coli"],"a":0,"e":"Streptococcus pneumoniae is the commonest bacterial cause of acute otitis media, followed by Haemophilus influenzae.<br><br>The other organisms are less frequent; the leading cause is pneumococcus."},
/*1062*/ {"q":"Most common cause of conductive hearing loss in adults:","o":["Otosclerosis / cerumen","Presbycusis","Acoustic neuroma","Noise exposure"],"a":0,"e":"Otosclerosis and impacted cerumen are common causes of conductive hearing loss in adults; otosclerosis fixes the stapes footplate.<br><br>Presbycusis and acoustic neuroma cause sensorineural loss; conductive loss is from otosclerosis/cerumen."},
/*1063*/ {"q":"Most common cause of sensorineural hearing loss in elderly:","o":["Presbycusis","Otosclerosis","Cerumen","Otitis media"],"a":0,"e":"Presbycusis, age-related degeneration of cochlear hair cells, is the commonest cause of sensorineural hearing loss in the elderly.<br><br>Otosclerosis causes conductive loss; the elderly sensorineural cause is presbycusis."},
/*1064*/ {"q":"Rinne and Weber tests are used to differentiate:","o":["Conductive vs sensorineural hearing loss","Vertigo causes","Tinnitus types","Otitis types"],"a":0,"e":"The Rinne and Weber tuning fork tests differentiate conductive from sensorineural hearing loss.<br><br>They do not assess vertigo or tinnitus; their purpose is distinguishing conductive from sensorineural loss."},
/*1065*/ {"q":"Most common benign salivary gland tumor:","o":["Pleomorphic adenoma","Warthin tumor","Oncocytoma","Basal cell adenoma"],"a":0,"e":"Pleomorphic adenoma (benign mixed tumour) is the commonest salivary gland tumour, usually in the parotid.<br><br>Warthin tumour is less common; the commonest benign salivary tumour is pleomorphic adenoma."},
/*1066*/ {"q":"Most common malignant salivary gland tumor:","o":["Mucoepidermoid carcinoma","Adenoid cystic carcinoma","Acinic cell carcinoma","Squamous cell carcinoma"],"a":0,"e":"Mucoepidermoid carcinoma is the commonest malignant salivary gland tumour.<br><br>Adenoid cystic carcinoma is less common; the commonest malignant salivary tumour is mucoepidermoid carcinoma."},
/*1067*/ {"q":"Warthin tumor (papillary cystadenoma lymphomatosum) occurs almost exclusively in:","o":["Parotid gland","Submandibular gland","Sublingual gland","Minor salivary glands"],"a":0,"e":"Warthin tumour occurs almost exclusively in the parotid gland, often bilaterally, and is associated with smoking.<br><br>Other glands are rarely involved; Warthin tumour is essentially a parotid lesion."},
/*1068*/ {"q":"Most common cause of acute pharyngitis:","o":["Viral","Group A Streptococcus","Mycoplasma","Fungal"],"a":0,"e":"Most cases of acute pharyngitis are viral; Group A Streptococcus is the commonest bacterial cause.<br><br>Per source key the marked commonest overall cause is viral pharyngitis."},
/*1069*/ {"q":"Quinsy is:","o":["Peritonsillar abscess","Retropharyngeal abscess","Ludwig angina","Epiglottitis"],"a":0,"e":"Quinsy is a peritonsillar abscess, a complication of tonsillitis presenting with trismus and uvular deviation.<br><br>It is not retropharyngeal; quinsy is a peritonsillar abscess."},
/*1070*/ {"q":"Most common cause of epistaxis:","o":["Little area (Kiesselbach plexus) trauma","Tumor","Hypertension","Coagulopathy"],"a":0,"e":"Most epistaxis arises from the anterior nasal septum at Little's area (Kiesselbach plexus), often from minor trauma or nose-picking.<br><br>Tumour and coagulopathy are uncommon; the usual source is Kiesselbach plexus."},
/*1071*/ {"q":"Most common site of nasopharyngeal carcinoma association:","o":["Epstein-Barr virus","HPV","HSV","CMV"],"a":0,"e":"Nasopharyngeal carcinoma is strongly associated with Epstein-Barr virus, particularly in endemic regions.<br><br>HPV relates to oropharyngeal cancer; nasopharyngeal carcinoma links to EBV."},
/*1072*/ {"q":"Most common cause of stridor in infants:","o":["Laryngomalacia","Croup","Foreign body","Epiglottitis"],"a":0,"e":"Laryngomalacia is the commonest cause of chronic stridor in infants, due to a floppy supraglottic larynx, usually self-resolving.<br><br>Croup and epiglottitis are acute; chronic infant stridor is usually laryngomalacia."},
/*1073*/ {"q":"Epiglottitis is most commonly caused by:","o":["Haemophilus influenzae type b","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Parainfluenza virus","RSV"],"a":0,"e":"Acute epiglottitis is classically caused by Haemophilus influenzae type b, presenting with the tripod position, drooling and stridor.<br><br>Parainfluenza causes croup; epiglottitis is typically Hib."},
/*1074*/ {"q":"Most common location of oral squamous cell carcinoma:","o":["Lateral border of tongue / floor of mouth","Hard palate","Gingiva","Buccal mucosa"],"a":0,"e":"Oral squamous cell carcinoma most commonly arises on the lateral border of the tongue and the floor of the mouth.<br><br>Other sites are less frequent; the commonest location is the lateral tongue/floor of mouth."},
/*1075*/ {"q":"Leukoplakia is best described as:","o":["A white patch that cannot be scraped off, potentially premalignant","Reversible candidal plaque","Always benign","Always malignant"],"a":0,"e":"Leukoplakia is a clinical white patch that cannot be wiped off and carries premalignant potential, requiring biopsy.<br><br>Candidal plaques scrape off; leukoplakia is a non-scrapable potentially premalignant lesion."},
/*1076*/ {"q":"Most common cause of hemolytic anemia worldwide:","o":["G6PD deficiency","Hereditary spherocytosis","Sickle cell disease","Thalassemia"],"a":0,"e":"Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase deficiency is the commonest enzymatic cause of hereditary haemolytic anaemia worldwide.<br><br>The other causes are less prevalent globally; the commonest is G6PD deficiency."},
/*1077*/ {"q":"Heinz bodies and bite cells are seen in:","o":["G6PD deficiency","Hereditary spherocytosis","Iron deficiency","Thalassemia"],"a":0,"e":"Heinz bodies (denatured haemoglobin) and bite cells appear in G6PD deficiency during oxidative haemolytic crises.<br><br>Spherocytosis shows spherocytes; the Heinz body/bite cell picture is G6PD deficiency."},
/*1078*/ {"q":"Hereditary spherocytosis is due to a defect in:","o":["RBC membrane proteins (spectrin/ankyrin)","Hemoglobin","Enzymes","Globin genes"],"a":0,"e":"Hereditary spherocytosis is caused by defects in red cell membrane skeletal proteins such as spectrin and ankyrin, producing spherocytes with increased osmotic fragility.<br><br>It is not a globin or enzyme defect; the defect is in membrane proteins."},
/*1079*/ {"q":"Target cells are characteristically seen in:","o":["Thalassemia and liver disease","Spherocytosis","G6PD deficiency","Hemophilia"],"a":0,"e":"Target cells (codocytes) are characteristically seen in thalassaemia, liver disease and post-splenectomy states.<br><br>Spherocytosis shows spherocytes; target cells point to thalassaemia or liver disease."},
/*1080*/ {"q":"Howell-Jolly bodies in red cells indicate:","o":["Hyposplenism / post-splenectomy","Iron deficiency","Lead poisoning","Megaloblastic anemia"],"a":0,"e":"Howell-Jolly bodies (nuclear remnants) in red cells indicate absent splenic function, as after splenectomy or in hyposplenism.<br><br>They are normally removed by the spleen; their presence indicates hyposplenism."},
/*1081*/ {"q":"Basophilic stippling of red cells is characteristic of:","o":["Lead poisoning","Iron deficiency","Folate deficiency","G6PD deficiency"],"a":0,"e":"Coarse basophilic stippling of red cells is characteristic of lead poisoning (also sideroblastic anaemia).<br><br>Iron and folate deficiencies give different smears; basophilic stippling indicates lead poisoning."},
/*1082*/ {"q":"Hypersegmented neutrophils are characteristic of:","o":["Megaloblastic anemia (B12/folate deficiency)","Iron deficiency","Hemolysis","Aplastic anemia"],"a":0,"e":"Hypersegmented neutrophils are characteristic of megaloblastic anaemia from vitamin B12 or folate deficiency.<br><br>Iron deficiency shows microcytosis; hypersegmented neutrophils indicate megaloblastic anaemia."},
/*1083*/ {"q":"Pancytopenia with hypocellular marrow indicates:","o":["Aplastic anemia","Leukemia","Myelofibrosis","Megaloblastic anemia"],"a":0,"e":"Pancytopenia with a hypocellular (fatty) bone marrow is the hallmark of aplastic anaemia.<br><br>Leukaemia gives a hypercellular marrow; pancytopenia with hypocellular marrow is aplastic anaemia."},
/*1084*/ {"q":"Most common inherited bleeding disorder:","o":["Von Willebrand disease","Hemophilia A","Hemophilia B","Factor XI deficiency"],"a":0,"e":"Von Willebrand disease is the commonest inherited bleeding disorder, impairing platelet adhesion and factor VIII carriage.<br><br>Haemophilias are less common; the commonest hereditary bleeding disorder is von Willebrand disease."},
/*1085*/ {"q":"Hemophilia A is a deficiency of:","o":["Factor VIII","Factor IX","Factor XI","Von Willebrand factor"],"a":0,"e":"Haemophilia A is an X-linked recessive deficiency of clotting factor VIII, causing haemarthroses and a prolonged APTT.<br><br>Factor IX deficiency is haemophilia B; haemophilia A is factor VIII deficiency."},
/*1086*/ {"q":"Hemophilia B (Christmas disease) is a deficiency of:","o":["Factor IX","Factor VIII","Factor XI","Factor VII"],"a":0,"e":"Haemophilia B (Christmas disease) is an X-linked deficiency of factor IX, clinically similar to haemophilia A.<br><br>Factor VIII deficiency is haemophilia A; haemophilia B is factor IX deficiency."},
/*1087*/ {"q":"Prolonged PT with normal APTT suggests deficiency of:","o":["Factor VII","Factor VIII","Factor IX","Von Willebrand factor"],"a":0,"e":"An isolated prolonged prothrombin time with a normal APTT indicates factor VII deficiency, since factor VII is unique to the extrinsic pathway.<br><br>Intrinsic factor deficiencies prolong the APTT; isolated PT prolongation is factor VII deficiency."},
/*1088*/ {"q":"DIC laboratory findings include:","o":["Prolonged PT/APTT, low platelets, raised D-dimer","Normal coagulation","Isolated thrombocytosis","Isolated high fibrinogen"],"a":0,"e":"Disseminated intravascular coagulation shows prolonged PT and APTT, thrombocytopenia, low fibrinogen and elevated D-dimer/FDPs.<br><br>Coagulation is markedly deranged; the DIC profile is prolonged times with low platelets and raised D-dimer."},
/*1089*/ {"q":"Most common cause of thrombocytopenia in an otherwise well child:","o":["Immune thrombocytopenic purpura","Leukemia","Aplastic anemia","DIC"],"a":0,"e":"Immune (idiopathic) thrombocytopenic purpura is the commonest cause of isolated thrombocytopenia in an otherwise well child, often after a viral illness.<br><br>Leukaemia has other cytopenias; the usual cause is ITP."},
/*1090*/ {"q":"Schistocytes (fragmented red cells) are characteristic of:","o":["Microangiopathic hemolytic anemia","Iron deficiency","Megaloblastic anemia","Spherocytosis"],"a":0,"e":"Schistocytes (helmet/fragmented cells) are characteristic of microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, as in DIC, TTP and HUS.<br><br>The other anaemias do not fragment cells; schistocytes indicate microangiopathic haemolysis."},
/*1091*/ {"q":"Pentad of TTP includes all except:","o":["Hypertension","Thrombocytopenia","Microangiopathic hemolysis","Neurological signs"],"a":0,"e":"The classic TTP pentad is thrombocytopenia, microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, neurological signs, renal impairment and fever; hypertension is not part of it.<br><br>The exception not in the pentad is hypertension."},
/*1092*/ {"q":"Most common leukemia in children:","o":["Acute lymphoblastic leukemia","Acute myeloid leukemia","Chronic myeloid leukemia","Chronic lymphocytic leukemia"],"a":0,"e":"Acute lymphoblastic leukaemia is the commonest leukaemia of childhood.<br><br>AML and chronic leukaemias are less common in children; the commonest is ALL."},
/*1093*/ {"q":"Most common leukemia in adults (Western countries):","o":["Chronic lymphocytic leukemia","Acute lymphoblastic leukemia","Chronic myeloid leukemia","Acute myeloid leukemia"],"a":0,"e":"Chronic lymphocytic leukaemia is the commonest leukaemia in adults in Western countries.<br><br>ALL is paediatric; in adults the commonest is CLL."},
/*1094*/ {"q":"Smudge cells on peripheral smear are characteristic of:","o":["Chronic lymphocytic leukemia","Acute myeloid leukemia","CML","Hairy cell leukemia"],"a":0,"e":"Smudge (basket) cells, fragile lymphocytes ruptured during smear preparation, are characteristic of chronic lymphocytic leukaemia.<br><br>The other leukaemias lack them; smudge cells indicate CLL."},
/*1095*/ {"q":"Tartrate-resistant acid phosphatase positivity indicates:","o":["Hairy cell leukemia","CLL","AML","CML"],"a":0,"e":"Tartrate-resistant acid phosphatase (TRAP) positivity is characteristic of hairy cell leukaemia, a B-cell neoplasm with cytoplasmic projections.<br><br>The other leukaemias are TRAP negative; TRAP indicates hairy cell leukaemia."},
/*1096*/ {"q":"Most common type of non-Hodgkin lymphoma:","o":["Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma","Follicular lymphoma","Burkitt lymphoma","Mantle cell lymphoma"],"a":0,"e":"Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma is the commonest non-Hodgkin lymphoma.<br><br>Follicular lymphoma is the next commonest; the commonest NHL is diffuse large B-cell lymphoma."},
/*1097*/ {"q":"Burkitt lymphoma is associated with translocation:","o":["t(8;14) c-myc","t(14;18) bcl-2","t(11;14) cyclin D1","t(9;22)"],"a":0,"e":"Burkitt lymphoma is associated with the t(8;14) translocation activating the c-myc oncogene, with a starry-sky histology.<br><br>t(14;18) is follicular lymphoma; Burkitt is t(8;14)."},
/*1098*/ {"q":"Follicular lymphoma is associated with translocation:","o":["t(14;18) bcl-2","t(8;14) c-myc","t(11;14)","t(9;22)"],"a":0,"e":"Follicular lymphoma is associated with the t(14;18) translocation overexpressing the anti-apoptotic BCL-2 protein.<br><br>t(8;14) is Burkitt; follicular lymphoma is t(14;18)."},
/*1099*/ {"q":"Multiple myeloma classically shows:","o":["Lytic bone lesions, M-spike, Bence Jones proteinuria","Sclerotic lesions only","Normal protein electrophoresis","Polycythemia"],"a":0,"e":"Multiple myeloma shows punched-out lytic bone lesions, a monoclonal M-spike on electrophoresis, Bence Jones proteinuria, hypercalcaemia and renal failure.<br><br>Lesions are lytic not sclerotic; the classic triad is lytic lesions, M-spike and Bence Jones protein."},
/*1100*/ {"q":"Rouleaux formation of red cells is associated with:","o":["Multiple myeloma","Iron deficiency","G6PD deficiency","Spherocytosis"],"a":0,"e":"Rouleaux formation (stacked red cells) is associated with the high paraprotein levels of multiple myeloma and other hyperglobulinaemic states.<br><br>The other conditions do not cause it; rouleaux indicates a paraproteinaemia such as myeloma."},

/*1101*/ {"q":"Most common cause of microcytic hypochromic anemia:","o":["Iron deficiency anemia","Thalassemia","Sideroblastic anemia","Anemia of chronic disease"],"a":0,"e":"Iron deficiency anaemia is the commonest cause of microcytic hypochromic anaemia worldwide.<br><br>Thalassaemia and sideroblastic anaemia are less frequent; the leading cause is iron deficiency."},
/*1102*/ {"q":"Most common cause of iron deficiency anemia in adult men and postmenopausal women:","o":["Chronic GI blood loss","Dietary deficiency","Menstruation","Hemolysis"],"a":0,"e":"In adult men and postmenopausal women, chronic gastrointestinal blood loss (including occult malignancy) is the commonest cause of iron deficiency anaemia.<br><br>Menstruation does not apply here; the leading cause is chronic GI blood loss."},
/*1103*/ {"q":"Pernicious anemia is caused by:","o":["Autoimmune destruction of parietal cells / intrinsic factor deficiency","Iron deficiency","Folate deficiency","Chronic disease"],"a":0,"e":"Pernicious anaemia results from autoimmune atrophic gastritis destroying parietal cells, causing intrinsic factor deficiency and vitamin B12 malabsorption.<br><br>It is not iron or folate related; pernicious anaemia is intrinsic factor deficiency."},
/*1104*/ {"q":"Schilling test was used to diagnose:","o":["Vitamin B12 absorption defect","Iron deficiency","Folate deficiency","Hemolysis"],"a":0,"e":"The Schilling test was historically used to assess vitamin B12 absorption and localise the cause of B12 deficiency.<br><br>It does not assess iron or folate; the Schilling test evaluates B12 absorption."},
/*1105*/ {"q":"Anemia of chronic disease is typically:","o":["Normocytic normochromic with high ferritin","Microcytic with low ferritin","Macrocytic","Hemolytic"],"a":0,"e":"Anaemia of chronic disease is usually normocytic normochromic with raised or normal ferritin and low serum iron due to hepcidin-mediated iron sequestration.<br><br>Iron deficiency has low ferritin; chronic disease anaemia has high/normal ferritin."},
/*1106*/ {"q":"Sickle cell disease results from a point mutation causing:","o":["Glutamate to valine substitution in beta-globin","Alpha-globin deletion","Beta-globin absence","Spectrin defect"],"a":0,"e":"Sickle cell disease is caused by a single point mutation substituting valine for glutamate at position 6 of the beta-globin chain.<br><br>It is not a deletion or membrane defect; sickle cell is a glutamate-to-valine substitution."},
/*1107*/ {"q":"Most common cause of death in sickle cell disease in adults:","o":["Acute chest syndrome / infection","Splenic sequestration","Aplastic crisis","Stroke"],"a":0,"e":"Acute chest syndrome and infection are leading causes of death in adults with sickle cell disease.<br><br>Splenic sequestration is a childhood threat; in adults the major causes are acute chest syndrome and infection."},
/*1108*/ {"q":"Functional asplenia in sickle cell disease increases risk of infection by:","o":["Encapsulated organisms","Viruses","Fungi","Anaerobes"],"a":0,"e":"Functional asplenia in sickle cell disease predisposes to overwhelming infection by encapsulated organisms such as pneumococcus and Haemophilus.<br><br>The spleen clears encapsulated bacteria; asplenia raises risk from these organisms."},
/*1109*/ {"q":"Beta-thalassemia major presents with:","o":["Severe anemia, skeletal changes, hepatosplenomegaly in infancy","Mild asymptomatic anemia","No anemia","Polycythemia"],"a":0,"e":"Beta-thalassaemia major presents in infancy with severe transfusion-dependent anaemia, marrow expansion causing skeletal deformity, and hepatosplenomegaly.<br><br>The trait is mild; major disease is severe with skeletal and organ changes."},
/*1110*/ {"q":"HbA2 is elevated in:","o":["Beta-thalassemia trait","Iron deficiency","Alpha-thalassemia","G6PD deficiency"],"a":0,"e":"Elevated HbA2 on electrophoresis is diagnostic of beta-thalassaemia trait.<br><br>Iron deficiency and alpha-thalassaemia do not raise HbA2; the elevation indicates beta-thalassaemia trait."},
/*1111*/ {"q":"Hydrops fetalis with no functional alpha chains is:","o":["Hb Barts (alpha-thalassemia major)","Beta-thalassemia major","Sickle cell disease","HbC disease"],"a":0,"e":"Deletion of all four alpha-globin genes produces Hb Barts, causing hydrops fetalis and intrauterine death (alpha-thalassaemia major).<br><br>Beta-thalassaemia major presents postnatally; the no-alpha-chain hydrops is Hb Barts."},
/*1112*/ {"q":"Polycythemia vera is associated with mutation in:","o":["JAK2","BCR-ABL","RET","p53"],"a":0,"e":"Polycythaemia vera, a myeloproliferative neoplasm, is associated with the JAK2 V617F mutation in most cases.<br><br>BCR-ABL is CML; polycythaemia vera carries the JAK2 mutation."},
/*1113*/ {"q":"Most common cause of secondary polycythemia:","o":["Chronic hypoxia (lung disease, altitude)","Renal tumor","Dehydration","Smoking only"],"a":0,"e":"Chronic hypoxia, as in lung disease or high altitude, raises erythropoietin and is the commonest cause of secondary polycythaemia.<br><br>Renal tumours are rare causes; the leading cause is chronic hypoxia."},
/*1114*/ {"q":"Erythropoietin is produced mainly by:","o":["Kidney (peritubular cells)","Liver","Spleen","Bone marrow"],"a":0,"e":"Erythropoietin is produced chiefly by the peritubular interstitial cells of the kidney in response to hypoxia.<br><br>The fetal liver makes some; in adults the main source is the kidney."},
/*1115*/ {"q":"Most common transfusion reaction:","o":["Febrile non-hemolytic reaction","Acute hemolytic reaction","Anaphylaxis","TRALI"],"a":0,"e":"Febrile non-haemolytic transfusion reactions, caused by recipient antibodies against donor leucocytes, are the commonest transfusion reactions.<br><br>Acute haemolysis is rarer; the commonest reaction is febrile non-haemolytic."},
/*1116*/ {"q":"Acute hemolytic transfusion reaction is most commonly due to:","o":["ABO incompatibility (clerical error)","Rh mismatch","Bacterial contamination","Citrate toxicity"],"a":0,"e":"Acute haemolytic transfusion reactions are most commonly caused by ABO incompatibility from clerical/identification errors.<br><br>Rh mismatch causes delayed reactions; the acute severe reaction is ABO incompatibility."},
/*1117*/ {"q":"Most common cause of massive transfusion-related coagulopathy:","o":["Dilutional thrombocytopenia and factor deficiency","Hypercoagulability","Polycythemia","Hypernatremia"],"a":0,"e":"Massive transfusion causes coagulopathy chiefly through dilution of platelets and clotting factors, plus hypothermia and citrate effects.<br><br>It does not cause hypercoagulability; the mechanism is dilutional thrombocytopenia and factor deficiency."},
/*1118*/ {"q":"Most common inherited thrombophilia:","o":["Factor V Leiden","Protein C deficiency","Protein S deficiency","Antithrombin deficiency"],"a":0,"e":"Factor V Leiden (activated protein C resistance) is the commonest inherited thrombophilia.<br><br>Protein C/S and antithrombin deficiencies are rarer; the commonest is factor V Leiden."},
/*1119*/ {"q":"Heparin acts by potentiating:","o":["Antithrombin III","Protein C","Plasmin","Factor VII"],"a":0,"e":"Heparin exerts its anticoagulant effect by potentiating antithrombin III, which inactivates thrombin and factor Xa.<br><br>It does not act via protein C or plasmin; heparin enhances antithrombin III."},
/*1120*/ {"q":"Warfarin inhibits vitamin K-dependent factors:","o":["II, VII, IX, X (and proteins C, S)","V and VIII","XI and XII","Fibrinogen"],"a":0,"e":"Warfarin inhibits the vitamin K-dependent clotting factors II, VII, IX and X, plus proteins C and S, by blocking gamma-carboxylation.<br><br>Factors V and VIII are not vitamin K dependent; warfarin affects II, VII, IX, X."},
/*1121*/ {"q":"Protamine sulfate is the antidote for:","o":["Heparin","Warfarin","Aspirin","Streptokinase"],"a":0,"e":"Protamine sulfate reverses the anticoagulant effect of heparin by forming an inactive complex.<br><br>Warfarin is reversed by vitamin K/FFP; protamine reverses heparin."},
/*1122*/ {"q":"Heparin-induced thrombocytopenia is mediated by antibodies against:","o":["Platelet factor 4-heparin complex","GpIIb/IIIa","Von Willebrand factor","Factor VIII"],"a":0,"e":"Heparin-induced thrombocytopenia is caused by antibodies against the platelet factor 4-heparin complex, paradoxically causing thrombosis.<br><br>It does not target GpIIb/IIIa; the antibodies are against the PF4-heparin complex."},
/*1123*/ {"q":"Most common cause of vitamin K deficiency in neonates:","o":["Physiological (immature gut flora, low stores)","Liver disease","Malabsorption","Antibiotics"],"a":0,"e":"Newborns are physiologically deficient in vitamin K due to immature gut flora, low placental transfer and low stores, hence routine prophylaxis at birth.<br><br>The other causes are uncommon in neonates; the usual cause is physiological deficiency."},
/*1124*/ {"q":"Cryoprecipitate is rich in:","o":["Fibrinogen, factor VIII, von Willebrand factor","Factor IX","Albumin","Immunoglobulins"],"a":0,"e":"Cryoprecipitate is rich in fibrinogen, factor VIII, von Willebrand factor and factor XIII, used in fibrinogen deficiency and DIC.<br><br>It is not an immunoglobulin product; cryoprecipitate contains fibrinogen and factor VIII/vWF."},
/*1125*/ {"q":"Most common cause of folate deficiency:","o":["Poor dietary intake / increased demand","Pernicious anemia","Ileal resection","Pancreatic insufficiency"],"a":0,"e":"Folate deficiency is most commonly due to inadequate dietary intake or increased demand (pregnancy, haemolysis), as body stores are limited.<br><br>Ileal resection causes B12 deficiency; folate deficiency is usually dietary."},
/*1126*/ {"q":"Most radiosensitive phase of the cell cycle:","o":["G2/M phase","S phase","G1 phase","G0 phase"],"a":0,"e":"Cells are most radiosensitive during the G2 and M phases of the cell cycle and most resistant in late S phase.<br><br>Resting G0 cells are relatively resistant; the most radiosensitive phase is G2/M."},
/*1127*/ {"q":"Most radiosensitive tissue among the following:","o":["Bone marrow / lymphoid tissue","Muscle","Bone","Nerve"],"a":0,"e":"Rapidly dividing tissues such as bone marrow and lymphoid tissue are the most radiosensitive, while muscle and nerve are radioresistant.<br><br>The keyed most sensitive tissue is bone marrow/lymphoid tissue."},
/*1128*/ {"q":"Radiation causes cell injury mainly by:","o":["Free radical generation and DNA damage","Direct protein denaturation only","Membrane lysis only","Mitochondrial swelling only"],"a":0,"e":"Ionising radiation injures cells mainly by generating reactive oxygen free radicals that damage DNA, causing strand breaks and mutation.<br><br>Protein and membrane effects are secondary; the principal mechanism is free-radical DNA damage."},
/*1129*/ {"q":"Deterministic radiation effects are characterized by:","o":["A threshold dose with severity proportional to dose","No threshold","Random occurrence","Genetic only"],"a":0,"e":"Deterministic (tissue) radiation effects have a threshold dose below which they do not occur and severity increasing with dose, e.g. skin erythema, cataract.<br><br>Stochastic effects have no threshold; deterministic effects are threshold-dependent."},
/*1130*/ {"q":"Stochastic radiation effects include:","o":["Cancer induction and heritable mutations","Skin erythema","Cataract","Sterility"],"a":0,"e":"Stochastic radiation effects, such as cancer induction and heritable mutation, have no threshold and probability increases with dose.<br><br>Erythema and cataract are deterministic; stochastic effects are carcinogenesis and mutation."},
/*1131*/ {"q":"The unit of absorbed radiation dose is:","o":["Gray","Sievert","Becquerel","Curie"],"a":0,"e":"The gray (Gy) is the SI unit of absorbed radiation dose (joules per kilogram).<br><br>The sievert is equivalent dose and becquerel is activity; absorbed dose is measured in gray."},
/*1132*/ {"q":"The unit of equivalent (effective) dose is:","o":["Sievert","Gray","Becquerel","Roentgen"],"a":0,"e":"The sievert (Sv) is the SI unit of equivalent and effective dose, accounting for radiation type and tissue sensitivity.<br><br>The gray is absorbed dose; equivalent dose is measured in sieverts."},
/*1133*/ {"q":"The unit of radioactivity is:","o":["Becquerel","Gray","Sievert","Rad"],"a":0,"e":"The becquerel (Bq), one disintegration per second, is the SI unit of radioactivity.<br><br>The gray and sievert measure dose; activity is in becquerels."},
/*1134*/ {"q":"X-rays are produced when:","o":["High-speed electrons strike a metal target (anode)","Protons decay","Neutrons collide","Light is reflected"],"a":0,"e":"X-rays are produced in an X-ray tube when high-speed electrons accelerated from the cathode strike a metal (tungsten) anode target.<br><br>It does not involve proton or neutron processes; X-rays arise from electrons hitting the anode."},
/*1135*/ {"q":"Characteristic X-rays are produced by:","o":["Inner-shell electron transitions in the target atom","Bremsstrahlung","Pair production","Compton scatter"],"a":0,"e":"Characteristic X-rays are emitted when an electron fills a vacancy in an inner shell of the target atom, releasing a photon of characteristic energy.<br><br>Bremsstrahlung is the braking radiation; characteristic X-rays come from inner-shell transitions."},
/*1136*/ {"q":"Bremsstrahlung radiation is produced by:","o":["Deceleration of electrons near the nucleus","Inner-shell transitions","Nuclear fission","Annihilation"],"a":0,"e":"Bremsstrahlung (\"braking radiation\") is produced when electrons decelerate in the electric field of the target nucleus, emitting a continuous X-ray spectrum.<br><br>Inner-shell transitions give characteristic X-rays; the continuous spectrum is bremsstrahlung."},
/*1137*/ {"q":"The predominant interaction of diagnostic X-rays with soft tissue is:","o":["Compton scattering","Photoelectric effect","Pair production","Coherent scatter"],"a":0,"e":"At diagnostic X-ray energies in soft tissue, Compton scattering is the predominant interaction, contributing to image noise and scatter.<br><br>Pair production needs high energy; the main soft-tissue interaction is Compton scatter."},
/*1138*/ {"q":"The photoelectric effect is more important at:","o":["Lower photon energies and high atomic number","High energies","All energies equally","Only in air"],"a":0,"e":"The photoelectric effect predominates at lower photon energies and in high atomic number materials such as bone and contrast media, giving high subject contrast.<br><br>It diminishes at high energy; it dominates at low energy/high Z."},
/*1139*/ {"q":"Contrast in radiography is improved at:","o":["Lower kVp","Higher kVp","Higher mAs only","No relation to kVp"],"a":0,"e":"Lower kilovoltage (kVp) increases the photoelectric contribution and improves radiographic subject contrast, at the cost of higher patient dose.<br><br>Higher kVp reduces contrast; lower kVp improves contrast."},
/*1140*/ {"q":"mAs primarily controls:","o":["Quantity of X-rays (image density/noise)","Beam quality","Penetration","Wavelength"],"a":0,"e":"The milliampere-seconds (mAs) primarily controls the quantity of X-ray photons, affecting image density and noise.<br><br>kVp controls beam quality/penetration; mAs controls photon quantity."},
/*1141*/ {"q":"ALARA principle in radiology means:","o":["As Low As Reasonably Achievable radiation dose","Maximum permissible dose","No radiation at all","Average dose"],"a":0,"e":"ALARA stands for As Low As Reasonably Achievable, the principle of minimising radiation dose to patients and staff while achieving the diagnostic aim.<br><br>It is not a fixed maximum; ALARA is dose minimisation."},
/*1142*/ {"q":"Most radiosensitive period for the developing fetus is:","o":["Organogenesis (weeks 2-8)","First week","Third trimester","At birth"],"a":0,"e":"The fetus is most radiosensitive during organogenesis (about weeks 2-8), when radiation may cause major congenital malformations.<br><br>Later gestation is less sensitive; the critical period is organogenesis."},
/*1143*/ {"q":"Best imaging modality for acute intracranial hemorrhage:","o":["Non-contrast CT","MRI","Ultrasound","Plain X-ray"],"a":0,"e":"Non-contrast CT is the first-line, rapid and sensitive modality for detecting acute intracranial haemorrhage.<br><br>MRI is better for ischaemia/chronic blood; acute haemorrhage is best seen on non-contrast CT."},
/*1144*/ {"q":"Best imaging modality for acute ischemic stroke (early):","o":["Diffusion-weighted MRI","Non-contrast CT","Plain X-ray","Ultrasound"],"a":0,"e":"Diffusion-weighted MRI is the most sensitive modality for detecting acute ischaemic stroke within the first hours.<br><br>Early CT may be normal; DWI MRI best shows early infarction."},
/*1145*/ {"q":"Investigation of choice for renal stones:","o":["Non-contrast CT KUB","Ultrasound","Plain X-ray KUB","IVU"],"a":0,"e":"Non-contrast CT of the kidneys, ureters and bladder is the investigation of choice for urinary tract calculi, detecting nearly all stones.<br><br>Ultrasound and plain film miss small or radiolucent stones; CT KUB is the gold standard."},
/*1146*/ {"q":"Investigation of choice for suspected pulmonary embolism:","o":["CT pulmonary angiography","Chest X-ray","V/Q scan first-line","Echocardiography"],"a":0,"e":"CT pulmonary angiography is the investigation of choice for diagnosing pulmonary embolism in most patients.<br><br>V/Q scan is reserved for contrast contraindications; the first-line test is CTPA."},
/*1147*/ {"q":"Investigation of choice for soft tissue and spinal cord lesions:","o":["MRI","CT","Ultrasound","Plain X-ray"],"a":0,"e":"MRI provides superior soft-tissue contrast and is the investigation of choice for spinal cord, brain and musculoskeletal soft-tissue lesions.<br><br>CT is better for bone/acute bleed; soft tissue and cord are best on MRI."},
/*1148*/ {"q":"First-line imaging for suspected gallstones:","o":["Ultrasound abdomen","CT abdomen","Plain X-ray","MRI"],"a":0,"e":"Abdominal ultrasound is the first-line investigation for gallstones and biliary disease, being sensitive, cheap and radiation-free.<br><br>CT is less sensitive for stones; the first-line test is ultrasound."},
/*1149*/ {"q":"Gold standard for diagnosing coronary artery disease:","o":["Coronary angiography","ECG","Echocardiography","Chest X-ray"],"a":0,"e":"Invasive coronary angiography is the gold standard for delineating coronary artery stenosis.<br><br>ECG and echo are non-invasive adjuncts; the definitive test is coronary angiography."},
/*1150*/ {"q":"Contrast-induced nephropathy is best prevented by:","o":["Adequate hydration and minimizing contrast volume","High-dose diuretics","Withholding all fluids","Routine dialysis"],"a":0,"e":"Contrast-induced nephropathy is best prevented by adequate intravenous hydration and using the lowest necessary contrast volume in at-risk patients.<br><br>Diuretics and fluid restriction worsen risk; prevention is hydration and dose minimisation."},

/*1151*/ {"q":"Most common modality for fetal assessment in pregnancy:","o":["Ultrasound","CT","MRI","X-ray"],"a":0,"e":"Ultrasound is the modality of choice for fetal assessment, being safe and free of ionising radiation.<br><br>CT and X-ray are avoided in pregnancy; fetal imaging uses ultrasound."},
/*1152*/ {"q":"Mammography is primarily used to detect:","o":["Breast microcalcifications and masses","Bone lesions","Lung nodules","Liver cysts"],"a":0,"e":"Mammography is a low-dose breast X-ray used to detect microcalcifications and masses for breast cancer screening.<br><br>It does not image lung or liver; mammography detects breast lesions."},
/*1153*/ {"q":"DEXA scan is used to measure:","o":["Bone mineral density","Liver fat","Cardiac function","Renal flow"],"a":0,"e":"Dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry (DEXA) measures bone mineral density to diagnose osteoporosis.<br><br>It does not assess liver or heart; DEXA quantifies bone mineral density."},
/*1154*/ {"q":"T-score on DEXA of -2.5 or below indicates:","o":["Osteoporosis","Osteopenia","Normal bone","Osteomalacia"],"a":0,"e":"A DEXA T-score of -2.5 or lower defines osteoporosis; a T-score between -1 and -2.5 indicates osteopenia.<br><br>Values above -1 are normal; -2.5 or below is osteoporosis."},
/*1155*/ {"q":"Best modality to evaluate the biliary tree non-invasively:","o":["MRCP","ERCP","Plain X-ray","CT without contrast"],"a":0,"e":"Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP) is the best non-invasive modality to image the biliary and pancreatic ducts.<br><br>ERCP is invasive/therapeutic; non-invasive ductal imaging is MRCP."},
/*1156*/ {"q":"ERCP is primarily used for:","o":["Therapeutic biliary intervention (stone removal, stenting)","Screening","Bone imaging","Fetal assessment"],"a":0,"e":"Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography is now mainly therapeutic, for stone extraction, sphincterotomy and stenting of the biliary tree.<br><br>Diagnosis is largely by MRCP; ERCP is chiefly therapeutic."},
/*1157*/ {"q":"Best modality for staging most solid tumors:","o":["CT with contrast","Plain X-ray","Ultrasound","Fluoroscopy"],"a":0,"e":"Contrast-enhanced CT is the workhorse for staging most solid tumours, assessing size, nodes and metastases.<br><br>Plain films are insufficient; tumour staging usually uses contrast CT (with PET/MRI as adjuncts)."},
/*1158*/ {"q":"PET scan detects tumors based on:","o":["Increased glucose (FDG) metabolism","Calcium uptake","Iron content","Air content"],"a":0,"e":"FDG-PET detects malignant tissue based on its increased glucose metabolism, taking up the radiolabelled glucose analogue.<br><br>It does not rely on calcium or iron; PET maps metabolic (glucose) activity."},
/*1159*/ {"q":"Bone scan (technetium-99m) detects:","o":["Osteoblastic activity (metastases, infection)","Soft tissue tumors","Lung nodules","Renal stones"],"a":0,"e":"A technetium-99m bone scan detects areas of increased osteoblastic activity, useful for skeletal metastases, osteomyelitis and occult fractures.<br><br>It does not image soft tissue; the bone scan maps osteoblastic activity."},
/*1160*/ {"q":"Radioactive iodine (I-131) is used in:","o":["Thyroid imaging and therapy","Bone imaging","Renal imaging","Cardiac perfusion"],"a":0,"e":"Iodine-131 is concentrated by thyroid tissue and is used for thyroid scanning and for treating hyperthyroidism and thyroid carcinoma.<br><br>It is not a bone or cardiac agent; I-131 is thyroid-specific."},
/*1161*/ {"q":"Most common cause of a solitary pulmonary nodule that is benign:","o":["Granuloma","Hamartoma","Metastasis","Bronchogenic carcinoma"],"a":0,"e":"An infectious granuloma (often old tuberculous or fungal) is the commonest benign cause of a solitary pulmonary nodule.<br><br>Hamartoma is less common; the commonest benign nodule is a granuloma."},
/*1162*/ {"q":"Popcorn calcification of a pulmonary nodule suggests:","o":["Hamartoma","Carcinoma","Metastasis","Abscess"],"a":0,"e":"Popcorn calcification within a pulmonary nodule is characteristic of a benign pulmonary hamartoma.<br><br>Malignant nodules rarely calcify this way; popcorn calcification indicates hamartoma."},
/*1163*/ {"q":"Eggshell calcification of hilar lymph nodes is seen in:","o":["Silicosis","Asbestosis","Sarcoidosis","Tuberculosis"],"a":0,"e":"Peripheral eggshell calcification of hilar lymph nodes is characteristic of silicosis (and sometimes sarcoidosis).<br><br>Asbestosis causes pleural plaques; eggshell nodal calcification indicates silicosis."},
/*1164*/ {"q":"Honeycomb lung on HRCT indicates:","o":["End-stage pulmonary fibrosis","Acute pneumonia","Pulmonary edema","Pneumothorax"],"a":0,"e":"A honeycomb pattern on high-resolution CT indicates end-stage pulmonary fibrosis with destroyed, cystic lung architecture.<br><br>Acute processes look different; honeycombing means established fibrosis."},
/*1165*/ {"q":"Kerley B lines on chest X-ray indicate:","o":["Interstitial pulmonary edema","Pneumothorax","Consolidation","Emphysema"],"a":0,"e":"Kerley B lines are short horizontal peripheral lines representing interlobular septal thickening, typically from interstitial pulmonary oedema.<br><br>They are not seen in pneumothorax; Kerley B lines indicate interstitial oedema."},
/*1166*/ {"q":"Bat-wing (perihilar) opacification on chest X-ray suggests:","o":["Pulmonary edema","Lobar pneumonia","Pneumothorax","Pleural effusion"],"a":0,"e":"A bilateral perihilar bat-wing pattern of air-space opacification is characteristic of pulmonary oedema.<br><br>Lobar pneumonia is localised; the bat-wing pattern indicates pulmonary oedema."},
/*1167*/ {"q":"Most common radiographic sign of pneumoperitoneum:","o":["Free air under the diaphragm on erect film","Air-fluid levels","Ground glass","Honeycombing"],"a":0,"e":"Free gas under the diaphragm on an erect chest or abdominal film is the classic radiographic sign of pneumoperitoneum from a perforated viscus.<br><br>Air-fluid levels indicate obstruction; subdiaphragmatic free air indicates perforation."},
/*1168*/ {"q":"Coffee-bean sign on abdominal X-ray indicates:","o":["Sigmoid volvulus","Small bowel obstruction","Pneumoperitoneum","Toxic megacolon"],"a":0,"e":"The coffee-bean (or inverted U) sign is characteristic of a sigmoid volvulus, a dilated closed loop arising from the pelvis.<br><br>Small bowel obstruction shows different features; the coffee-bean sign indicates sigmoid volvulus."},
/*1169*/ {"q":"String sign on barium study is characteristic of:","o":["Crohn disease","Ulcerative colitis","Colon cancer","Diverticulitis"],"a":0,"e":"The string sign, a narrowed segment of terminal ileum from inflammation and spasm, is characteristic of Crohn disease.<br><br>Ulcerative colitis differs; the string sign indicates Crohn disease."},
/*1170*/ {"q":"Lead-pipe colon on barium enema is seen in:","o":["Chronic ulcerative colitis","Crohn disease","Colon cancer","Diverticulosis"],"a":0,"e":"A featureless \"lead-pipe\" colon with loss of haustra on barium enema is characteristic of chronic ulcerative colitis.<br><br>Crohn shows skip strictures; the lead-pipe colon indicates ulcerative colitis."},
/*1171*/ {"q":"Double-bubble sign on neonatal abdominal X-ray indicates:","o":["Duodenal atresia","Pyloric stenosis","Hirschsprung disease","Necrotizing enterocolitis"],"a":0,"e":"The double-bubble sign (distended stomach and proximal duodenum) on neonatal radiograph indicates duodenal atresia, often associated with Down syndrome.<br><br>Pyloric stenosis gives a single bubble; the double bubble indicates duodenal atresia."},
/*1172*/ {"q":"Target/doughnut sign on ultrasound suggests:","o":["Intussusception","Appendicitis","Volvulus","Pyloric stenosis"],"a":0,"e":"A target or doughnut sign on ultrasound of the abdomen is characteristic of intussusception, showing bowel-within-bowel.<br><br>Pyloric stenosis shows a thickened pylorus; the target sign indicates intussusception."},
/*1173*/ {"q":"Most common cause of bowel gas pattern with multiple air-fluid levels:","o":["Intestinal obstruction","Pneumoperitoneum","Ascites","Ileus only if generalized"],"a":0,"e":"Multiple dilated bowel loops with air-fluid levels on an erect film indicate mechanical intestinal obstruction.<br><br>Pneumoperitoneum shows free air; the air-fluid levels pattern indicates obstruction."},
/*1174*/ {"q":"Soap-bubble appearance of bone is seen in:","o":["Giant cell tumor / aneurysmal bone cyst","Osteosarcoma","Osteoid osteoma","Paget disease"],"a":0,"e":"A soap-bubble (multiloculated lytic) appearance of bone is characteristic of giant cell tumour and aneurysmal bone cyst.<br><br>Osteosarcoma shows a sunburst; the soap-bubble lesion is giant cell tumour/aneurysmal bone cyst."},
/*1175*/ {"q":"Salter-Harris classification is used for:","o":["Pediatric growth plate (physeal) fractures","Skull fractures","Pelvic fractures","Vertebral fractures"],"a":0,"e":"The Salter-Harris classification grades fractures involving the growth plate (physis) in children, important for prognosis.<br><br>It is not for skull or pelvis; Salter-Harris classifies physeal fractures."},
/*1176*/ {"q":"Most common site of avascular necrosis:","o":["Femoral head","Humeral head","Scaphoid","Talus"],"a":0,"e":"The femoral head is the commonest site of avascular necrosis, due to its precarious retinacular blood supply.<br><br>The scaphoid and talus are also at risk but less common; the commonest site is the femoral head."},
/*1177*/ {"q":"Most common cause of avascular necrosis of the femoral head (non-traumatic):","o":["Corticosteroid use and alcohol","Diabetes","Hypertension","Smoking"],"a":0,"e":"Non-traumatic avascular necrosis of the femoral head is most commonly associated with corticosteroid therapy and alcohol abuse.<br><br>The other factors are weaker; the leading non-traumatic causes are steroids and alcohol."},
/*1178*/ {"q":"Scaphoid fracture characteristically risks:","o":["Avascular necrosis of proximal pole","Malunion only","Compartment syndrome","Nerve injury"],"a":0,"e":"A scaphoid fracture risks avascular necrosis of the proximal pole because its blood supply enters distally and runs retrograde.<br><br>The retrograde supply makes the proximal fragment vulnerable to avascular necrosis."},
/*1179*/ {"q":"Most common carpal bone fractured:","o":["Scaphoid","Lunate","Triquetrum","Pisiform"],"a":0,"e":"The scaphoid is the commonest carpal bone fractured, typically from a fall on the outstretched hand, with tenderness in the anatomical snuffbox.<br><br>The other carpals fracture less often; the commonest is the scaphoid."},
/*1180*/ {"q":"Most common shoulder dislocation direction:","o":["Anterior","Posterior","Inferior","Superior"],"a":0,"e":"Anterior dislocation is by far the commonest type of shoulder dislocation, often risking the axillary nerve.<br><br>Posterior dislocation (e.g. seizures) is rare; the commonest is anterior."},
/*1181*/ {"q":"Most common nerve injured in anterior shoulder dislocation:","o":["Axillary nerve","Radial nerve","Median nerve","Ulnar nerve"],"a":0,"e":"The axillary nerve is the most commonly injured nerve in anterior shoulder dislocation, causing deltoid weakness and regimental-badge sensory loss.<br><br>The radial nerve is at risk in humeral shaft fractures; the dislocation injures the axillary nerve."},
/*1182*/ {"q":"Most common nerve injured in mid-shaft humeral fracture:","o":["Radial nerve","Axillary nerve","Median nerve","Ulnar nerve"],"a":0,"e":"The radial nerve, running in the spiral groove, is the most commonly injured nerve in mid-shaft humeral fractures, causing wrist drop.<br><br>The axillary nerve relates to the surgical neck; mid-shaft injures the radial nerve."},
/*1183*/ {"q":"Most common nerve injured in supracondylar fracture of humerus in children:","o":["Anterior interosseous / median nerve","Ulnar nerve","Radial nerve","Axillary nerve"],"a":0,"e":"Supracondylar humeral fractures in children most commonly injure the median nerve (anterior interosseous branch), risking also the brachial artery.<br><br>The ulnar/radial are less often involved; the classic injury is to the median nerve."},
/*1184*/ {"q":"Volkmann ischemic contracture results from:","o":["Untreated forearm compartment syndrome","Nerve transection","Bone infection","Joint dislocation"],"a":0,"e":"Volkmann ischaemic contracture is a permanent flexion deformity resulting from untreated forearm compartment syndrome and muscle ischaemia, classically after supracondylar fracture.<br><br>It is not from simple nerve injury; it follows ischaemic muscle necrosis."},
/*1185*/ {"q":"Most common site of compartment syndrome:","o":["Anterior compartment of the leg","Forearm flexor","Thigh","Foot"],"a":0,"e":"The anterior compartment of the leg is the commonest site of acute compartment syndrome, often after tibial fracture.<br><br>The forearm is next; the commonest site is the anterior leg compartment."},
/*1186*/ {"q":"Earliest and most reliable sign of compartment syndrome:","o":["Pain out of proportion, worse on passive stretch","Pulselessness","Paralysis","Pallor"],"a":0,"e":"Pain out of proportion to the injury, worsened by passive muscle stretch, is the earliest and most reliable clinical sign of compartment syndrome.<br><br>Pulselessness and paralysis are late; the early sign is disproportionate stretch pain."},
/*1187*/ {"q":"Most common cause of fat embolism syndrome:","o":["Long bone fractures","Burns","Sepsis","Pancreatitis"],"a":0,"e":"Long bone (especially femoral) fractures are the commonest cause of fat embolism syndrome, with respiratory distress, petechiae and neurological changes.<br><br>The other causes are uncommon; the leading cause is long bone fracture."},
/*1188*/ {"q":"Most common organism in open fracture wound infection:","o":["Staphylococcus aureus","Streptococcus","Clostridium","Pseudomonas"],"a":0,"e":"Staphylococcus aureus is the commonest organism causing infection in open fracture wounds.<br><br>Clostridium causes gas gangrene less commonly; the leading organism is Staph aureus."},
/*1189*/ {"q":"Gas gangrene is caused by:","o":["Clostridium perfringens","Staphylococcus aureus","Streptococcus pyogenes","E. coli"],"a":0,"e":"Gas gangrene (clostridial myonecrosis) is caused by Clostridium perfringens, producing alpha-toxin, crepitus and rapid tissue necrosis.<br><br>The other organisms cause different infections; gas gangrene is clostridial."},
/*1190*/ {"q":"Tetanus is caused by the toxin of:","o":["Clostridium tetani","Clostridium botulinum","Clostridium difficile","Clostridium perfringens"],"a":0,"e":"Tetanus is caused by tetanospasmin from Clostridium tetani, which blocks inhibitory neurotransmitters causing spastic paralysis (lockjaw).<br><br>Botulinum causes flaccid paralysis; tetanus is due to C. tetani."},
/*1191*/ {"q":"Most common cause of septic arthritis in young adults:","o":["Neisseria gonorrhoeae","Staphylococcus aureus","Streptococcus","E. coli"],"a":0,"e":"Neisseria gonorrhoeae is the commonest cause of septic arthritis in sexually active young adults; Staph aureus is commonest overall.<br><br>Per source key the marked answer for young adults is gonococcal arthritis."},
/*1192*/ {"q":"Most common joint affected in septic arthritis (adults):","o":["Knee","Hip","Shoulder","Wrist"],"a":0,"e":"The knee is the most commonly affected joint in adult septic arthritis.<br><br>The hip is commonest in children; in adults the knee is most often involved."},
/*1193*/ {"q":"Most common primary malignant bone tumor in children/adolescents:","o":["Osteosarcoma","Ewing sarcoma","Chondrosarcoma","Multiple myeloma"],"a":0,"e":"Osteosarcoma is the commonest primary malignant bone tumour in children and adolescents, typically around the knee.<br><br>Ewing sarcoma is next; the commonest in this age group is osteosarcoma."},
/*1194*/ {"q":"Chondrosarcoma most commonly occurs in:","o":["Older adults (pelvis, axial skeleton)","Children","Neonates","Adolescents only"],"a":0,"e":"Chondrosarcoma typically occurs in older adults, often in the pelvis and axial skeleton, in contrast to osteosarcoma in the young.<br><br>It is not a paediatric tumour; chondrosarcoma affects older adults."},
/*1195*/ {"q":"Most common benign soft tissue tumor:","o":["Lipoma","Leiomyoma","Hemangioma","Fibroma"],"a":0,"e":"Lipoma is the commonest benign soft tissue tumour, a slow-growing painless mass of mature adipocytes.<br><br>The others are less common; the commonest benign soft tissue tumour is lipoma."},
/*1196*/ {"q":"Most common soft tissue sarcoma in adults:","o":["Undifferentiated pleomorphic sarcoma / liposarcoma","Rhabdomyosarcoma","Osteosarcoma","Ewing sarcoma"],"a":0,"e":"Undifferentiated pleomorphic sarcoma and liposarcoma are among the commonest soft tissue sarcomas in adults.<br><br>Rhabdomyosarcoma is commonest in children; per source key the marked adult answer is undifferentiated pleomorphic sarcoma/liposarcoma."},
/*1197*/ {"q":"Most common soft tissue sarcoma in children:","o":["Rhabdomyosarcoma","Liposarcoma","Leiomyosarcoma","Synovial sarcoma"],"a":0,"e":"Rhabdomyosarcoma is the commonest soft tissue sarcoma in children, arising from skeletal muscle precursors.<br><br>Liposarcoma affects adults; in children the commonest is rhabdomyosarcoma."},
/*1198*/ {"q":"Psammoma bodies are NOT typically seen in:","o":["Medullary thyroid carcinoma","Papillary thyroid carcinoma","Meningioma","Serous ovarian carcinoma"],"a":0,"e":"Psammoma bodies are seen in papillary thyroid carcinoma, meningioma and serous ovarian carcinoma, but not typically in medullary thyroid carcinoma.<br><br>The exception lacking psammoma bodies is medullary thyroid carcinoma."},
/*1199*/ {"q":"Most common cause of cancer death worldwide:","o":["Lung cancer","Breast cancer","Colon cancer","Stomach cancer"],"a":0,"e":"Lung cancer is the commonest cause of cancer-related death worldwide.<br><br>Breast and colon cancers cause fewer deaths overall; the leading cause of cancer death is lung cancer."},
/*1200*/ {"q":"Most common cancer in men worldwide:","o":["Lung/prostate cancer","Colon cancer","Stomach cancer","Liver cancer"],"a":0,"e":"Lung and prostate cancers are the commonest malignancies in men worldwide, varying by region.<br><br>Per source key the marked answer is lung/prostate cancer as the commonest in men."},

/*1201*/ {"q":"Most common cancer in women worldwide:","o":["Breast cancer","Cervical cancer","Lung cancer","Colon cancer"],"a":0,"e":"Breast cancer is the commonest malignancy in women worldwide.<br><br>Cervical and lung cancers are less common overall; the leading female cancer is breast cancer."},
/*1202*/ {"q":"Tumor suppressor gene most commonly mutated in human cancers:","o":["p53","RB","APC","BRCA"],"a":0,"e":"The p53 tumour suppressor gene is the most commonly mutated gene across human cancers, guarding the G1/S checkpoint and apoptosis.<br><br>RB and APC are mutated in specific cancers; the most frequently mutated is p53."},
/*1203*/ {"q":"Li-Fraumeni syndrome is due to germline mutation of:","o":["p53","RB","APC","BRCA1"],"a":0,"e":"Li-Fraumeni syndrome results from a germline p53 mutation, predisposing to multiple early cancers (sarcomas, breast, brain, adrenal).<br><br>It is not RB or APC related; Li-Fraumeni is a germline p53 disorder."},
/*1204*/ {"q":"Retinoblastoma gene (RB) follows:","o":["Knudson two-hit hypothesis","Single-hit dominant","Mitochondrial","Non-genetic"],"a":0,"e":"Retinoblastoma exemplifies Knudson's two-hit hypothesis, requiring inactivation of both RB alleles for tumour development.<br><br>One hit is insufficient; RB follows the two-hit model."},
/*1205*/ {"q":"Familial adenomatous polyposis is due to mutation of:","o":["APC gene","RB gene","p53 gene","RET gene"],"a":0,"e":"Familial adenomatous polyposis results from germline APC gene mutation, causing hundreds of colonic adenomas with near-certain progression to carcinoma.<br><br>RET relates to MEN2; FAP is an APC disorder."},
/*1206*/ {"q":"Hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer (Lynch syndrome) is due to defect in:","o":["DNA mismatch repair genes","APC","RB","BRCA"],"a":0,"e":"Lynch syndrome (HNPCC) is caused by defects in DNA mismatch repair genes (e.g. MLH1, MSH2), producing microsatellite instability.<br><br>APC defines FAP; Lynch syndrome is a mismatch repair disorder."},
/*1207*/ {"q":"BRCA1/BRCA2 mutations predispose to:","o":["Breast and ovarian cancer","Colon and gastric cancer","Lung cancer","Leukemia"],"a":0,"e":"Germline BRCA1 and BRCA2 mutations markedly increase the risk of breast and ovarian cancer (BRCA2 also prostate/pancreatic).<br><br>They are not colon/lung genes; BRCA mutations predispose to breast and ovarian cancer."},
/*1208*/ {"q":"Philadelphia chromosome results from translocation:","o":["t(9;22)","t(8;14)","t(14;18)","t(15;17)"],"a":0,"e":"The Philadelphia chromosome arises from the t(9;22) translocation creating the BCR-ABL fusion gene of chronic myeloid leukaemia.<br><br>t(15;17) is APL; the Philadelphia chromosome is t(9;22)."},
/*1209*/ {"q":"Acute promyelocytic leukemia is associated with translocation:","o":["t(15;17)","t(9;22)","t(8;14)","t(14;18)"],"a":0,"e":"Acute promyelocytic leukaemia is associated with the t(15;17) PML-RARA fusion, responsive to all-trans retinoic acid.<br><br>t(9;22) is CML; APL is t(15;17)."},
/*1210*/ {"q":"Oncogene activated by point mutation in many carcinomas:","o":["RAS","RB","p53","APC"],"a":0,"e":"The RAS proto-oncogene is frequently activated by point mutation in many human carcinomas, driving constitutive growth signalling.<br><br>RB, p53 and APC are tumour suppressors; the commonly mutated oncogene is RAS."},
/*1211*/ {"q":"HER2/neu overexpression is associated with:","o":["Aggressive breast cancer (targeted by trastuzumab)","Good prognosis colon cancer","Benign tumors","Leukemia"],"a":0,"e":"HER2/neu (ERBB2) amplification is associated with aggressive breast carcinoma and is the target of trastuzumab therapy.<br><br>It is not a colon or leukaemia marker; HER2 overexpression marks aggressive breast cancer."},
/*1212*/ {"q":"Most important risk factor for hepatocellular carcinoma worldwide:","o":["Chronic hepatitis B/C and cirrhosis","Alcohol only","Aflatoxin only","Smoking"],"a":0,"e":"Chronic hepatitis B and C infection with resulting cirrhosis is the most important risk factor for hepatocellular carcinoma worldwide.<br><br>Aflatoxin and alcohol contribute; the leading risk is chronic viral hepatitis/cirrhosis."},
/*1213*/ {"q":"Aflatoxin (Aspergillus) is associated with:","o":["Hepatocellular carcinoma","Bladder cancer","Lung cancer","Skin cancer"],"a":0,"e":"Aflatoxin B1 from Aspergillus contamination of food causes a characteristic p53 mutation and is associated with hepatocellular carcinoma.<br><br>It is not a bladder or lung carcinogen; aflatoxin links to liver cancer."},
/*1214*/ {"q":"Vinyl chloride exposure is associated with:","o":["Hepatic angiosarcoma","Bladder cancer","Mesothelioma","Leukemia"],"a":0,"e":"Vinyl chloride exposure (plastics industry) is associated with hepatic angiosarcoma.<br><br>Asbestos links to mesothelioma; vinyl chloride causes hepatic angiosarcoma."},
/*1215*/ {"q":"Aniline dye (aromatic amine) exposure is associated with:","o":["Bladder transitional cell carcinoma","Liver cancer","Lung cancer","Skin cancer"],"a":0,"e":"Aromatic amines (aniline dyes, rubber industry) are associated with bladder transitional cell carcinoma.<br><br>They are not liver or lung carcinogens; aromatic amines cause bladder cancer."},
/*1216*/ {"q":"Schistosoma haematobium infection is associated with:","o":["Squamous cell carcinoma of bladder","Adenocarcinoma of colon","Hepatocellular carcinoma","Gastric cancer"],"a":0,"e":"Chronic Schistosoma haematobium infection is associated with squamous cell carcinoma of the urinary bladder.<br><br>It is not a colon or liver cause; schistosomiasis links to bladder squamous carcinoma."},
/*1217*/ {"q":"Helicobacter pylori is associated with all except:","o":["Hepatocellular carcinoma","Gastric adenocarcinoma","Gastric MALT lymphoma","Peptic ulcer"],"a":0,"e":"Helicobacter pylori is associated with peptic ulcer, gastric adenocarcinoma and gastric MALT lymphoma, but not hepatocellular carcinoma.<br><br>The exception not linked to H. pylori is hepatocellular carcinoma."},
/*1218*/ {"q":"Human papillomavirus is most strongly associated with:","o":["Cervical and oropharyngeal carcinoma","Gastric cancer","Liver cancer","Leukemia"],"a":0,"e":"High-risk HPV is strongly associated with cervical, anal and oropharyngeal squamous carcinomas.<br><br>It is not a gastric or liver virus; HPV links to cervical and oropharyngeal cancer."},
/*1219*/ {"q":"Epstein-Barr virus is associated with all except:","o":["Hepatocellular carcinoma","Burkitt lymphoma","Nasopharyngeal carcinoma","Hodgkin lymphoma"],"a":0,"e":"Epstein-Barr virus is associated with Burkitt lymphoma, nasopharyngeal carcinoma and Hodgkin lymphoma, but not hepatocellular carcinoma.<br><br>The exception not linked to EBV is hepatocellular carcinoma."},
/*1220*/ {"q":"Human T-lymphotropic virus type 1 (HTLV-1) causes:","o":["Adult T-cell leukemia/lymphoma","Burkitt lymphoma","Hodgkin lymphoma","Hepatocellular carcinoma"],"a":0,"e":"HTLV-1 is the cause of adult T-cell leukaemia/lymphoma, endemic in parts of Japan and the Caribbean.<br><br>EBV causes Burkitt lymphoma; HTLV-1 causes adult T-cell leukaemia/lymphoma."},
/*1221*/ {"q":"Human herpesvirus 8 (HHV-8) is associated with:","o":["Kaposi sarcoma","Burkitt lymphoma","Cervical cancer","Hepatocellular carcinoma"],"a":0,"e":"Human herpesvirus 8 is the cause of Kaposi sarcoma, particularly in immunosuppressed and HIV patients.<br><br>It is not linked to Burkitt or cervical cancer; HHV-8 causes Kaposi sarcoma."},
/*1222*/ {"q":"Tumor marker for medullary thyroid carcinoma:","o":["Calcitonin","Thyroglobulin","TSH","T4"],"a":0,"e":"Calcitonin is the tumour marker for medullary thyroid carcinoma, secreted by the parafollicular C cells of origin.<br><br>Thyroglobulin marks differentiated follicular-cell tumours; medullary carcinoma is monitored with calcitonin."},
/*1223*/ {"q":"Tumor marker for pancreatic carcinoma:","o":["CA 19-9","CEA","AFP","beta-hCG"],"a":0,"e":"CA 19-9 is the tumour marker associated with pancreatic carcinoma, used for monitoring rather than screening.<br><br>AFP relates to liver/germ cell tumours; the pancreatic marker is CA 19-9."},
/*1224*/ {"q":"Tumor marker for prostate carcinoma:","o":["Prostate-specific antigen (PSA)","CEA","CA 125","AFP"],"a":0,"e":"Prostate-specific antigen (PSA) is the tumour marker used for prostate cancer screening and monitoring.<br><br>CA 125 relates to ovarian cancer; the prostate marker is PSA."},
/*1225*/ {"q":"Tumor marker for testicular germ cell tumors:","o":["AFP and beta-hCG","PSA","CA 125","CEA"],"a":0,"e":"Alpha-fetoprotein and beta-hCG are the tumour markers for non-seminomatous testicular germ cell tumours, used for diagnosis and monitoring.<br><br>PSA and CA 125 are unrelated; testicular germ cell tumours use AFP and beta-hCG."},
/*1226*/ {"q":"Tumor marker for ovarian epithelial carcinoma:","o":["CA 125","PSA","AFP","Calcitonin"],"a":0,"e":"CA 125 is the tumour marker associated with ovarian epithelial carcinoma, used for monitoring response and recurrence.<br><br>AFP relates to germ cell tumours; the ovarian epithelial marker is CA 125."},
/*1227*/ {"q":"Tumor marker for colorectal carcinoma follow-up:","o":["CEA","CA 19-9","AFP","PSA"],"a":0,"e":"Carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA) is used for monitoring and detecting recurrence of colorectal carcinoma.<br><br>CA 19-9 relates to pancreatic cancer; the colorectal follow-up marker is CEA."},
/*1228*/ {"q":"Most radiosensitive cell type:","o":["Lymphocyte","Neuron","Muscle cell","Hepatocyte"],"a":0,"e":"Lymphocytes are among the most radiosensitive cells in the body, despite being non-dividing, undergoing rapid apoptosis after irradiation.<br><br>Neurons and muscle are radioresistant; the most radiosensitive is the lymphocyte."},
/*1229*/ {"q":"Grading of a tumor refers to:","o":["Degree of differentiation","Extent of spread","Tumor size only","Patient age"],"a":0,"e":"Tumour grade describes the degree of histological differentiation and anaplasia, indicating aggressiveness.<br><br>Spread is described by staging; grading refers to differentiation."},
/*1230*/ {"q":"Staging of a tumor refers to:","o":["Extent of spread (TNM)","Degree of differentiation","Mitotic rate","Nuclear pleomorphism"],"a":0,"e":"Tumour stage describes the anatomical extent of spread using the TNM system (tumour size, nodes, metastasis) and is the strongest prognostic factor.<br><br>Differentiation is grading; extent of spread is staging."},
/*1231*/ {"q":"The most important prognostic factor for most solid tumors is:","o":["Stage","Grade","Patient age","Tumor markers"],"a":0,"e":"For most solid tumours, the anatomical stage (extent of spread) is the single most important prognostic factor.<br><br>Grade matters but stage predominates; the key prognostic factor is stage."},
/*1232*/ {"q":"Carcinoma in situ is characterized by:","o":["Malignant cells confined by the basement membrane","Invasion through basement membrane","Distant metastasis","Benign behavior"],"a":0,"e":"Carcinoma in situ shows full-thickness epithelial malignant change that has not breached the basement membrane, so it cannot metastasise.<br><br>Invasion defines invasive carcinoma; in situ disease is confined by the basement membrane."},
/*1233*/ {"q":"Hallmark distinguishing malignant from benign tumors:","o":["Invasion and metastasis","Encapsulation","Slow growth","Differentiation"],"a":0,"e":"The capacity for invasion of surrounding tissue and metastasis is the defining hallmark of malignancy.<br><br>Benign tumours are encapsulated and non-invasive; malignancy is defined by invasion and metastasis."},
/*1234*/ {"q":"Most common route of metastasis for carcinomas:","o":["Lymphatic spread","Hematogenous","Transcoelomic","Perineural"],"a":0,"e":"Carcinomas characteristically metastasise first via lymphatic spread to regional lymph nodes, whereas sarcomas favour haematogenous spread.<br><br>Per source key the marked typical carcinoma route is lymphatic spread."},
/*1235*/ {"q":"Most common route of metastasis for sarcomas:","o":["Hematogenous (blood)","Lymphatic","Transcoelomic","Perineural"],"a":0,"e":"Sarcomas characteristically spread haematogenously, commonly to the lungs.<br><br>Carcinomas favour lymphatic spread; sarcomas spread via the bloodstream."},
/*1236*/ {"q":"Most common site of hematogenous metastasis overall:","o":["Lung and liver","Brain","Skin","Spleen"],"a":0,"e":"The lung and liver are the commonest sites of haematogenous metastasis, acting as capillary filters for venous and portal blood.<br><br>The spleen is rarely involved; the commonest sites are lung and liver."},
/*1237*/ {"q":"Cancer cachexia is mediated mainly by:","o":["TNF-alpha and other cytokines","Insulin","Growth hormone","Thyroxine"],"a":0,"e":"Cancer cachexia, with weight loss and muscle wasting, is mediated chiefly by tumour-derived cytokines such as TNF-alpha (cachectin).<br><br>It is not simply reduced intake; cachexia is cytokine-mediated, especially TNF-alpha."},
/*1238*/ {"q":"Paraneoplastic SIADH is most commonly caused by:","o":["Small cell lung carcinoma","Squamous cell lung carcinoma","Renal cell carcinoma","Colon cancer"],"a":0,"e":"Ectopic antidiuretic hormone secretion causing paraneoplastic SIADH is most commonly due to small cell lung carcinoma.<br><br>Squamous lung cancer causes hypercalcaemia; SIADH is typically small cell carcinoma."},
/*1239*/ {"q":"Paraneoplastic hypercalcemia from PTHrP is most commonly caused by:","o":["Squamous cell carcinoma (lung)","Small cell carcinoma","Adenocarcinoma","Carcinoid"],"a":0,"e":"Humoral hypercalcaemia of malignancy from parathyroid hormone-related peptide is most commonly caused by squamous cell carcinoma, classically of the lung.<br><br>Small cell causes SIADH/ACTH; PTHrP hypercalcaemia is typically squamous carcinoma."},
/*1240*/ {"q":"Paraneoplastic Cushing syndrome (ectopic ACTH) is most commonly caused by:","o":["Small cell lung carcinoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Renal cell carcinoma","Colon cancer"],"a":0,"e":"Ectopic ACTH secretion causing paraneoplastic Cushing syndrome is most commonly due to small cell lung carcinoma.<br><br>Squamous carcinoma causes hypercalcaemia; ectopic ACTH is typically small cell carcinoma."},
/*1241*/ {"q":"Lambert-Eaton myasthenic syndrome is associated with:","o":["Small cell lung carcinoma","Thymoma","Breast cancer","Colon cancer"],"a":0,"e":"Lambert-Eaton myasthenic syndrome, due to antibodies against presynaptic voltage-gated calcium channels, is associated with small cell lung carcinoma.<br><br>Thymoma associates with myasthenia gravis; Lambert-Eaton links to small cell carcinoma."},
/*1242*/ {"q":"Acanthosis nigricans as a paraneoplastic sign is most associated with:","o":["Gastric adenocarcinoma","Lung cancer","Breast cancer","Prostate cancer"],"a":0,"e":"Paraneoplastic acanthosis nigricans, when sudden and extensive in an adult, is most associated with gastric (and other intra-abdominal) adenocarcinoma.<br><br>The other cancers are less typical; the classic association is gastric adenocarcinoma."},
/*1243*/ {"q":"Trousseau sign of malignancy refers to:","o":["Migratory thrombophlebitis","Carpal spasm","Facial twitch","Skin pigmentation"],"a":0,"e":"Trousseau sign of malignancy is migratory superficial thrombophlebitis, a hypercoagulable paraneoplastic phenomenon classically with pancreatic and other adenocarcinomas.<br><br>Carpal spasm is the hypocalcaemia sign; the malignancy sign is migratory thrombophlebitis."},
/*1244*/ {"q":"Most common cause of death in cancer patients:","o":["Infection","Hemorrhage","Organ failure from metastasis","Cachexia"],"a":0,"e":"Infection is a leading cause of death in cancer patients, often from immunosuppression and neutropenia.<br><br>Per source key the marked commonest cause of death is infection."},
/*1245*/ {"q":"Tumor lysis syndrome is characterized by:","o":["Hyperkalemia, hyperuricemia, hyperphosphatemia, hypocalcemia","Hypokalemia","Hypouricemia","Hypercalcemia"],"a":0,"e":"Tumour lysis syndrome, after treatment of bulky tumours, causes hyperkalaemia, hyperuricaemia, hyperphosphataemia and secondary hypocalcaemia with acute kidney injury.<br><br>The opposite electrolyte pattern is wrong; tumour lysis gives high K, urate, phosphate and low calcium."},
/*1246*/ {"q":"Rasburicase is used in tumor lysis syndrome to lower:","o":["Uric acid","Potassium","Phosphate","Calcium"],"a":0,"e":"Rasburicase, a recombinant urate oxidase, lowers uric acid by converting it to soluble allantoin in tumour lysis syndrome.<br><br>It does not directly lower potassium or phosphate; rasburicase reduces uric acid."},
/*1247*/ {"q":"Most common second malignancy after radiotherapy:","o":["Sarcoma in the irradiated field","Leukemia only","Skin cancer only","No risk"],"a":0,"e":"Radiation-induced sarcomas arising within the previously irradiated field are a recognised late second malignancy after radiotherapy, alongside leukaemia.<br><br>Per source key the marked answer is in-field sarcoma."},
/*1248*/ {"q":"Chemotherapy drug classically causing pulmonary fibrosis:","o":["Bleomycin","Vincristine","Cisplatin","Methotrexate"],"a":0,"e":"Bleomycin classically causes dose-dependent pulmonary fibrosis as its major toxicity.<br><br>Vincristine causes neuropathy; the lung-fibrosis agent is bleomycin."},
/*1249*/ {"q":"Chemotherapy drug classically causing cardiotoxicity:","o":["Doxorubicin (anthracycline)","Bleomycin","Vincristine","Cisplatin"],"a":0,"e":"Doxorubicin and other anthracyclines classically cause dose-dependent dilated cardiomyopathy and cardiotoxicity.<br><br>Bleomycin affects the lungs; the cardiotoxic agent is doxorubicin."},
/*1250*/ {"q":"Chemotherapy drug classically causing peripheral neuropathy:","o":["Vincristine","Doxorubicin","Bleomycin","5-Fluorouracil"],"a":0,"e":"Vincristine classically causes dose-limiting peripheral neuropathy by disrupting microtubule-dependent axonal transport.<br><br>Doxorubicin is cardiotoxic; the neuropathy agent is vincristine."},

/*1251*/ {"q":"Chemotherapy drug classically causing nephrotoxicity and ototoxicity:","o":["Cisplatin","Vincristine","Bleomycin","5-Fluorouracil"],"a":0,"e":"Cisplatin classically causes dose-dependent nephrotoxicity and ototoxicity, mitigated by hydration and dose limitation.<br><br>Vincristine causes neuropathy; the nephro/ototoxic agent is cisplatin."},
/*1252*/ {"q":"Chemotherapy drug classically causing hemorrhagic cystitis:","o":["Cyclophosphamide","Doxorubicin","Bleomycin","Vincristine"],"a":0,"e":"Cyclophosphamide and ifosfamide cause haemorrhagic cystitis from the metabolite acrolein, prevented by mesna and hydration.<br><br>The other agents do not; the haemorrhagic-cystitis drug is cyclophosphamide."},
/*1253*/ {"q":"Methotrexate toxicity is reversed by:","o":["Folinic acid (leucovorin) rescue","Vitamin K","Protamine","N-acetylcysteine"],"a":0,"e":"Folinic acid (leucovorin) rescue bypasses dihydrofolate reductase inhibition and reverses methotrexate toxicity.<br><br>Vitamin K reverses warfarin; methotrexate is rescued with folinic acid."},
/*1254*/ {"q":"Tamoxifen used in breast cancer increases the risk of:","o":["Endometrial carcinoma","Ovarian cancer","Cervical cancer","Colon cancer"],"a":0,"e":"Tamoxifen, a selective oestrogen receptor modulator, has oestrogenic effects on the endometrium and increases endometrial carcinoma risk.<br><br>It is protective for breast/bone; its key risk is endometrial carcinoma."},
/*1255*/ {"q":"Imatinib targets:","o":["BCR-ABL tyrosine kinase","EGFR","HER2","VEGF"],"a":0,"e":"Imatinib is a tyrosine kinase inhibitor targeting the BCR-ABL fusion protein of chronic myeloid leukaemia.<br><br>It does not target HER2 or VEGF; imatinib inhibits BCR-ABL."},
/*1256*/ {"q":"Trastuzumab targets:","o":["HER2/neu receptor","BCR-ABL","EGFR","CD20"],"a":0,"e":"Trastuzumab is a monoclonal antibody against the HER2/neu receptor, used in HER2-positive breast cancer.<br><br>Rituximab targets CD20; trastuzumab targets HER2."},
/*1257*/ {"q":"Rituximab targets:","o":["CD20 on B cells","CD3 on T cells","HER2","VEGF"],"a":0,"e":"Rituximab is a monoclonal antibody against CD20 on B lymphocytes, used in B-cell lymphomas and autoimmune disease.<br><br>It does not target T cells or HER2; rituximab targets CD20."},
/*1258*/ {"q":"Bevacizumab targets:","o":["VEGF (angiogenesis)","HER2","CD20","BCR-ABL"],"a":0,"e":"Bevacizumab is a monoclonal antibody against vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF), inhibiting tumour angiogenesis.<br><br>It does not target HER2 or CD20; bevacizumab targets VEGF."},
/*1259*/ {"q":"Most common acute side effect of radiotherapy to the skin:","o":["Erythema and desquamation","Fibrosis","Necrosis","Pigment loss only"],"a":0,"e":"Acute radiation skin reaction presents with erythema progressing to dry then moist desquamation; fibrosis is a late effect.<br><br>Fibrosis develops later; the acute effect is erythema and desquamation."},
/*1260*/ {"q":"Most radioresistant of the following tumors:","o":["Melanoma","Seminoma","Lymphoma","Small cell carcinoma"],"a":0,"e":"Melanoma is classically among the most radioresistant tumours, whereas seminoma and lymphoma are highly radiosensitive.<br><br>The keyed most radioresistant tumour here is melanoma."},
/*1261*/ {"q":"Most radiosensitive of the following tumors:","o":["Seminoma","Melanoma","Osteosarcoma","Renal cell carcinoma"],"a":0,"e":"Seminoma is one of the most radiosensitive solid tumours, alongside lymphoma.<br><br>Melanoma and renal cell carcinoma are radioresistant; the most radiosensitive here is seminoma."},
/*1262*/ {"q":"Fractionation in radiotherapy is used to:","o":["Spare normal tissue while killing tumor","Increase total dose only","Reduce treatment time","Avoid imaging"],"a":0,"e":"Fractionating the radiation dose exploits differential repair and reoxygenation, sparing normal tissue while maximising tumour cell kill.<br><br>It is not merely about time; fractionation spares normal tissue while killing tumour."},
/*1263*/ {"q":"Brachytherapy refers to:","o":["Placement of a radioactive source close to/within the tumor","External beam radiation","Systemic chemotherapy","Whole-body irradiation"],"a":0,"e":"Brachytherapy delivers radiation by placing a sealed radioactive source within or adjacent to the tumour, giving a high local dose with rapid falloff.<br><br>External beam is teletherapy; brachytherapy is local source placement."},
/*1264*/ {"q":"The therapeutic ratio in radiotherapy describes:","o":["Tumor control relative to normal tissue damage","Cost vs benefit","Dose vs time only","Imaging quality"],"a":0,"e":"The therapeutic ratio compares the probability of tumour control against the probability of normal tissue complications, guiding dose selection.<br><br>It is not a financial concept; it balances tumour control against normal tissue damage."},
/*1265*/ {"q":"Most common indication for palliative radiotherapy:","o":["Painful bone metastases","Curative intent","Screening","Prophylaxis only"],"a":0,"e":"Palliative radiotherapy is commonly used to relieve pain from bone metastases, as well as for bleeding and obstruction.<br><br>It is not curative; a common palliative indication is painful bone metastases."},
/*1266*/ {"q":"Radiation pneumonitis typically occurs:","o":["Weeks to months after thoracic radiotherapy","Immediately","Years before treatment","Never"],"a":0,"e":"Radiation pneumonitis typically develops weeks to a few months after thoracic irradiation, with cough, dyspnoea and infiltrates in the radiation field.<br><br>It is not immediate; it is a subacute effect weeks to months later."},
/*1267*/ {"q":"Most common late effect of pelvic radiotherapy:","o":["Radiation proctitis/cystitis and fibrosis","Acute nausea only","Immediate marrow failure","No late effects"],"a":0,"e":"Late effects of pelvic radiotherapy include radiation proctitis, cystitis and fibrosis with strictures, occurring months to years later.<br><br>Nausea is acute; the late effects are proctitis/cystitis and fibrosis."},
/*1268*/ {"q":"Total body irradiation is mainly used before:","o":["Bone marrow/stem cell transplantation","Appendectomy","Routine imaging","Skin biopsy"],"a":0,"e":"Total body irradiation is used as conditioning before haematopoietic stem cell (bone marrow) transplantation, to ablate marrow and immunosuppress.<br><br>It is not for minor procedures; TBI is a transplant conditioning regimen."},
/*1269*/ {"q":"Most sensitive imaging for detecting bone metastases early:","o":["Radionuclide bone scan / MRI","Plain X-ray","Ultrasound","Fluoroscopy"],"a":0,"e":"A radionuclide bone scan (and MRI) detects bone metastases earlier than plain radiographs, which require significant bone loss to show change.<br><br>Plain films are insensitive early; the sensitive modalities are bone scan/MRI."},
/*1270*/ {"q":"Lytic bone metastases are most characteristic of:","o":["Multiple myeloma and renal/thyroid carcinoma","Prostate carcinoma","Always sclerotic","No bone involvement"],"a":0,"e":"Purely lytic bone metastases are characteristic of multiple myeloma and renal and thyroid carcinoma.<br><br>Prostate gives sclerotic lesions; the lytic pattern is typical of myeloma and renal/thyroid cancer."},
/*1271*/ {"q":"Most common primary tumor causing brain metastasis:","o":["Lung carcinoma","Prostate carcinoma","Thyroid carcinoma","Cervical carcinoma"],"a":0,"e":"Lung carcinoma is the commonest primary tumour to metastasise to the brain, followed by breast and melanoma.<br><br>Prostate rarely goes to brain; the commonest source is lung cancer."},
/*1272*/ {"q":"Most common primary tumor causing liver metastasis:","o":["Colorectal carcinoma","Brain tumor","Skin cancer","Renal cyst"],"a":0,"e":"Colorectal carcinoma is the commonest primary tumour to metastasise to the liver, via the portal venous drainage.<br><br>Brain tumours rarely metastasise systemically; the commonest hepatic metastasis source is colorectal cancer."},
/*1273*/ {"q":"Most common cause of a cannonball metastasis pattern in the lungs:","o":["Renal cell carcinoma / choriocarcinoma","Lung primary","Brain tumor","Skin cancer"],"a":0,"e":"Multiple large round \"cannonball\" pulmonary metastases are characteristic of renal cell carcinoma and choriocarcinoma (also sarcoma).<br><br>Per source key the marked answer is renal cell carcinoma/choriocarcinoma."},
/*1274*/ {"q":"Most common cause of pathological fracture due to malignancy:","o":["Metastatic carcinoma (breast, prostate, lung)","Primary bone sarcoma","Osteoid osteoma","Benign cyst"],"a":0,"e":"Metastatic carcinoma, particularly from breast, prostate and lung, is the commonest malignant cause of pathological fracture.<br><br>Primary bone sarcomas are rarer; the commonest malignant cause is metastatic carcinoma."},
/*1275*/ {"q":"Spinal cord compression from malignancy is an emergency requiring:","o":["Urgent MRI and corticosteroids/radiotherapy","Routine outpatient referral","No treatment","Antibiotics only"],"a":0,"e":"Malignant spinal cord compression is an oncological emergency requiring urgent MRI, high-dose corticosteroids and prompt radiotherapy or surgery to preserve neurological function.<br><br>Delay risks permanent paralysis; it demands urgent imaging and treatment."},
/*1276*/ {"q":"Superior vena cava obstruction is most commonly caused by:","o":["Bronchogenic carcinoma (right-sided)","Aortic aneurysm","Thyroid goiter","Thymoma"],"a":0,"e":"Superior vena cava obstruction is most commonly caused by a right-sided bronchogenic carcinoma compressing or invading the SVC, with facial swelling and distended neck veins.<br><br>The other causes are less frequent; the leading cause is bronchogenic carcinoma."},
/*1277*/ {"q":"Most common cause of a mediastinal mass in the anterior mediastinum:","o":["Thymoma (and other T's: teratoma, thyroid, lymphoma)","Neurogenic tumor","Bronchogenic cyst","Aortic aneurysm"],"a":0,"e":"Anterior mediastinal masses are classically the \"4 T's\": thymoma, teratoma, thyroid mass and (terrible) lymphoma, with thymoma a common cause.<br><br>Neurogenic tumours are posterior; an anterior mass is often thymoma."},
/*1278*/ {"q":"Most common posterior mediastinal mass:","o":["Neurogenic tumor","Thymoma","Teratoma","Lymphoma"],"a":0,"e":"Neurogenic tumours arising from the sympathetic chain or nerve roots are the commonest posterior mediastinal masses.<br><br>Thymoma and teratoma are anterior; the posterior mass is typically neurogenic."},
/*1279*/ {"q":"Pancoast tumor (superior sulcus) characteristically causes:","o":["Horner syndrome and arm pain","Bitemporal hemianopia","Hemiparesis","Jaundice"],"a":0,"e":"A Pancoast (superior sulcus) tumour invades the lower brachial plexus and sympathetic chain, causing arm/shoulder pain and ipsilateral Horner syndrome.<br><br>The visual/neurological distractors are unrelated; Pancoast tumour causes Horner syndrome and arm pain."},
/*1280*/ {"q":"Most common cause of a coin lesion in the lung in a young non-smoker:","o":["Granuloma (infectious)","Bronchogenic carcinoma","Metastasis","Hamartoma"],"a":0,"e":"In a young non-smoker, a solitary pulmonary coin lesion is most commonly a benign infectious granuloma.<br><br>Carcinoma is unlikely at that age; the commonest cause is a granuloma."},
/*1281*/ {"q":"Most common benign tumor of the lung:","o":["Hamartoma","Bronchial adenoma","Lipoma","Fibroma"],"a":0,"e":"Pulmonary hamartoma is the commonest benign lung tumour, often showing popcorn calcification on imaging.<br><br>The others are rarer; the commonest benign lung tumour is hamartoma."},
/*1282*/ {"q":"Bronchial carcinoid tumor characteristically:","o":["Is low-grade and may cause carcinoid syndrome","Is highly aggressive always","Never secretes hormones","Is the commonest lung cancer"],"a":0,"e":"Bronchial carcinoid is a low-grade neuroendocrine tumour that may cause carcinoid syndrome, especially with hepatic metastases.<br><br>It is not the commonest lung cancer; carcinoid is low-grade with possible carcinoid syndrome."},
/*1283*/ {"q":"Most common cause of massive hemoptysis:","o":["Bronchiectasis / tuberculosis","Pulmonary embolism","Pneumothorax","Asthma"],"a":0,"e":"Massive haemoptysis is most commonly caused by bronchiectasis and tuberculosis, from erosion of bronchial vessels.<br><br>Embolism and pneumothorax rarely cause massive bleeding; the leading causes are bronchiectasis and TB."},
/*1284*/ {"q":"Most common cause of pleural exudate:","o":["Infection (parapneumonic) and malignancy","Heart failure","Cirrhosis","Nephrotic syndrome"],"a":0,"e":"Exudative pleural effusions are most commonly due to infection (parapneumonic) and malignancy.<br><br>Heart failure and cirrhosis cause transudates; exudates are usually infective or malignant."},
/*1285*/ {"q":"Light criteria are used to differentiate:","o":["Pleural exudate from transudate","Pneumonia types","Stridor causes","Hemoptysis causes"],"a":0,"e":"Light's criteria use pleural fluid protein and LDH ratios to distinguish an exudate from a transudate.<br><br>They are not for pneumonia classification; Light's criteria separate exudate from transudate."},
/*1286*/ {"q":"Most common cause of transudative pleural effusion:","o":["Congestive heart failure","Pneumonia","Malignancy","Tuberculosis"],"a":0,"e":"Congestive heart failure is the commonest cause of a transudative pleural effusion, from raised hydrostatic pressure.<br><br>Pneumonia and malignancy cause exudates; the leading transudate cause is heart failure."},
/*1287*/ {"q":"Chylothorax is characterized by pleural fluid rich in:","o":["Triglycerides (lymph/chyle)","Glucose","Protein only","Red cells"],"a":0,"e":"Chylothorax is an accumulation of lymphatic chyle in the pleural space, with a milky fluid rich in triglycerides, often from thoracic duct injury or lymphoma.<br><br>It is not defined by glucose; chylothorax fluid is triglyceride-rich."},
/*1288*/ {"q":"Most common cause of empyema:","o":["Bacterial pneumonia (parapneumonic)","Tuberculosis","Trauma","Malignancy"],"a":0,"e":"Empyema (pus in the pleural space) most commonly arises as a complication of bacterial pneumonia.<br><br>The other causes are less frequent; the leading cause is bacterial pneumonia."},
/*1289*/ {"q":"Most common cause of spontaneous pneumothorax in a young tall male:","o":["Rupture of subpleural apical bleb","Asthma","Pneumonia","Malignancy"],"a":0,"e":"Primary spontaneous pneumothorax in a tall young male is typically due to rupture of a subpleural apical bleb.<br><br>The other causes are less typical in this group; the usual cause is bleb rupture."},
/*1290*/ {"q":"Tension pneumothorax is managed immediately by:","o":["Needle decompression / chest drain","Observation","Antibiotics","Bronchodilators"],"a":0,"e":"Tension pneumothorax is a life-threatening emergency requiring immediate needle decompression followed by a chest drain.<br><br>Observation is dangerous; immediate decompression is required."},
/*1291*/ {"q":"Most common cause of acute respiratory distress syndrome:","o":["Sepsis","Asthma","COPD","Pulmonary embolism"],"a":0,"e":"Sepsis is the commonest cause of acute respiratory distress syndrome, producing diffuse alveolar damage and non-cardiogenic pulmonary oedema.<br><br>The obstructive diseases are different entities; the leading ARDS cause is sepsis."},
/*1292*/ {"q":"Hyaline membranes in alveoli are characteristic of:","o":["Diffuse alveolar damage (ARDS / neonatal RDS)","Asthma","Emphysema","Bronchiectasis"],"a":0,"e":"Hyaline membranes lining alveoli are characteristic of diffuse alveolar damage, seen in ARDS and neonatal respiratory distress syndrome.<br><br>The obstructive diseases lack them; hyaline membranes indicate diffuse alveolar damage."},
/*1293*/ {"q":"Neonatal respiratory distress syndrome is due to deficiency of:","o":["Surfactant","Insulin","Thyroxine","Albumin"],"a":0,"e":"Neonatal respiratory distress syndrome results from pulmonary surfactant deficiency in premature infants, causing alveolar collapse.<br><br>It is not a hormonal or protein deficiency primarily; the cause is surfactant deficiency."},
/*1294*/ {"q":"Surfactant is produced by:","o":["Type II pneumocytes","Type I pneumocytes","Clara cells only","Alveolar macrophages"],"a":0,"e":"Pulmonary surfactant is produced by type II pneumocytes, reducing alveolar surface tension and preventing collapse.<br><br>Type I cells perform gas exchange; surfactant is made by type II pneumocytes."},
/*1295*/ {"q":"Lecithin/sphingomyelin (L/S) ratio is used to assess:","o":["Fetal lung maturity","Renal function","Liver function","Cardiac maturity"],"a":0,"e":"The amniotic fluid lecithin/sphingomyelin ratio assesses fetal lung maturity, a ratio above 2 indicating adequate surfactant.<br><br>It is not a renal or hepatic test; the L/S ratio assesses fetal lung maturity."},
/*1296*/ {"q":"Most common cause of chronic cough in a non-smoker:","o":["Postnasal drip, asthma, GERD","Lung cancer","Tuberculosis","Heart failure"],"a":0,"e":"In non-smokers with a normal chest X-ray, chronic cough is most commonly due to upper airway cough syndrome (postnasal drip), asthma and gastro-oesophageal reflux.<br><br>Serious causes are less common; the usual causes are postnasal drip, asthma and GERD."},
/*1300*/ {"q":"Most common cause of clubbing in the chest:","o":["Bronchogenic carcinoma and suppurative lung disease","Asthma","Simple bronchitis","Common cold"],"a":0,"e":"Finger clubbing in respiratory disease is most commonly caused by bronchogenic carcinoma and chronic suppurative lung disease such as bronchiectasis and lung abscess.<br><br>Asthma and bronchitis do not cause clubbing; the leading causes are carcinoma and suppurative disease."},
/*1301*/ {"q":"Most common cause of upper lobe fibrosis on chest X-ray:","o":["Tuberculosis (and silicosis, sarcoidosis)","Asbestosis","Bronchiectasis","Pneumonia"],"a":0,"e":"Upper zone pulmonary fibrosis is classically caused by tuberculosis, silicosis and sarcoidosis.<br><br>Asbestosis causes lower-zone fibrosis; the upper-lobe pattern points to TB and similar causes."},
/*1302*/ {"q":"Most common cause of lower lobe fibrosis on chest X-ray:","o":["Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis and asbestosis","Tuberculosis","Silicosis","Sarcoidosis"],"a":0,"e":"Lower zone pulmonary fibrosis is characteristically caused by idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis and asbestosis.<br><br>TB and silicosis affect the upper zones; the lower-lobe pattern indicates IPF and asbestosis."},
/*1303*/ {"q":"Gold standard for confirming pulmonary tuberculosis:","o":["Sputum culture for Mycobacterium tuberculosis","Chest X-ray","Tuberculin skin test","Clinical signs"],"a":0,"e":"Sputum culture for Mycobacterium tuberculosis is the gold standard for confirming pulmonary tuberculosis and allows drug-sensitivity testing.<br><br>X-ray and skin test are supportive only; the definitive test is sputum culture."},
];
